<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0824 03-31 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0824,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Reagan Administration Deserted American Dream</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, His speech, to UPDATE with speech
delivered; new grafs 6-9 to UPDATE with new material from news
conference</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis said Thursday the Reagan administration has ``walked away
from the American dream'' with policies to help the rich at the
expense of working people.
   ``I'm running for president because during the past seven years
I've seen too many people thrown out into the streets after decades
on the job. ... I've talked to too many local leaders who've seen
their communities become ghost towns of boarded up hopes and
foreclosed dreams,'' the Massachusetts governor said.
   His speech at Serb Hall, a traditional rallying spot for
presidential hopefuls in Wisconsin, came with polls suggesting
Dukakis is in a virtual dead heat with Jesse Jackson heading into
Tuesday's primary.
   Jackson has been making a strong pitch in Wisconsin to
blue-collar workers, asking them to support him as he supported
striking meatpackers and paperworkers as well as Kenosha
autoworkers about to lose their jobs because of a plant closing.
   While hitting hard at the Reagan administration, Dukakis
refrained from criticizing other Democratic candidates. One day
earlier, he had spoken in general terms of his differences with
Jackson and then had criticized Gore for demanding he be more
specific.
   At a news conference after the speech, Dukakis, responding to
questions, said he felt he was better qualified than Jackson to be
president because of his experience as a governor of Massachusetts.
But he stopped well short of criticizing Jackson.
   Dukakis also called for the resignation of Attorney General
Edwin Meese III.
   Asked why he felt he was better qualified than Jackson, Dukakis
said: ``I think I am going to be a better president because I think
I have the strength, the experience and the values to lead this
country, because I am somebody who not only believes in good jobs
and good wages for people, I've helped to create them.''
   In his speech, Dukakis reserved his criticism for the Reagan
White House.
   ``This administration has walked away from the American dream,''
Dukakis said Thursday. ``They've walked away from the basic
contract that says if you work hard and pay your taxes and live
within the law, you have a right to a good job; and the right to a
life where you don't have to go to bed every night worried about
whether that job will still be there in the morning.''
   Dukakis said the Reagan administration has done nothing to move
people from welfare to jobs, to fight adult illiteracy, to preserve
good-paying jobs or to provide adequate health care to the needy.
   He said he is running for president ``because I believe that
every American should have a house _ not a slab of concrete or a
heating grate _ that they can call home.''
   Dukakis also promised what he called a real war on drug and
alcohol dependency and asked, ``How can we tell our children to say
no to drugs when this administration can't say no to one of the
largest drug peddlers in this hemisphere?'' _ an apparent reference
to Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
</TEXT>
