<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Gore     03-31 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,1st Ld-Writethru, a0771,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Calls For Meese Removal, Defends Criticism of Jackson</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 7 grafs, Gore on Meese, picks up 3rd graf pvs,
bgng: ``Forty makes</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Albert Gore Jr. defended his
criticism of rival Jesse Jackson on Thursday and took issue with
Michael Dukakis for being ``afraid to say a single word about Jesse
Jackson.'' Later, he called for the removal of Attorney General
Edwin Meese.
   At a Florida fundraiser, Gore said the attorney general should
step down because it is ``time to remove the cloud over the
Department of Justice.''
   ``How long will it take this administration to understand the
importance of integrity in government?'' Gore asked a crowd at the
posh Grove Isle resort. ``We cannot tolerate a situation where the
nation's chief law enforcement officer is constantly testifying as
a suspect before grand juries, constantly operating under a cloud
of suspicion.''
   The Tennessee senator pointed to the departure of top Justice
Department officials and reports that they had quit because they
believed Meese was hurting the department by staying on.
   ``President Reagan and Vice President Bush say, `Oh, it's no bid
deal. There are resignations all the time.' What insensitivity!
What contempt for the American people!'' said Gore.
   The Gore campaign raised about $108,000 at the Florida event,
said Mitchell Berger, one of the organizers.
   Earlier, Gore commented after a Capitol Hill celebration marking
his 40th birthday, an event that came as a relief to the candidate
who has grown weary of answering questions about running for
president while still in his 30s.
   ``Forty makes all the difference,'' he said.
   Gore reacted to questions at a news conference about his remarks
on Monday in New York, when he criticized Jackson as without
experience and said he was dismayed by the candidate's associations
with PLO leader Yasser Arafat and Cuban President Fidel Castro.
   Gore said that by his criticism he was holding Jackson, the
civil rights activist, to the same standard as other candidates.
   ``I've said exactly the same thing I've said over the last year,
and all of a sudden it's a big deal,'' Gore said. ``Well, the only
reason it seems to some people like a big deal is that Mike Dukakis
is afraid to say a single word about Jesse Jackson.''
   Dukakis, however, began cautiously speaking of differences
between himself and Jackson on the Middle East and domestic policy
on Wednesday. Dukakis said ``from time to time differences will
arise ... and those will come out over time.''
   Dukakis and Jackson have won the most Democratic delegates so
far, with Gore in third place.
   The Tennesse senator spoke to reporters in the sunshine in front
of the Capitol after joining in a birthday celebration in a Senate
office building.
   ``You know, Jack Benny was perpetually 39,'' Gore said. ``I've
been doing a kind of reverse Jack Benny in this campaign _ I've
been trying to turn 40.''
   Gore planned to spend the next four days campaigning in
Wisconsin before Tuesday's primary there.
   His campaign began airing a new television ad in that state
attacking Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca for closing the
Chrysler assembly plant in Kenosha. It shows Gore stating that
Iacocca was paid $20 million in 1986. ``I'll make these
corporations pay their share of the taxes and create jobs here in
America,'' Gore said in the ad.
   Gore was asked about his criticism of Jackson a day after his
rival said Gore's comments amounted to a personal attack and
canceled a meeting between the two. Gore called that
characterization ridiculous, and he faulted Dukakis for what he
termed a ``ludicrous'' hesitancy to engage Jackson in debate or
criticism.
   Gore is still trying to restart his campaign in the North, where
he has failed to duplicate his Southern success _ or even to
register in double-digits in the Illinois primary and Michigan
caucuses.
   He reacted strongly when asked by a questioner whether he has
been privately encouraged to rop out of the presidential race in
order to stop splitting the white vote _ a question that suggested
Jackson was profiting by the battle between Gore and Dukakis.
   Gore said the ``question has a racial if not racist premise.''
He said he had not been so urged and called it inappropriate to
talk about such racial divisions.
</TEXT>
