<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Africans-Marijuana     03-31 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Africans-Marijuana,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kenyan Ex-President's Nephew Fined $5,000 In Pot Importation
Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nephew of Kenya's founding president has
been fined $5,000 and credited for time served for his role in a
1,900-pound marijuana importation conspiracy.
   ``For your greed, you ... have failed your government and
certainly your family,'' U.S. District Judge Alfred M. Wolin said
Wednesday in sentencing Samuel Muigai, 36, nephew of Kenya's first
president Jomo Kenyatta.
   Muigai walked away a free man after paying the fine and serving
more than five months in jail since his arrest in October on
charges of conspiring to import the marijuana. Three co-defendants
were sentenced to prison.
   Muigai pleaded guilty to conspiring to import an unspecified
quantity of the drug, which carries a maximum term of five years in
prison.
   Wolin, who sentenced two Kenyan co-defendants to six years in
prison and a third to nine years for their guilty pleas, found that
Muigai played a ``truly passive'' role ``limited to greed,'' in the
scheme.
   A fifth Kenyan, millionaire arms dealer and land developer
Stephen Mwangi, 49, was found innocent after a trial earlier this
month. A Ugandan defendant, Mpigi Kabasha Mbogo, 39, is to be
sentenced Monday.
   The six men were arrested after they traveled to Gloucester
City, where the pot had just arrived aboard a ship. They were to be
paid $1 million in the deal, negotiated through undercover agents
in telephone calls to Kenya.
   Though Muigai's crime was an ``affront to the people of the
United States,'' Wolin said he was satisfied Muigai was remorseful
and had learned a ``bitter lesson.'' He also took note that Muigai
was the first to plead guilty.
   Muigai, dressed in a gray pin-stripped suit and white loafers,
apologized for his involvement in what he called an ``unfortunate
incident.''
   ``I would like to assure you, sir, that I don't intend and I
don't think I will ever stand in another court of law for charges
of any sort of criminal activity,'' he told the judge.
   Muiga's his attorneys argued that Muigai's co-defendants invited
him to meet with wealthy American businessmen interested in
developing some of his property.
   Even after learning the discussions with the ``businessmen,''
who turned out to be federal agents, concerned marijuana, Muigai
went along, hoping still to discuss the land deal, the court papers
said.
   The stiffest sentence, nine years, went to Steven Thuku, who
Wolin determined was the principal in the deal for making the
contacts with the sources of the marijuana and the other defendants.
   Wolin found that Geoffrey M. Tumbo, 45, and Daniel M. Githegi,
36, had less culpability and gave them six-year prison terms.
   They pleaded guilty to conspiring to import more than 110 pounds
of marijuana, a charge carrying a 20-year maximum penalty.
</TEXT>
