<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Wallach-Chinn 1stLd-Writethru a0910 03-31 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wallach-Chinn, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0910,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Friend: Should Have Been More Sensitive To Appearance Of
Impropriety</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 2nd graf to show that interview published Thursday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III's friend
E. Robert Wallach says he should have been more sensitive to an
appearance of impropriety in helping Meese set up a financial
partnership with an investment manager who wound up on the board of
Wedtech Corp.
   In an interview published Thursday in the San Jose (Calif.)
Mercury News, Wallach said that he ``missed the boat completely''
on the potential conflict of interest in linking Meese with the
investment manager, W. Franklyn Chinn of San Francisco in May 1985.
   Meese knew at the time that Chinn was doing work for Wedtech.
Chinn subsequently become a member of Wedtech board of directors.
   Wallach and Chinn were indicted in December on racketeering
charges for allegedly extracting payments from Wedtech as part of a
scheme to influence Meese and other public officials to assist the
defense contractor.
   In 1981 and 1982, Wallach wrote Meese a dozen memos urging the
then-White House counselor's support for the Bronx, N.Y. defense
contractor. Meese interceded on Wedtech's behalf in connection with
the company's efforts to get a $32 million no-bid contract to build
small engines for the army. Wedtech ended up wining the contract in
1982.
   ``I just missed the boat completely on the Wedtech connection,''
Wallach said, referring to the potential for a conflict of
interest. ``Wedtech at the time was just an irrelevancy.
   ``I knew that my memos (to Meese) had had nothing to do with the
award of the (Wedtech) contract in 1982. ... We (Wallach and Meese)
were trapped by our own honest conduct. We never thought of
Wedtech. ... Our state of mind in April '85 was, we had not played
a major role in Wedtech.''
   Wallach also insisted that neither he nor Meese was aware of
memos in 1981 and 1982 from then White House counsel Fred Fielding
warning Meese's top deputy and other administration officials not
to intercede in Wedtech's military contract discussions because of
ethical and procedural considerations.
   ``On reflection, a more cautious approach on my part would have
been wise,'' said Wallach. ``A more cautious approach on his
(Meese's) part would have been wise.''
   In the interview with the San Jose newspaper, Wallach also said
Meese had ``nothing absolutely'' to do with a $150,000 payment to
Wallach in 1985 in connection with a $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline
deal.
   The $150,000 was a legal fee to Wallach by one of his clients,
Swiss oilman Bruce Rappaport, a partner in the pipeline project.
   The $150,000 wound up in a stock trading account owned by Chinn
and the money was, in effect, pooled with that of other investors,
including Meese, to generate profits in highly speculative stock
trading of brand new stock issues which were bought and sold on the
same day.
   Under this arrangement, Chinn turned a $40,000 profit for Meese
on a $50,000 investment in just 18 months.
   The pooling of money from Chinn's various investors, including
Meese, helped the financial manager obtain the funds to get new
stock issues. It would have been difficult for Chinn to obtain the
new issues of stock with Meese's money alone.
   Wallach said that when all of the facts are known, his and
Chinn's handling of the $150,000 originally paid to Wallach will
emerge as ``the classic bureaucratic error.'' He declined to
elaborate.
   Wallach said the main reason he introduced Meese to Chinn was
because Meese stood to make more money investing with Chinn than
with more conventional institutions.
   ``I probably was influenced disproportionately by Frank's
offering a high return,'' Wallach said.
   ``Should I have been more prudent and recommended him (Meese) to
a more major investment firm?'' Wallach asked. ``In retrospect,
yes.''
</TEXT>
