<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OtherKillings     03-31 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Other Killings,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chambers Case Vs. Other Murders: A Tale Of Two Worlds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are at least four men in New York prisons
who have something in common with a new inmate, Robert Chambers:
They all killed somebody in New York City on Aug. 26, 1986.
   But the similarities end there. Unlike the killer of Jennifer
Levin, they are serving their time in obscurity. No camera-wielding
mobs hounded them when they surrendered, no tabloids splashed their
names in headlines.
   All four cases were in the impoverished South Bronx, uptown from
the grassy spot in Central Park where the former prep school
student killed Miss Levin, from the bar on Manhattan's East Side
patronized by Chambers, Miss Levin and other affluent young people.
   ``It isn't fair,'' said Angel Traverso, 16, a neighbor of one of
the victims, Rosa Dueno, 44. ``They make such a big deal out of
Jennifer Levin's death and Rosa's death means nothing.''
   Chambers, 21, started a five- to 15-year sentence Saturday for
killing Miss Levin, 18, during what he initially called an episode
of ``rough sex.'' The day before, while a jury deliberated murder
charges against him, he pleaded guilty to first-degree manslaughter.
   Chambers and the other defendants all killed people they knew,
and they were arrested quickly. Three of the four Bronx killers
pleaded guilty after bargaining with prosecutors, as Chambers did.
   But none went through the protracted litigation that Chambers
did, and all but one are serving longer sentences.
   The one who received a lighter term was Ms. Dueno's killer, Juan
Enrique. He had a history of beating Ms. Dueno, who was his
girlfriend, and on Aug. 26, 1986, he stabbed her to death.
   He was never charged with murder. He pleaded guilty to
second-degree manslaughter and was sentenced May 19 to
two-and-a-third to seven years in prison.
   In a city that averages about five homicides a day, the deaths
of Ms. Dueno and the others were largely unnoticed. The disposition
of the cases went unnoticed as well:
   _ Santos Cuello Valdez, charged with second-degree murder for
shooting Daniel Alvarez to death, pleaded guilty last May 14 to
first-degree manslaughter. Justice Elbert Hinkson sentenced him on
June 26 to seven to 21 years in prison.
   _ A grand jury charged Juan Quinones with second-degree murder
in the stabbing of Rachel Pajooh, 48. She allegedly had shot at him
once when he tried to rob her and had reported him to police. After
a non-jury trial, Justice Lawrence Bernstein convicted Quinones of
first-degree manslaughter and sentenced him on Oct. 7, 1987, to 12{
to 25 years in prison.
   _ Ronald Matthews, indicted on a charge of second-degree murder
after he smashed his father's head with a sledgehammer, pleaded
guilty to first-degree manslaughter and was sentenced by Justice
Ivan Warner on Oct. 13 to six to 18 years in prison.
   There is no indication as to whether the families of the victims
were consulted when the guilty pleas were negotiated; prosecutors
gave the Levin family the right to veto their agreement with
Chambers.
   And no news conferences were called when the Bronx cases were
wrapped up.
   Ed McCarthy, a spokesman for the Bronx district attorney's
office, said the assistant district attorneys who prosecuted the
cases were not available to discuss them, or to compare them with
the more celebrated case in Manhattan.
   ``It's apples and oranges,'' he said. ``What happened there,
happened there. What happens here, happens here.''
</TEXT>
