<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APArts:Babette'sFeast     03-31 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Babette's Feast,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feast for the Body Follows One for the Mind</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY MacVEAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For $2 or so, you can hungrily cradle a barrel
of popcorn while watching characters in ``Babette's Feast'' ravish
blini with black caviar, quail stuffed with foie gras and other
magnificent morsels in what has to be one of the most inspiring
meals ever shown on the screen.
   For $88 more, you can follow this feast for the eyes with one
for the body.
   ``One thing will happen after you see this movie: You will be
starving,'' said Dro E. Proudian, general manager at Petrossian
Inc., whose restaurant is one of several around the the country
serving the seven-course feast during the run of the movie,
Denmark's entry for an Academy Award as best foreign film.
   ``When you see the film, how complicated the meal is, how
expensive, all the marketing,'' there will be a greater
understanding of the art of preparing a great meal, said Yannick
Cam, chef and owner at Le Pavillion in Washington, which begins
serving the feast in April.
   The movie, based on a story by Isak Dinesen, tells of two
unmarried and pious sisters who take a French political refugee,
Babette, into their home on the bleak coast of Norway, in return
for housekeeping. Fourteen years later, when Babette wins 10,000
francs in the lottery, she repays them with a feast so strange to
them that one sister, in anticipation, compares it to a witch's
sabbath.
   But Babette fills the hearts, as well as the bellies, of her 12
guests, mostly members of the sisters' religious community.
   ``It was a whole experience, that's why we did it,'' said Stella
Geller of West Orange, N.J., who with her husband followed the film
with dinner recently at Petrossian. ``I didn't leave a bite of
anything. I ate every bite.''
   So far, plans have been made for the feast at restaurants in
Philadelphia, Miami, Los Angeles, Washington, San Francisco and
Laguna Niguel, Calif., according to Alfred Rosenthal, Orion
Classics' gastronomic consultant for the dinners. Prices will vary
slightly, with $80 the lowest, without wines, he said.
   That will buy: turtle soup; blini with black caviar; quail
stuffed with foie gras baked in a pastry nest with truffle sauce;
salad; cheeses; rum cake with candied fruit; fresh fruit; coffee.
Add $35 for four wines.
   As the movie opens in more cities, theater owners and
restaurateurs can use a guide written by Rosenthal to help them
present the feast and find such ingredients as turtle meat.
   While the meal is expensive, Proudian called it a bargain,
noting the normal prices of just three ingredients: 30 grams of
fresh Russian Sevruga caviar ($21); 2{ ounces of fresh foie gras
($15); three-quarters of an ounce of black truffle ($30).
   ``The people who come here are adventurous, a lot of romantic
people,'' Proudian said in a recent interview at Petrossian, a
mirrored and marbled restaurant near Carnegie Hall.
   To meet their expectations and recreate the sense of abundance
evident on Babette's table, he said, ``the caviar has to be
heaping, you have to see the truffles, not just a speck here, a
slice there. When you put your knife into the quail, you have to
feel the foie gras.''
   ``It was extraordinarily difficult, because we had to recreate a
visual image on a plate,'' he said.
   Petrossian's chef, Michel Attali, said he encountered one
problem. In the film, the quail is served sitting in its pastry
nest with the head on. Believing that would not be acceptable here,
Attali fashioned pastry ``heads'' for the tiny game birds.
   But no matter how faithful, diners will not experience the same
mood as in the film, Cam said: ``First the house in the film, and
it was a little religious dinner. I don't think we can reproduce
that.''
   Still, Proudian said, ``The star of the movie is the food. So if
you are in this business, it's nice to see all of this dignity and
respect given to the preparation of food.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
