<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0107EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Nicaragua Bjt   03-31 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Nicaragua, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Reagan and Ortega Battle to a Draw</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It looks more and more as though President
Reagan will leave office without achieving his stated goal of
making Daniel Ortega say ``Uncle.''
   In the view of many Latin American experts, Reagan's policy of
keeping the pressure on Ortega's Nicaraguan government to bring
about peace and democracy has failed.
   ``You have peace, but you don't have freedom,'' says Neil
Pickett, an expert on national and international security affairs
at the Hudson Institute in Indianapolis.
   ``They're about to leave office, and they've got a Contra
program that's falling apart on them,'' says Ed King, Latin
American adviser to Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd.
   As G. Pope Atkins, senior associate specializing in South
American affairs at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, sees it, the stated goal of the policy has kept shifting.
   ``The first one was simply to interdict Nicaraguan arms to El
Salvador,'' Atkins said. ``Then it was rather strongly implied that
the idea was to bring down the regime. And now the idea is that if
they (Nicaragua's leaders) will change, everything will be all
right.''
   Marlin Fitzwater, the president's chief spokesman, says the
administration's goal remains the same: ``The situation is that we
need aid to the Contras in the worst way.''
   But questions remain whether Wednesday's House vote to continue
non-lethal aid and leave the door open for military aid, and the
expected Senate vote today, will help further Reagan's objectives.
   Reagan has said his goal is to keep pressure on the Sandinistas
so they will live up to the promises of democratic reform that they
made when they took over from dictator Anastasio Somoza in 1979.
   At a news conference Feb. 21, 1985, Reagan was asked whether he
was advocating the overthrow of the Nicaraguan government. His
reply was: ``Not if the present government would turn around and
... say, `Uncle. All right, come back into the revolutionary
government, and let's straighten this out and institute the
goals.'''
   Now that the two sides have agreed on a cease-fire, will
Nicaragua's Marxist-led Sandinista government reform? And if it
doesn't, can the Contra rebels the Reagan administration has backed
survive as an effective force?
   Many think not.
   ``I think it would be awfully difficult to reorganize them,''
said Atkins. ``I doubt if they would be particularly interested in
that. I don't think they would want to go through the convolutions
of U.S. policy again.''
   King added that ``it's over for the time being unless the
Sandinistas back up on what they say they are going to do, and have
done, and the Contras change their orientation from where they are,
which is: let's get some kind of political opening going.''
   Pickett, too, sees ``the end of the resistance'' in the latest
developments, ``barring some miracle or barring some violation
before the truce is signed.''
   ``If the Sandinistas do something stupid before that, the
Contras can be saved,'' he said.
   King, the adviser to Byrd, said: ``The objective of the whole
exercise in the beginning was to protect U.S. security concerns in
the region. U.S. security concerns in the region are removal of the
Soviet and the Cuban advisers, guarantees of no bases, reduction of
Soviet weapons and guarantees of no border crossing.
   ``Now they are at a point where they don't have any of those
things arranged, they're about to leave office, and they've got a
Contra program that's falling apart on them,'' King said. ``I think
the whole thing is a disaster, frankly.''
   The less partisan sources are not calling it a disaster, but
they aren't proclaiming it a success either.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   W. Dale Nelson covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
