<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FederalSpending     03-31 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federal Spending,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Spending: $3,433 Per Person</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska continues to lead the nation in per
capita federal spending, but Virginia is closing in, new federal
figures show.
   The U.S. government spent about $5,421 per resident in Alaska
last year, making it the leading state in per capita spending.
   But second-place Virginia _ which moved up from third a year
earlier _ wasn't far behind at $5,317 per capita, according to the
Census Bureau.
   That $104 per capita difference in spending between the states
was down from a $246 spread in 1986.
   Maryland, which had been second in 1986, dropped to third place
with 1987 spending of $5,113.
   Both Maryland and Virginia benefit from their location adjacent
to the nation's capital. Many federal agencies have offices in the
suburbs, which also are home for consultants and suppliers of goods
for the government.
   If it were a state, the District of Columbia would easily lead
in per capita spending, averaging $23,360.
   Nationwide, federal spending averaged nearly $3,433 per American
last year, about $41 more than the year before.
   The report, ``Federal Expenditures by State for Fiscal Year
1987,'' broke down spending totaling $848 billion, covering
virtually everything except interest on the national debt.
   Direct payments to people was the largest share, totaling $384
billion. That includes Social Security, Medicare, food stamps and
other such programs.
   Buying goods and services was second, with $196 billion spent.
Salaries for federal employees totaled $127 billion, with $108
billion sent out to state and local governments and $33 billion
spent on research grants, agriculture subsidies and various other
purposes.
   Per capita, that amounts to $1,555 paid to individuals; $795 in
procurement; $514 in salaries; $437 in grants to state and local
government and other spending of $133.
   Alaska's top finish included high levels of aid to state and
local governments as well as pay for federal employees, but it was
way down the list in payments to individuals.
   Florida topped that category, with Social Security and Medicare
benefits for its large elderly population raising the state's
average.
   California was easily the leader in total federal spending, with
its large population, military bases and industry helping bring in
$100.7 billion. Even so, the Golden State finished only 14th in per
capita spending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MilitaryPurchases     03-31 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Military Purchases,410</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6 a.m. EST, Time set by source.</NOTE>
<HEAD>GAO Cites Weaknesses in Military Purchasing Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional investigators say the Defense
Logistics Agency should tighten controls over its ``fast-pay''
program to avoid paying for supplies that are never delivered.
   According to a General Accounting Office report released today,
one DLA purchasing office failed to take action to ensure
collection of more than $7 million in overpayments.
   ``I'm appalled that DLA is paying money for supplies that it
never received,'' said Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, who, along with
Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., released the GAO report. ``We need
sound business management at DLA.''
   The agency purchases food, clothing, fuel oil and other supplies
for the armed services.
   Under the fast-pay program, the agency pays vendors based on
shipping invoices instead of verifying receipt of the supplies. The
procedure is designed to expedite payments for small purchases.
   ``Internal controls established by the DLA purchasing offices do
not prevent possible fast-pay program abuse,'' said the GAO, the
investigative arm of Congress. ``Potential missing depot shipments
are not always detected for timely follow-up and resolution.''
   The GAO said that in 52 fast-pay shipments valued at $71,267 to
the Defense Electronics Supply Center in Dayton, Ohio, the center
could not document the receipt of 16 shipments valued at $18,618.
In addition, the center failed to notify some of the vendors of the
missing shipments within 90 days.
   It also said action had not been taken as of last May to collect
more than $7 million in previously identified overpayments owed the
Defense Personnel Support Center in Philadelphia.
   The GAO also said that vendors with performance problems on
previous contracts have continued to receive fast-pay awards and
that controls have not been established to ensure the receipt of
supplies sent directly from vendors to overseas locations.
   In 1985, the Office of Management and Budget issued instructions
to limit the use of fast pay, saying it should not be used to
replace stocks in depots or when timely payment can be made. The
GAO said DLA believes it is not required to follow the requirements
until they are incorporated into the Federal Acquisition
Regulations.
   However, DLA spokesman Larry Wilson said the agency plans to be
in compliance with the OMB requirements by the end of the year even
though it is expected to cost an additional $2.5 million to process
the extra paperwork.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
