<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirControllers     03-31 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Controllers,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes To Rehire Some Controllers Fired In 1981</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation calling for the rehiring of 1,000
air traffic controllers fired nearly seven years ago has won strong
approval in the House, although the Senate has yet to consider a
similar bill.
   The Reagan administration has steadfastly refused to rehire any
of the 11,400 controllers who were fired after they walked off
their jobs in 1981. The Transportation Department has urged that
such legislation be vetoed by President Reagan if it clears
Congress.
   The 234-180 House vote Wednesday calling for some of the fired
controllers to return to the Federal Aviation Administration came
two years after similar legislation was defeated by a 193-226
margin.
   Supporters of the legislation argued that there are too few
controllers to handle air traffic needs, especially at some of the
busiest towers and traffic control centers, and that the former
controllers could become fully trained more quickly than trainees
off the street.
   Rep. Guy Molinari, sponsor of the House resolution, said a
selected number of fired controllers should be rehired by the FAA
``for the sake of safety and the convenience of the flying public.''
   ``Today it's clearer than ever that the air traffic control
system is still severely strained,'' Molinari, R-N.Y., said during
floor debate. The legislation calls for selectively hiring 500 of
the fired controllers this year and another 500 next fiscal year.
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, has estimated that as many as 6,000 of the 11,400 former
controllers still have an interest in returning to the FAA. Under
the legislation the FAA would be free to select the controllers it
wants to rehire.
   The FAA has steadily been increasing its controller workforce
and now has 14,450 controllers at various experience levels,
compared with 16,375 before the 1981 strike. The Transportation
Department plans to hire another 1,350 over the next 1{ years.
   While support for rehiring at least some of the fired
controllers was widespread, some congressmen continued to have deep
concerns about such a move.
   ``Putting the strikers and their replacements in the same
control tower is sure to create animosity between the two
factions,'' suggested Rep. John Paul Hammerschmidt, R-Ark.
   Rep. Gerald Solomon, R-N.Y., said the legislastion is ``sending
the wrong message'' to government workers and their unions. ``The
right to fire illegal strikers must not be compromised,'' Solomon
declared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
