<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignNotebook     03-31 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Notebook,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Road With Bush: Tongue Twisters and Bowling Technique</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Audiences seem to know what he means, but Vice
President George Bush doesn't always get the words out exactly
right as he campaigned this week in Wisconsin.
   During an appearance at Lawrence Univeristy in Appleton, Wis.,
the Republican presidential candidate told his audience, ``I want
to be the education president.''
   ``There is a need for help at the federal level ... so you can
afford to send your college to children,'' Bush declared.
   At another time in the same speech, he meant to talk about the
``high cost of college,'' but it came out: ``the high cost of
courage.''
   Speaking to a rally in a Milwaukee suburb, Bush appeared to
invent a new federal tax on farmers, declaring he favored a lower
``capital grains tax.''
   No doubt, he was referring to the capital gains tax. Bush has
urged a partial repeal of the part of the 1987 tax overhaul law
that taxes capital gains _ such as from the sale of a house, stocks
or business assets _ at the same level as other income.
   Bush's verbal tongue-twisting seems to be catching.
   Introducing the vice president at another Milwaukee-area
function, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson asserted: ``As the Reagan
presidency ends, it's time for the Bush pregnancy to begin.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   As he campaigned in the area, Bush was repeatedly reminded by
local reporters of a previous campaign visit here, when he went to
a Milwaukee bowling alley _ and wound up sprawled on the lane.
Questions like ``Plan to do any bowling this time?'' have abounded.
   ``You have a good memory,'' he told one inqusitor.
   ``I did fall down. But so did nine pins,'' he said in defense of
his technique.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   At an aviation musuem in Oshkosh, Bush was presented with a
brown leather aviator's jacket and he climbed readily into the
cockpit of a 1949 Bearcat fighter.
   The plane was billed as similar to one he had flown as a Navy
pilot during World War II, a past his campaign strategists would
like to have remembered as often as possible.
   Well, it wasn't exactly like the kind of planes he used to fly,
``but it has the same engine,'' Bush said.
   Then Bush, who frequently has posed on and in various kinds of
heavy equipment during his campaign, held his right arm over his
head and flashed a ``V'' sign for photographers.
   ``Is this the Red Baron look?'' he asked.
   Then Bush was led to a full-scale replica of the Voyager, the
lightweight plane that set a record for flying non-stop around the
world.
   ``I'm anxious to learn about this,'' Bush said. ``This looks
like it may be a little tough.''
   He elaborated further. ``There's the inevitable question,'' he
said. ``How does one go to the bathroom?''
</TEXT>
