<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PresidentialYacht     03-31 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Yacht,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Yacht, Rescued from Oblivion, on National Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The restored presidential yacht USS Sequoia is
making a national tour before being returned once again to the
president of the United States after an 11-year hiatus.
   The Sequoia, which was sold in 1977 by President Carter as part
of an austerity move, has been repaired by a private group. It was
launched Wednesday on a 100-city, 22-state tour that will enable
thousands to see the vessel before it is officially returned to the
White House Nov. 15.
   ``What we have here is a Fourth of July celebration every
weekend in cities throughout the country,'' said Michael McGehee, a
member of the group that raised money to repair the 105-foot yacht.
``We're taking a piece of American history to the American people.''
   Private and corporate funding paid for the Sequoia's
restoration, and Josh Lanier, who chairs the nine-member
Presidential Yacht Trust's board of trustees, hopes the tour will
raise money for an endowment to pay for the ship's upkeep.
   ``This tour is a little like running a campaign,'' he joked.
``We have a good candidate, no opposition, and we're confident she
won't screw up on the evening news.''
   The Sequoia was built in 1925 and sold to the Commerce
Department in 1931. In 1933, after President Hoover wintered on it
in Florida, the Sequoia was acquired by the Navy and became the
president's official yacht.
   Over the next 44 years, the Sequoia served eight presidents. It
was the site of talks on nuclear controls during the Truman
administration, the venue of gala celebrations by President Kennedy
and the place where President Nixon told his family in 1974 that he
would resign the presidency.
   In 1977, as part of a widespread retrenchment program, Carter
directed that the vessel be sold. It was purchased for $286,000 by
a group of private investors.
   Over the next four years, the craft changed hands three times
and began to deteriorate. In 1981, a private trust was established
to purchase and restore the boat.
   After reading news accounts in 1983 about the boat's dilapidated
condition, Lanier, a former aide to Sen. Herman Talmadge, D-Ga.,
joined the effort to refurbish the craft.
   ``I remember thinking it was a crying shame that this boat had
fallen on such bad times, because I remember how it was used in the
Nixon and Ford administrations,'' he said.
   Minor repairs were made, and a little-publicized, 16-state tour
during the summer of 1984 drew surprisingly large crowds.
   ``Everyone told us it was a mistake for the federal government
to have sold the Sequoia,'' Lanier said. ``We then started raising
money for a full restoration, with the intention of returning the
vessel to the office of the president.''
   In June 1986, a six-month, $3.5 million restoration was
completed, and the Sequoia sailed to New York for the Statue of
Liberty centennial celebration. Since then, the Sequoia has been
moored in Washington and used for government functions.
   The Sequoia's tour will include ports in Virginia, South
Carolina and Florida in April, and to Gulf Coast cities in Alabama,
Louisiana and Texas in May. It then will sail up the Mississippi
River in June and July, stopping at ports in Mississippi, Arkansas,
Tennessee, Missouri, Illinois and Michigan.
   After visiting Great Lakes ports in August, the Sequoia will
stop at cities between Boston and Baltimore in September. The tour
will end Oct. 30 in Alexandria, Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
