<HEAD>Soviet Team Visits British Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COMBWICH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four officials from the Soviet Union
made the first-ever visit by a Soviet delegation to a British
nuclear plant.
   The Soviet nuclear power officials, who are on an official
four-day visit to Britain this week, have been discussing with
their British counterparts methods of making nuclear power stations
safer.
   The delegation, led by Vadim M. Malyshev, chairman of the Soviet
State Committee on Supervision of Nuclear Power Safety, was given a
tour Wednesday of Hinkley Point station near Combwich in Somerset,
in southwest England.
   Malyshev told reporters Monday the Soviet Union is designing new
nuclear reactors since the April 1986 disaster at the Chernobyl
plant in the Ukraine, which killed 31 people and sent radiation
drifting over Europe.
