<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dole     03-31 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dole,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Wants To Remain Senate GOP Leader After 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole says he gave no serious thought
to quitting politics after his presidential campaign fizzled and
will try to keep his Republican leadership post in the next session
of Congress.
   ``I don't have any regrets,'' Dole said Wednesday in an
interview a day after he exited the GOP presidential race. ``I
think obviously you don't like to lose. But I think it probably
strengthens my convictions about politics and that you can make a
difference.''
   Relaxed in his Capitol office, Dole still expressed frustration
with his inability to blunt Vice President George Bush's success in
running as the heir apparent to President Reagan.
   Dole maintained that was the main reason for his downfall _ not
what he conceded were several tactical mistakes by his campaign.
   ``The bottom line is you can't beat Ronald Reagan,'' Dole said.
``I was running against Ronald Reagan Jr. in the South.''
   Added Dole, ``It's just this promotion idea that you just ought
to go up the ladder.''
   Republican Party ``winner-take-all'' rules in the primaries and
caucuses also contributed to his exit from the race, Dole said. If
delegates were divided proportionally, he said, ``I'd still be in
the race.''
   Although disappointed with the outcome of his presidential bid,
Dole said he was committed to serving out his full six-year term in
the Senate, which ends in 1992. In addition, he said he would seek
to remain the Republican leader when the Senate reorganizesafter
this fall's elections.
   ``I don't have anybody threatening me,'' Dole said. ``Pretty
tough precinct, but I think we're in good shape.''
   In analyzing the GOP presidential race, Dole conceded that his
campaign organization had blundered, particularly in New Hampshire
and South Carolina, and that those mistakes weakened his candidacy
early in the nominating process.
   The campaign, for example, did not respond to last-minute
television ads by Bush raising questions about whether Dole would
increase taxes. His campaign spent heavily early in the nominating
process, which caused problems in later contests.
   ``Now had we won New Hampshire, we still would have had a tough
race,'' Dole said.
   ``South Carolina we probably should have bypassed instead of
getting in there,'' he added.
   He said Bush's win in South Carolina helped boost the vice
president to a sweep of the Super Tuesday primaries in the South,
including North Carolina, Missouri and Oklahoma _ states the Dole
campaign had hoped to win.
   After Super Tuesday came Illinois. Dole said, ``I knew that we
weren't going to win Illinois and I knew then it was probably
over.''
   The campaign, he said, would end with a ``little debt'' but he
didn't know the exact amount. He also expressed reservations about
the management of the campaign, saying: ``I think as far as
organization, I'm not certain whether we had enough direction.''
   Asked what he would do differently, Dole replied: ``Keep the
press off the plane.''
   A contingent of reporters traveled on the same plane as Dole and
the senator said he thought he had received some unfair coverage
during the campaign.
   For example, Dole singled out the numerous stories written about
one of his Kansas associates, Dave Owen, who resigned as national
finance chairman of the Dole campaign in January after reports
raised questions involving his financial dealings.
   Dole complained that reporters on the campaign plane ``sit back
there and they scheme up these little things and the next thing
they're in Time or Newsweek.''
</TEXT>
