<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     03-31 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says His Record Makes Him More Qualified</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis says he does
not intend to use negative campaigning to win the Democratic
presidential nomination over his primary rival, Jesse Jackson.
   Dukakis commented after another Democratic hopeful, Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. of Tennessee, criticized Jackson for his lack of
experience in government.
   ``We can discuss issues without attacking each other,'' Dukakis
said Wednesday. ``(The voters) don't want to know what Gore thinks
of Jackson.''
   Dukakis said his record as governor separates him from the other
candidates and gives him the best chance of beating Republican
candidate Vice President George Bush in November.
   ``I respect the other candidates,'' he said. ``But obviously I'm
in this to win. And I believe I have the best chance to beat Mr.
Bush in the fall.''
   This sentiment was echoed by Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., who
announced his endorsement of Dukakis.
   ``Michael Dukakis has the best chance to unify the party and win
the White House for the Democrats in November,'' Obey said.
   Jackson has emerged as Dukakis' main challenger after last
weekend's win in the Michigan caucuses. Dukakis responded with a
big win Tuesday in the Connecticut primary, and all the Democratic
candidates are aiming at the Wisconsin primary Tuesday, along with
Colorado's caucuses on Monday.
   Dukakis, asked whether he lacks the passionate campaign style
used by Jackson, said: ``I don't want to go down as a great
communicator. There's no question my strength is as a doer. I want
to be a great builder.''
   Dukakis spoke earlier in the evening to students at Marquette
University, where he gave a detailed discussion of his views on
Central America.
   ``I want to help build a Central America ... where our energy
and our resources are devoted to building and educating and
investing, not killing and sabotaging and tearing down,'' he said.
   Dukakis said while the United States must respond ``firmly and
forcefully'' to any attempts by one country to subvert another, he
added that too often America has ``shown our neighbors a fist when
they needed a helping hand.''
   Dukakis said he is encouraged by the negotiations between the
Nicaraguan Sandinistas and Contra rebels, and he would push all
parties to meet the obligations under the peace plan of Costa Rican
President Oscar Arias.
</TEXT>
