<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingEinstein     03-31 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Einstein,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Einstein Page Of Notes Recovered; Teen Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police recovered a page of notes written by
Albert Einstein that had been taken from a University of Texas
display case, and arrested the grandson of former football coach
Darrell Royal.
   An investigator said the page of handwritten notes was found
Tuesday at the home of 18-year-old Samuel K. Royal. Royal was
arrested Wednesday evening, said university police Lt. Ronald
Thomas.
   The page was reported missing last week from a locked glass
display case in a campus building. It was among six pages on
display from a series addressing Euclidean rotation.
   Investigators from the district attorney's office and the
university police department recovered the manuscript late Tuesday,
said District Attorney Ronald Earle. The investigators searched the
duplex on a tip provided by Crime Stoppers, he said.
   Royal's grandfather coached at Texas from 1957 through 1976, was
UT athletic director until 1979 and now is special assistant to the
president of the university. Darrell Royal did not return telephone
calls for comment to his Austin residence.
   The younger Royal leaves near the UT campus but is not a
student, officials said.
   The missing page is part of an archive of 60 to 70 pages ``upon
which Einstein wrote the notes representing his thinking as he was
trying to work out his theories near the end of his life,'' said
John Chalmers, librarian for the university's Harry Ransom
Humanities Research Center.
   Einstein, the famed physicist who formulated the theory of
relativity, apparently wrote the notes in the early 1950s. He died
in 1955.
   The display case was locked and the glass unbroken when the
theft was discovered. It is unclear whether the person who took the
document had a key to the case or removed the document in some
other way, Chalmers said.
   Although the page likely could have been sold for a few thousand
dollars, its value far exceeds that amount, Chalmers said.
   ``For all of us, it's a piece of our heritage, and it is not to
be replaced,'' he said. ``In that sense, it has no price.''
</TEXT>
