<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialMoney     03-31 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Money,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Total Of $2.6 Million Handed Out To Eight Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission has given the
presidential candidates another $2.6 million, bringing the total
dispensed from the public treasury for the 1988 campaign to $48.1
million.
   As of Wednesday, former TV evangelist Pat Robertson, who is
trailing far behind Vice President George Bush in the Republican
delegate race, remained the leader in overall matching funds
received, at nearly $8.5 million.
   Bush has collected $7.4 million and Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, who
dropped out of the race Tuesday, has received $7.1 million.
   Another recipient, Democrat Richard Gephardt, a congressman from
Missouri, also dropped out this week.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., D-Tenn., faces loss of eligibility for
matching funds by virtue of receiving less than 10 percent of the
vote in two successive primaries _ Illinois and Connecticut.
   Gore notified the Federal Election Commission, as is his legal
prerogative, that he did not want the Puerto Rico ``beauty
contest'' primary on March 20 to count toward his eligibility, said
FEC spokesman Fred Eiland. A candidate may take that option if he
chooses not to campaign actively in a given state.
   Gore's matching funds for continued campaigning will be cut off
in 30 days unless he can get at least 20 percent in a primary
contest before that time. If he did not, he could receive matching
funds only for winding-down costs and debt satisfaction.
   The federal fund matches every contribution of $250 or less that
the candidates raise from individuals.
   The fund is supported by the $1 voluntary checkoff on individual
income tax returns.
   To be eligible, a candidate must first raise $100,000 across 20
states in contributions of $250 or less, with a minimum of $5,000
total from each state.
   The amounts certified on Wednesday, followed by the total the
candidates have received to date, are:
   Bush, $557,185, $7.4 million.
   Dole, $469,054, $7.1 million.
   Michael Dukakis, $254,386, $5.9 million.
   Gephardt, $286,176, $2.6 million.
   Gore, $117,312, $2.7 million.
   Jesse Jackson, $450,547, $1.5 million.
   Robertson, $307,766, $8.5 million.
   Paul Simon, $115,346, $2.8 million.
</TEXT>
