<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Nussbaum     03-31 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Nussbaum,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Believed World's Oldest Person Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOSHEN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ulysses S. Grant was in the White House and
Gen. George Custer was one year away from making his last stand
when Orpha Nussbaum was born Aug. 13, 1875.
   Mrs. Nussbaum, believed by the Guinness Book of World Records to
be the world's oldest person, died Wednesday at age 112.
   She had pneumonia recently, but an official cause of death was
not released, said Diane Hostetler, director of nursing at
Fountainview Nursing Home, where Mrs. Nussbaum lived.
   ``Her condition worsened during the weekend,'' Miss Hostetler
said.
   ``She couldn't do anything for herself anymore,'' said a
stepdaughter-in-law, Betty Nussbaum. ``You can't do anything for a
person who doesn't want to live anymore.''
   Betty Nussbaum said she was saddened by the death, but said Mrs.
Nussbaum had lived a good life.
   Last month, Guinness officials said they believed she was the
oldest person alive.
   Mrs. Nussbaum was honored at a special ceremony in January when
officials placed the Goshen city seal on census documents
indicating she was born in 1875 on the family farm near Middlebury
about 10 miles away. She spent most of her life in Middlebury until
moving to the nursing home in 1982.
   Florence Knapp, who lived in a Philadelphia suburb, had been
recognized as the world's oldest person until her death Jan. 11.
She was 114 years and 94 days old.
   Guinness restricts recognition to those who can provide birth
records and other documentation.
   There had been some confusion whether Mrs. Nussbaum would be 112
or 113 last Aug. 13. For years she had maintained she was a year
older than she actually was.
   But a document found in the public library in this northern
Indiana city last September showed that the former Orpha Ulery was
4 years old when she was counted in the U.S. Census of 1880, making
her 112.
   Mrs. Nussbaum attributed her longevity to her strict obedience
to a biblical command, Betty Nussbaum said. ``She honored her
father and mother. That's it,'' she said.
   For many years Mrs. Nussbaum taught Sunday school in the Elkhart
and Goshen areas. When she was 93, she resumed writing poetry, a
hobby she had stopped in the 1920s.
   Mrs. Nussbaum married John Mischler, a minister, in 1897. After
his death, she married Frank Nussbaum in 1947. He died in 1959.
</TEXT>
