<DOCNO> AP880331-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0154EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrainImplants 1stLd-Writethru a0665 03-31 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brain Implants, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0665,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brain Implants Relieve Alcohol-Related Memory Deficit in Rats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of acetylcholine, sted acetycholine, in
9th-12th grafs pvs, bgng, `The fetal...'. Picks up 13th graf, `In
alcoholics...'. National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism
is cq, 4th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Memory problems in rats caused by chronic
alcohol intake were mostly reversed with brain tissue transplants,
and such therapy may someday help alcoholics and victims of
Alzheimer's disease, a researcher says.
   ``I think that really means there's hope, if you blow your mind
with too much whiskey, maybe we'll be able to repair it with
transplants,'' or similarly ease mental deficits in Alzheimer's,
said Jeffrey Gray of the Institute of Psychiatry in London.
   But experts in alcohol-induced memory problems were skeptical,
questioning the resemblance of the rats' condition to that of
alcoholics and cautioning that any implication for treatment is
only speculation.
   Still, ``I think it's going to stimulate lots of excitement and
lots of further research,'' said Michael Eckardt, chief of the
clinical brain research section in the laboratory of clinical
studies at the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism.
   Gray, head of the psychology department at the psychiatric
institute in London, reports the research with colleagues in
Thursday's issue of the British journal Nature.
   About 10 percent of alcoholics develop long-lasting memory loss,
either by itself or as part of an overall loss in intellectual
abilities, according to the federal alcohol institute.
   In the new work, 78 male rats drank an alcohol solution as the
only fluid in an otherwise normal diet for 28 weeks. Four weeks
later, they did poorer than other rats in learning to find food in
a maze.
   But rats that then got transplants of fetal rat brain tissue to
two brain areas, the neocortex and the hippocampus, later performed
almost as well as normal rats, the researchers said.
   The fetal tissue was rich in a substance called acetylcholine,
which some brain cells use to communicate. The transplants
apparently worked by raising inadequate levels of the substance in
the brain, Gray said.
   Alzheimer's is not related to alcohol. But an acetylcholine
defect has also been identified in that disease, which involves
problems in memory and thinking, Gray said.
   David Drachman of the University of Massachusetts in Worcester,
an Alzheimer's expert, said previous research has shown that
impairment of the brain's acetylcholine circuitry can hinder mental
performance. Treating that impairment has helped in regaining
mental powers, he said.
   But Alzheimer's affects far more of the brain than just
acetylcholine-using cells, and whether Gray's strategy would
significantly help Alzheimer patients remains to be seen, he said.
   In alcoholics, memory loss without other intellectual decline is
called Korsakoff's psychosis. Eckardt said scientists are still
studying whether it is caused by excessive alcohol intake, by a
deficiency of the vitamin thiamine in the alcoholic's usually poor
diet, or by a combination of those factors.
   The new research did not involve thiamine deficiency, so
connecting its results to Korsakoff's is speculative, Eckardt said.
   The rats did not display a type of brain damage, called
diencephalic lesions, that is characteristic of Korsakoff's. The
researchers said that suggests the lesions are not responsible for
the memory problems.
   But that is ``much too speculative,'' and clashes with evidence
that does implicate the lesions, said Philip Langlais, a
Korsakoff's researcher at the University of California, San Diego.
   The lesions are generally accepted as causing the memory
deficits in the condition, so the rats did not truly have an animal
version of Korsakoff's psychosis, said Marlene Oscar Berman,
professor of neurology and psychiatry at the Boston University
School of Medicine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0254EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContraAidChronology     03-31 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid Chronology,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Contra Aid Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since President Reagan took office in 1981,
his policy of financing the Contra rebels in their war against
Nicaragua's Sandinista government has been one of the most divisive
foreign-policy questions facing Congress and the nation. Here is a
chronology of the ups and downs of that policy:
   1981 _ Congress, late in the year, approves $19 million in
covert military aid to the rebels. The money, to be managed by the
CIA, is part of a classified intelligence bill.
   1982 _ A second infusion of $19 million, again part of a
classified bill, is approved. This time, restrictive provisions are
added that prevent any of the money from being used to overthrow
the Sandinista government. There are reports, as well, that the CIA
has used an additional $10 million from its contingency fund.
   1983 _ The House votes to end Contra aid, but a later compromise
results in the appropriation of $24 million for the rebels. This
time, the money is appropriated openly, and the CIA is barred from
using any money from its contingency fund to supplement the new aid.
   1984 _ In April, reports surface that the CIA has supervised the
mining of three Nicaraguan ports, and Congress votes to cut off aid
to the rebels. But at the end of the year, lawmakers vote to set
aside $14 million for the rebels, to be released after Feb. 28,
1985, if Congress approves in a separate vote at that time.
Congress adds new restrictions, saying the CIA and the Pentagon may
not use the money to support paramilitary operations in Nicaragua
unless specifically authorized by Congress.
   1985 _ In April the Senate votes to release the $14 million, but
the House votes against the resolution, denying the money to the
rebels. That summer, Congress approves $27 million for the Contras
but restricts its use to food, clothing, medicine and other
``humanitarian'' aid. The money is directed to be used by the
administration as leverage to promote peace negotiations, and the
CIA and Defense Department are barred from any role in distributing
the money.
   1986 _ In the fall, Congress approves $100 million _ its largest
single appropriation for the rebels _ the bulk of it for military
aid. Restrictions on the CIA's role are lifted, except that the
agency remains barred from using its contingency fund.
   1987 _ In March, the House passes a moratorium on Contra aid in
an effort to hold up the final $40 million of the aid bill approved
in 1986, but the measure dies in the Senate. At the end of the
fiscal year, on Sept. 30, Congress begins a series of stopgap
funding measures that include money for ``non-lethal'' aid for the
rebels totaling another $20 million.
   1988 _ Under procedures laid out in late 1987, the House on Feb.
3 kills President Reagan's request for $36 million in rebel aid,
including $3.6 million in military aid. A month later, the House
also rejects a Democratic alternative that would have provided $30
million in solely humanitarian aid. The rebels reach a negotiated
truce with the Sandinistas on March 23, and a new $48 million
proposal is drafted in the House with bipartisan support.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
