<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Opera     03-31 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kraus Is Splendid in Met's `Werther'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenor Alfredo Kraus brought dignity and elegance
to the title role of Massenet's ``Werther,'' the final opera to
enter this season's repertory at the Metropolitan Opera.
   Some tenors portray Werther as a self-pitying nut case as he
pines for his beloved Charlotte, who has married another man to
fulfill a promise to her dying mother.
   But in Wednesday's performance Kraus gave him the dignity of a
man feeling overwhelming love. Vocally he was lean, elegant,
refined, distinguished.
   Frederica von Stade as Charlotte sang well throughout but rather
blandly in the first two acts, as she denied her love for Werther
and stuck steadfastly to her husband. In Act 3, with her love
churning to the surface as Werther falls into suicidal depression,
Miss von Stade came through with passionate vocalizing.
   Dawn Upshaw sang Charlotte's sister Sophie in a voice as fresh
as spring. It almost seemed to lilt. Richard Stilwell did well with
Albert. All voices were well focused. Jean Fournet conducted his
first ``Werther'' at the Met, beautifully shaping the music.
   The present production, last heard at the Met eight years ago,
was new in 1971. Rudolf Heinrich's sets for Acts 1 and 2 are
realistic and attractive. After Werther's mind cracks, set walls
meet at odd angles. In the finale scene, his room looks like a coal
cellar.
   ``Werther'' will be heard on the Metropolitan's last Saturday
afternoon broadcast. The season ends April 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
