<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Passover Bjt   03-31 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Passover, Bjt,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jews Find Fewer Soviet Obstacles To Passover Celebrations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jews are celebrating Passover with an abundance of
matzoh, the ancient symbol of freedom that is more available in
Moscow this year.
   Other changes since last Passover include a modest expansion of
Jewish culture, limited availability of some kosher foods and
visits by Soviet Jews to relatives abroad.
   Many of the capital's 200,000 Jews have been flocking to the
main synagogue to buy the thin, cracker-like unleavened bread eaten
during the eight-day commemoration of the freeing of the ancient
Hebrews from slavery in Egypt.
   Several Jews making purchases in the dark lobby of the Moscow
Choral Synagogue said matzoh is not as difficult to obtain as it
has been in the past.
   ``Times have become easier with glasnost,'' said Sasha, 26,
referring to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of more
openness on some issues. ``Under (former Soviet leader Leonid I.)
Brezhnev, people gathering in large groups around the synagogue
waiting to buy matzoh were driven away.''
   Earlier years also saw matzoh shortages.
   ``There were deficit problems with flour. Now, everything is
OK,'' said an elderly man who carried a rectangular package of
matzoh.
   Several afternoons before the start of the holiday at sundown
Friday, a steady stream of customers bought matzoh wrapped in white
or brown paper marked ``Kosher for Passover'' in Russian and Hebrew.
   Yuri A. Korzhenevich, one of the synagogue's two rabbis,
acknowledged in an interview that the government didn't provide
enough flour for matzoh from 1965-1969 but said this year's
allotment of 135 tons satisfied the demand.
   Trucks made deliveries daily to the synagogue from what
Korzhenevich calls a ``matzoh bakery,'' a tiny two-story,
pre-revolutionary brown building in downtown Moscow.
   The chief matzoh maker, Pavel N. Spaskin, gave a reporter a tour
of the bakery, tucked behind apartment buildings and across the
street from a popular cooperative restaurant.
   ``We've been producing matzoh here for 20 years,'' said Spaskin,
a small gray-haired man of 38.
   The bakery already had stopped production for the year, and its
stainless steel mixers and dough-rolling tables lay idle.
   Spaskin said he recently compared his product with American
matzoh.
   The American matzoh ``was more airy,'' he said. ``It would be
interesting to know the technology Americans use, or maybe it's a
different flour.''
   Aside from abundant matzoh supplies, the government has allowed
these improvements in Jewish life since last Passover:
   _Hungary's Jews sent in some Kosher wine, chickens and salami.
Religious books also have been imported.
   _A Jewish museum and library have been set up in private Moscow
apartments.
   _Last year, as relations with the West improved, more than 8,000
Soviet Jews were permitted to leave the country, nearly eight times
as many as the year before and the highest total since 1981.
   Among those who have left in recent months are longtime Jewish
activists and refuseniks Josef Begun, Vladimir Slepak, Ida Nudel,
Noam Meiman and Alexander Lerner and pianist Vladimir Feltsman.
   Soviet authorities also are allowing increased numbers of Jews
to travel to the West to visit relatives.
   In an exchange with the New York City Jewish community, American
Rabbi Marc Schneier and Cantor Joel Selter are scheduled to lead
Passover services in the Moscow Choral Synagogue on Friday, and the
Choral Synagogue's chief rabbi, Abraham Shayevich, will be in the
pulpit in New York.
   And there are more subtle signs of change. Michael Stolar, the
28-year-old son of Chicago-born refusenik Abe Stolar, said he and a
group of six friends meet daily in the Choral Synagogue to study
the Talmud, the writings on Jewish civil and religious law.
   ``Two to four years ago, you had to be quite careful about where
you prayed or studied. You could have an unexpected visit by the
militia,'' he said.
   Still, problems remain.
   Thousands of Jews are waiting to leave. And anti-Semitism
persists: a Soviet newspaper this week accused Moscow's other
synagogue of brainwashing Jewish children into wanting to go to
Israel, and the word ``No!'' was scrawled in English next to a Star
of David on an outside wall of the matzoh bakery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
