<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barbara Bush Mum On Who Bush Might Consider For Veep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOODBURY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush says her husband is not ready
to start thinking about a Republican vice-presidential running mate
yet _ and even if he were, he'd keep it to himself.
   ``He ...said he didn't want to give it away now, or it would be
a boring Republican convention,'' Mrs. Bush said as she campaigned
for her husband at a country club lunch here on Wednesday.
   Mrs. Bush said she doesn't plan to change her style if her
husband is elected to the White House. The white-haired,
62-year-old Mrs. Bush said she shrugs off remarks that she looks
old enough to be the mother of her youthful-looking husband.
   ``I'd love to be a size 4, beautiful and twenty-years old,''
quipped Mrs. Bush. ``But I know I can't be that so I'll just be me.
... Sometimes the comments can be brutal but most times I make a
joke about it.''
   She said she enjoys the campaigning but doesn't think her
husband's public image reflects his real personality.
   ``People have no inkling how funny George is and how
extraordinarily caring he is,'' she said. ``I adore George Bush.
It's easy to.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Goldwater Says Jackson `Most Intelligent' Democratic Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Republican Sen. Barry Goldwater
says Jesse Jackson is the most intelligent Democratic presidential
candidate in the 1988 race.
   Goldwater, a Republican presidential candidate in 1964, said of
Jackson, ``he's the most intelligent man running on the Democratic
side, and not by a little, by a lot.''
   ``Whether he'll make a good president, well, that's something
you can ask about any president,'' Goldwater said Wednesday.
   The 79-year-old former Arizona senator spoke at a news
conference prior to receiving Princeton University's 1988 James
Madison Award for Distinguished Public Service.

</TEXT>
<HEAD>Pollster Says Jackson Can't Win California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pollster Mervin Field says it is very
unlikely that Jesse Jackson could win the June 7 California
Democratic presidential primary in a two-man race against Michael
Dukakis.
   ``If Jesse Jackson wins in California, this would rank as one of
the biggest political happenings since the country was founded,''
Field told a luncheon of the Sacramento Press Club on Wednesday.
   But he said Jackson could do better in a three-way race
including Albert Gore.
   The San Francisco-based political pollster, who publishes the
California Poll, said he doesn't think the California primary ``is
as promising as Michigan and the other industrial states'' for
Jackson.
   California is not as economically distressed as those states and
Jackson's appeal is to the economically distressed, he said. And
the black population in California is not as large as in some other
states: 8 percent of the general population and 14 percent of
Democrats, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Official Predicts 1.6 Million Turnout In Wisconsin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 1.6 million voters are
expected to go to the polls Tuesday in Wisconsin's presidential
preference primary, a state Elections Board official says.
   That turnout would be about 45 percent of Wisconsin's estimated
3.5 million eligible voters, said Kevin Kennedy, the board's
executive director.
   In Wisconsin's 1984 primary, voter participation dropped to 27.4
percent of the voting-age population.
   One factor in that turnout was the insistence of the national
Democratic Party that Wisconsin Democrats use a caucus system
instead of its open primary to select delegates to the national
convention.
   This year, the open primary, in which voters are not required to
state party preference, will again be used for delegate selection.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>California Backers Fail To Get Cuomo's Name On Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mario Cuomo supporters have failed to
gather enough signatures to put the New York governor's name on
California's presidential primary ballot, state officials say.
   But the head of a draft Cuomo committee said his group plans to
try to convince a court to add Cuomo to the list of Democratic
candidates on the June 7 ballot.
   ``We knew that when we submitted the names that we did not have
enough signatures, but we did it anyway because we felt that we had
substantially complied with a law that has serious constitutional
problems,'' said Steven Polard, a Los Angeles attorney who heads
the California Draft Cuomo for President Committee.
   Committee members turned in about 16,000 signatures, Polard
said. They needed at least 22,500 _ a minimum of 500 from each of
the state's 45 congressional districts, according to Caren
Daniels-Meade, a spokeswoman for Secretary of State March Fong Eu.
   But state election officials had said earlier that even if the
committee collected enough signatures they would not put Cuomo's
name on the ballot unless he authorized it.
   The New York governor has refused to enter the presidential
primaries but he has not ruled out accepting a draft at the
Democratic National Convention.
   Daniels-Meade said Cuomo will not appear on the California
ballot now unless he announces his candidacy for president,
qualifies for federal matching funds and actively campaigns for the
office.
   If those things happen, Eu can add Cuomo's name to the ballot,
she said.
</TEXT>
