<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget     03-31 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Passes Budget Plan Following Reagan's Priorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A big boost for the space program along with
cuts in aid to local and state governments are contained in the
$1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget approved by the Senate Budget
Committee.
   The plan, closer to President Reagan's priorities than the
budget passed by the House earlier this month, was approved 18-3 on
Wednesday and sent to the full Senate for consideration.
   Committee chairman Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., and Sen. Pete V.
Domenici of New Mexico, the panel's senior Republican, drafted the
bipartisan compromise and it sailed through the committee in a
single day.
   There's even an outside chance Congress will meet its April 15
deadline for final budget action, although the Senate doesn't plan
to vote on the resolution until after next week's holiday recess.
   But opponents and supporters complained that while they were
living up to the terms of last fall's deficit reduction agreement
with Reagan, the result was to put off much-needed fiscal reforms
until next year.
   ``We need to get this out and then start showing what the
problems are going to be,'' said Chiles.
   Sen. Bill Armstrong, R-Colo., said it was mostly a plan to ``get
past the November election.''
   ``There's an old saying, `No guts, no glory,''' said Armstrong.
``And this is a no-glory budget.'' Armstrong and Sens. Steve Symms,
R-Idaho, and Kent Conrad, D-N.D., voted against the plan.
   Total deficit reduction in the Senate budget proposal would be
$7.2 billion, accomplished in part by holding spending on most
programs short of the full inflation increases they would normally
get. More than half the saving would come from selling off
government assets.
   It would meet the $136 billion deficit-reduction target of the
Gramm-Rudman budget balancing law only because the committee
decided to use optimistic White House economic projections. The
non-partisan Congressional Budget Office predicts a deficit more
than $30 billion higher.
   Last fall's pact with the president set overall spending limits
of $294 billion, $16.1 billion for foreign aid and $169.2 billion
for domestic spending other than Social Security and entitlement
programs.
   The agreement also included $14 billion in new taxes that were
enacted last year and will be in effect for fiscal 1989, which
begins Oct. 1.
   The Senate budget envisions spending $13 billion of the domestic
allocation on space and science in the year beginning Oct. 1, about
the same amount Reagan requested and nearly $1 billion more than
the House approved.
   In addition to the 27 percent increase for the space program,
that money would boost National Science Foundation programs by 11
percent and move ahead the proposed construction of a giant physics
project known as the superconducting super collider.
   Like the House, the Senate committee declined to kill any
programs, relying instead on across-the-board spending restraint to
reach deficit-reduction targets without making those tough choices
in an election year.
   But while most programs would get at least a partial inflation
boost, community and regional development would be cut $100 million
from last year's $5.8 billion last year.
   Tom Cochran, executive director of the U.S. Conference of
Mayors, said aid to localities has been cut too deeply already
during the Reagan years. ``The priorities of this thing are out of
whack,'' he said of the Senate plan.
   A Republican amendment to carry out some of Reagan's plan to
eliminate those development programs was withdrawn, and Domenici
was defeated when he tried to require selling off two federally
owned oil tracts, and said that,
   ``Sooner or later, we're going to have to get rid of some
programs.'' But it was, Domenici said, still a ``a fair, balanced
budget.''
   The proposal would, like the administration and House budgets,
call for big increases in spending on AIDS research, air traffic
safety and education.
   The Senate plan assumes that if legislation providing
catastrophic health insurance for Medicare recipients is approved,
there will be an accompanying increase in premiums to cover the
cost.
   An additional $500 million would be provided to continue
supplying cheese and other surplus commodities to the needy.
   Like the president's budget, the Senate plan would grant 4.3
percent pay raises for the military and 2 percent for civilian
federal workers. The House adopted a 3 percent across-the-board pay
hike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     03-31 0940</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,1000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>March Farm Price Index Up 10 Percent From Last Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lettuce prices bounced up again in March but
didn't approach their winter peaks, and the farm prices of cattle
eggs and broilers were up, too.
   But the Agriculture Department says this month's farm prices for
hogs, milk, wheat and sweet corn were down, and that left the March
index where it was in February.
   Even so, the March average of prices received by farmers was up
7.4 percent from a year ago, the department's Agricultural
Statistics Board said Wednesday.
   ``The price of lettuce increased sharply from February to March
but was well below record levels during the November through
January 1988 period,'' the report said. ``Calf prices dropped
slightly from February to March but were at the second highest
level since June of 1979.''
   Prices of cattle sold for beef were the highest since May 1979,
the report said. Hog and wheat prices declined from February, while
corn prices rose slightly.
   Department economists say net cash income of farmers may be in
the range of $50 billion to $55 billion this year, down from the
record level of $57 billion in 1987. That is the difference between
cash receipts and cash expenses during the calendar year.
   Consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent
this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987.
   According to the preliminary March figures, based mostly on
mid-month averages, the index for crop prices was up 0.9 percent
from February and averaged 10 percent more than a year ago.
   Commercial vegetable prices rose 11 percent from last month but
were down 7.1 percent from March 1987.
   ``Higher prices for lettuce and tomatoes were major contributors
to the increase in the (vegetable) index,'' the report said.
   Lettuce prices were reported at $21.30 per 100 pounds, compared
with $11.10 in February and $35.60 in January.
   The index for livestock and livestock products was down 0.7
percent from February but was 4.2 percent above March 1987. Prices
were higher for cattle, eggs and broilers but were lower for hogs
and milk.
   March farm commodity prices averaged 130 percent of a 1977 base
used for comparison, according to the preliminary figures, the same
as in February. A year ago the March index was 121 percent.
   No new figures for farm production costs were included in the
report. Those have been confined to quarterly averages because of
budget cutbacks.
   In January, however, farm expenses were unchanged from last fall
but averaged 4.4 percent above a year earlier. The next quarterly
figures will be reported in April.
   The report said:
   _Cattle averaged $68.40 per 100 pounds of live weight
nationally, up from $67.40 in February and the $59.30 reported for
March 1987. Those are averages for all types of cattle sold as beef.
   _Hogs averaged $41.90 per 100 pounds, compared with $45.80 in
March and $47.40 a year earlier.
   _Corn, at $1.84 a bushel, was up from $1.83 in February and the
average of $1.47 per bushel a year earlier.
   _Wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures,
averaged $2.64 per bushel, compared with $2.79 in February and
$2.57 a year earlier.
   _Rice averaged $8.46 per 100 pounds, compared with $8.97 in
February and $3.62 a year earlier.
   _Soybeans were $5.93 per bushel, compared with $5.97 in February
and $4.73 a year earlier.
   _Upland cotton was reported at 56.9 cents per pound, compared
with 56.8 in February and 47.5 cents in March 1987.
   _Eggs were 50.8 cents per dozen, compared with 46.9 cents in
February and 54.4 cents a year earlier.
   _Milk was $12 per 100 pounds, compared with $12.30 in February
and $12.50 a year earlier.
   _Broilers were 27.5 cents per pound, live weight, compared with
25.7 cents in February and 29.1 cents a year ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Association of Wheat Growers says
its producers should receive incentives from the Agriculture
Department to sell grain on the open market rather than have to
forfeit it to the government when price support loans come due.
   Frank Johannsen, association president, said Wednesday that
wheat producers deserve the same kind of consideration given corn
producers who are being allowed to keep their grain under federal
price support for an additional year.
   That was a reference to Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng's
announcement Tuesday that price support loans for some old-crop
corn and sorghum will be extended a year longer than their normal
maturity dates.
   Johannsen, a Bayard, Neb., wheat farmer, said in a statement
released here that the association is ``seeking a way to encourage
growers to settle their maturing loans'' by paying them off with
generic certificates.
   The certificates are issued by USDA as payment-in-kind under
crop programs and can be exchanged for surplus commodities owned by
the department's Commodity Credit Corp.
   If the price support loans are not repaid, a farmer must forfeit
the grain to the CCC, which cancels the debt.
   Once the CCC takes over the grain, it must be moved into
government storage. Much of the CCC wheat is currently being sold
back into the market in weekly auctions.
   ``Since current estimates are that it costs the government at
least 20 cents a bushel to move, store, catalog and exchange
forfeited wheat through weekly auctions, our proposal won't cost
anything extra and it will reduce some of the government's
logistical problems,'' Johannsen said. ``It has the added benefit
of keeping wheat moving in the pipeline of our much-improved
market.''
   Besides, he said, grain farmers ``have a right to expect
even-handed treatment'' from the department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
