<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Coors-Teamsters     03-31 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coors-Teamsters,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Win Right To Try To Organize Coors Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Teamsters Union has eliminated a rival in
trying to unionize the once bitterly anti-union Adolph Coors Co.
after organizing Anheuser-Busch's newest brewery just two weeks ago.
   The AFL-CIO on Wednesday awarded sole organizing rights to the
Teamsters at Coors' lead brewery at Golden, Colo., less than 50
miles away from the new Anheuser-Busch facility at Fort Collins,
Colo.
   The labor federation ordered one of its veteran affiliates, the
Machinists Union, to withdraw from its campaign to organize the
same 3,200 Coors workers, saying the Teamsters had a much better
chance of succeeding.
   The decision was an outgrowth of the Teamsters' decision last
October to reaffiliate their 1.6 million members with the AFL-CIO.
The union was expelled from the federation 30 years earlier on
charges of corruption.
   A major factor in the AFL-CIO's decision to readmit the
Teamsters was ending the expensive fights and membership raids that
the two organizations constantly waged against each other. Many
employers often were able to avoid collective bargaining altogether
by playing one union against the other.
   The AFL-CIO last September had awarded the sole organizing
rights at Coors to the Machinists. The Teamsters had challenged
that ruling as soon as they were re-admitted to the federation last
Nov. 1.
   Coors, in the face of an intensive organizing effort by the
Teamsters since early 1986, last August signed an agreement with
the AFL-CIO ending a 10-year-old nationwide boycott of its beer by
the labor movement.
   In exchange, the company agreed to forgo erecting the usual
legal hurdles available to employers in opposing unions and allow
an AFL-CIO affiliate an unfettered attempt to organize its Golden
work force.
   However, that was before the Teamsters were back in the AFL-CIO.
And Teamsters officials admitted they now have concerns now about
how the Coors-AFL-CIO pact will hold up in the face of Wednesday's
action.
   ``We're elated,'' said Charles Klare, director of the Teamsters'
100,000-member brewery and soft drinks division. ``But there's a
lot to be found out yet. We've got to meet with Coors and determine
if they accept the fact that the AFL-CIO picked us.''
   The Machinists Union had argued before an arbitrator picked by
AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland that the Teamsters should give up
the Coors effort based on last September's decision.
   The Teamsters countered they had an ongoing organizing campaign
at Coors a year before the Machinists entered the picture and had
gotten signatures on Teamster union cards from more than 30 percent
of the workers at Golden.
   Kirkland agreed with the Teamsters, according to witnesses at
the arbitration proceedings.
   ``It was a black-and-white case,'' said Vicki Saporta, the
Teamsters' director of organizing. ``We were there first and they
didn't have a single card signed. We're also the predominant union
in the industry. We have contracts at all 12 Anheuser-Busch
breweries covering some 9,000 workers.''
   Ms. Saporta said the Teamsters have another tactical advantage
in that it also has union contracts representing employees of more
than 180 local distributors of Coors' products nationwide.
   The Teamsters just last week ratified a new contract with
Anheuser-Busch raising the base pay for brewery production workers
from its current $16.50 an hour to $17.25 over the next three years.
   Just a week earlier, the union won a an organizing effort at
Anheuser-Busch's newest facility at Fort Collins to represent its
current work force of about 340 people, which is expected to grow
to 550 by next January.
   ``That was one of the factors the arbitrator took into
consideration,'' Klare said. ``Coors workers are averaging about
$3.50 to $4 an hour less than our members. Seeing how fellow
workers down the road are doing gives them a big incentive to come
in.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
