<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Panama-Chronology     03-31 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Panama-Chronology,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of events in the Panamanian crisis:
   THURSDAY, FEB. 25 _ Panama's president, Eric Arturo Delvalle,
announces he is dismissing Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, indicted on
U.S. drug charges, as head of the 15,000-strong Defense Forces and
replacing him with Col. Marcos Justines, chief of staff. Justines
refuses the job.
   FRIDAY, FEB. 26 _ The Noriega-dominated National Assembly votes
to oust Delvalle. Education Minister Manuel Solis Palma is named
new head of state. Noriega opponents call for a general strike in
protest.
   SATURDAY, FEB. 27 _ Delvalle goes into hiding in Panama, defying
Noriega's order to leave the country.
   MONDAY, FEB. 29 _ General strike begins with mixed participation.
   TUESDAY, MARCH 1 _ Strike gains support. Locally owned banks
close. International banks limit withdrawals. Security forces crack
down on protests amid scattered violence.
   WEDNESDAY, MARCH 2 _ Doctors join businesses in general strike.
U.S. officials say they will ask U.S. banks to freeze Panamanian
government assets.
   THURSDAY, MARCH 3 _ Organizers end general strike as support
fades. U.S. federal courts block withdrawal of Panama funds from
U.S. banks.
   FRIDAY, MARCH 4 _ National Bank of Panama says it cannot meet
banks' cash demands. International banks fearing a run on deposits
close their doors. Local banks remain closed.
   SUNDAY, MARCH 6 _ Retired people who are unable to cash pension
checks rally in streets.
   MONDAY, MARCH 7 _ Riot police disperse demonstrators in Panama
with tear gas and birdshot.
   TUESDAY, MARCH 8 _ Government says banks can reopen but no one
can cash checks or withdraw funds. Few banks respond.
   FRIDAY, MARCH 11 _ Reagan imposes economic sanctions, including
eliminating trade preferences for Panama and withholding Panama
Canal fees from the Noriega government by placing them in escrow.
Noriega government meets army payroll. Spain tells United States it
would accept Noriega if he asked for asylum.
   MONDAY, MARCH 14 _ Public employees stage work stoppages and
riot after government can't pay wages. Riot police use tear gas and
truncheons to disperse hundreds blocking traffic. U.S. sends 100
additional military personnel to beef up security around canal.
   TUESDAY, MARCH 15 _ At least a dozen are injured in
demonstrations as civil servants take to the streets to demand
paychecks. Government says it will make partial payments to public
employees.
   WEDNESDAY, MARCH 16 _ Noriega survives coup attempt by dissident
officers of Defense Forces. Violent demonstrations occur and
workers strike at state-run electric, water and telephone
companies, ports in Panama City and Colon and government ministries.
   THURSDAY, MARCH 17 _ Government declares a ``state of urgency''
and soldiers patrol capital. Defense Forces take control of
utilities and ministries, but most workers remain off their jobs.
   FRIDAY, MARCH 18 _ Noriega meets with U.S. State Department
officials who offer freedom from extradition on drug charges if he
will seek asylum in third country. Noriega reportedly says he wants
to remain in Panama and take part in formation of transitional
government.
   SUNDAY, MARCH 20 _ Secretary of State George P. Shultz says
indictments against Noriega will not be dropped and Noriega cannot
have a say about government after his departure.
   MONDAY, MARCH 21 _ Armed soldiers patrol Panama City as general
strike paralyzes nation. Solis Palma announces Noriega has offered
to resign before May 1989 elections if opponents agree to talks.
Opposition leaders and United States reject Noriega's offer.
   MONDAY, MARCH 28 _ Riot troops smash an anti-government march by
10,000 people and more than 20 members of the opposition are
arrested in a raid on a hotel in Panama City. Some journalists are
also detained.
   WEDNESDAY, MARCH 30 _ The 10-day-old general strike loses ground
with the opening of the capital's major supermarket chains,
although industry, construction and most commerce remain virtually
paralyzed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0348EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Leader     03-31 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Leader,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says He's A Leader, Even If He Hasn't Held Office</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: May be topped with morning events</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CUDAHY, Wisc. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, answering critics who say he
lacks the government experience to be president, says ``Some
leaders don't hold office.''
   The Democratic presidential candidate also accused fellow
hopeful Albert Gore Jr. of personal attacks on him, a day after
Gore said Jackson lacked the qualifications for the presidency.
   Jackson returned to a site of his activism last year to
emphasize Wednesday that his personal style of leadership has been
in the streets, not in the government halls.
   ``Leadership stands with the people in the time of crisis,'' he
told about a 1,000 people at St. Frederick's Church here late
Wednesday. ``I stood with the people ... I stood with the P-40
workers in Cudahy.''
   Almost exactly a year ago _ on Palm Sunday 1987 _ Jackson
marched in the streets of this Milwaukee suburb to protest
management's actions in the strike of the United Food and
Commercial Workers local at the Patrick Cudahy meatpacking plant
here.
   Workers went on strike on Jan. 4, 1987, and are still out.
Replacement workers have been hired, but the company, owned by
Smithfield Foods, is trying to reoganize under the backruptcy laws.
   ``In your time of crisis, you called out to me and I
responded,'' Jackson told the crowd. ``In the time of this nation's
crisis, I want to be your president and I need your help.''
   Jackson began a three-day Wisconsin campaign swing Wednesday
after a day of private meetings in Washington with key leaders of
the party's Washington establishment and with campaign aides. He
planned a full day of campaigning across the state both today and
Saturday.
   ``Some officeholders are leaders. Some leaders don't hold
office,'' he said. ``But leaders stand with the people in the hour
of hardship and challenge.''
   On Tuesday, fellow Democratic candidate Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of
Tennessee attacked Jackson for lacking the requisite experience to
be president, and criticized his foreign policy views.
   On Wednesday, Jackson said he viewed Gore's comments as
``attacks, which were more personal than principled.'' The two were
to meet, but it fell through.
   Gore, told of Jackson's remark, asked: ``Is there supposed to be
some unwritten rule why Jesse Jackson cannot be criticized, why his
positions have to be just sacrosanct and nobody can say anything
about them for fear somebody will just misinterpret what you're
saying?''
   Jackson did not refer to Gore directly in his speech, but he did
tell reporters that he will lay his differences with the other
candidates as appropriate.
   ``If there are distinctions, I will discuss them,'' Jackson said.
   He emphasized that he wanted to keep his message positive and
pledged not to engage in personal attacks.
   But Gerald Austin, Jackson's campaign manager, told reporters on
the plane that Gore ``is the Democratic bully'' who has attacked
other candidates before. Austin derided Gore for saying
complimentary things about Jackson in a Monday debate and then
criticizing Jackson the next day.
   ``Gore doesn't deserve your attention or ours until he starts
winning some votes _ or at least breaks into double digits,''
Austin said of Gore's recently poor showing in primaries.
   Jackson's speech at the Cudahy church laid out more specifically
than before his definition of leadership.
   ``I have learned to lead in the gap ... the leadership gap in
the White House and the Executive Office building,'' he said.
``When the drugs flow into our country, Mrs. Reagan just says no.
Mr. Bush just says nothing. Mr. Reagan does nothing.
   ``I led the drive to ban drugs and to ban guns,'' Jackson said.
Jackson listed a variety of his previous actions as demonstrations
of leadership. He mentioned his ``standing with the auto workers at
Kenosha'' Wis., where Chrysler closed a plant shortly after
promising to keep it open for several more years. He talked of
standing with family farmers at foreclosure sales.
   He talked of his leadership in the fight against South Africa
and in personally asking Soviet leaders to improve human rights in
that nation.
   Jackson refered to his campaign as featuring ``a clear message
and an authentic leader who speaks directly to the people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
