<DOCNO> AP880331-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Oil     03-31 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Oil,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Boosts Fuel Imports As Tanker War Takes Its Toll</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi air raids on Iran's refineries and
tankers in recent weeks appear to be taking an increasing toll on
Tehran's vital oil industry as the Persian Gulf war escalates
sharply.
   Shipping analysts believe the Iraqis will intensify air strikes
aimed at throttling Iran's oil exports while hammering Tehran and
other cities in a drive to pressure Iran to the negotiating table.
   ``We can't see an end to the tanker war,'' Eric Ramheim of the
Oslo-based International Association of Independent Tanker Owners
said.
   ``We had hoped the tanker war was coming to an end after a
recent lull, but the situation is worse now than it's been for a
long time. You think it's reached a peak, and then it just gets
worse,'' he said in a phone interview.
   Iran, one of the world's major oil producers, is having to
import record amounts of refined petroleum products, such as
kerosene and jet fuel, the Middle East Economic Survey reported
this week.
   ``This unprecedented sudden import of gas oil could be due to
damage inflicted on Iranian refineries because of the war,'' the
respected oil industry newsletter noted.
   But it noted as well that Tehran may also be ``taking
precautionary measures and stocking up these products in
anticipation of a further escalation in the war.''
   The sudden surge in refined imports has strategic implications
in the 7{-year-old war. It coincides with an unprecedented Iraqi
missile bombardment of Tehran and other key cities over the last
month.
   The Iranians may fear their battered refineries could be knocked
out altogether.
   The Economic Survey, a weekly published in Nicosia, said the
Iranians have chartered a 200,000-ton tanker from West Germany's
Marimpex trading company to deliver a full load of gas oil _ more
than 2 million barrels _ from Rotterdam next month.
   The Iranians have already taken delivery of nearly 3 million
42-gallon barrels of gas oil in recent weeks, industry sources
noted.
   That is a massive increase over the 300,000 barrels a day it has
been importing for the last 18 months. Recent Iraqi air raids have
reduced Iran's domestic refining capacity by as much as one-third.
   A large formation of Iraqi fighter-bombers attacked Iran's big
Kharg Island oil terminal in the northern end of the gulf on March
19, badly damaging two of the estimated 25 tankers that shuttle oil
to makeshift terminals farther south for transshipment to delivery
tankers.
   The 316,379-ton Avaj and the 249,829-ton Sanandaj were left in
flames with 50 crewmen killed. Shipping sources said both vessels
were so badly hit they will likely be scrapped.
   The loading facilities on Kharg, heavily defended by
anti-aircraft missile batteries, also were damaged, the economic
survey said.
   The main systems on the west of the island were knocked out in
the bombing, forcing the Iranians to switch loading to a smaller
jetty, slowing down exports that are Tehran's main source of
revenue for its war effort.
   Several other shuttle tankers, either owned by the state-run
National Iranian Tanker Co., or chartered by it, are believed to
have been put out of action in recent Iraqi air strikes.
   ``The Iraqis are the key,'' stressed Ramheim, of the
International Association of Independent Tanker Owners. ``Now
they're attacking again, we think the situation's going to get
worse because Iran always retaliates.''
   Because Iraq's gulf ports have been closed since the early days
of the war, the Iranians have to take revenge by attacking neutral
ships.
   After Iraq reported three air strikes on Iranian tankers,
Iranian gunboats on Monday attacked a Danish supertanker and a
Norwegian-operated tanker, setting both ablaze.
   London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit says 4.7 million
tons of shipping has been sunk or written off since December
because of the tanker war. That includes the 280,000-ton Iranian
tanker Susangird, which went down after it was set on fire by Iraqi
Exocet missiles, killing 21 crewmen.
   Altogether, about 15 million tons of shipping has been lost
since 1981, Lloyd's and other agencies reported. That's more than
half the 24 million tons of merchant shipping sunk in World War II.
   Iran must ship its oil exports through the gulf, where its
tankers are prey to marauding Iraqi jets. Iraq exports its oil
through pipelines across neighboring Turkey and Saudi Arabia which
are far less vulnerable to attack.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
