<HEAD>Music Awards for R&B, Jazz, Gospel and Rap Announced</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Levert and Cassanova in 3rd graf cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop superstar Michael Jackson's
``Bad'' album, which failed to win him Grammy gold, was named best
album of the year at the second annual Soul Train Music Awards.
   At the awards ceremony Wednesday night, ``Bad'' also was named
best album of 1987 by a male vocalist and the title song was
honored as best single in the male vocalist category.
   Whitney Houston's ``Whitney'' was named best album by a female
vocalist.
   In the group category, Levert took best jazz album and best
album of the year for ``The Big Throwdown,'' and best single for
``Cassanova.''
   Gladys Knight and the Pips won the Heritage Award, a special
tribute to artists whose accomplishments have had a positive effect
on music acceptance and appreciation worldwide.
   Singers Dionne Warwick and Luther Vandross were hosts of the
two-hour televised ceremony at the Civic Auditorium attended by a
black-tie audience, including Smokey Robinson and other Motown
stars.
   Among those presenting awards were singers Anita Baker, Sheena
Easton and Chaka Khan, Los Angeles Lakers star Magic Johnson,
Indianapolis Colts running back Eric Dickerson and jazz musicians
David Sanborn and Dexter Gordon.
   The show is a tribute to creative excellence in black music,
honoring the year's best performances in rhythm and blues, jazz and
contemporary, gospel, and rap music.
   The other winners:
   _Best new artist: Miki Howard.
   _Best music video: Janet Jackson, ``Control.''
   _Best female single: Natalie Cole, ``I Live for Your Love.''
   _Best solo jazz album: Najee, ``Najee's Theme.''
   _Best solo gospel album: Vanessa Bell Armstrong, ``Following
Jesus.''
   _Best gospel album by a group or choir: The Winans,
``Decisions.''
   _Best rap single: LL Cool J, ``I Need Love.''
   _Best rap album: LL Cool J, ``Bigger & Deffer.''
