<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Holmes     03-31 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Holmes,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>John Clellon Holmes, Author, Chronicler Of Beat Generation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLD SAYBROOK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist John Clellon Holmes, the
first to describe 1950s youth as a ``beat'' generation, died of
cancer. He was 62.
   Holmes, who died Wednesday, was a companion of Jack Kerouac,
Allen Ginsburg, William Burroughs and other chroniclers of the
``beat'' lifestyle in New York City after World War II.
   His first novel, ``Go,'' published in 1952, was about the beat
world, and appeared five years before Kerouac's more popular
beatnik novel, ``On The Road.''
   Holmes, a Holyoke, Mass., native, who was also a poet and a
critic, wrote more about the period and its philosophy in ``Nothing
More To Declare,'' published in 1967.
   However, he criticized the beatniks' 1960s successors, the
hippies, saying they had a ``fad culture'' characterized by ``a
feeling of helplessness.''
   Holmes became a visiting lecturer at the University of Arkansas
in 1957. In 1966, he became the school's first writer-in-residence.
He also taught at Yale, the University of Iowa, Bowling Green
University and Brown University. Holmes retired from teaching in
1986.
   ``Displaced Person: The Travel Essays of John Clellon Holmes,''
was published earlier this month by the University of Arkansas
Press.
   Holmes is survived by his wife, Shirley Allen Holmes; his mother
and two sisters.
</TEXT>
