<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Corruption, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0496,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Charges Government Cover-Up Over Corruption</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To CORRECT spelling of movement's name to Undong, sted Udong
and sent, SUB 6th graf: `The former ... development program.' Picks
up 7th graf, `The younger ...
^By BARRY RENFREW</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition today accused the
government of concealing massive corruption involving hundreds of
millions of dollars and demanded former President Chun Doo-hwan be
questioned about missing funds.
   The country's two main opposition parties claimed the government
had limited the scope of a probe into alleged corruption by Chun's
younger brother, charging information about the Chun family's
activities was being suppressed.
   ``The government has orchestrated another cover-up and fooled
the people,'' the Reunification Democratic Party charged.
   The Party for Peace and Democracy demanded President Chun be
questioned about allegations of widespread corruption under his
government and called for a full investigation.
   The governing Democratic Justice Party denied there was any
attempt to cover up corruption and said it was determined to expose
any official wrongdoing.
   The former president's brother, Chun Kyung-hwan, was charged
early today with embezzling $10.4 million as head of Saemaul Undong
(New Community), a semi-official development program.
   The younger Chun, who was taken to a Seoul prison in handcuffs,
also was charged with taking bribes, influence peddling, evading
taxes and violation of business, land and construction laws.
   If convicted under special laws covering massive public fraud,
Chun could receive a sentence ranging from 10 years in prison to
death.
   Ten other people, including aides of the younger Chun and senior
Saemaul officials, also were indicted on embezzlement, bribery,
influence peddling and corruption charges, officials said.
   The other suspects include Chun Kyung-hwan's two brothers-in-law.
   The opposition charged that the younger Chun and his associates
had embezzled hundreds of millions of dollars, and the government
was concealing evidence to prevent a political backlash.
   Chief Prosecutor Kang Won-il said the younger Chun amassed a
fortune in money, land and stocks by using government and family
connections during the seven years he headed Saemaul.
   The former president had appointed him to the post.
   ``It is agonizing to me that I have caused trouble to my
brother,'' the younger Chun was quoted as saying by prosecutors.
   Kang said the younger Chun diverted government and Saemaul
funds, pressured corporations into making illegal donations,
arranged to get private businesses government contracts and
permits, and misappropriated land and buildings built with
government funds.
   Kang said the investigation was centering on charges Chun
diverted huge sums of money overseas for land speculation in the
United States and Australia. The prosecutor said the probe was
continuing and further revelations were expected.
   Saemaul was founded in 1971 to promote urban and rural
development. The younger Chun resigned as its chief in 1987 after
being linked to gangsters.
   Prosecutors are questioning government officials about charges
they aided or concealed Saemaul corruption to protect the former
president and his family.
   Former President Chun, who left office Feb. 25 after seven years
in power, has not been implicated in the Saemaul affair. He is on a
private American tour and met last week with President Reagan.
</TEXT>
