<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurers Offer Lower Rates for Air Bag-Equipped Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several of the largest insurance companies are
offering sharp discounts in premiums for drivers of cars with air
bags, the safety devices that inflate and protect a driver in a
serious accident.
   USAA, the country's sixth largest insurance company, announced
Wednesday a premium discount of up to 60 percent for personal
injury and medical coverage for air bag-equipped cars.
   The company also said it would contribute $300 to the purchase
or lease of a 1988 car equipped with an air bag.
   State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Co. on Tuesday announced
a premium discount of from $3 to $24 for cars equipped with air
bags or passive belts, which automatically wrap around a car
occupant.
   Robert F. McDermott, chairman of USAA, told a news conference he
expected air bags to be available as an option or standard
equipment in several million cars within the next 18 months.
   The auto industry in the past has complained that while
insurance companies have campaigned to get air bags into cars they
have not offered car owners financial incentives to order the
safety devices.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Census-OMB Settle on 1990 Questions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispute between government agencies over the
questions to be asked on the 1990 Census has been settled, before
Friday's deadline for reporting to Congress.
   The Census Bureau reported Wednesday that it had settled its
differences with the White House Office of Management and Budget
over how many households would receive the longer, more detailed
form to obtain the national head count.
   OMB had wanted to reduce paperwork by deleting some questions
and reducing the number of people who get the more complex long
form.
   The two agencies have agreed that all 106 million households in
the nation will be sent the short form, while the more detailed
long form will go to 17.7 million. Census had wanted to sent it to
nearly 20 million households, OMB to limit it to 10 million.
   Short form questions on plumbing facilities and condominiums
will be switched to the long form, as OMB suggested. But other
questions will be retained, including the cost of uilities.
   Some things that were asked in the 1980 census will be dropped
in 1990. These include employment five years earlier, marital
history, weeks spent looking for work, number of bathrooms, air
conditioning and heating equipment, presence of an elevator and
type of fuel used for cooking and heating water.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Navy Secretary Takes Oath of Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Ball has become the nation's 67th
secretary of the Navy, pledging to keep his forces ``strong and
prepared'' to meet any challenge.
   Standing in an ornate Old Executive Office Building room first
used by Navy Secretary Richard Thompson in 1879, Ball said
Wednesday that by maintaining military strength, the United States
``preserve the peace and ultimately extend the special gift that is
freedom the world over.''
   President Reagan, making remarks at the swearing-in ceremony for
his former legislative liaison, said Ball had ``won the respect of
the leaders of both parties.'' He said ``I've repeatedly turned''
to Ball for help and advice in recent years.
   White House chief of staff Howard Baker swore in Ball as several
Cabinet officers, members of Congress and military officers looked
on. After Thompson, who served under President Rutherford B. Hayes,
14 Navy secretaries used the room, heavily decorated in naval motif.
   Ball, 39, succeeds James Webb, who resigned in a dispute with
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci over Pentagon budgetary
priorities, including a delay in reaching the 600-ship level for
the Navy.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sears to Halt Lawn Dart Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. has agreed to halt
sales of lawn darts, following a federal complaint about the
potentially dangerous sports items, according to the Consumer
Product Safety Commission.
   Sears agreed in a consent decree to stop selling lawn darts
within a week, the commission said Wedenesday.
   The decree settles charges that the nationwide retailer offered
lawn darts for sale without required warning labels and in areas
near toy sales.
   ``Sears' prompt response to the commission's concerns should
serve as an example for manufacturers and other retailers of lawn
darts,'' said commission Chairman Terrence M. Scanlon.
   Lawn darts are an outdoor game in which large, pointed darts are
tossed at targets on the ground. They can pose a serious hazard,
with three deaths reported in the last 18 years and an estimated
670 annual injuries, the safety agency said.
   The agency asked that consumers report injuries or improper
sales of lawn darts by calling it at 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
