<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HeartDisease-Stress     03-31 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heart Disease-Stress,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`21st Century Medicine' Finding New Ways To Test, Manage Stress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someday, doctors will have a system for
identifying stress-plagued patients who are headed for heart
trouble even though their blood pressure readings may look normal,
says a heart researcher.
   Dr. Robert S. Eliot, a cardiovascular researcher from Denver,
told cardiologists meeting in Atlanta this week that new ways of
testing can identify ``hot reactors'' _ stressed but seemingly
healthy people.
   ``These are people who fight saber-toothed tigers 30, 40 times a
day and don't even know it,'' Eliot told reporters Wednesday at the
annual meeting of the American College of Cardiology.
   ``A doctor can't tell from resting blood pressure (tests taken
at rest),'' he said, adding that conventional blood pressure
readings don't tell how much blood is pumping or how much
resistance the heart is fighting.
   Eliot, director of the cardiovascular institute at Denver's
Swedish Medical Center, has worked 10 years on ways to measure the
rapid, stress-induced fluctuations in the cardiovascular system.
   That work, he said, has yielded a 30-minute test using devices
to monitor heart performance, blood pressure and other factors to
find ``hot reactors,'' who apparently make up more than 10 percent
of the population.
   With so many seemingly healthy people at risk of illness, within
three to eight months in some cases, he said, ``I think it's worth
testing in people.''
   Eliot and his colleagues plan to expand their efforts to three
other locations next year. Someday soon, he hopes, physicians will
agree on a standard way of conducting such stress tests.
   ``We have a model,'' he said. ``It's been successful.''
   Those efforts are part of what Eliot terms ``a new kind of
medicine,'' emphasizing not just technical medical techniques, but
beneficial lifestyle adjustments. Some, he noted, have called it
``medicine from the 21st century _ teaching people what they can do
for themselves.''
   ``Drugs and surgery are not sufficient for most people'' with
cardiovascular problems, said Dr. Dean Ornish, an assistant
professor at the University of California at San Francisco School
of Medicine and president of the Preventative Medicine Research
Institute.
   ``Cardiology has tended to ignore the role of the brain on the
heart,'' Ornish said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0067 </DOCNO>
