<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     03-31 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedtech Witness: They Didn't Ask, I Didn't Tell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Wedtech Corp. official has admitted
that he waited months before telling prosecutors about his alleged
attempt to offer a $200,000 bribe to U.S. Attorney General Edwin
Meese III.
   Mario Moreno, former vice chairman of the defunt Bronx defense
contractor, says prosecutors didn't ask him about Meese and he
didn't volunteer the information.
   A prosecutor, however, objected to defense attorney Dominick
Amorosa's line of questioning Wednesday at the racketeering trial
of Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., and six others.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mary Shannon explained, with the jury
out of the room, that prosecutors in Manhattan were barred from
inquiring about Meese because he was then being investigated in
Washington under the special prosecutor law.
   Meese has not been charged with any wrongdoing, although a
special prosecutor continues to investigate his dealings with
Wedtech, a local manufacturer that won millions of dollars in
defense contracts.
   The attorney general's legal troubles have placed him under
increasing pressure to step down, triggered in part by the
resignation of some of his top aides earlier this week.
   Ms. Shannon also said the special prosecutor initially was
investigating former White House aide Lyn Nofziger, not Meese,
until last May. Nofziger was convicted last month of illegal
lobbying for Wedtech.
   Biaggi, his eldest son, Richard, and the other co-defendants are
accused of turning Wedtech into a racketeering enterprise that paid
bribes to public officials and others.
   Moreno is one of four former Wedtech officers cooperating with
the government in a bid for leniency.
   He has previously testified that he and former Wedtech President
Anthony Guariglia offered $200,000 to E. Robert Wallach, a close
friend of the attorney general, ``to fix the case'' with Meese.
   He also said that Wallach never got back to them and the money
never was paid.
   In his 12th day on the witness stand, Moreno admitted under
prodding by Amorosa, Richard Biaggi's attorney, that he did not
tell prosecutors about the bribe offer until at least August 1987,
more than eight months after he and the other ex-Wedtech officers
began cooperating with investigators.
   Wallach, former Meese financial adviser W. Franklyn Chinn, and
another man have been indicted in a separate case, charged with
allegedly taking payoffs from Wedtech to influence Meese and other
government officials.
   All three have pleaded innocent.
</TEXT>
