<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-Nuclear     03-31 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Nuclear,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Replacing Nuclear Plant That Concerned U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official today confirmed that
Taiwan is replacing a research nuclear reactor. The United States
long has worried the reactor could be used in an atomic weapons
development program.
   Liu Kuang-chi, secretary-general of the government Atomic Energy
Council, said the United States was assisting in converting the
reactor to a new system that would provide ``less possibility to
produce plutonium,'' a key component in the production of atomic
weapons.
   The comments were made one week after The New York Times
reported the Reagan administration pressured Taiwan to close the
reactor and to stop work on a secret installation that could have
processed the reactor's spent fuel to extract plutonium.
   Liu had earlier confirmed that the research reactor at Lung Tan,
25 miles southwest of Taipei, was closed in January but denied the
move was made because of U.S. pressure.
   Today, however, he acknowledged that ``maybe there's some
influence (from) the United States'' behind the decision to replace
the reactor, adding that Washington ``did express its concern about
our research.''
   The energy official said the U.S. concern over Lung Tan goes
back many years and may partly be caused by reports that India
developed atomic weaponry using a reactor of the same design.
   Liu reiterated Taiwan's position of not developing atomic bombs
and said of the Lung Tan overhaul, ``Since we decided not to make
(atomic) weapons, why not make them (the United States) happy?''
   Liu said the main reason for changing Lung Tan's design was to
make it compatible with Taiwan's nuclear power reactors, which run
on a different system.
   ``It's a major change, the reactor is completely changed,'' Liu
said. ``It is a very major task ... It is keeping everybody busy.''
He said the conversion would take at least two years, but he did
not have a cost estimate.
   According to Liu, the United States is providing technical help
and will provide assistance in obtaining fuel for testing the new
core.
   The Lung Tan reactor, which opened in 1973, has used heavy water
to control the splitting of atomic nuclei, a system that can use
natural uranium as fuel. The reactor is being converted to a
``light water'' system that requires enriched uranium fuel.
   Chang Kuo-lung, professor of physics of the National Taiwan
University, said the high-tech production of enriched uranium is
limited to a few countries, making the fuel comparatively difficult
to obtain and its use easier to monitor. Liu said Taiwan cannot
make the enriched fuel.
   Liu also stressed that Taiwan doesn't have facilities to process
spent fuel into weapons-grade plutonium. When asked whether Taiwan
had worked on a secret processing installation, he replied:
``Baloney.''
   Still, local newspapers have been filled with reports that the
U.S. government learned from a missing top-level Taiwanese nuclear
researcher that Taiwan had plans to make nuclear weapons.
   The media reports claim that Col. Chang Hsien-yi, former deputy
director of the official Nuclear Energy Research Center, is working
for the CIA and has moved to the United States since disappearing
in January.
   Liu, who previously worked with Chang, said he did not know
where the missing official was or what had happened to him.
   Taiwan's nuclear policy is a particularly sensitive topic
because Communist China has said Taiwan production of atomic
weapons would be a reason for invading the island, which Beijing
views as a renengade province.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
