<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NaslundMemorial     03-31 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Naslund Memorial,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Inters Mementos Of Daughter Allegedly Slain by Bundy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A casket empty except for a dress, a rose and
other remembrances was interred during a brief ceremony attended by
a dozen mourners of Denise Naslund, allegedly murdered by killer
Ted Bundy 14 years ago.
   The 20-minute memorial on Wednesday was as close as Denise's
mother, Eleanor Rose, could get to the realization of a longtime
wish that her 18-year-old daughter be buried.
   Fragments of Denise's bones were found strewn in the wooded
Cascade foothills east of Seattle in the summer of 1974. King
County authorities, who kept the remains as part of their
investigation of Bundy, lost them years ago.
   Looking on through tears, Ms. Rose watched Wednesday as a pink
casket, containing only her daughter's favorite dress, a silk rose,
a crucifix and some photographs and letters, was buried at a
cemetery on a West Seattle hillside.
   ``Oh for the touch of a vanished hand and the sound of a voice
that is still,'' the Rev. Desmond McMahon quoted poet Alfred
Tennyson during the service.
   King County police called Bundy, 41, their prime suspect in the
deaths of Ms. Naslund and 23-year-old Janice Ott, but he never was
charged in the cases. He is on death row in Florida for three
murders in that state.
</TEXT>
