<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BankDeregulation     03-31 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Deregulation,440</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: RETRANSMITTING a0435 to correct overline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bank Securities Bill Clears Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation granting bank holding companies
broad new securities powers is heading into the House after getting
an overwhelming endorsement in the Senate.
   Senators voted 94-2 Wednesday night to approve a bill that would
permit the mingling of commercial and investment banking for the
first time since the Depression.
   The legislation substantially revises restrictions on banks in
the Glass-Steagall Act, passed in 1933 in reaction to abuses
preceding the 1929 stock market crash.
   Proponents of change argued that developments in the financial
system, particularly in the last decade, threaten the ability of
banks to compete. Securities firms, for instance, offer bank-like
services such as commercial paper and money market mutual funds.
   The Senate bill would permit bank holding companies to
underwrite and sell mortgage-backed securities, commercial paper
and municipal revenue bonds immediately after the bill is approved
by both houses of Congress and signed by President Reagan, who
favors the bill.
   Bank holding companies would be allowed to underwrite and sell
corporate bonds and mutual funds six months after enactment. A vote
by Congress would be required in 1991 before bank holding companies
could underwrite corporate stock, the most lucrative securities
activity.
   Wednesday evening's vote came after nearly six hours of debate
in which Senate Banking Committee Chairman William Proxmire,
D-Wis., warded off amendments that could have unraveled the
delicate compromise adopted on an 18-2 vote by his committee
earlier this month.
   The bill is seen as something of a swan song for Proxmire, who
retires next year after more than 30 years in the Senate. Just
before its adoption, it was named the Proxmire Financial
Modernization Act of 1988.
   Donald Ogilvie, executive vice president of the American Bankers
Association, the biggest industry group pushing for the bill's
passage, praised it as benefiting consumers.
   ``This should accelerate the momentum for enlightened financial
reform legislation in the House,'' he said.
   However, the House Banking Committee is split into many
factions. Its chairman, Rep. Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I., has
released a proposal that would grant banks only a few securities
powers _ commercial paper, mortgage revenue bonds and asset-backed
securities _ and places more restrictions on banks.
   Ogilvie said bankers would work in the House to defeat limits on
banks' insurance activities, but his industry faces tougher going
there than it did in the Senate.
   One provision of the Senate bill would require banks to prove
they are meeting the needs of poor citizens and neighborhoods
before getting permission to exercise the new powers authorized in
the bill.
   Another prohibits misleading savings account advertisements, and
another requires lenders to disclose terms of home equity loans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0640EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GuardianConvicted     03-31 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Guardian Convicted,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Public Guardian Found Guilty Of Theft, Misconduct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former public guardian, convicted of
stealing as much as $200,000 from mentally handicapped or elderly
wards, may have to repay all the money, a prosecutor says.
   Multnomah County Circuit Judge Winston L. Bradshaw on Wednesday
found Paul E. Nizdil, 44, guilty of 12 counts of felony theft and
12 counts of official misconduct, a misdemeanor. Sentencing was set
for May 24.
   Nizdil, who was fired in October as the county's public guardian
and conservator, was convicted after the defense and prosecution
agreed to submit police reports as the only evidence.
   The agreement calls for Nizdil to repay the stolen money, but
the exact amount was not set, defense attorney Janet Hoffman said.
The total could be upwards of $200,000, said Deputy District
Attorney Jeffrey Martin.
   Each theft count carries a maximum sentence of five years in
prison. Each misconduct count carries a maximum penalty of a year
in jail.
   Nizdil remains free on his own recognizance pending sentencing.
   Ms. Martin said the state had not yet prepared a sentencing
recommendation, but said the state had made no sentencing
concessions in its agreement with Nizdil.
   Nizdil was indicted on 22 counts each of theft and misconduct.
Ms. Martin said there was evidence of additional thefts, but said
that evidence will not be presented to a grand jury because of the
agreement.
   Ms. Martin said an investigation into Nizdil's conduct before
his firing had not been completed. If Nizdil continues cooperating
with the investigation, the state will move for dismissal of the
remaining counts, she said.
   Ms. Hoffman said Nizdil suffers from a compulsion to gamble, and
told the judge she would call two doctors to testify on Nizdil's
behalf at his sentencing.
   Last month, Nizdil repaid the county $65,334, the amount
identified up to that point as having been stolen.
   Since then, the state's estimate of the total amount taken from
elderly or mentally handicapped wards has increased from $114,000
to $200,000.
   Nizdil admitted to police that on several occasions he made
checks payable to a fictitious name for repairs allegedly made to
houses owned by wards. Nizdil told police he used money from the
checks to pay gambling debts.
   Nizdil was fired for reasons unrelated to the thefts. County
officials did not discover the missing money until January, when
tenants renting a house owned by a ward complained that repairs had
not been made.
</TEXT>
