<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FlyBoy     03-31 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fly Boy,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>9-Year-Old Boy Begins 10-Day Cross-Country Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old nicknamed ``Buzz'' is
winging his way across America on a 10-day flight planned as the
longest trip by a boy believed to be the nation's youngest
unlicensed pilot.
   Tony Aliengena of San Juan Capistrano, who earlier this month
made a one-mile solo in an ultra-light plane, was at the controls
of his father's twin-engine Cessna on Wednesday as it left John
Wayne Airport.
   Tony was accompanied by his flight instructor, Ed Fernett, and
Don Taylor, an observer from the National Aeronautics Association.
Taylor will verify that Tony is at the controls throughout the
flight.
   ``The goal is to do it by myself. Even if we lose an engine, I'm
gonna do it,'' Tony said in an interview before leaving.
   Tony's father, Gary Aliengena, said his son would fly four to
seven hours a day during the 10-day trip. Tony will not fly Sunday
so he can spend Easter with relatives in Massachusetts.
   Tony wants to break the longest-trip-by-youngest-pilot record
set by 10-year-old Christopher Lee Marshall of Oceano, who flew
from San Luis Obispo County to Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and back to
Burbank last August.
   On March 13, Tony set a record as the youngest pilot to fly solo
when he flew his father's ultra-light plane _ which is not
regulated by the Federal Aviation Administration _ around Oceanside
Municipal Airport.
   In order for Tony to fly a larger plane like the Cessna, Tony
must have a licensed instructor in the cockpit with him.
   His latest trip includes landings in El Paso, Texas; Dallas;
Memphis, Tenn.; Gastonia, N.C.; Richmond, Va.; Bedford, Mass.;
Washington; Evansville, Ind.; St. Louis; Oklahoma City; Tucumcari,
N.M.; and Phoenix, Ariz.
</TEXT>
