<HEAD>Woman Claims As Many As 20 Men Raped Her</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine men have been charged with raping a
woman who told authorities that her attackers urged other men
gathered at an illegal cockfight to join in.
   The 19-year-old woman said she was abducted as she walked on a
street and taken to a rural South Texas area where as many as 20
men raped her in a parked car, according to assistant district
attorney Rodolfo V. Gutierrez.
   Warrants charging nine local men with sexual assault were
issued, said Efrain Perez, chief investigator with the Duval County
Sheriff's Department. Four were arrested as of Wednesday, and more
arrests were expected, said Gutierrez. Charges of kidnapping could
be added, he said.
   Authorities said many of the approximately 30 men at the illegal
sporting event Saturday night knew the attack was going on but did
nothing to rescue the victim, a mother of two children, even though
she was crying out for help.
   ``Morally, it was not right for them to stand there,'' Gutierrez
said, noting that legally the individuals could be charged with
failure to render aid.
   ``I don't think it was planned. I think it was spontaneous,'' he
said. ``There is no way to justify this.
   The victim was taken Sunday morning to Humana Hospital at Corpus
Christi for treatment and was released earlier this week, Carrillo
said.
   ``She was afraid to tell her husband,'' Carrillo said. ``He had
been looking for her all night.'' He said her husband convinced her
to file charges on Monday.
   Ricardo ``Rocky'' Carrillo, an investigator with the Duval
County District Attorney's office, said some of the alleged rapists
``egged others on'' to sexually assault the victim.
   Authorities said the woman was able to identify some of the men
while others attempted to disguise themselves by holding their
hands over their faces.
   The four arrested were Jose Carlos ``Payo'' Briones, 29, Roel
``Roy'' Torres, 24, Adolfo Quintanilla Jr., 28, and Roberto Andres
Garcia, 21, all of San Diego.
   All four were free on bonds of $20,000 each, a spokeswoman for
Justice of the Peace Amado Garcia Jr. said.
   Sexual assault is a second-degree felony punishable by a
sentence of two to 20 years in prison.
