<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MiniskirtPoll     03-31 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miniskirt Poll,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Surprise: Men Prefer Short Skirts On Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While conceding that the style is inappropriate
at times, men are far less willing than women to once again consign
the miniskirt to fashion history, according to a poll published
today.
   Some 36 percent of men say they prefer above-the-knee hemlines
for women's skirts, according to the New York Times-CBS News poll.
That compares with only a quarter of adult women who say they've
worn a skirt that short in the past year.
   In addition, 71 percent of the men surveyed say they favor
skirts at or above the knee, while 46 percent of women say they
prefer skirts below the knee.
   While men, such as Greg Parker, a 25-year-old Palm Bay, Fla.
engineer, said they found the short skirts ``attractive'' and
``sexy-looking,'' they also admit that longer lengths are often
more practical.
   ``If you're in a (business) meeting and everyone's dressed
conservatively, there's less distraction'' with longer skirts,
Parker said.
   Ted Austin, a Richmond, Va. real-estate broker and developer,
likened working women in short skirts to men in shorts and beach
shirts at the office.
   ``I don't think it's acceptable today,'' he said.
   The less-than eager reaction from women to the shorter lengths
introduced en masse for spring precipitated a recent return by
designers to some longer lengths in their fall collections.
   Among different age groups, slightly more than half of women 18
to 29 years old said they'd worn miniskirts, while 27 percent of
women 30 to 44 and only 8 percent of women 45 to 64 said they had.
   That perhaps confirms the opinion of one poll respondent,
24-year-old model Regina Lynn of Rogersville, Ala., who said she's
noticed ``older women don't look good in them.''
   Only 20 percent of married women said they had worn miniskirts
in the last year, compared with 56 percent of the
never-been-marrieds.
   One unmarried woman who did not want her name used said it would
be a lie to say she did not choose her clothes partly to please men.
   ``I don't go out of my way if I'm going to be in a meeting all
day just with women,'' she said.
   The poll of 1,654 adults was conducted by telephone between
March 19 and 22 and had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus
3 percent for women and 4 percent for men. The potential error for
smaller subgroups is larger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
