<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Witness-Reward,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Witness Gets $126,500 from City for House and a $25,000
Reward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug-case witness whose house was being
guarded by a police officer who was killed will receive a $25,000
reward in addition to $126,000 for his house.
   The city agreed to buy the home of Arjune, a Guyanese immigrant
who uses only one name, after officer Edward Byrne was slain Feb.
26 while guarding it. The officer was there because the house had
been firebombed twice after Arjune complained about neighborhood
drug dealers.
   Since Byrne's killing, for which four men have been arrested,
the city had been using the house as a base for a narcotics task
force.
   The city originally offered $140,000 for the house, which was
appraised at at $126,000.
   City Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin last week forced a $13,500
cut in the price, arguing that if the city wanted to give Arjune a
reward, it should not do so by inflating the price of the house.
   Goldin said Wednesday he had arranged for private donors who
wished to remain anonymous to give the witness a $25,000 reward.
