<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Waldheim     03-31 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Waldheim,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Waldheim May Have Worked For U.S., British
Intelligence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kurt Waldheim may have cooperated with U.S. and
British intelligence services after World War II in return for
having his German army record purged of incriminating evidence, a
British newspaper reported today.
   A panel of historians has concluded the Austrian president was
``in close proximity'' to some Nazi atrocities in the Balkans, knew
they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them. It also
said Waldheim concealed his wartime past and tried to make it seem
harmless once he could no longer hide it.
   The international panel of historians left open the question of
whether he was guilty of any crime. Waldheim has denied any
wrongdoing.
   The Times of London said today it had unearthed evidence that
British wartime documents and subsequent British Foreign Office
papers likely to relate to Waldheim's wartime role had been
suppressed.
   The report, by correspondent Robert Fisk, said the suppression
raised suspicion Waldheim may have collaborated with the Americans
and British after the war in return for having his German army
record purged.
   Fisk quoted Robert Herzstein, a University of South Carolina
history professor, as saying he believes Waldheim passed on large
amounts of information after the war to Allied intelligence agents,
especially on communist partisans in Yugoslavia and guerrillas in
Greece.
   Herzstein is due to publish a book next week that suggests
Waldheim worked for the Americans after the war.
   Fisk quoted him as saying several records of the British element
in the United Nations War Crimes Commission appeared to be missing
from the British government's Public Records Office.
   Fisk's report said The Times had examined hundreds of wartime
files at the Public Records Office. Fisk said that in one file on
military activities in Yugoslavia between May 1944 and the end of
the war, when Waldheim was in Dubrovnik, an entire section listed
in the index as ``allegations of murder of British prisoners of
war'' was missing.
   The reporter said a government order had closed a file on the
slayings to public access until the year 2021.
   He quoted officials at the Public Records Office as saying they
did not know when the order was issued. But he said the government
decision to prevent public access was taken before 1982, when
Waldheim ended his 10-year term as U.N. secretary-general.
   Allegations about Waldheim's alleged links to wartime atrocities
surfaced in 1986 during his campaign for the Austrian presidency.
   Fisk said attempts by The Times to seek access to specific
``closed'' files and to obtain reasons for their retention were
refused.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0745EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-Gunboat     03-31 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Gunboat,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Finds Anti-Aricraft Missiles, Rockets on Iranian Boat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two portable anti-aircraft missiles,
tentatively identified as Soviet-made SAM-7s, were found aboard an
Iranian gunboat recovered by the U.S. Navy last week, a Navy
spokesman said today.
   The weapons on the boat, found abandoned and drifting in the
Strait of Hormuz, also included three ``chaff rockets'' of unknown
origin and four other unidentified rockets with fusing devices.
   Chaff is a material blown into the air to confuse the homing
system of a radar-guided missile.
   Maj. Barry Willey, a spokesman for the U.S. Central Command,
said the twin-barrelled gun mounted in the cockpit of the 30-foot
boat was a Soviet-made ZSU 23mm anti-aircraft weapon.
   The gun apparently had been used for attacks on ships in the
southern Persian Gulf and the Hormuz. It was rusty, but functional,
and was loaded for firing when found.
   Authoritative references say the Soviet SAM-7, a shoulder-fired
missile similar to the American-made Redeye, is known to be a part
of Iran's weapons inventory. But Willey said he did not know
whether it had previously been seen in the gulf.
   Iran also is believed to possess some U.S.-made Stinger
missiles, a more advanced missile than the Redeye. It fired at
least one at a U.S. helicopter last October, but missed.
   Several Stingers and a spent launcher were found in a sunken
Iranian speedboat recovered by U.S. Navy divers on Jan. 3.
   The gunboat, an open-cockpit, twin-diesel craft, was found by
the guided missile frigate Reuben James, drifting in 10-foot seas
in the Hormuz passage last Thursday.
   The boat's whereabouts were not disclosed. Willey would say only
that it was in U.S. Navy custody.
   U.S. officers have said they do not know why the boat apparently
was abandoned by the Iranians. It appeared to have been recently
vacated by its crew and was trailing a sea anchor.
   The fiberglass-hulled boat was the fourth Iranian small craft
captured by the Navy in the Persian Gulf in the past six months,
but the first taken in the southern waterway where Iran's naval
frigates and Revolutionary Guards concentrate their surface raids
on neutral shipping.
   In addition to the rockets and missiles, Willey said the boat
yielded one Soviet-designed AK-47 assault rifle and 203 rounds of
ammunition, 500 rounds of ammunition for the mounted gun, and
related items.
   The missiles apparently were contained in a sealed wooden box,
six feet long, found in the bottom of the boat.
   Officers on the Reuben James did not open the box, but there was
speculation at the time that it might contain Stingers or other
portable rockets.
   The SAM-7, known as the ``Strela,'' or arrow in Russian, has an
effective range of about two miles, atttacking aircraft by homing
in on their engine exhaust.
   Although it has been replaced in the Soviet inventory by a newer
portable missile, the SAM-14, the Strela is still being produced
for Soviet forces and for export sales.
   It also is manufactured by China and Egypt, and more than 40
countries, including both Iran and Iraq, are believed to have the
weapon in their arsenals.
   U.S. officials gave no further information on the chaff rockets
found on the Iranian boat. Such rockets are carried aboard most
warships and aircraft in the gulf.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0085 </DOCNO>
