<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MolePatrol 1stLd-Writethru a0507 03-31 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mole Patrol, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0507,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mole Mobiles Help Catch Thief, Please Merchants</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf and 11th graf, ``Myers said xxx, to CORRECT
that concourse is NOT above ground; and SUBS 7th graf, ``We see
xxx, to delete extraneous said</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Mole Patrol'' is on a roll.
   For nine years, Officer Charles Myers worked underground,
patrolling the 3{-mile network of corridors, platforms and tunnels
of Philadelphia's mass-transit system. His unit was justly dubbed
the Mole Patrol.
   He now helps run the Police Department's two battery-powered
carts, which cruise silently through the concourse at the hub of
the city's transportation system.
   The white and blue industrial carts, fitted with searchlights,
rescue gear, two-way radio, roll bar and dome lights, can carry
8,400 pounds and have a top speed of about 10 mph. They cost $6,200
apiece.
   The new carts were quickly dubbed ``mole mobiles.'' After all,
``transit response vehicles'' just sounds too stuffy.
   Before the carts came, if Myers heard of trouble in another part
of the concourse, ``it would be a footrace,'' he said. ``You'd be
exhausted by the time you got there.''
   ``We see a very positive response by all the store owners,''
Capt. Lawrence Norton, commander of the transit unit, said
Wednesday.
   ``They see this cart, they come out and want to say hello. The
public stops you all the time,'' he said. ``They get a real kick
out of the fact that the police are down here in strength.''
   Within the next year the department hopes to add five more of
the vehicles, because a cart is cheaper than paying for extra
officers, Norton said.
   The vehicles are parked and recharged during morning and evening
rush hours, when the transit system's 350,000 daily passengers clog
the passageways.
   Myers said he and another officer arrested a burglar their first
night, when they received a suspicious-person report and sped off
to a far-off part of the concourse, which features stores,
restaurants and banks.
   ``Lo and behold, there's a man standing there inside a closed
store,'' Myers said. ``The only thing he said was, `I didn't hear
you coming.'''
</TEXT>
