<HEAD>Sir William McMahon, Former Australian Prime Minister, Dead At 80</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf: ``He became...'' to CLARIFY that Gorton was
ousted in 1971. Pick up 5th graf pvs: ``Prime Minister...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir William McMahon, a former prime
minister, died today after a long battle with cancer. He was 80.
   McMahon died early today at St. Luke's Hospital in Sydney and
was cremated in a private service shortly afterward, family members
said.
   McMahon served as prime minister and head of the Liberal Party
in 1971-72, and previously headed the Treasury and Foreign Affairs
Department.
   He became prime minister on March 10, 1971, after John Gorton
was ousted as prime minister and Liberal Party leader in a dispute
within the party. But McMahon lost to Gough Whitlam the following
year. McMahon entered Parliament in 1949.
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke of the Labor Party praised McMahon's
service.
   ``Although on opposite sides of the political fence, I found Sir
William a generous opponent. He maintained an enormous enthusiasm
for and interest in public affairs after his retirement from
Parliament and was constructive in his discussions on economics and
political matters,'' Hawke said in a statement.
   Liberal Party leader John Howard said: ``Few parliamentarians in
the postwar period could boast a career as rich and diverse as Sir
William's.''
   Former Liberal Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser called McMahon a
vigorous administrator and tenacious member of Parliament who would
be remembered for three decades of dedicated service.
   McMahon is survived by his wife, Lady Sonia, his son, Julian,
and two daughters, Belinda and Deborah.
</TEXT>
