<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SexOffenderSign     03-31 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sex Offender Sign,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Woman To Wear Sign Declaring Herself Sex Offender</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former preschool worker has been ordered to
wear a sign around her neck about her sex offenses after she
pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges of sexually assaulting two
girls.
   King County Superior Court Judge Warren Chan on Wednesday gave
Julia Lynn Guptill-Gilbert of Bothell a choice between spending 30
days in jail or wearing the sign for 60 days every time she goes
out in public.
   Ms. Guptill-Gilbert chose to wear the sign. She taught at a
Montessori school at the time of the assaults on two girls, aged 4
and 5.
   Chan left it up to county prosecutors to decide the size and
exact wording of the sign to be worn by the 19-year-old woman, who
is five months pregnant.
   ``My words to her were that she must wear a sign saying: `I've
been convicted of communicating with a minor for immoral
purposes,''' Chan said.
   Chan also ordered Ms. Guptill-Gilbert to write letters of
apology to both victims, who were in court.
   Both prosecution and defense attorneys objected to the ruling.
   ``Our office has a preference for punishment that includes
confinement, supervision and treatment, and we prefer those methods
over the ones used by the judge in this case,'' said Dan Donohoe,
the King County prosecutor's administrative assistant.
   ``You get to the matter of whether the punishment is cruel and
unusual,'' he said. ``I'm not a lawyer, but I do think it's
unusual.''
   Prosecutors had recommended a suspended one-year jail term for
Ms. Guptill-Gilbert, plus payment of counseling costs for the
children and a mental health evaluation for Ms. Guptill-Gilbert.
   Defense attorney Michael Frost said Ms. Guptill-Gilbert is
likely to stay in her residence the entire 60-day period to avoid
wearing the sign in public.
   Ms. Guptill-Gilbert already has moved to California, raising
questions about how sign order will be enforced.
   Chan has scheduled a court hearing May 4 to find out whether
California authorities will assume responsibility for monitoring
the punishment. The 60-day period for wearing the sign isn't to
begin until then.
   ``If she feels that wearing a sign is too much of a burden for
her out in the public, all she has to do is stay home, which serves
the same purpose as keeping her in the jail,'' Chan said.
</TEXT>
