<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0526 03-31 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Missiles Hit Iran; Iranian Gunboats Attack Tanker In Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with three missiles fired at Iran
before proposed truce to go into effect, Iran agreeing to truce,
Navy finds abandoned Iranian gunboat and seizes its arms. No pickup.
^By MONA ZIADE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said today it would stop missile
attacks on Iranian cities for three days beginning at midnight,
then said it fired three missiles into Iran 10 hours before the
truce was to begin.
   In another development, an Iranian warship today attacked and
set ablaze a Cypriot supertanker in the southern Persian Gulf. The
tanker's crew of 45 was rescued by salvage tugboats after the
tanker ran aground.
   Also today, the U.S. Navy said two anti-aircraft missiles that
may be Soviet-made SAM-7s were found aboard an Iranian gunboat the
Navy discovered abandoned and drifting at the southern end of the
gulf.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said one
of the three Iraqi long-range missiles fired at Iran hit Qom, seat
of Iran's religious hierarchy, and two hit Isfahan, capital of the
ancient Persian empire.
   It said the missiles were fired about 2 p.m. local time, 10
hours before the proposed cease-fire was to begin.
   Iran had no immediate reaction to the missile attacks on
Isfahan, in western Iran, and Qom, 100 miles south of Tehran.
   But an Iranian Embassy official in Ankara, Turkey, was quoted as
saying today that Iran will comply with the proposed cease-fire if
Iraq does.
   ``Iranian attacks will automatically come to an end if Iraq
stops the war of the cities,'' embassy spokesman Riza Bagri was
quoted as saying by the semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
   Hundreds of civilians have been killed in the missile duel
during which Iraq fired 105 missiles into Tehran, 13 into Qom and
10 into Isfahan since Feb. 29. Iran says it fired 45 missiles into
Baghdad, a city of 5 million people, and dozens into the northern
city of Mosul and other cities in Iraq.
   The Iraqi News Agency today quoted an unidentified government
spokesman as saying the cease-fire was ``a gesture of courtesy'' to
Turkish Prime Minister Turgut Ozal, who was scheduled to begin a
48-hour visit to Iraq on Friday.
   Ozal was on an official visit to Tehran on Feb. 29, and one of
the first Iraqi missiles fired into Tehran crashed near a downtown
hotel where members of the Turkish delegation were staying. None of
the Turkish officials was hurt.
   In the Persian Gulf, an Iranian warship attacked the 232,164-ton
Haven tanker near the Strait of Hormuz at the southern end of the
gulf sand set its load of Saudi crude oil on fire, gulf-based
shipping executives said.
   The ship drifted for more than three hours after the dawn attack
and eventually ran aground off the United Arab Emirates, said the
executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The crew was
rescued by salvage tugboats.
   At least eight tugs fought the fire on the grounded tanker for
three hours before the blaze was controlled, the executives said.
Oil was gushing out of two blasted cargo holds, burning on the
waters around the tanker.
   They said the Iranian warship launched three separate attacks on
the Haven over the course of an hour. The London-based Lloyd's
Shipping Intelligence Unit said the Iranian ship was a frigate and
the tanker was bound for Indonesia.
   A U.S. Navy spokesman today said two portable anti-aircraft
missiles, tentatively identified as Soviet-made SAM-7s, were aboard
an Iranian gunboat the Navy found abandoned and drifting in the
Strait of Hormuz last week.
   Maj. Barry Willey, a spokesman for the U.S. Central Command,
said the twin-barrelled gun mounted in the cockpit of the 30-foot
boat was a Soviet-made ZSU 23mm anti-aircraft weapon.
   The gun, rusty but functional and loaded for firing when found,
apparently had been used for attacks on ships in the southern gulf
and Hormuz. The gun apparently was used for attacks on ships in the
southern gulf and the Hormuz.
   Authoritative references say the Soviet SAM-7, a shoulder-fired
missile similar to the U.S.-made Redeye, is known to be a part of
Iran's arms arsenal. But Willey said he did not know whether it was
previously seen in the gulf.
</TEXT>
