<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Backseat Delivery,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Lawsuit in Highway Birth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medical malpractice attorney Harvey Wachsman
momentarily weighed the possibility of a lawsuit against the doctor
who delivered his son in the back seat of his car on Grand Central
Parkway in Queens.
   ``Maybe I should sue, just for practice,'' he said on Wednesday.
   But he immediately decided against it because the defendant
would have been, well, himself.
   Derek Wachsman weighed in at 6 pounds, 9 ounces at about 1 a.m.
Wednesday in the back seat of a Mercedes 560 SEL about 200 yards
west of La Guardia Airport.
   The elder Wachsman and his wife Kathy, also a malpractice
lawyer, left their home on Long Island about 12:15 a.m., heading
full-tilt for Mount Sinai Hospital in Manhattan.
   But the baby wanted out well short of the hospital so Wachsman,
who was a neurosurgeon before he became a lawyer, pulled over,
delivered the baby and tied the umbilical cord with a shoelace.
   And what will Derek be when he grows up?
   ``A doctor and a lawyer,'' Wachsman said.
