<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Nusbaum 1stLd-Writethru a0460 03-31 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Nusbaum, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Believed World's Oldest Person Dies
^Eds: CORRECTS name to Nusbaum, sted Nussbaum, thruout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOSHEN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ulysses S. Grant was in the White House and
Gen. George Custer was one year away from making his last stand
when Orpha Nusbaum was born Aug. 13, 1875.
   Mrs. Nusbaum, believed by the Guinness Book of World Records to
be the world's oldest person, died Wednesday at age 112.
   She had pneumonia recently, but an official cause of death was
not released, said Diane Hostetler, director of nursing at
Fountainview Nursing Home, where Mrs. Nusbaum lived.
   ``Her condition worsened during the weekend,'' Miss Hostetler
said.
   ``She couldn't do anything for herself anymore,'' said a
stepdaughter-in-law, Betty Nusbaum. ``You can't do anything for a
person who doesn't want to live anymore.''
   Betty Nusbaum said she was saddened by the death, but said Mrs.
Nusbaum had lived a good life.
   Last month, Guinness officials said they believed she was the
oldest person alive.
   Mrs. Nusbaum was honored at a special ceremony in January when
officials put the Goshen city seal on census documents indicating
she was born in 1875 on the family farm near Middlebury about 10
miles away. She spent most of her life in Middlebury until moving
to the nursing home in 1982.
   Florence Knapp, who lived in a Philadelphia suburb, had been
recognized as the world's oldest person until her death Jan. 11.
She was 114 years and 94 days old.
   Guinness restricts recognition to those who can provide birth
records and other documentation.
   There had been some confusion whether Mrs. Nusbaum would be 112
or 113 last Aug. 13. For years she had maintained she was a year
older than she actually was.
   But a document found in the public library in this northern
Indiana city last September showed that the former Orpha Ulery was
4 years old when she was counted in the U.S. Census of 1880, making
her 112.
   Mrs. Nusbaum attributed her longevity to her strict obedience to
a biblical command, Betty Nusbaum said. ``She honored her father
and mother. That's it,'' she said.
   For many years Mrs. Nusbaum taught Sunday school in the Elkhart
and Goshen areas. When she was 93, she resumed writing poetry, a
hobby she had stopped in the 1920s.
   Mrs. Nusbaum married John Mischler, a minister, in 1897. After
his death, she married Frank Nusbaum in 1947. He died in 1959.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0859EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-HeartDisease     03-31 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Heart Disease,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heart Disease Early Indicator Of Some AIDS Cases, Researchers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardiologists should be aware that heart disease
can be an early indicator of AIDS, and some patients can live
longer with proper cardiac care, according to research presented at
the American College of Cardiology convention.
   In a 1983-86 study of 86 AIDS patients in Paris and Miami, 18
had heart disease and seven of those had heart disease before other
AIDS-related ailments, Dr. Evlin Kinney of the University of Miami
School of Medicine said Wednesday at the ACC meeting.
   ``Heart disease was present in 5 percent of all AIDS patients _
that's our estimate based on the patients we have seen,'' she said.
``Cardiologists need to be aware of AIDS heart disease.''
   While little could be done for AIDS patients suffering from
tumor-based heart disease, she said, cardiac disease stemming from
opportunistic infections such as tuberculosis _ rather than from
tumors _ can be treated, prolonging the lives of terminally ill
patients.
   ``There were patients who, with treatment, survived as long as
(AIDS) patients without heart disease,'' Kinney said. ``Some of
these patients, we did manage to prolong their lives for many
months.''
   AIDS cripples the body's ability to fight off disease, allowing
a variety of ailments _ including heart disease _ to cause death.
   Fourteen of the 18 AIDS heart patients were dead within four
months of diagnosis, but the other four _ all with
infection-related heart disease _ lived for about two years, she
said.
   Another participant in the study, Dr. Jean-Jacques Monsuez of
Hopital St. Louis in Paris, said early, specific diagnosis of the
ailments plaguing AIDS patients can help physicians prolong life.
Tuberculosis, for instance, is a frequent ailment in AIDS patients,
and it can be treated.
   ``If we can treat each organ involved, it's a very important
thing,'' Monsuez said.
   Kinney noted that there were only eight women among the 86 AIDS
patients studied, but half of them were suffering from AIDS-related
heart disease. While noting that the number of female patients was
small, she said, ``Females seem to be more susceptible to AIDS
heart disease ... the women were represented disproportionately.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
