<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0542,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Netanyahu Resigned To Protest Shultz Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with new quotes. Pick up 8th
graf pvs: `He said...' TRIMS thereafter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benjamin Netanyahu today said he resigned as
Israel's United Nations ambassador so he could speak out against
Secretary of State George P. Shultz's meeting with two
Arab-Americans linked to the PLO.
   ``The meeting raises a larger question of the value of American
commitments to us when we have made huge concessions to obtain
these guarantees,'' Netanyahu told The Associated Press, referring
to a 1975 American pledge not to meet with PLO members.
   ``As long as I was wearing an ambassador's suit, I couldn't
speak out openly,'' he told NBC ``Today'' from Tel Aviv. He said
the meeting could ``jeopardize Israel's very existence.''
   Netanyahu said he had been planning to resign in a few weeks,
but decided to speed it up after the Shultz meeting.
   His resignation was to take effect immediately. Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres has suggested Asher Ben-Natan, a former ambassador to
France and Germany, as a possible replacement.
   Netanyahu's resignation was the strongest message yet from
Israel regarding its displeasure over Shultz's meeting five days
ago with two members of the Palestine National Council, the PLO's
self-declared legislative body.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, meanwhile, sharpened his
opposition to the session with Edward Said and Ibrahim Abu Lughod,
both American citizens.
   He told members of his right-wing Likud bloc the meeting was ``a
slap in the face'' and said: ``The two men were representatives of
the PLO. It was possible to see on television how much they hate
Israel,'' the daily Yediot Ahronot reported today.
   Netanyahu, 39, who gained prominence as an articulate defender
of Israel's policies during his four years as U.N. ambassador, made
a surprise announcement of his resignation on Israel Television
Wednesday night.
   He said he was planning to resign ``in a matter of weeks''
anyway to allow him to begin campaigning for a seat as a Likud
legislator in November's elections.
   While stressing that he still had ``warm personal regard'' for
Shultz, Netanyahu said the secretary's meeting with Said and Abu
Lughod, both American citizens, had created ``a deep rift'' between
the United States and Israel.
   ``Even friends can sometimes take steps which are unacceptable
or dangerous,'' he said.
   Because of Shultz's meeting, Netanyahu said, ``It appears the
Palestine Liberation Organization will be introduced into the
proposed international conference through the back door.''
   ``The very clear possibility exists now that the PLO will sit
across the table from Israel in this conference and will be the
party we will be demanded to give land to,'' he said.
   ``Then the conference could result in a PLO state right in the
heart of Israel, threatening our very security, our very future.''
   Netanyahu said he would publicly oppose the American peace
initiative, particularily the portion which calls for an
international conference including the parties to the conflict and
the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council _ the
United States, Soviet Union, China, Britain and France.
   ``I will pound the pavement from city to city in order to
explain to the public the dangers of an international conference,''
he said.
</TEXT>
