<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SkiTrain     03-31 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ski Train,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cog Railway Owners Will Not Turn Away Skiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LACONIA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can carry your skis on the Mount
Washington Cog Railway, but you better not try to use them to ski
down the famous _ and treacherous _ Tuckerman Ravine.
   ``We don't plan to let the people who ride the train ski down
Tuckerman Ravine,'' said U.S. Forest Service spokesman Ned
Therrien. ``We will take some action to prevent people from
trespassing under federal regulations.''
   The railway last year proposed running a spring ski train to the
top of New England's highest peak for the Tuckerman ski season,
normally April and May. The Forest Service denied the necessary
permits.
   Railway Vice President Wayne Presby said the railway hasn't
advertised for skiers this year, but officials don't intend to try
to keep them off the rails.
   ``As a public utility, I can't discriminate against hikers,
sightseers or skiers,'' he said.
   The Forest Service said it feared letting skiers ride the train
up the mountain would increase the number of inexperienced skiers
trying to make the dangerous run down the ravine and its famed
headwall.
   Skiers who make the run have to hike nearly three miles to the
top of the mountain with their skis strapped to their backs.
   The Forest Service says forcing skiers to hike up the mountain
limits those who attempt the hairy descent to only the heartiest
and most experienced.
   Presby said the railway will begin operating this year on April
16.
   Meantime, Forest Service officials met Wednesday with Albert
Risch, who carries skiers to the headwall via chartered helicopter,
and urged him to stop the flights. The helicopter uses private
land, so the agency cannot order it to stop.
   Risch said he has not decided whether he'll bow to the agency's
wishes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
