<HEAD>Lebanese Troops Kill Two Syrian Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese soldiers killed two Syrian
soldiers in a battle in a Christian enclave early today, the first
clash between the forces in more than two years, military sources
said.
   The Lebanese opened fire on a Syrian patrol that entered the
eastern edge of the Christians' 300-square-mile enclave in
northeast Lebanon before dawn, one source said.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the two
sides clashed for about 30 minutes with automatic weapons and
grenades near the village of Zighrine. No Lebanese casualties were
reported.
   Zighrine, a Christian village, lies 15 miles northeast of Beirut.
   The source said the Syrian patrol ``withdrew from the Zighrine
area after the clash.'' He did not elaborate.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 25,000 troops
in eastern and northern provinces under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   Syria also has 7,500 troops in Moslem west Beirut seeking to
restore law and order after years of militia anarchy.
   The Lebanese army fought a series of battles with the Syrians in
the northeastern mountains in January 1986 after Christian
President Amin Gemayel torpedoed a Syrian-brokered accord to end
Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war.
