<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cuba-CIA     03-31 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-CIA,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Says Two CIA Spies Sentenced to Eight Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba's official news agency reported that a
brother and sister were sentenced to eight-year prison terms in
Cuba after admitting that they spied for the CIA.
   The Prensa Latina dispatch from Havana, received here late
Wednesday, identified the two as Nestor Norberto Garcia Hernandez
and Gladys Juana Garcia Hernandez and said they had ``proven ties''
to the CIA.
   Prensa Latina said the two ``admitted during the trial their
activity in Cuba for that American center of espionage.''
   It said the maximum sentence for the charges was 10 years
imprisonment, and the Havana judge trying the case reduced it to
eight because the two confessed.
   Cuban television had reported in May 1987 that Ms. Garcia
Hernandez, said to be a Cuban resident of the United States,
recruited and trained her brother to work as a CIA agent.
   According to Prensa Latina's account of the televised charges,
Garcia Hernandez, believed to be a Cuban citizen, sent radio
messages from May 1985 to April 1987 to the CIA at its headquarters
in Langley, Va.
   The Cuban news agency also said that during the trial it was
proven that the two ``gathered economic, political and military
information for the CIA.''
</TEXT>
