<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--FloatingCocaine 1stLd-Writethru a0555 03-31 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Floating Cocaine, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0555,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Makes Second Largest Cocaine Seizure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds one graf with estimated value</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abandoned fishing boat stacked with 3,765 pounds
of cocaine was seized within sight of Miami's skyline in the second
largest cocaine haul ever made by the U.S. Coast Guard, officials
said.
   ``It was in bales spread out on the deck,'' said Coast Guard
Petty Officer Joe Dye on Wednesday.
   The seizure ranked second to a two-ton shipment found on a
fishing boat off Puerto Rico last fall. The cocaine was in an
unregistered, twin-engine, 26-foot open fishing boat. There were no
belongings aboard.
   ``A passing boater called us and basically said, `Hey, there's a
boat out here and it's loaded,''' Dye said.
   At first, authorities thought it was loaded with marijuana,
which is normally found in bales of 50 to 100 pounds, Dye said.
   ``Originally they thought it was pot because it was packed in
Marlboro (cigarette) cartons,'' Dye said. ``They packed the cartons
with the kilos (of cocaine) and put the cartons into cases, which
were also marked `Marlboro.'''
   The wholesale value of the cocaine was estimated at about $26
million and its value on the streets could be as high as $169
million, said a spokesman for the Drug Enforcement Administration
Task Force in Miami.
</TEXT>
