<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     03-31 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan Says Ready to Sign Accord; Soviet Says No Surprise if
Talks Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan said today it is ready to sign a
settlement to end the Afghanistan conflict and expects progress
soon on deciding when outside military aid to the Soviet-backed
government and guerrillas will end.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said in an
interview released today it was possible the Afghanistan peace
talks would fail, but he said that would not necessarily stop the
Soviets from withdrawing their troops.
   The New York Times said Wednesday that U.S. officials received
indications the Soviet Union will consider allowing American aid to
the rebels to continue after the 115,000 Red Army troops begin
leaving Afghanistan.
   U.S. and Pakistani officials have said the issue of continued
aid to the Afghan government and the rebels fighting it is the last
obstacle in the way of an accord to end the war.
   Zain Noorani, Pakistan's acting Foreign Minister, said his
country will sign ``any time during the day or after the Easter
break, when the other three parties are ready to sign.''
   Noorani spoke after his side and an Afghan government delegation
resumed the U.N.-mediated talks. Pakistan represents the rebels,
and the other parties are the Soviet Union and the United States.
   ``From our point of view, all the ... instruments (of the peace
package) are complete,'' he said. ``We are hopeful that in the next
few days there ought to be some kind of progress'' on the aid
issue, he added.
   Washington has said it will not guarantee a settlement unless
the Soviet Union agrees to stop funding the Kabul government at the
same time the United States stops aid to the rebels.
   Shevardnadze's interview with the Bulgarian newspaper
Rabotnichesko Delo was carried by the Soviet news agency Tass.
Shevardnadze was in Bulgaria earlier this week for a Warsaw Pact
meeting.
   ``Not everything depends solely on us and the Afghan
government,'' Shevardnadze said, referring to the outcome of the
talks. ``This is why one cannot but take into account the
possibility that the talks may not lead to the accords expected of
them.''
   Shevardnadze said that if the Geneva talks fail, the Soviet
Union will withdraw its soldiers ``in a way convenient for the
government of Afghanistan and ourselves.'' He gave no indication
whether the Soviet Union would stick to the nine-month timetable
for withdrawal already agreed to in Geneva.
   He said an agreement could be implemented without U.S.
participation if Pakistan was willing to sign a document spelling
out the details of the Soviet withdrawal.
   ``It would certainly be better if it (the United States) becomes
a guarantor. But it is quite possible, in our opinion, to conclude
the Geneva process without the U.S. guarantees,'' he said.
   Zoorani rejected this, saying everything would have to be
renegotiated if one of the superpowers refuses its guarantor role.
   The Times, citing unidentified senior U.S. officials, said the
United States was considering an arrangement under which Pakistan
would sign the accord, but the United States and the Soviet Union
would have a separate understanding on aid to the insurgents.
   The new position was discussed by telephone Wednesday by
President Reagan and Pakistani President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, the
newspaper said.
</TEXT>
