<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Armenia     03-31 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Officials In City of Labor Unrest Appeal for Help to
National Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party officials of a southern city
paralyzed by a strike again appealed to Soviet leaders to resolve a
dispute between two Soviet ethnic groups but condemned the tactics
of protesters, a newspaper reported today.
   The appeal, adopted at a meeting Wednesday, did not persuade
people to return to work, according to one resident who said the
strike continued today in Stepanakert, the main city of the
disputed region of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   The majority of people living in the region are Armenian, but it
is part of the republic of Azerbaijan. Armenians are demanding that
it be made part of neighboring Armenia.
   ``People aren't even thinking of going to work,'' said the
resident, a man answering the telephone at the Sovietsky Karabakh
newspaper. He refused to give his name or position.
   The government newspaper Izvestia said the meeting of the
Stepanakert City Committee was stormy and that one speaker, an
engineer, cried.
   ``The majority of the Communists decisively condemned the tactic
of `forced pressure' on the country's leadership, and along with
that every speaker underlined that the Nagorno-Karabakh problem has
not been removed, that it still needs a settlement,'' Izvestia said
in a report from Stepanakert.
   The City Committee passed a resolution containing the appeal to
national leaders, Izvestia said. It provided no other details.
   Wednesday's Soviet press reports said workers vowed to continue
the walkout until the government and party reversed their decisions
to leave Nagorno-Karabakh under the control of Azerbaijan.
   The city committee had asked national leaders to reconsider the
annexation demand in February after the Communist Party Central
Committee said Nagorno-Karabakh belongs to Azerbaijan. The
Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the national parliament, approved
a package of cultural and economic improvements for the region on
March 23 but did not address the territorial issue.
   Street demonstrations and strikes in Nagorno-Karabakh and
Armenia's capital, Yerevan, have tested Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness. At least 32 people
were killed in ethnic violence in Sumgait in Azerbaijan last month.
   All but essential services such as bread and milk factories and
some public transportation and medical clinics have been closed in
Stepanakert since the strike began March 24.
   The man at the Sovietsky Karabakh newspaper said there were no
demonstrations in Stepanakert and that police were keeping a low
profile.
   Yerevan police last week arrested several Armenian nationalists
who had been advocating the annexation.
   Today, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov
provided the first official confirmation that Paruyr Ayrikyan, a
former political prisoner, was among those arrested.
   The spokesman, at a regular news briefing, said he did not know
under which criminal statute Ayrikyan was being held. Dissidents
have said authorities charged Ayrikyan with violating a law against
defamation of the Soviet state.
   The Soviet government has forbidden foreign journalists from
traveling to Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh.
</TEXT>
