<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0583 03-31 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0583,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Imposes New Restrictions, Shamir Vows to Crush Uprising</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to note that Netanyahu had planned to
resign in a few weeks. Pick up 5th pvs, `On Wednesday...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel today clamped new restrictions on
Palestinians, and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told hundreds of
cheering Jewish settlers in the West Bank that Israel would crush
the Palestinian uprising.
   ``We will continue to act against the violence until we stamp it
out,'' Shamir, leader of the right-wing Likud bloc, told hundreds
of cheering Jewish settlers during a tour of Herodion, 5 miles
south of Bethlehem.
   In the West Bank town of Ramallah, Israeli troops sealed off the
city hall after reports of a bomb threat, Arab witnesses said.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz defended his recent meeting
with Arab-Americans who belong to the Palestine Liberation
Organization's parliament-in-exile. Benjamin Netanyahu, Israel's
ambassador to the United Nations, said he was resigning
immediately, a few weeks earlier than he originally planned, to
speak out against the meeting.
   On Wednesday, when Palestinians observed Land Day, Israel
clamped down on Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip with
its toughest restrictions in 20 years of occupation.
   Land Day commemorates a confrontation on March 30, 1976, when
Israeli Arabs protested the forced sale of 1,600 acres of their
land for Jewish settlement. Six Arabs were killed.
   The army barred reporters from entering the West Bank and Gaza
Strip except in news pools with an army escort, and restricted the
movement of Palestinians.
   The measures, however, failed to prevent violence. Officials
said four Arabs were shot and killed and 39 were wounded by gunfire
Wednesday, and two were injured in Gaza.
   Israel radio said today the Interior Ministry placed new travel
restrictions on Palestinians from east Jerusalem, where 130,000
Arabs live. Israel annexed the predominantly Arab sector of the
city in 1967.
   It said Palestinians aged 16 to 35 now need special permits to
travel to Jordan, and these will be issued only if the request is
for a stay of at least nine months. The object is to stop the PLO
from sending couriers into the occupied territories.
   In Ramallah, Chamber of Commerce head Hadar Kasis told a
reporter the military authorities informed him Palestinians could
withdraw only $1,000 a month from bank accounts.
   Earlier restrictions bar Arabs from bringing more than $1,200 at
a time across the bridges from Jordan. The moves are designed to
keep the PLO from compensating merchants and workers for loss of
income during anti-Israeli strikes and protests.
   ``We are prepared for anything. ... We can exist just on bread
and zatar (a peppery spice),'' said Kasis, a gift-store owner.
   The Israeli army said it received reports of an explosion in the
Ramallah city hall area about midday today, and Arab witnesses said
soldiers briefly sealed off the area.
   The witnesses said Israeli or municipal officials apparently had
received a bomb threat, but the details were sketchy. Israel sealed
off the West Bank to media Monday night and the movements of
journalists were severely limited.
   The Israeli-appointed acting mayor, Ahmed Assayad, said there
was an unsuccessful attempt late Wednesday to break into the
building. He said he left City Hall about 11 a.m. (4 a.m. EST) and
knew of no attack.
   Underground leaflets signed by the PLO have ordered all Arab
municipal councils to resign, accusing them of collaborating with
Israeli authorities.
   In remarks broadcast today by Israel radio, Shultz reacted to
Israeli protests over his meeting last Saturday with Edward Said
and Ibrahim Abu Lughud. He said it was ``beyond the pale'' to
suggest he could not meet American citizens.
   Shultz also stressed the importance of finding Palestinian
negotiators: ``Palestinians are part of the peace issue. We have
got to find a way to be in contact with them.''
   Netanyahu resigned Wednesday because he contended the Reagan
administration was violating a commitment not to talk directly with
the PLO.
   ``I could not speak freely (about this) as long as I was
ambassador,'' he told The Associated Press.
   Shultz said he would press ahead with his peace initiative _
essentially an exchange of land for peace with the Arabs _ but
would wait until Arabs and Israelis are ready to talk peace before
asking U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez De Cuellar to send out
invitiations to an international conference.
   Violent protests by Palestinians against Israeli rule of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip began Dec. 8.
   Wednesday's fatalities brought to at least 123 the number of
Arabs killed by Israelis in the unrest, according to U.N. figures.
One Israeli soldier has been killed.
</TEXT>
