<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSTest-Suit     03-31 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Test-Suit,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Men Tested Without Permission For AIDS, Suing Doctors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men are suing doctors for allegedly
testing them for AIDS without their permission, complaining their
privacy was violated and that the test results caused them mental
anguish.
   The lawsuits say one of the three considered suicide and another
was forced to leave his home town because of societal pressure
after they were told they tested positive for the AIDS virus.
   Lawyer David Webber, who filed all three suits, said such
testing occurs more often than patients realize.
   ``I believe that such testing is going on all over,'' Webber
said. ``In most cases, people are tested without their knowledge
and simply never know.''
   Anna Forbes, a spokeswoman for Action AIDS, a nonprofit
organization that assists people with AIDS in the Philadelphia
area, said AIDS testing without permission is ``happening far too
frequently.''
   ``Often this testing is being done without consideration of the
impact it has on people and their families,'' she said. ``Telling
people that they are infected with the virus is a psychological
bombshell because you are dealing with an incurable disease.''
   A study published last week in the Journal of the American
Medical Association said 34 percent of 189 U.S. hospitals surveyed
rarely asked patients' permission before testing for the AIDS virus.
   The three men, who were not identified at their request, are
suing the doctors for more than $200,000 in damages. The doctors
and their representatives refused comment to comment on the suits.
   In one lawsuit, filed Wednesday in federal court in Harrisburg,
a 40-year-old man contends he was forced to leave his home after he
tested positive for exposure to the virus that causes acquired
immune deficiency syndrome. He said his physician never asked his
permission.
   The man said although he is infected with the virus, he does not
have AIDS or AIDS-related diseases.
   The plaintiff in another suit, filed in Philadelphia Common
Pleas Court, said he went to a hospital for treatment of a minor
eye infection and gave permission for a blood test but not for an
AIDS test. He contemplated suicide after he was told he tested
positive for AIDS, according to the suit.
   In the third suit, also filed in Philadelphia court, the
plaintiff alleges that he was tested for the AIDS virus without
permission after he went to her for a premarital blood test. A
second test showed he was not infected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
