<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Afghanistan     03-31 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Afghanistan,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Aid to Rebels Will Continue If Soviets Aid Regime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Pakistani President
Mohammed Zia ul-Haq agreed during telephone talks to continue
aiding Afghan resistance forces after Soviet troops leave
Afghanistan if the Soviets continue backing the Kabul regime, U.S.
officials said today.
   The officials also confirmed reports that the Reagan
administration is actively involved in a new effort to settle the
aid issue with the Soviets.
   ``The United States has not and will not stop assisting the
Afghan resistance unless the Soviets stop aiding the Kabul
regime,'' State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said.
   She said Reagan and Zia ``reaffirmed'' this view during a
telephone conversation on Wednesday.
   There has been concern within the administration that Pakistan _
through which U.S. assistance to the guerrillas is funnelled _
would halt the flow of aid once an agreement is signed.
   Pakistan is eager for a settlement and a Soviet troop withdrawal
because a pact would presumably permit millions of Afghan refugees
in Pakistan to return to their homeland.
   The presidents' conversation and a flurry of diplomatic activity
with the Soviets are part of an effort to finish a U.N.-sponsored
accord that would permit the orderly withdrawal of the Soviet
Union's 115,000 troops from Afghanistan and require a cessation of
outside aid to the guerrillas.
   The United States has agreed in principle to be a ``guarantor''
of the agreement, but has insisted it will stop aiding the Afghan
rebels after Soviet withdrawal only if Moscow stops sending
supplies and financial support to the Afghan government. The
Soviets have said they have a right to continue such aid under
treaties with the Kabul government.
   A State Department official today confirmed reports in The
Washington Post and The New York Times that the United States would
ask the Soviets to agree to a continuation of the two superpowers'
aid to their clients in the Afghan struggle.
   Instead of agreeing to a parallel cessation of aid, Moscow and
Washington would agree to a parallel continuation of assistance,
according to the proposal.
   During talks in Washington last week, Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze reportedly did not specifically reject the
idea, but a State Department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said ``it would go too far to say he agreed to consider
it.
   ``There is some disagreement'' even within the administration on
how to interpret Shevardnadze's comments, the official added.
   Publicly, at a news conference March 23, Shevardnadze rejected
calls for a cessation of Soviet aid.
   The U.S. official who spoke on condition of anonymity said some
administration figures were concerned about the legality of the
United States signing an Afghan peace accord that required a cutoff
of aid to the resistance forces while agreeing separately with the
Soviets to continue such assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
