<1ST_LINE>u i PM-WarsawPact 1stLd-Writethru   03-31 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Warsaw Pact, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0498,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Calls For Swift Strategic Arms Accord</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th, `The offer...' to ADD NATO
comment. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `The appeals ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Warsaw Pact has offered to hold
separate talks on conventional forces and battlefield nuclear arms
and urged the superpowers to sign by July 1 a pact to halve their
long-range nuclear arsenals.
   The Soviet-led alliance's seven foreign ministers also said
Wednesday after a two-day meeting in the Bulgarian capital of Sofia
that the superpowers should agree to abide by the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty. Moscow says the treaty bars
development of a space-based missile defense system.
   The Warsaw Pact foreign ministers urged NATO to begin talks this
year on reducing conventional forces in Europe and backed down from
a longstanding position by offering separate negotiations on
battlefield nuclear weapons.
   The offer appeared aimed at overcoming a more than year-old
absence of movement toward new talks on reducing conventional
forces across Europe.
   ``We welcome the statements of the Warsaw Pact foreign ministers
... to the extent that they seem to reflect some of the concerns of
NATO members,'' said a NATO statement released today in Brussels,
Belgium.
   The statement added that it was important that the Warsaw Pact's
words be translated into concrete proposals at the negotiating
table.
   The appeals, published by the Bulgarian news agency BTA and
monitored in Vienna, indicated Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
is eager to seal a pact on intercontinental nuclear missiles but
not insisting it be ready to sign when he meets President Reagan in
Moscow May 29 to June 2.
   Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Vadim Loginov told journalists in
Sofia that the Kremlin still hopes the agreement can be signed
during the Moscow summit.
   But the Warsaw Pact statement indicated Moscow links a pact on
strategic arms to adherence to the 1972 ABM treaty, which sets
limits on superpower missile defenses.
   The Reagan administration has argued that the ABM accord permits
research and testing of the its space-based missile defense
project, popularly called ``Star Wars.'' Moscow insists the ABM
accord rules out any such system.
   The Warsaw Pact statement said talks on what the 16-nations
North Atlantic Treaty Organization calls conventional stability
should begin this year, but set no time for the separate
negotations on tactical nuclear and dual capability weapons.
   East-West disagreement over how to count Warsaw Pact and NATO
troop levels has stalled Vienna talks on reducing conventional
forces in central Europe since they opened in 1973. Those
negotations are likely to be wound down if new talks on
conventional stability are started.
   Agreement on new talks on conventional forces may pave the way
for settlement of other disputes, including human rights issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
