<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Violence     03-31 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Violence,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Reported Killed When Troops Fire on Stonethrowers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramilitary troops killed nine people
and injured 36 when they fired on a group of people who threw
stones at the soldiers' camp, news reports said today.
   Indian newspapers said the firing Tuesday night and Wednesday by
a unit of the paramilitary Assam Rifles occurred in Aizawl, the
capital of the northeastern state of Mizoram.
   A nighttime curfew was clamped on the town about 990 miles east
of New Delhi.
   Mizoram was the scene of a 20-year guerrilla war for
independence until 1986, when a peace accord was signed with the
Indian government.
   It was unclear what set off the incident, but the United News of
India said the civilians were angered over an alleged assault on a
local policeman Tuesday by members of the paramilitary unit.
   State Chief Minister Laldenga has asked Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi to remove Assam Rifles personnel from Mizoram for mutiny and
rebellion against the government, UNI said.
   Laldenga was the leader of the independence movement.
   The movement was fueled by what local residents, mainly members
of the Mizo tribe, perceived as a cultural threat from settlements
by Assamese and other ethnic groups from the west.
   The Assam Rifles were deployed in Mizoram during the guerrilla
war and remained after the peace pact as a reserve police force.
   UNI did not give details of the assault on the local policeman,
but many former guerrillas have been inducted into the state police
force since the accord was signed.
</TEXT>
