<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoldierofFortune     03-31 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldier of Fortune,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial of Man Accused of Soliciting Contract Killings to Start
Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who has already been convicted
in one killing will go on trial here Monday on charges of
soliciting contract killings through Soldier of Fortune magazine,
officials said.
   Richard Michael Savage, 39, had been scheduled for trial earlier
this month in Houston, but U.S. District Judge James DeAnda granted
a change of venue after ruling Savage could not get a fair trial
there because of publicity in an unrelated civil case involving
Soldier of Fortune.
   On March 3, a federal civil jury in Houston awarded a $9.4
million judgment against Soldier of Fortune when it found the
magazine was negligent by publishing a classified advertisement
that led to a woman's slaying. Savage was not involved in that
killing.
   Gary Cobe, the assistant U.S. attorney in Houston who will
prosecute Savage, declined comment on the case Wednesday, but
confirmed the trial will begin Monday.
   Savage is already serving a 40-year prison term in Florida for
arranging the 1985 beating death of former West Palm Beach
Assistant City Manager Anita Spearman through an advertisement in
Soldier of Fortune.
   Alice V. Brado allegedly hired Savage through a Soldier of
Fortune advertisement to kill Dana Free.
   Savage was indicted in October 1986 along with Ms. Brado and
others in the murder-for-hire scheme. Among the charges against him
are four counts of use of interstate commerce facilities in the
commission of murder for hire, aiding and abetting, according to
the U.S. district clerk's office in Houston.
   Ms. Brado allegedly hired Savage through an ad in the magazine
to arrange the death of Free, whom she said absconded with her
$300,000 life savings. She pleaded guilty to charges stemming from
the scheme and died of emphysema in a Kentucky prison while serving
a five-year term.
   The indictment stated Brado paid Savage $20,000 to arrange
Free's murder, to have been carried out by William Clayton Buckley,
36, and Sherry Lynn Breeden, 22, both of Knoxville, Tenn.
   The pair allegedly tried to bomb Free's car in Atlanta during
June 1985, but Free escaped. On Oct. 12, 1985, two grenades were
thrown through his living room window, but no one was injured.
   Buckley and Ward C. Lambeth, a 61-year-old co-defendant, also
have pleaded guilty to charges in connection with the grenade
attack.
</TEXT>
