<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoriegaCase-Arrest     03-31 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega Case-Arrest,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Arrest Linked To Ring Allegedly Tied To Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been arrested on charges linked to
a drug ring that was allegedly involved with Panamanian Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, authorities said.
   Kenneth Mark Kiken, 37, was captured Wednesday in the southern
New Jersey town of Avalon on a fugitive warrant, John C. McGinley,
head of the FBI's New Jersey office. Kiken was arrested after a
routine license check by Avalon police on an out-of-state license
plate, he said.
   Kiken was named in a two-count indictment last January charging
him with conspiring to import and attempting to import 165,000
pounds of marijuana seized by the U.S. Coast Guard seized in
October 1985.
   The shipment was included in a June 1986 indictment in Tampa,
Fla. accusing Leigh Bruce Ritch and Steven Kalish of running a drug
ring that imported millions of pounds of marijuana and thousands of
pounds of cocaine into the United States.
   Kalish, who was arrested in July 1984, pleaded guilty,
cooperated with authorities in the investigation of Noriega and was
sentenced Feb. 25 to 14 years in prison, said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Mark Jackowski in Tampa.
   Noriega was indicted Feb. 4 for taking $4 million from Kalish
and Ritch in payoffs to protect their operation and with laundering
more than $100 million of the ring's profits.
   The Noriega indictment covers the time period of June 1983 to
July 1984, and Jackowski said the government does not allege a
specific link between the charges against the Panamanian strongman
and the charges against Kiken.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Lucy McClain in Camden said Kiken waived
bail, a lawyer and opposition to sending him to Tampa authorities.
   Jackowski said Kiken would likely be brought to Florida next
week or the week after.
   Ritch was sentenced to 30 years for his conviction on the 1986
Tampa indictment, Jackowski said.
</TEXT>
