<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MurderAcquittal     03-31 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Murder Acquittal,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Cleared; Said She Shot Boss To Defend Against Sexual
Harassment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bookkeeper who admitted she shot her boss
to death has been acquitted of second-degree murder after
testifying that she was a victim of sexual harassment.
   Roxanna Ullery, 23, told a circuit court jury she killed Wayne
Evans at his Winter Park home Feb. 16, 1987, because he moved
threateningly toward her and a friend and she feared he was about
to rape and kill them.
   Ms. Ullery was convicted Wednesday of carrying a concealed
weapon and shooting a firearm, and prosecutors said she would
likely get a year of probation.
   The defendant said Evans, 30, owner of Cinco Construction Co.,
continually made lewd comments during her six months on the job and
would lift up her dress, fondle her breasts and call her into his
office where he would be masturbating.
   However, prosecutors claimed Ms. Ullery shot Evans because he
found out earlier in the day that she was embezzling money by
writing paychecks to people who did not work at the company. He
called her to his home to discuss the embezzlement, prosecutors
said.
   Jurors looked at checks totaling $9,000 that prosecutors said
Ms. Ullery signed and cashed. She said she did that at his
direction and that he had withheld more than $160,000 in Social
Security taxes from the government.
   The defense said Evans threatened her with jail if she didn't do
what he wanted.
   ``He threatened to turn her in and kill her and her son,'' said
defense attorney Charles Willits. ``What it amounted to was
psychological warfare.''
</TEXT>
