<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Cubans-Disturbance     03-31 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cubans-Disturbance,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officers Quiet Disturbance Among Cuban Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLADEGA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Extra officers were called to the
Talladega Federal Correctional Institute to quell an hour-long
disturbance involving Cuban prisoners, a spokeswoman said today.
   No injuries were reported in the Wednesday incident, but guards
had to use a tear gas-like chemcial agent on four detainees who
resisted officers, said Karen Stephens.
   ``At no time was the security or safety of the facility in
danger,'' she said. Ms. Stephens said it was unclear what prompted
the disturbance.
   Brian Ross, another spokesman for the facility, said the
disturbance was confined to one cell block holding 16 Cubans. He
said they made a lot of noise and covered the front of the block so
they could not be seen or counted.
   The Talladega prison holds 167 Cuban detainees, some of whom
were transferred to the facility following uprisings at federal
prisons in Atlanta and Oakdale, La., late last year.
   The Cubans arrived in the United States during the 1980 Mariel
boat lift.
</TEXT>
