<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1150EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Daedalus 2ndLd-Writethru   03-31 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Daedalus, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0565,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human-Powered Plane Makes Successful Test Flight</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with no flight scheduled Friday.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-tech human-powered aircraft made a
successful series of test flights today in preparation for a
world-record distance attempt that also will recreate the ancient
Daedalus myth.
   But organizers of the Daedalus project called off plans for a
record bid on Friday because southerly gales were expected with
winds gusting up to 30 mph.
   Flight Director Steve K. Bussulari told reporters that the
68-pound ultralight Daedalus 88 ``is in good shape ... and we may
see favorable conditions'' for a flight on Saturday or Sunday.
   The aircraft completed six flights lasting less than three
minutes each in calm dawn weather above a Greek air force base
adjoining Iraklion airport.
   Five athlete pilots took turns to pedal the shimmering
pink-and-silver plane at speeds of around 14 mph, flying about 15
feet above the tarmac.
   The three-year Massachusetts Institute of Technology project
aims at breaking the world record for human-powered flight over the
74-mile distance from Crete to the island of Santorini, also known
as Thira.
   The flight also will update the myth of Daedalus. According to
the 3,500-year-old myth, the inventor and his son, Icarus, tried to
escape from Crete on wings made of feathers and wax. Daedalus
succeeded, but Icarus flew too close to the sun, the wax melted and
he fell into the sea.
   After nine days of blustery weather, conditions today appeared
near-perfect for the Santorini flight, which requires temperatures
below 70 degrees Fahrenheit and almost dead calm, a rare occurrence
on this wind-swept southern island.
   ``It feels like a day for the record, pretty calm. I was flying
the plane with no hands,'' said Frank Scioscia, 27, a professional
cyclist from Scranton, Pa.
   Bussulari, an MIT aerospace expert who will make the decision to
fly, said the record probably could have been set today, although
the plane would have met strong headwinds about five miles off
Santorini.
   ``But we felt we needed a test flight to shake down the
aeroplane,'' he said.
   The pilots _ four Americans and one Greek _ are taking turns to
stand by for 48 hours in readiness for the flight. The pilot who
had been scheduled to fly Friday is Greg Zack, 26, of Wilmington,
N.C., whose father was born in Greece.
   The pilot pumps bicycle pedals that turn the contraption's
propeller, and steers the plane with a joystick, coordinating with
ground-based radio instructions.
   ``For the record the pilot must keep pedaling a steady 15 mph
but the effort is equivalent to riding 23 miles an hour on land,''
said Glenn Tremml, a medical student from New Haven, Conn.
   Tremml set the 37.2-mile world record for human-powered flight
in California in 1987, flying a Daedalus prototype.
   After an unassisted takeoff, the pilot will skirt the offshore
island of Dia and head due north hoping to land on a sandy beach on
Santorini.
   Two Greek navy patrol boats and a flotilla of inflatable crafts
will escort the plane across the Aegean sea, ready to pick up the
pilot if he crashes and salvage the aircraft, although it probably
would be unuseable.
   Two backup flying machines are ready for assembly here if needed.
   Like Daedalus 88, they are constructed of lightweight composite
material _ graphite epoxy, plastic fiber and mylar, an extra-thin
plastic skin that covers the jetliner-sized 112-foot wingspan.
   The $1 million Daedalus project, with its 36-member team, has
produced new information on endurance and low altitude flying
aerodynamics and meteorology during its three years of development,
its organizers said.
   ``The project does have a research and educational application,
particularly in human physiology and aeronautics,'' said John S.
Langford, the project director. ``The plane itself doesn't have any
practical application. It should be seen as a work of art.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
