<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--CruiseFire     03-31 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cruise Fire,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaky Oil Pipe Suspected in Cruise Ship Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leaky fuel pipe spilling oil onto
a hot engine is believed to have triggered a fire that crippled the
cruise ship Scandinavian Star earlier this month near Cancun,
Mexico.
   The leak occured in an inch-thick pipe that carries oil to the
main engine on the starboard side, said Lou Colucciello of the
National Transporation Safety Board. The pipe apparently leaked
near the engine and the oil ignited when it spilled on the hot
surface, he said.
   The fire March 16 on the St. Petersburg-based ship stranded 447
passengers on the return leg of a Mexican cruise about 35 miles off
the Yucatan peninsula.
   The passengers were flown back to Tampa.
   A four-member team from the NTSB Marine Accident Division spent
last week inspecting the ship in Miami and returned to Washington
to conduct more tests and analyze findings, Colucciello said.
   He said investigators have found no other possible cause;
however, the findings won't be conclusive until they test a piece
of pipe and some of the ship's fuel at a laboratory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
