<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SriLanka     03-31 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 17 Killed As Tamils Attack Moslem Villages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil militants attacked and set fire
to two Moslem fishing villages in eastern Sri Lanka today, and at
least 17 people were killed, Indian and Sri Lankan sources said.
   The sources said the attackers burned a mosque and more than 80
mud-and-straw houses in villages near Kalmunai, 137 miles northeast
of Colombo, the capital. The sources spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Some reports said the death toll was higher. There also was
confusion over how many of the dead were Tamils and how many were
Moslems because a battle apparently broke out after the initial
attack.
   Moslems make up 7 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. They
have been caught up only rarely in the Tamil rebels' nearly
five-year war against the dominant Sinhalese for a separate Tamil
nation.
   But the Moslems make up about one-third of the population in
eastern Sri Lanka, which the rebels want as part of their homeland,
and they recently have come under attack.
   Under an Indian-sponsored peace accord, a vote is be held in the
island's north and east for a temporary council to rule the two
areas as one province.
   Both Sinhalese and Moslem leaders charge that the Tamils are
trying to drive out members of the other two communities to gain
political advantage.
   An Indian diplomat in Colombo said Indian peacekeeping troops
investigating the attack found 17 bodies in the villages of
Sainthamaruthu and Malaiyandu.
   The diplomat, who spoke on condition her name not be used, said
six people also were injured. ``Indian troops have now moved a
battalion to the stricken villages,'' she said.
   India mantains about 40,000 soldiers in Sri Lanka under a peace
accord signed last July.
   A police official in Kalmunai, who also spoke anonymously, said
86 houses, all belonging to Moslem fisherman, were burned to the
ground. Many people fled into the nearby jungle, he said.
   Mohamad Ashroof, general secretary of the Sri Lankan Moslem
Congress, said in Colombo that he had firm reports the death toll
was 20 Moslems, including six who perished after taking refuge in
the mosque.
   But sources in the coastal city of Batticaloa, north of
Kalmunai, said survivors' accounts indicated 17 died, including
seven Tamils killed when Moslem villagers tried to repulse the
attack.
   The largest rebel militia, the Liberation Tigers, have been
operating in eastern Sri Lanka since being driven out of their
stronghold in the north by Indian troops.
   They have resisted the peace accord, which calls on the rebels
to give up their fight in exchange for more autonomy for Tamils.
   Tamils, mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of the population.
They claim they are discriminated against by the Buddhist
Sinhalese, who form 75 percent and dominate the government and
military.
   Within the last month, nearly 150 civilians have been killed in
Sri Lanka's Eastern Province in attacks blamed on the Tamil rebels.
   Within the past week more than 30 Moslem-owned homes and
businesses have been looted or set afire in Kalmunai. Two weeks ago
seven Moslem businessmen in the area were kidnapped and are still
missing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
