<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GypsyBurglary     03-31 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gypsy Burglary,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Members of Alleged Gypsy Burglar Ring Stole Nationwide, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty Polish Gypsies who were arrested
at Los Angeles International Airport while carrying jewelry-stuffed
bags are part of an elusive nationwide burglary ring, authorities
said.
   Nineteen of the 20 men and women pleaded innocent in Pasadena
Municipal Court on Monday and Tuesday to charges of receiving
stolen property. One suspect is still to be arraigned.
   Sheriff's Detective Terry Wiese, who has tracked members of the
group since 1984, said they specialized in rifling senior citizens'
houses from coast to coast, often while the victims were at home.
   Group members are wanted in connection with a string of similar
burglaries across the country and in Canada, he said.
   ``We haven't even touched the tip of the iceberg, that's how big
we believe this activity is across the United States,'' Wiese said.
   Los Angeles Police Detective Larry Kagele, working with more
than two dozen law enforcement agencies in the case, said the
Gypsies would drive through affluent neighborhoods looking for
senior citizens standing outside their homes, watering their lawns
or chatting with neighbors.
   While a man remained at the wheel of the car, a woman would ask
the homeowner for directions or a drink of water. A second woman
would sneak into the house and rummage through bedroom dressers and
closets in search of jewelry, expensive heirlooms and silver,
Kagele said.
   ``If the woman was seen inside the house, she would make up a
quick story that she's looking for a `Joe' or `Sandy' and must have
the wrong address,'' Kagele said. ``It wasn't all that
sophisticated, but it worked.''
   Still wanted is the group's alleged Gypsy ``queen,'' Danuta
Reszuta, 31, authorities said.
   All 20 people arrested last week have been charged with one
count of receiving stolen property and held in lieu of $500,000
bail each. Police said the high bail was needed because alleged
members of the group have fled before trial in the past.
   Polish translators are assisting the Gypsies because none of the
20 speak enough English to follow their court proceedings.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service agents also are reviewing
their files on the suspicion that several may be in the United
States illegally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
