<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1223EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Cabinet     03-31 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Cabinet,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mulroney Shuffles Cabinet Heading Into Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney shuffled his
Cabinet today with major changes in the controversial trade and
immigration portfolios. Mulroney faces a re-election campaign later
in the year.
   International Trade Minister Pat Carney, noted for her combative
style, was replaced by former Transport Minister John Crosbie, who
will take over responsibility for implementing the free-trade
agreement negotiated last year with the United States.
   The agreement dismantles tariffs and other trade barriers over
the next decade. It faces a ratification battle in Parliament later
this year and stubborn opposition from at least two of Canada's 10
provinces.
   Carney takes over as president of the Treasury Board, a post
formerly held by Deputy Prime Minister Don Mazankowski.
   Changing more than a quarter of his 38-member Cabinet, Mulroney
replaced both Immigration Minister Benoit Bouchard and his deputy,
Gerry Weiner, following two years in which Canada has struggled to
curb an influx of up to 2,000 illegal aliens a month.
   Bouchard takes over as transport minister while Weiner becomes
minister of state for multiculturalism.
   Barbara McDougall, formerly in charge of women's affairs and
privatization, becomes immigration minister.
   In a surprise move, Mulroney reached outside Parliament to name
his old school friend Lucien Bouchard, recently Canada's ambassador
to France, his new secretary of state. He replaces David Crombie,
who resigned on Wednesday to take up a new government job as head
of a royal commission on the development of the Lake Ontario
waterfront in Toronto.
   The only other newcomer in the Cabinet is Vancouver-area member
of Parliament Gerry St. Germain, who becomes minister of state for
transport, the equivalent of a deputy minister.
   Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party was elected to a
five-year term in September 1984. He is expected to call an early
election this fall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
