<1ST_LINE>u w PM-HeroinArrests 1stLd-Writethru a0607 03-31 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heroin Arrests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,190</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs pvs grafs 2-3, The arrests, with 5 new grafs including
further details on arrests. Will be led after Meese news conference
scheduled to start at 12:30 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI cracked a major heroin-importing ring
involving trafficking through Sicily with the arrest today of more
than 200 organized crime figures, Justice Department sources said.
   The arrests are the result of a lengthy criminal investigation
in cooperation with Italian authorities, said the sources, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   The government obtained warrants for the arrest of 45 people in
New York City, 11 in the nation's capital and 160 in Italy,
according to one source.
   Arrests were also expected in other cities, possibly including
Houston, Charlotte, N.C., and Los Angeles as well as in Florida,
the source said.
   The operation began in Washington in the fall of 1986 when an
undercover agent began purchasing drugs from a waiter at a local
restaurant, according to the source.
   Large quantities of cocaine and heroin were purchased in
Washington between October 1986 and last fall, the source said.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III and FBI officials were
scheduled to disclose details of the case at a news conference
later today at FBI headquarters in Washington.
</TEXT>
