<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-CentralAmerica Bjt   03-31 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Central America, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latin America Keeps Its Distance from U.S. Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials point proudly to how many Latin
American countries have become democratic in recent years, but on
the hemispheric issues of most concern to President Reagan _
Nicaragua and Panama _ it's hard to find one willing to align
itself with American policy.
   On Tuesday, a day when the administration was issuing veiled
warnings about the possibility of military intervention in Panama,
a regional conclave in Caracas, Venezuela, decided that the United
States had already gone too far in its campaign against military
strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``We urge the U.S. government to revoke immediately the coercive
measures it has adopted against Panama,'' the Latin American
Economic System said in a communique after a two-day meeting.
Nations ranging from rightist Chile to Marxist Cuba signed the
declaration.
   The underlying message was clear: the 26 countries are worried
that the United States is setting a precedent in Panama that could
be used against any one of them in the future.
   This consideration far outweighs the distaste that many have for
Noriega, named in two federal narcotics indictments. They believe
they themselves might be an American target some day if they get
caught smuggling drugs to the United States or run afoul of U.S.
policy in some other way.
   Over the past month, the administration has contributed to
Panama's economic collapse through measures that have had the
effect of aggravating an acute cash shortage in Panama.
   It has, for example, taken steps to deny Noriega access to some
$50 million in official Panamanian funds deposited in U.S. banks
and has withheld a $6.5 million payment due to Panama for services
related to Panama Canal operations.
   But many in Congress, where opposition to Noriega is virtually
unanimous, believe the administration has not gone far enough. Some
advocate a comprehensive trade embargo.
   The administration has moved against Noriega in the name of
restoring democracy in Panama, but none of the democracies which
now dominate the hemisphere has seen fit to back the U.S. actions.
   The one source of comfort for the United States concerning
Panama is that the only nations that have provided overt support
for Noriega are Cuba and Nicaragua.
   Another frustration for the administration has been the
persistent refusal of Latin American nations to support the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels. Some countries, such as Mexico, have
fought U.S. policy since the beginning while many others finessed
the issue by refusing to take a stand.
   Asked for an explanation, U.S. officials say many nations have
expressed support for the Contras in private but refuse to do so
publicly.
   The reason, officials say, is that these countries fear a
left-wing backlash at home if they side with the United States. To
ensure domestic tranquility, disassociation from U.S. policy has
been a time-honored tactic.
   All this generates considerable hand-wringing among
administration officials. The United States was once routinely
accused of backing unpopular dictators against the wishes of their
subjects.
   But, particularly in the case of Panama, the United States has
not been able to count on Latin American support even when it takes
an assertive stand against a strongman like Noriega.
   A generation ago, it was relatively easy for the United States
to win diplomatic support in the hemisphere. With minimal
opposition, Washington orchestrated the diplomatic and economic
isolation of Cuba's revolutionary government and won Latin American
support, with some exceptions, for its armed intervention in the
Dominican Republic in 1965.
   The sole recent instance in which the United States and Latin
America have been in harmony was in 1979, when there was a common
effort to bring down the Somoza family dynasty in Nicaragua. The
Carter administration called on President Anastasio Somoza to step
down and, within a month, he was gone.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
