<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Uganda-Prostitutes     03-31 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Uganda-Prostitutes,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uganda Prostitutes Don School Garb To Lure AIDS-Wary Clients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prostitutes are masquerading as
schoolgirls to lure clients wary of getting infected with AIDS, the
head of Uganda's task force on the disease said Thursday.
   Dr. Samuel Okware, the head of the National Committee for
Prevention of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndome, said his
organization had started a nationwide program to warn people of the
charade.
   Men are ``diverting their attention to schoolgirls and ignoring
bar maids and prostitutes'' because of their fear of catching the
sexually transmitted disease, he said.
   Prostitutes are donning school uniforms and carrying books
during the late afternoon when students normally return home from
school, Okware said.
   He said in the last three months, the practice had become common
among prostitutes in Masaka, about 85 miles southwest of Kampala,
the capital.
   There are 2,300 confirmed cases of AIDS in Uganda, said Okware.
</TEXT>
