<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GeneralHospital Bjt   03-31 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-General Hospital, Bjt,0805</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`General Hospital' Celebrates 25 Years on the Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The soap opera ``General Hospital''
celebrates its 25th anniversary on Friday showing no signs of ill
health in the Nielsen ratings, a recovery that began when it went
on location and added such contemporary anti-heroes as Luke and
Laura.
   The show, which began as a straightforward hospital drama on
April 1, 1963, was almost dead in the ratings when Gloria Monty
took over as executive producer in 1978, infusing the show with
contemporary plots and characters. Since 1979, it has been
consistently No. 1 in daytime.
   In 1981, the wedding of shady characters Luke and Laura
attracted an audience of nearly 17 million people _ in prime time,
the equivalent might be a combination of a Super Bowl and the ``Who
Shot J.R.?'' episode of ``Dallas.''
   The show was so popular, even Elizabeth Taylor did a guest shot.
A popular song was inspired _ ``General Hospi-tale.''
   For the first quarter of 1988, ``General Hospital'' tied with
CBS' ``The Young and the Restless'' for first place in the daytime
Nielsens, with an average rating of 8.6 and 27 share. The rating is
a percentage of 88.6 million U.S. households with televisions. The
share is a percentage of the sets in use.
   John Beradino, as Dr. Steve Harvey, and Emily McLaughlin, as
nurse Jessie Brewer, have been with the show since it began. Rachel
Ames, who joined the next year as Audrey Hardy, also still appears.
   Under Monty's guidance the show was expanded to an hour and took
on action-oriented storylines that turned it into a pop phenomenon.
   ``General Hospital'' was one of the first daytime dramas to go
on location, shorten scenes to quicken the pacing and introduce
more contemporary characters.
   Wes Kenney, who had produced CBS' ``The Young and the Restless''
and NBC's ``Days of Our Lives,'' took over as executive producer
when Monty left a year ago.
   ```General Hospital' is an adventure-driven show that also
depends heavily on its characters,'' said Kenney. ``Lots of shows
rely on character and romance, but what Gloria introduced was
adventure and suspense, which no soap had ever done before. Another
thing Gloria introduced was remotes (location shooting). Last year
we did more than 17. We got to Nashville, Niagara Falls and Mount
Rushmore. We blew up a whole mountain in Pacific Palisades. We had
a snow storm at Big Bear.
   ``There's a tendency for all soaps to go on location, but I
think `General Hospital' has carried it out more successfully. We
use the remotes to push the story ahead rather than just as an
excuse to get out of the studio.''
   Since the departure of actors Anthony Geary and Genie Francis as
Luke Spencer and Laura Baldwin, no one has heated up the airwaves
the way they did. Luke and Laura were a departure from the good vs.
evil staple of daytime drama. They became magazine-cover heroes,
even though Laura once killed off an old boyfriend, and when she
was raped, the culprit turned out to be Luke.
   Among characters who now populate ``General Hospital'' are:
   _ The menage a trois of Robert Scorpio (Tristan Rogers), Anna
Devane (Finola Hughes), and Duke Lavery (Ian Buchanan). Scorpio and
Anna were once married and had a child, but Scorpio later married
Holly (Emma Samms, before she went to ``Dynasty''). Anna and Duke
are now married, but there is a continuing competition for Anna by
the two men.
   _ Bobbie Spencer Meyer (Jackie Zeman) and Scott Baldwin (Kin
Shriner). Troublemaker Scott has just returned to the show and
renewed his relationship with Bobbie.
   _ Lucy Coe (Lynn Herring) and her husband Tony Jones (Brad
Maule). Lucy, who had been an in-house villain, has turned around
with her marriage to surgeon Tony Jones. Some people still don't
like her, but her marriage gives her respect.
   _ Felicia Jones (Kristina Malandro) has not had a relationship
since the departure of Frisco (Jack Wagner) a year ago. Frisco is
supposedly away on a spy mission, but now that it appears Wagner
will not return, the writers will involve her in another
relationship. Her new story will center on her search for Frisco.
   _ Tom Hardy (David Wallace) has returned to the show and married
Simone Ravelle (Laura Carrington) in the first interracial marriage
on a soap opera.
   ``I think people like stories that continue so they can relate
to these people,'' said Kenney. ``They become like a family, and
the viewer becomes emotionally involved. There seem to be two
attitudes by viewers. One, that the stories are similar to what
happened to them in real life, or two, thank goodness that isn't
me.''
</TEXT>
