<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ProsecutorsResign     03-31 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prosecutors Resign,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Resign Following Accusations That One Led Police On Chase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two prosecutors involved in a high-speed
chase have resigned in the wake of accusations that the driver was
semi-nude and tried to intimidate officers who stopped her.
   Assistant State Attorney Janine A. Bamping, 32, was stopped
March 20 and cited for allegedly fleeing and attempting to elude
police in a chase through Bradenton Beach.
   Her passenger, Assistant State Attorney Jerome B. Blevins, 27,
wasn't charged.
   Police said they didn't ask Ms. Bamping to get out of the car
for a sobriety test because she was undressed from the waist down.
Belvins was fully clothed, officers said.
   When asked while she was only partially clothed, she became
angry, flashed her state prosecutor's badge and used the name of a
county judge suggesting retribution against them, the officers said.
   Ms. Bamping was suspended with pay last week while State
Attorney Frank Schaub was on vacation. Schaub met with the
assistants Monday and accepted their resignations Wednesday.
   ``Both are competent prosecutors and their work will be
missed,'' Schaub said in a statement. He said he has asked the
governor's office to assign an outside state attorney to review the
charges, which Ms. Bamping apparently intends to fight.
   Schaub heads a staff of 46 assistants in the 12th Judicial
Circuit of three counties.
</TEXT>
