<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1258EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Vietnam-MIA     03-31 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-MIA,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Government Will Repatriate Remains of 27 Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vietnamese government has informed the
United States it will repatriate the remains of what it believes
may be 27 American servicemen missing from the Vietnam War, the
Pentagon said today.
   The remains will be delivered to U.S. military officials in
Hanoi on April 6 and transported to the Army's Central
Identification Laboratory in Honolulu for identification, the
Pentagon said in a statement.
   ``The U.S. government appreciates the initiative taken by
Vietnam to repatriate these remains and hopes it represents just
one of many continued steps to resolve this long-standing
humanitarian issue,'' the Pentagon said.
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, said the
repatriation would be the largest single such transfer of remains
since the end of the war. The largest previous tranfer occurred on
Aug. 14, 1985, when the Vietnamese returned 26 remains.
   There are currently 2,404 Americans still listed as missing in
Indochina as a result of the Vietnam War, of whom 1,767 are listed
as missing in either North or South Vietnam. The remains of 152
Americans have been repatriated to the United States and
subsequently identified by the laboratory since the end of the war.
   On March 2, the Vietnamese turned over 17 remains to U.S.
officials. Those remains have yet to be identified, however.
   The upcoming transfer would be the fourth since retired Army
Gen. John Vessey traveled to Hanoi last August as a special
presidential emissary, hoping to step up the process of accounting
for missing Americans.
   ``We've continued to press the Vietnamese and we are getting
some results,'' Howard said today.
   Asked if the Pentagon could explain the sudden increase in
repatriations, Howard replied: ``It's really not for us to do that.
The Vietnamese are the ones who should be explaining to the
American people and to the world what happened to the rest of the
remains and where they are.''
   Lt. Col. Keith Schneider, a Pentagon spokesman, said the
Vietnamese government notified U.S. officials during technical
meetings in mid-March that they were investigating 29 new reports
of remains being found or information regarding servicemen
uncovered.
   Earlier this week, the Vietnamese informed the United States it
did have 27 remains to repatriate, Schneider said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
