<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PostalRates     03-31 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postal Rates,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raising Stamp Prices: How It's Done</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New postal rates taking effect Sunday complete
a complex process that got under way 11 months ago.
   While most of the attention on the new 25-cent stamp has
occurred in the last few weeks, the rate was actually proposed by
the U.S. Postal Service in May 1987.
   Since then, there has been so much discussion that some
consumers may be confused about how many times rates have risen,
said John Griesemer, chairman of the Board of Governors of the
Postal Service.
   When it was made an independent federal agency in the early
1970s, the U.S. Postal Service was directed to break even by
raising rates to cover costs. The taxpayer subsidy that had been
provided to the old Post Office was gradually eliminated.
   But to prevent sudden, sharp rate hikes, a separate Postal Rate
Commission was set up to monitor mailing costs.
   Under the law, the Postal Service balances its funds over a term
of years. When losses accumulate it raises rates. Subsequently it
may show a surplus for some years, until costs rise to push it back
into the red and again result in another hike.
   The Postal Service lost $223 million in fiscal 1987, and the red
ink was expected to increase this year despite cost-cutting efforts.
   The agency had a $305 million surplus in 1986, following sharp
cost-cutting in the wake of 1985's loss of $251 million, agency
managers reported.
   Surpluses were reported in 1984, 1983 and 1982, following rate
increases in 1981.
   After the Postal Service's Board of Governors proposed new rates
last May, the case went to the Postal Rate Commission, which is
charged with listening to all interested persons and recommending
whether the new rates should take effect.
   The commission has 10 months to reach a decision, which then
goes back to the postal Board of Governors.
   The commission issued its ruling March 4, three days early. That
decision on a rate hike, which was close to the original request,
was then ordered into effect by the postal governors.
</TEXT>
