<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HumorIndex     03-31 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Humor Index,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laughter Costs More, But You Can Insure Against `Bombs'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans are paying more to laugh
less. But don't worry, the presidential election campaign should
produce some cheap chuckles.
   The 1988 Cost of Laughing Index, released to coincide with April
Fool's Day and adjusted for inflation, showed a 5.8 percent
increase in the humor scale over last year.
   The annual index, which measures 18 leading humor indicators,
compares the punch line to the bottom line. It showed the wholesale
price of rubber chickens increased $4.80 per dozen during the past
12 months.
   ``The trend in playful poultry is particularly worrisome,'' said
Malcolm Kushner, a self-described humor consultant who compiled the
index. ``Over the past two years, rubber chickens prices have
jumped 23 percent and dancing chicken telegrams have risen by 9
percent.
   ``Funny fowl may soon become a memory for most American
consumers.''
   Other increases included an 8 percent hike in comedy club ticket
prices and an 11 percent jump in the newstand price of Mad
Magazine. On the up side, the wholesale price of Groucho glasses
and arrow-through-the-head gags did not change.
   Former attorney Kushner, whose consulting operation is based in
Santa Cruz, also gives seminars on how to use humor to communicate.
His clients include IBM, Lockheed and the notoriously funny IRS.
</TEXT>
