<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BearEscape     03-31 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bear Escape,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wrestling Bear Escapes From Cage, Sits On Neighbor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRONGSVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man trying to return a neighbor's
escaped pet wound up like an amateur facing pro wrestlers Hulk
Hogan or Andre the Giant _ he was pinned on the first fall by a
700-pound wrestling bear.
   Harry Dodge, a retired Cleveland Heights animal warden, opened
his door Wednesday when he heard a noise on his porch and spotted
his neighbor's trained and declawed black bear, Smoky.
   He realized Smoky apparently had broken out of his cage and took
some apples to lure him back home.
   The 7-foot-tall bear just tripped him and sat on him.
   ``The bear thought it was a wrestling match,'' said Lorain
County Deputy Sheriff Gary Abicht.
   The bear performs under the stage name Caesar at taverns or
social events and wrestles with anyone who thinks they can beat him.
   When authorities tried to remove Smoky from Dodge's yard in this
Cleveland suburb, the bear wouldn't even budge for four Lorain
County deputies, three or four policemen from Strongsville and two
officers from Olmsted Falls. So they tied him to a tree with a rope
until they located Smoky's owner, Salvatore Mazzola.
   Then, ``they gave him some peanut butter or something and lured
him into a trailer'' used to transport him, Abicht said.
   Abicht said Mazzola quarreled with a game warden at the scene
and was charged with obstructing official business. He was freed on
$1,500 bond.
   State Game Protector Tom Harrod said Thursday he was preparing
additional charges against Mazzola for not having state licenses
for Smoky and a bear cub named Magnum, or for a raccoon that lives
in Mazzola's house.
   Harrod said he put the animals in the custody of another animal
handler until Mazzola gets the permits.
   Dodge was treated at Southwest General Hospital for back and
neck strain.
</TEXT>
