<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Strategy Bjt   03-31 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Strategy, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Focuses on General Election Amid Talk of James Baker Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, his grip now firm
on the Republican presidential nomination, is shifting his focus to
the fall election amid speculation that Treasury Secretary James A.
Baker III will resign to oversee his campaign.
   Reagan administration sources suggested that Baker, a longtime
Bush ally, likely would not make such a move before the GOP
convention in New Orleans Aug. 15-18, despite the withdrawal this
week of Sen. Bob Dole.
   Dole's exit from the race, virtually guaranteeing Bush will be
the GOP candidate, heightened expectations that Baker might speed
up a decision to join the Bush team.
   But a Treasury Department official, commenting only on condition
of anonymity, said on Thursday there was no truth to suggestions
that Baker might resign as early as August 1. The official would
not elaborate.
   Baker intends to participate in the seven-nation economic summit
in Toronto in late June, administration officials said.
   Meanwhile, President Reagan may begin campaigning for Bush even
before the party convention, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said. The
White House had previously said that Reagan would remain neutral
until the convention.
   Fitzwater said that policy is being reconsidered ``in view of
the way the campaign has developed, and in view of the vice
president's now seemingly assured nomination.''
   Baker has longstanding ties to Bush and managed his 1980
presidential bid. He also was chairman of President Ford's 1976
camaign and senior adviser to the 1980 Reagan-Bush campaign.
   Peter Teeley, a Bush campaign spokesman, said a discussion of
what role Baker might play in the Bush campaign, if any, was only
speculative at this time.
   However, Teeley added, ``Jim is very close to the vice president
and has been for a quarter of a century. There's no secret what
their relationship has been.''
   Baker could probably have any job in a Bush presidency that he
wanted, and there have been rumors for some time that he would like
to be secretary of state rather than continue on as treasury
secretary _ even though he has built an international reputation in
his current post and appears to enjoy the job.
   Bush on Wednesday told reporters he intended to ``have a new
Cabinet'' if elected. The answer responded specifically to a query
on embattled Atty. Gen. Edwin Meese III but might also be taken as
a signal that there would be a new treasury secretary in a Bush
presidency.
   Baker became treasury secretary in 1985 after four years as
Reagan's chief of staff.
   Bush was back in Washington Thursday after a three-day swing
through Wisconsin. He scaled back campaign stops in that state,
which holds its primary election next Tuesday, after Dole's
withdrawal.
   Reagan had his regular weekly lunch with Bush on Thursday, but
Fitzwater said he did not know if campaign plans were discussed.
   The president's spokesman said a decision on any presidential
campaign activity in Bush's behalf before the convention ``has not
been finally made, although ... the vice president is very close to
having the nomination.''
   ``Pat Robertson is still a candidate, in a declared sense, but
he too recognizes the realities of the situation,'' Fitzwater said.
   The vice president called his new status, without a major GOP
rival, ``exhilarating,'' and campaign aides made use of the time in
Washington to plot future strategy _ including ways to keep
attention focused on Bush now that the nomination appears sewn up.
   ``It does take us out of the spotlight,'' spokesman Teeley
acknowledged. ``But he is the vice president. He will be the
nominee of the party. And he will be able to generate news.''
   For now, Bush is continuing with plans for campaign appearances
in states that have upcoming primaries and that will also be
important in the general election _ including New York, New Jersey,
Ohio and Pennsylvania.
   He is also planning fund-raising trips late next week to Texas
and Florida, states where he has already won primaries.
   While running on the record of the eight-year Reagan-Bush
administration, Bush has also been seeking to develop and flesh out
his own themes, including a heavy emphasis on educational issues.
   ``George Bush's job now is to solidify the Republican Party. He
can develop themes now for the Republicans in November. That's
something the Democrats can't do,'' said Rep. James Sensenbrenner,
R-Wis., who traveled with the vice president in Wisconsin this week.
   And, jokes Bush, ``It's important for a vice president not to
upstage his boss. And you don't know how hard it's been for me to
keep my charisma in check for the past seven years.''
</TEXT>
