<2ND_LINE>PM-Mummy Found, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0603,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Pleads Guilty In Mummy Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Kunce pleading innocent and
ADD details on child neglect charges and Stevens' death; picks up
7th graf pvs, ``Stevens' withered ... ''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who concealed her husband's death
for eight years and tended the corpse as if it were alive pleaded
guilty today to a felony forgery charge stemming from the death.
   But a former Chicago-area dentist accused of assisting her in
the forgery pleaded innocent and a jury trial was ordered.
   Carole Stevens, 42, entered her plea today in Knox County
Circuit Court before Associate Judge Harry Bulkeley.
   Mrs. Stevens was sentenced to two years probation and 12 days in
the county jail, for which she received credit for 12 days already
served. Officials said Mrs. Stevens still faces a hearing on child
neglect charges involving her two children, who are in foster care.
   Besides probation, Bulkeley ordered Mrs. Stevens to undergo a
psychiatric examination and told her to have no further contact
with her alleged partner in the deception, Richard G. Kunce, 56, a
former Aurora dentist.
   Kunce, in a brief appearance today before Judge Stephen Mathers,
pleaded innocent and left the courtroom. He still awaits a court
appearance on a felony charge of cruelty to children.
   In February, Mrs. Stevens and Kunce both pleaded guilty in Knox
County Court to misdemeanor charges of failing to report the May
1979 death of Carl L. Stevens, a diabetic who authorities say died
shortly after he joined a holistic health cult and stopped taking
his daily insulin shots.
   Steven's withered corpse was found Jan. 29 on a bed in the home,
where officials said his widow had cared for the body daily over
the past eight years, changing its clothes and moving it from room
to room.
   Following their guilty pleas on the misdemeanor charges, both
Mrs. Stevens and Kunce also faced felony forgery charges.
   Mrs. Stevens was accused of fabricating a power of attorney for
her dead husband in 1984. Kunce, who was a guest in the Stevens
house the past year, was charged with forgery for signing his name
to the document as a witness.
   Last week, Kunce asked a judge to withdraw his guilty plea on
the charge of failure to report Stevens' death. The hearing on
Kunce's request was postponed until late April.
  
</TEXT>
