<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PeachBottom     03-31 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peach Bottom,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Year After Nuke Shutdown, Plant Appeals Directly To Public</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the year since Peach Bottom became the
first nuclear plant shut down because workers slept on the job,
shareholders have absorbed $72 million in replacement energy costs,
its operator said Thursday.
   Philadelphia Electric Co. said in a blunt ``open letter'' to
civic and governmental organizations in southeastern Pennsylvania
and northern Maryland that the episode has been ``an embarassment''
and that the plant would not restart until the company is
``completely satisfied'' conditions had changed.
   On March 31, 1987, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission ordered
Peach Bottom closed indefinitely, citing a pattern of control room
operators dozing on duty and saying continued operation posed ``an
immediate threat to health and safety.''
   ``To date, the shutdown has caused the company's shareholders to
absorb approximately $72 million of higher replacement energy
costs, while the Pennsylvania Public Utility Commission has ordered
PE customers' rates to be reduced by $30.4 million per year until
restart,'' PE said in the letter.
   ``There is no question that the public confidence has been
shaken as the result of this shutdown and this is the type of
communication with the public that will begin to rebuild that,'' PE
spokesman Neil McDermott said.
   The letter was signed by PE President and Chief Operating
Officer Joseph Paquette, who took over three weeks ago, after James
Everett III resigned in the face of mounting criticism over Peach
Bottom's restart.
   Paquette blamed problems at Peach Bottom in part on a lack of
leadership by senior managers and a stagnant ``culture'' at the
plant that was devoid of individual accountability and open
communication.
   Since the shutdown, PE has proposed reorganizing work crews,
removed all supervisors who were at the plant one year ago, hired a
former Navy rear admiral as plant manager, instituted a new
training program for operators, and fired four employees and
suspended seven others for drug-related activities. Most of the
drug problems were said to be with maintenance workers.
   PE officials hope Peach Bottom, near the Maryland border, will
be restarted this fall. But officials must first apply to the NRC
regional office, and the regional office would inform the NRC in
Washington when it was convinced the plant was ready.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
