<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Jackson, whose ``Bad'' album
failed to win any Grammys last month, was a big winner in the
second annual Soul Train Music Awards.
   Jackson was honored for 1987 male vocalist album of the year and
the title song was named best single by a male vocalist Wednesday.
   In the female vocalist category, Whitney Houston won best album
for ``Whitney,'' and Natalie Cole took the best single award for
``I Live for Your Love.''
   Janet Jackson, Michael Jackson's sister, won the best music
video award for ``Control.''
   Levert won best group jazz album for ``The Big Throwdown'' and
best group single for ``Cassanova.''
   Another double winner was LL Cool J, whose ``I Need Love'' won
best rap single, and ``Bigger & Deffer'' was named best rap album.
   The night's biggest loser was Jody Watley, last month's best new
artist Grammy winner. She had tied Michael Jackson for most
nominations with three, including best female single and album and
best video, but came up empty-handed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WAUKESHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight hundred people turned out to honor
musician Les Paul and his mother, Evelyn Polfuss, on her 100th
birthday.
   At her home town celebration Wednesday, Mrs. Polfuss received
proclamations from Gov. Tommy Thompson, the Legislature and
President Reagan. Paul was given a plaque for his induction into
the Wisconsin Area Music Industry Hall of Fame. ``It is just one of
the finest evenings we've had in this city,'' Mayor Paul Vrakas
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Joan Rivers has decided the
show must go on, even if she has to pick up the tab.
   Promoter Doug East said Wednesday he was canceling Miss Rivers'
performances Friday in Myrtle Beach and Saturday in Charleston
because of poor ticket sales.
   But Miss Rivers, who says she only canceled performances for
three months following the death of her husband last year, was
adamant.
   ``I don't do that to people who have bought tickets,'' she said
Wednesday from her Hollywood home. ``Even if there's only one
person in the audience, I'm going to do the show.
   ``I stand to lose about $50,000. I'm so (mad) I can't even
discuss it. But, I just don't operate that way. Maybe that's why
I've been in the business 22 years.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   P0NTIAC, Mich. (AP) _ John Z. De Lorean is suing his tax
attorney, saying he lost a $700,000 refund because the lawyer
missed a filing deadline.
   The 63-year-old former auto executive said in a lawsuit filed
Wednesday in Oakland County Circuit Court that he was entitled to
$700,127 for overpayment of his 1982 federal income taxes, but tax
attorney Frank C. Shaler missed the April 15, 1986, deadline.
   ``It's a friendly lawsuit,'' De Lorean said by telephone from
his home in Bedminster, N.J. ``It was a slip-up on Frank's part,
and he reported it to his insurance company. It was something he
just missed on the statute of limitations. He was the one who told
me about it.''
   ``He's still my accountant. He's a real sweet guy.''
   Shaler declined comment.
   De Lorean, whose Northern Ireland-based sports car company
collapsed in 1982, said he is preparing to get back into the auto
business with plans to build a new, ``exotic'' sports car in West
Germany. In 1984, he was acquitted of federal charges of selling
cocaine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guitarist Chet Atkins is $5 richer
thanks to a fellow musician who borrowed the money 30 years ago and
remembered it had not been repaid.
   Atkins found the $5 in his mail slot Wednesday from Ed
Dettenheim of Haynesville, La. In a note attached, Dettenheim said
he was repaying $5 that Atkins had wired him in 1958 to bail him
out of jail in Humboldt, Tenn., where he was being held on a
traffic charge.
   At the time, Dettenheim was playing guitar with the Rhythm
Rebels band.
   Atkins said Thursday he doesn't remember the loan. But he added,
``I'm glad I was a good neighbor.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias
Sanchez will be the principal speaker at the Harvard University
commencement in June.
   The author of a Central American peace plan, Arias won the 1987
Nobel Peace Prize for his ``outstanding contribution to the
possible return of stability and peace to a region long torn by
strife and civil war,'' the Nobel Committee said in awarding the
honor.
   Arias, 47, studied at Boston University and attended Harvard's
summer school before continuing his education abroad. He spoke last
year at Harvard's John F. Kennedy School of Government.
   Harvard announced the speaker Thursday. The 337th commencement
exercises will take place June 9.
</TEXT>
