<HEAD>Congressional Candidate Brewster Raps Exclusion From Stag Dinner
</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: `Lasociete' in 3rd graf is correct.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BECKLEY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman running for Congress says she's
been barred from an annual stag dinner that has become a regular
campaign event and which her opponent and several other candidates
are likely to attend.
   ``This isn't just a woman trying to get tickets,'' Marianne
Brewster said Wednesday. ``This is a candidate for the House of
Representatives.''
   Brewster, a Republican running in the 4th District race, said
she won't try to gain admission to the Forty & Eight Lasociete's
oyster dinner April 8 at Mount View High School.
   ``I do plan to stand outside and shake hands and do it that
way,'' said Brewster, a Bluefield businesswoman. ``I don't want to
cause problems, but it's difficult to have to combat this.''
   Frank Pisano, a member of Forty & Eight, an offshoot of the
American Legion, said he expects up to 1,200 people to attend the
dinner. Dozens of local, state and national office seekers
typically attend.
   U.S. Rep. Nick Rahall, a Democrat seeking re-election to the 4th
District seat, previously has attended and he and several
candidates for high state office plan to attend this year, Pisano
said.
   Throughout its quarter-century history, the $15-a-head dinner
has been off limits to women, he said.
   ``The policy that we've had is that it's a stag affair,'' Pisano
said. ``I don't have the authority to say we can open it up to
these other people.''
</TEXT>
