<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Nofziger 2ndLd-Writethru a0624 03-31 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nofziger, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0624,640</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS six grafs with additional details.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential aide Lyn Nofziger should
be imprisoned because he showed a ``total lack of remorse'' when
convicted of illegally lobbying the White House, independent
counsel James C. McKay said today in court papers.
   McKay recommended that Nofziger receive a prison term for three
counts of violating the Ethics in Government Act to ``impress
present and former government employees, as well as the general
public that Congress intended those restrictions be taken seriously
and that they will be enforced with meaningful penalties.''
   The prosecutor noted that Nofziger, 63, former White House
political director, likened his crime to ``running a stop sign''
following his conviction Feb. 11 on three counts of illegal
lobbying his former agency within a year of leaving government.
   ``Since being found guilty, defendant Nofziger has made a number
of remarks showing a total lack of remorse or contrition for his
offenses,'' McKay said in a sentencing memo to U.S. District Judge
Thomas Flannery.
   ``That intransigent attitude is a consideration arguing in favor
of a sentence that includes a period of incarceration,'' McKay said.
   As further evidence of Nofziger's lack of contrition, McKay
quoted a Feb. 18 letter to the court in which Nofziger wrote: ``I
have never thought, and I do not think today, that I am guilty
morally, ethically or legally of the crimes of which I am
convicted.''
   Nofziger is scheduled to be sentenced April 8 and could receive
two-year prison terms and a $10,000 fine for each of the three
convictions of illegally lobbying on behalf of Wedtech Corp., a
maritime engineers union and the manufacturer of the Air Force A-10
anti-tank plane.
   In addition to an unspecified prison term, McKay recommended
``that an appropriate fine be imposed for each violation and that
the fines be imposed cumulatively for the three violations.''
   ``Nofziger's special entree to the most powerful officials in
government, including the president himself, epitomized the very
danger to public perception about the integrity of governmental
decision-making that motivated Congress to enact the one-year
no-contact prohibition,'' McKay said.
   McKay also dismissed Nofziger's argument that he misunderstood
the ethics law, saying he had received a White House manual that
instructed all members of President Reagan's staff to review
carefully the rules on post-employment lobbying.
   In addition, Nofziger received extensive legal advice from a
private law firm about the law, McKay said.
   The sentencing memo referred to an incident in which Nofziger
allegedly uttered a profanity when told by one of his lawyers not
to make any White House contacts ``without first clearing it with
his lawyers.''
   During a bench conference out of hearing of jurors and the
public, Associate Independent Counsel Merrick Garland told the
judge that after responding with a profanity, Nofziger said ``these
are my friends and I am going back to them if I want to'',
according to the memo.
   McKay noted that ``defense counsel has attempted to minimize the
significance of this episode by asserting that defendant Nofziger's
profanity in response to his lawyer's advice was characteristic of
their client's jocularity.''
   ``Perhaps so,'' the sentencing memo continued. ``But his lawyers
at the time took the incident seriously. They have told staff
members of the independent counsel that this episode caused
concern'' within the law firm.
   ``Whatever his choice of words, however, it is evident that
defendant Nofziger was alerted to and deliberately chose to ignore
written and oral advice that Section 207(c) (of the law) applied to
him,'' McKay said.
   During the trial, defense lawyers unsuccessfully sought to claim
that Nofziger had acted with the advice of his counsel when he
lobbied the White House on behalf of at least one client. Flannery
refused to allow the defense to raise this argument, saying it was
legally impermissible.
</TEXT>
