<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Bush     03-31 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Bush,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan May Stump for Bush in Early Summer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan may go on the road to
campaign for George Bush before the GOP convention to give his vice
president an edge going into the fall campaign, the White House
said Thursday.
   The move indicates that Reagan is ending his official neutrality
in the GOP race before the party's convention, scheduled for Aug.
15-18 in New Orleans.
   ``I just want to signal you that that is changing,''
presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters.
   ``The president has always been ready,'' the spokesman said.
``He's ready at the drop of a hat to get out there on the road.
He's ready to get into the campaign at any point.''
   However, Fitzwater said, ``The president has always wanted to
get involved in the political process as soon as possible. It's
simply that his position on neutrality required that that could not
happen until after the convention.''
   He said the president ``could decide to do some events earlier''
in the light of Bush's string of primary and caucus victories,
which have forced all other Republican candidates except the badly
lagging Pat Robertson from the field.
   ``I think that in view of the way the campaign has developed,
and in view of the vice president's now seemingly assured
nomination, that we would rethink that situation in view of those
new realities, and that we could see the president involved in some
political activities before the nominating convention _ activities
that are directly associated with the nominee,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said a decision ``has not been finally made, although
every one is aware ... that the reality of the situation is such
that the vice president is very close to having the nomination.''
   ``Pat Robertson is still a candidate, in a declared sense, but,
he, too recognizes the realities of the situation,'' he said.
   Bush has more than 800 of the 1,139 needed to win the
nomination, according to a count by The Associated Press. Robertson
has 17.
   Bush was having his regular weekly lunch with the president
Thursday. Fitzwater said he did not know what they planned to talk
about.
   Fitzwater said no decision had been made on an endorsement, and
no events had been scheduled or were expected to be scheduled soon.
   ``I simply want to open the door to this new prospect,'' he said.
   Reagan, who defeated Bush for the GOP presidential nomination in
1980, has often spoken of him in glowing terms, ranking him at or
near the top among U.S. vice presidents.
</TEXT>
