<HEAD>North Alabama Fugitive Known As `Wolf Boy' Recaptured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUPELO, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Alabama fugitive known as ``Wolf Boy''
faced federal charges today after a 16-year-old kidnap victim from
Illinois was found tied to a motel bed, FBI agents said.
   Agent Kevin Rust said Gary Williams, 30, an escape artist who
fled the county jail in Decatur, Ala., last October, was armed but
offered no resistance when FBI agents surrounded the Carro Motel
and arrested him Wednesday night.
   Agents had spotted the car of the kidnap victim at the Carro,
Rust said.
   Michelle Yokum, 16, of Casey, Ill., was found Wednesday morning
tied to a bed in a motel in nearby Corinth after employees heard
her cries.
   Yokum told authorities Williams had left in her car. She said
that she had been abducted at gunpoint Tuesday night in Illinois
while making a delivery in her car from the restaurant where she
worked. The teen-ager said she had not been harmed by Williams.
   Williams was scheduled for a hearing today on a federal escape
charge in Aberdeen, Miss.
   Williams reportedly has made 10 escapes in the last several
years and became known as ``Wolf Boy'' while hiding out in caves in
Alabama's Bankhead National Forest. He was serving a jail term for
grand larceny and had numerous property offenses on his record.
   Authorities said Williams apparently approached Yokum's car,
forced her at gunpoint to move over to the passenger's side, then
started driving south.
   FBI agents said Williams is a suspect in the abduction of a
24-year-old Cedar Key, Fla., woman who escaped from her kidnappers
in Adell, Ga., last week. Rust said Williams' brother, Jerry
Williams, 20, was arrested in Georgia in connection with that
kidnapping. Yokum said Williams told her that he had abducted a
woman in Florida but she got away in Georgia.
</TEXT>
