<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-PopulationOutlook Bjt   03-31 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Population Outlook, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Northeast Slipping to Least Populated Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The densely settled Northeast has become the
nation's least populated region, falling behind the West for the
first time, the Census Bureau reported Thursday.
   The bureau also projected that Texas will surpass New York for
second place behind California in population by 1995.
   And between now and the year 2000, half of all U.S. population
growth will occur in just three states: California, Texas and
Florida, the report said.
   The projections are based on assumptions about trends in births,
deaths, immigration and movement within the country, bureau
demographer Signe Wetrogen explained.
   The Northeast has been declining in its share of the U.S.
population, with less growth than other areas, Wetrogen said in a
telephone interview. ``It is the one region with the highest share
of population in the older ages, and has low birth rates.''
   Population shifts to the South and West in recent years have
drawn away many people in the prime ages of 18 to 24, ``so the
(Northeast) region is left with more older people, and it's left
without anybody to have more kids,'' she said.
   The Northeastern states, relatively smaller in land area than
other parts of the country, remain the mosty densely packed,
however. New Jersey leads the nation with more than 1,000 people
per square mile.
   Between 1987 and 1988, the Western region increased from 49.6
million people to 50.5 million, the report said. At the same time,
the population of the Northeast edged upward from 50.1 million to
50.3 million, to slip into last place.
   The 1988 estimates listed the South with 85.1 million people,
followed by the Midwest with 59.6 million.
   Historical records show that, while it was the center of early
American development, the Northeast hasn't actually been the most
populous region since 1820, when the South edged ahead. It remained
second until 1880, falling to third behind both the Midwest and
South.
   By 1990, the projections call for the South to have 87.3 million
people, followed by the Midwest, 59.8 million; West, 52.3 million;
and Northeast, 50.6 million.
   By 2000, the counts are expected to be 96.9 million for the
South, 59.6 million for the Midwest, 59.4 million for the West and
51.8 million for the Northeast.
   By 2010, the report added, the West could replace the Midwest as
the second-most-populous region.
   State population projections showed California remaining
unchallenged as the largest state, growing from 28 million people
today to 29.1 million in 1990 and 33.5 million in 2000.
   Texas is expected to surpass New York for second rank by 1995.
The Empire State now leads Texas 17.7 million to 17.2 million, but
by 1995 Texas is projected to have just over 19 million people,
with New York at only 17.9 million.
   Florida is expected to remain the fourth-largest state, although
by the year 2010 it may be closing in on New York as well, the
Census Bureau said.
   By the year 2000, Illinois will have replaced Pennsylvania in
fifth place and Georgia will move into 10th, displacing North
Carolina, the report said.
   The U.S. population was projected to grow from 243.3 million in
1987 to 267.7 million in 2000.
   In that period, California is expected to add 6 million
residents, Florida 3.5 million and Texas 3.3 million. That means
those states would have growth of 12.8 million people, 52 percent
of the national increase of 24.4 million.
   Pennsylvania, Ohio, Iowa, West Virginia and the District of
Columbia were projected to lose population this decade.
   Population losses in the 1990s were predicted for nine more
states: Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, Wisconsin, North Dakota,
Nebraska, Kentucky, Montana and Wyoming. On the other hand, growth
was predicted to resume in the District of Columbia.
   During the 1990s, the maturing of the post-World War II Baby
Boom generation will be reflected in the growth of the 45-64 age
group in all parts of the country. The number of people aged 24 to
44 is expected to drop in the Northeast and Midwest but grow
elsewhere, the report said.
   The study said the South continues to have the largest
percentage of blacks in its population, 16 percent. More than half
of all black Americans reside in the South, and that is expected to
continue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1401EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GandhiStatues     03-31 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gandhi Statues,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Nephew Wants To Erect U.S. Memorials To Non-Violent
Activist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A relative of India's revered pacifist
revolutionary, Mohandas Gandhi, is working to erect memorials to
him in 15 North American cities, but Boston is having a little
trouble finding a spot for its monument.
   The inspiration and money is coming from a foundation created by
Yoges Gandhi, a grandnephew of the man who led India to
independence in 1947 with non-violent protests.
   Gandhi said Wednesday he chose this city of monuments to
revolutionary heroes as one of the 15 cities because he wants to
remind people to be better to one another.
   ``The statue of Gandhi will encourage people to follow the path
of non-violence. We don't want to focus on the man, but what he has
done,'' said Gandhi.
   The founder and president of the 5-year-old Gandhi Foundation
said he already has $250,000 for the project. He wants the statues
erected by Oct. 2 for a national celebration of the 119th
anniversary of Gandhi's birth.
   Boston officials from Mayor Raymond Flynn on down have welcomed
the memorial.
   But finding a site for the statue or monument is a problem,
because of the city's current state of construction upheaval, from
its roads to its skyline.
   Mary Shannon is executive secretary of the Boston Art
Commission, the agency that decides what monuments look like and
where they go. She said the five-member panel is leaning toward a
bas relief that would include text to better convey Gandhi's
message.
   Mrs. Shannon said the site should be worked out within the next
few weeks and the design selected by May.
   A statue of Gandhi is not incongruous for Boston, where
Revolutionary War generals are remembered as well as abolitionists
and Gandhi devotee Martin Luther King Jr., said Mrs. Shannon.
   Two years ago the foundation erected a statue of Gandhi in New
York City's Union Square.
   Other cities on Gandhi's list are Atlanta, Chicago, Denver,
Honolulu, Houston, Los Angeles, Miami, Philadelphia, San Francisco,
Memphis, Tenn., and, in Canada, Montreal, Toronto and Vancouver.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1405EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SizableSavings     03-31 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sizable Savings,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man's Untouched Savings Account Nearly Tripled Since '72</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 77-year-old widower who lives
in a tiny mobile home and depends on a bicycle for transportation
has collected about $21,000 in interest from a long-ignored savings
account.
   ``I didn't forget about it,'' Henry Kinslow said. ``That's why
you put money in a bank _ to let it collect interest.''
   Kinslow closed his account at OneBank in North Little Rock on
Wednesday, saying he didn't want to pedal 30 miles from Conway to
keep tabs on it.
   Kinslow, a retired electrical engineer and former hobo, had been
told by the state auditor's office that his $34,482.29 in savings
was in danger of government seizure because of a lack of account
activity.
   Kinslow said the last bank statement he received showed a
balance of about $13,500.
   That was in 1972. The statements stopped because he didn't give
the bank his change of address.
   The state auditor's staff says $750,000 hasn't been claimed by
nearly 2,500 people whose accounts or other scheduled transactions,
like utility deposits, have been inactive for at least seven years.
   The office is conducting a drive, called the Great Arkansas
Treasure Hunt, to notify owners of such accounts under a 1987 law
which mandates that money from such accounts that is unclaimed by
April 7, 1990, goes into state general revenues.
   Kinslow's balance was the largest unclaimed amount, the
auditor's office said.
   A news report about the notification drive caught the attention
of a teller at Kinslow's bank in Conway. The teller notified the
owner of the mobile home park where Kinslow lives, and the park
owner drove Kinslow to the North Little Rock bank.
   ``I wanted my money. I worked for about 25 years to make it,''
Kinslow said.
   What are his plans for the windfall?
   ``Put it in another bank,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
