<DOCNO> AP880331-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1408EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 3rdLd-Writethru a0653 03-31 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0653,0833</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Move To Reconsider Dismissal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to update with talk of reconsidering
dismmissal; pick up 5th graf pvs: ``I've been taking ...''; SUBS
11th graf pvs, ``The dismissal xxx to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Senate began working today on
rules for its votes on two articles of impeachment to oust Gov.
Evan Mecham, and one lawmaker said he would try to reinstate a
third charge that was dismissed.
   The Senate, acting as judge and jury in the first-term
Republican's trial, met briefly and adjourned into separate party
caucuses to discuss how the vote should be taken. It was expected
to reconvene this afternoon.
   Republican Sen. John Mawhinney, who voted against the motion
Wednesday to dismiss a charge that Mecham concealed a $350,000
campaign loan, said some senators had second thoughts.
   Mawhinney said his proposal would still allow the Senate to vote
next week on the first two charges, on which testimony already has
been heard. The third charge would be heard if Mecham was acquitted
on the other two.
   Wednesday's vote came as a surprise to many senators and set the
stage for a vote as early as Monday on two other charges against
the governor, who also faces a May 17 recall election and an April
21 criminal trial.
   The motion to dismiss the third charge was approved on a 16-12
vote. However two GOP senators who opposed the dismissal were ill
Wednesday but attended today's session. Thus, lawmakers said they
would have to change two other senators' minds to get the 16 votes
to reconsider.
   One of the two who were absent Wednesday, Sen. Greg Lunn, said
he believed it was a ``serious error'' to dismiss the third charge.
   Meanwhile, lawmakers were considering whether to vote on each of
the two impeachment articles as a whole or take separate votes on
all 11 subsections of the two articles.
   ``I've been accepting the body blows for about 15 months now ...
and the ribs are a little bit bruised,'' Mecham, an auto dealer and
perennial political outsider, told a group of GOP supporters
Wednesday.
   But he said he still had plans for ``when I get back there'' in
the governor's office.
   The vote to dismiss the third charge Wednesday was a surprise to
most involved, including the senator who made the motion,
Republican Wayne Stump.
   Several of those who voted to dismiss said they wanted to avoid
prejudicing Mecham's upcoming criminal trial on felony charges that
he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan. That would have been the
subject of evidence on the third impeachment charge and Stump said
it would have put the governor in ``quasi-double jeopardy.''
   The decision set the stage for a vote as early as Monday on two
other charges against the first-term Republican, who also faces a
May 17 recall election and an April 21 criminal trial.
   Mecham remains accused of misusing $80,000 from the governor's
protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership and of trying to
thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state
official.
   Those voting for the dismissal motion were an unusual coalition
of all 11 Senate Democrats plus five Republicans who have
steadfastly supported the governor.
   Lawmakers refused to predict whether there will be the
two-thirds majority of the 30-member Senate needed to convict on
the remaining two charges..
   Democratic Sen. Peter Rios disputed speculation that Democrats
voted for the dismissal motion because they think they have the
votes to boot Mecham.
   ``I think this needs to be brought to a conclusion,'' he said of
the 5-week-old impeachment trial, ``and this is my view of one way
to bring it to a conclusion.''
   ``I've always been confident,'' Mecham told reporters Wednesday
night. He refused to comment directly on the dismissal. Defense
attorney Jerris Leonard said he considered it a victory.
   If Mecham is convicted, Secretary of State Rose Mofford, who has
been acting governor since Mecham's Feb. 5 impeachment by the
House, would become governor.
   The Senate was expected to receive jury instructions this
afternoon. Closing arguments are scheduled for Monday morning, and
a vote can be taken any time afterward.
   Mecham has repeatedly insisted he is innocent of all wrongdoing
and that he is the victim of persecution by the state GOP
establishment and the media.
   He has been surrounded by controversy since he took office in
January 1987. The day after taking office, Mecham canceled a Martin
Luther King holiday for state workers on grounds it was illegally
created by his predecessor, Democratic Gov. Bruce Babbitt.
   He also has made comments that angered blacks, homosexuals,
women, Jews and Japanese.
   The governor said Wednesday night that if he is returned to
office he would be willing to declare that ``bygones can be
bygones'' in his relations with the Legislature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
