<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-PLO     03-31 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-PLO,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Ambassador Says He Resigned Because of Shultz-Palestinian
Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benjamin Netanyahu said Thursday he resigned as
U.N. ambassador to protest Secretary of State George P. Shultz's
meeting with two Arab-Americans linked to the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Netanyahu said the meeting Saturday in Washington endangered
Israel's security and ``raises a larger question of the value of
American commitments to us when we have made huge concessions to
obtain these guarantees.''
   ``I could not speak freely (about this) as long as I was
ambassador. So I had to make a choice,'' he told The Associated
Press.
   The surprise resignation of the articulate, U.S.-educated
Netanyahu _ a rising star in Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
rightist Likud bloc _ was the strongest signal yet of Israeli
displeasure over the Shultz meeting.
   Shultz, in remarks on Israel radio, said it was unreasonable to
suggest he could not meet American citizens.
   But Netanyahu said Shultz's talks with Edward Said and Ibrahim
Abu Lughod violated a 1975 U.S. pledge not to meet with PLO
members. The two are members of the Palestine National Council, the
PLO's parliament-in-exile. U.S. officials said their membership on
the PNC doesn't make them PLO officials.
   In addition, he said, the United States appeared to be clearing
the way for PLO participation in Middle East peace talks and ``a
PLO state right in the heart of Israel, threatening our very
security, our very future.''
   Netanyahu, who had served as U.N. ambassador since 1984, said he
was planning to resign in several weeks anyway to begin campaigning
for a seat as a Likud legislator in November's elections.
   ``I decided to resign early because of the critical
developments,'' he said.
   Likud activists hope the 39-year-old Netanyahu will give an
electoral boost to the entire party, which narrowly missed winning
a majority in 1984 parliamentary elections.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres has suggested Asher Ben Natan, a
former ambassador to France and Germany, as a possible replacement
for Netanyahu.
   Netanyahu, considered a close friend of Shultz, said he still
had ``warm personal regard'' for the secretary of state but that
his meeting with Said and Abu Lughod had created ``a deep rift''
between the United States and Israel.
   ``Even friends can sometimes take steps which are unacceptable
or dangerous,'' he said.
   He said the meeting heightened Israeli concern about a
U.S.-Middle East peace plan, which calls for an international
conference leading to direct peace talks between Israel and its
Arab enemies.
   ``I will pound the pavement from city to city in order to
explain to the public the dangers of an international conference,''
he said.
   Shamir and fellow Likud mambers have staunchly opposed an
international forum, warning that Israel would be outnumbered by
its enemies and forced to make territorial concessions.
   ``The very clear possibility exists now that the PLO will sit
across the table from Israel in this conference and will be the
party we will be demanded to give land to,'' Netanyahu said.
   Shultz goes to Israel on Sunday in his second shuttle to
campaign for the peace plan, and he is likely to hear plenty of
complaints there about the meeting with Said and Abu Lughod.
   Shamir called the meeting ``a slap in the face'' and told party
members ``It was possible to see on television how much they (Said
and Abu Lughod) hate Israel,'' the daily Yediot Ahronot reported
Thursday.
   Netanyahu, the son of a Cornell University professor, has lived
in the United States most of his life. He attended high school in
Philadelphia and studied business administration at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   Netanyahu's brother, Jonathan, became a national hero as the
senior commander during Israel's 1976 rescue of hostages in
Entebbe, Uganda. He was the only Israeli officer killed in the
operation.
</TEXT>
