<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-HolyWeek     03-31 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Holy Week,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Celebrates Holy Thursday Mass, Washes Feet of Priests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Thursday re-enacted Jesus
Christ's last supper with his apostles by washing the feet of 12
priests in a solemn Holy Thursday ritual.
   Some 3,000 worshipers gathered for the two-hour ceremony in the
vast, marble-columned Basilica of St. John Lateran with its 16
rooftop figures of Christ, the apostles and saints silhouetted
against the early evening sky. The 17th century basilica, built on
an ancient Roman property, is the pope's church as bishop of Rome.
   Earlier Thursday, the pontiff celebrated Mass at St. Peter's
Basilica in Vatican City, leading Catholic clergymen _ including 22
cardinals, 30 bishops and some 1,000 priests _ in renewing their
vows of celibacy.
   During the evening ceremony, the 67-year-old pope, draped in
white vestments, washed the feet of the dozen mostly elderly
priests in a service symbolizing Jesus' humility before he was
crucified on Good Friday.
   Wearing a protective apron, the pontiff poured water from a
golden urn onto one foot of each priest, wiping it with a white
cloth before bending down to kiss it.
   The priests, dressed in white, red and gold, were seated on a
platform under the austere, gold-leaf nave of the basilica, which
is said to contain the heads of St. Peter and St. Paul and where
until a century ago popes were crowned.
   The service included hymns and chants by the Sistine Chapel
Choir, as well as a homily in Italian by the pope on the theme of
Christian humility.
   The two rites Thursday began four days of ceremonies that
culminate on Easter Sunday, celebrating the passion, death and
resurrection of Christ.
   On Friday, the pope is to carry a wooden cross in the
traditional Good Friday ceremony starting from the torch-lit
Colosseum. He will celebrate the Easter vigil on Saturday night,
and a Sunday Mass in St. Peter's Square.
</TEXT>
