<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1432EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BiennialSessions     03-31 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biennial Sessions,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Legislative Leaders Want Voters To Decide How Often
Legislature Meets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four legislative leaders on Thursday said
annual sessions were ``an experiment that didn't work'' and called
for a return to sessions every other year.
   ``We have seen legislative expenses rise and we have seen good
lawmakers make the hard choice not to run again because they cannot
be in Concord every year and at the same time make a living for
themselves and their families,'' House Speaker Douglas Scamman said
at a news conference.
   Scamman, House Majority Leader Vincent Palumbo, Senate President
William Bartlett, and Senate Democratic Leader Robert Preston
support a proposed constitutional amendment that would put the
change before voters in November.
   ``They (voters) should have the chance to judge the efficiency
of annual sessions based on the experience of the last four years
and to register their opinion with their vote,'' Scamman said.
   On Wednesday, the House Constitutional and Statuatory Revision
Committee voted 12-4 to recommend legislation that would put the
proposed constitutional amendment on the ballot. Voters approved
annual sessions in 1984.
   Those supporting annual sessions, including House Democratic
Leader Mary Chambers, say state business is too complicated for
legislators to meet every other year.
   ``I haven't seen a piece of legislation (this year) that
couldn't have waited until next year,'' Bartlett said.
</TEXT>
