<DOCNO> AP880331-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1434EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-HeroinArrests 3rdLd-Writethru a0682-a0689-a0695-a0700
03-31 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heroin Arrests, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0682-a0689-a0695-a0700,700</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs. Inserts graf 13, Sen. Howard Metzenbau, with
Metzenbaum comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI said today it had cracked a major
heroin-importing ring involving trafficking through Sicily and was
arresting 233 people in the United States and Italy.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III told a news conference it was
the largest international drug case ever developed by the federal
government and said it has been a ``stunning success.''
   The arrests were the result of a lengthy criminal investigation
in cooperation with Italian authorities, and involved the import of
southwest Asian heroin into the United States.
   The 69 defendants in the United States include 38 charged in New
York City, six in Los Angeles and Boston, 10 in Charlotte, N.C.,
eight in San Juan, Puerto Rico, two in Cleveland and five in
Washington, D.C. In Italy, authorities intend to charge 164 people,
the FBI said.
   U.S. Authorities seized six kilograms of heroin and four
kilograms of cocaine during the course of the investigation.
Italian authorities seized 22 kilograms of heroin last month.
   Meese said the purpose of the investigation has been to
penetrate organized drug operations and not just to make random
drug seizures.
   ``The tentacles of this network spread out across this
country,'' he said.
   The attorney general declined to speculate on what impact the
arrests will have on drug traffic in the United States.
   ``Nobody knows for sure the quantity of heroin or any other drug
coming into the United States,'' he said. But the FBI's strategy of
penetration ``is going to the heart of drug trafficing networks
rather than just cutting off the tentacles.''
   During the news conference to announce the drug arrests, Meese
refused to answer reporters' questions on the resignation of two of
his top aides amid increasing skepticism on Capitol Hill over
whether he can continue to run the Justice Department.
   Meese, who is the target of a broadening criminal investigation,
turned aside at least half a dozen questions relating to the
possibility that he might quit in the wake of Tuesday's
resignations of Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns and Assistant
Attorney General William Weld.
   ``The business of law enforcement is going forward energetically
and without interruption,'' Meese said. ``Our strong management
team is on the job.''
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, who has called for Meese's
resignation, said, ``I think he has lost his credibility. It's a
joke when he's talking about drug enforcement when everyone wants
to know why he's still attorney general.''
   Frank Story, chief of the narcotics section of the criminal
investigations division of the FBI, said authorities also have
seized business assets in connection with the arrests.
   Suspects arrested today have been charged with conspiracies to
import, possess and distribute drugs, the FBI said. Authorities
used physical and electronic surveillance during the investigation.
   Authorities were alerted to the presence of a Sicilian Mafia
drug network operating out of New York City and trafficking in
heroin by a 1985 drug case involving a New York pizza restaurant,
authorities said.
   A government affidavit filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
said two of the defendants in the current case operate pizza
restaurants in New York City and another is a former pizza
restaurant owner there.
   Two of the defendants in New York City and one of those charged
in Charlotte are fugitives from Italian drug convictions, The FBI
said.
   The Sicilian Mafia's drug trafficking plan involved exporting
cocaine from the United States to Italy, where it would be
exchanged for heroin and then smuggled back to the United States,
the FBI said.
   Meese said the difference in the price of cocaine here and in
Italy made the scheme profitable for the network.
   Meese and FBI Director William Sessions commended the
cooperation of the Italian government and law enforcement agencies
in coordinating the investigation and arrests.
   Sessions said Italian law enforcement officials have made 68
arrests so far and are pursuing fugitives in Italy, Sicily,
Venezuela and several U.S. cities.
   ``The Sicilian Mafia that today's actions are directed against
is one of the primary groups responsible for the importation of
southwest Asian heroin into the United States,'' he said.
   He said the three other primary groups bringing drugs into the
United States are Mexicans, Colombians and Asians.
</TEXT>
