<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Teamsters-Truckers     03-31 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters-Truckers,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Teamsters union and the trucking industry
reached a tentative agreement today on a national freight contract
covering some 200,000 drivers and warehouse workers.
   The three-year National Master Freight Agreement would replace a
contract of similar length with the industry's collective
bargaining arm, Trucking Management Inc., that was scheduled to
expire at midnight.
   Terms of the accord, which still must be ratified by
rank-and-file union members, were not disclosed immediately. But
Teamsters President Jackie Presser said it ``addresses the economic
need of our members and advances their legitimate claims for job
security.''
   Going into the talks, Teamsters officials were under pressure to
end a pattern of concessionary bargaining since the industry was
deregulated in 1980 and win wage and benefit gains in the range of
3 percent to 4 percent over their current base pay of $14.71 an
hour for drivers.
   While some large carriers are enjoying fairly healthy profits
now despite freight rate-cutting wars among them, several smaller
companies are having financial troubles.
   Teamster employees of the smaller firms had indicated they were
more interest in job protection than large wage gains.
   Since deregulation of trucking in the last year of the Carter
administration, at least 78 Teamster-organized carriers have gone
out of business or been swallowed up in mergers. The union has lost
about 120,000 members in the industry since 1979, although it has
stablized in recent years.
   ``Negotiations were difficult because the industry is in such
financial chaos,'' Presser said, encouraging his union's members to
ratify the accord. Under the Teamsters' constitution, it takes a
two-thirds membership vote to reject a contract approved by the
union's leaders.
   Duke Zeller, a spokesman for the union, said both sides had
agreed not to discuss details of the tentative contract until after
it had been submitted for a ratification vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
