<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1648EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolGuide     03-31 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Guide,0825</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bold New Consumer's Guide Rates School Districts On Scale Of 0-100</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A first-of-its-kind guidebook rating some 500
metropolitan school districts offers families relocating to a new
area a way to begin answering the question: Where are the good
schools?
   The answers in ``Public Schools USA,'' (Williamson Publishing,
$17.95) a 366-page book by 25-year veteran education writer Charles
H. Harrison, aren't surprising: Larger urban districts like
Chicago, Los Angeles and Washington generally rate low, and
wealthier suburban districts, especially in the Northeast, score
high.
   But what is surprising is the book's daring ``Effective Schools
Index,'' which rates all 500 or so districts on a scale of 0-100.
   The highest score by any district was Brighton, N.Y., an
affluent Rochester suburb cited for an excellent program for gifted
students, with a near-perfect 98.
   At the opposite end, Oakland, Calif., scored 13. The book noted
high levels of classroom disruption, vandalism, lack of funds and
``fair to poor'' building maintenance.
   Still, the book to be published late April is meant as a
consumer guide, not a scientific study or survey. Its introduction
stresses: ``We have not tried to pick the so-called `best
districts' in an area.''
   Harrison, who spent a year and about $10,000 of his money
researching the book, profiled each district using 22 statistics
gathered in mailed questionnaires filled out by the districts
themselves.
   Using 10 of those 22 statistics, Harrison devised his
``effective schools index.'' The median score nationwide was 58.
   School districts earned from zero to 10 points on each of 10
criteria: average daily attendance, spending per pupil, dropout
rate, average combined SAT or ACT scores, percentage of eligible
students taking the SAT or ACT, number of Advanced Placement
courses, teacher-student ratios in elementary and secondary grades,
counselor-student ratio, and number of students per music
specialist.
   Districts that didn't provide a statistic or misinterpreted a
question received a zero.
   Twenty of the 26 districts that scored 85 or higher were in the
Northeast. A dozen were in the New York metropolitan area, and
seven of those were in Nassau and Suffolk counties on Long Island.
   Outside the Northeast, Elmhurst, Ill., scored 91; Mayfield,
Ohio, 86; South Euclid-Lyndhurst, Ohio, 86; Bloomfield Hills,
Mich., 93; Westside School District, Omaha, Neb., 89, and Kirkwood,
Mo., 88.
   But quite a number of districts did not respond to Harrison's
mailed requests and therefore received no rating, including New
York City, Boston, Detroit, Kansas City, Mo., Boise, Idaho,
Charleston, S.C., Newark, N.J., New Orleans and San Francisco.
   And the guide covered only districts with at least 2,500
students located within 25 miles of 52 core cities _ meaning
thousands of districts were excluded because of size or location.
   The book also evaluated ``quality of school leadership,''
``quality of instruction,'' and ``quality of school environment,''
drawing on the expertise of about 1,000 local education reporters,
parent groups and others.
   Those write-ups offer consumers a way to look beyond the
statistics.
   ``Statistically, cities seem to look bad,'' said Harrison in an
interview. ``But our profiles point out that there are conclaves of
excellence, magnet schools of high quality, good principals and
good teachers. We didn't want to write the cities off.''
   Houston, for example, scored a below-average 30 on the book's
effectiveness index. But the district's profile praised its gifted
programs, and added building maintenance is good, ``especially for
a district of this size.''
   On the other hand, Grandview, Mo., rates a strong 70, but its
write-up warns readers to ``take note of the low score on the state
competency test in math.''
   While the numerical rankings are sure to attract the most
attention, they can be misleading taken alone.
   For example, Ridgewood, N.J. scored 86, earning perfect 10s in
many of the index's 10 statistical categories. But it received only
3 out of 10 points for spending $5,034 per pupil, well below the
$5,544 average for New Jersey.
   While Harrison's index penalizes Ridgewood for
``underspending,'' Ridgewood's taxpayers may, in fact, be getting
better value for their education dollars than, say, White Plains,
N.Y., which scored a comparable 88 but was awarded the full 10
points for spending $11,500 per pupil.
   ``Some persons might argue that our information does not provide
a complete picture of a district,'' Harrison wrote. ``Frankly, we
have never heard two educators agree on what data would constitute
a complete picture.
   ``What we have done,'' he said, ``is to enable every American to
fairly evaluate hundreds of school districts ... using a great many
yardsticks that educators themselves, government statisticians, and
scientific researchers consider important and valid.''
   Copies of the book, or information about it, can be obtained by
calling the publisher at 1-800-356-8791.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Lee Mitgang has covered education for the AP
since 1981.
</TEXT>
