<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-31 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOMERVILLE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials here have hired an outside
expert to generate noise in their courtrooms.
   Court administrator Eugene L. Farkas said Wednesday that some of
the courtrooms in the county's new $15 million judicial complex are
so well designed acoustically that jurors and spectators are privy
to even whispered conferences between lawyers and the judge at the
bench.
   ``In the circular courtrooms there is excellent paneling, recess
lighting, acoustical tiles and the sound seems to ring the ceiling
and come down upon you,'' Farkas said.
   Noise Unlimited Inc. of Somerville is working on the problem.
The firm is experimenting with a noise generator that utilizes the
sound system in each courtroom to pump in low-level sounds that
help mask conversations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men like to see women's legs. So what else is
new?
   What's new, according to a poll published Thursday, seems to be
that while 36 percent of men say they favor miniskirts on women,
and 71 percent say they like skirts at the knee or above, follow-up
interviews indicate men generally concede that women have to
consider whether showing too much leg is a wise career choice.
   Greg Parker, of Palm Beach, Fla., said he likes short skirts
because they're ``attractive'' and ``sexy.'' But, the 25-year-old
engineer said, ``if you're in a meeting and everyone's dressed
conservatively, there's less distraction.''
   In The New York Times-CBS telephone poll of 1,654 adults, a
quarter of the women questioned said they had worn a skirt above
their knees in the past year, while 46 percent of the women said
they prefer a length below the knee. The poll was conducted between
March 19 and 22.
   The tepid response of women to the new short styles had already
been made apparent at the cash registers to those in the fashion
trade, prompting designers to show some longer skirts in their fall
collections.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Snoopy pops up in the darndest places,
but when the cartoon beagle was found cavorting with a grizzly bear
and a laboring miner on the state shield, California officials
thought some prankster had gone too far.
   The ``Peanuts'' comic strip canine first surfaced in official
circles on the February issue of the Department of Corrections
newsletter. He appeared to have taken the place of the Roman
goddess Minerva as she stood on guard, the Sierra Nevada range at
her back, a cluster of grapes at her feet.
   ``Frankly, we first thought it might be the inmates'' up to a
prank, said corrections spokesman Mike Van Winkle. ``If I still
didn't know anything about it, I would think it was definitely a
Snoopy,'' he said.
   But, no. It was a simple case of bureaucratic thriftiness,
according to Curt Soderlund, spokesman for the state Department of
General Services. He said a thin line on a printing plate had worn
out, creating the appearance of ``something canine.''
   It cost $50 to fix, he said.
</TEXT>
