<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     03-31 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toshiba Import Ban Gets Approval from Trade Bill Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators agreed Thursday
to attach to their sweeping trade bill tough sanctions against
Toshiba Corp. of Japan and a subsidiary for selling submarine
silencing equipment to the Soviets.
   House members relented and agreed to the measure despite Reagan
administration warnings that a similar provision was too inflexible
and could bring on a presidential veto.
   Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah, urged lawmakers to ignore the warnings,
declaring that he was embarrassed by the Republican
administration's reluctance to discipline Toshiba.
   ``The State Department has been kicked in the shins and instead
of yelling `Ouch,' they have chosen to surrender,'' Garn said.
   The complex measure would ban U.S. government purchases of
Toshiba Corp. goods for three years. It would ban all sales in the
United States of products from its Toshiba Machine Co. subsidiary.
There would be no waivers, but exceptions could be made for
national security.
   The measure calls for two- to five-year import bans to punish
any companies that in the future might send militarily useful
equipment to communist countries in defiance of Cocom, an agreement
among Western nations that is designed to control the flow of such
goods.
   Retroactive sanctions contained in the measure also would apply
to Kongsberg Vapenfabrikk of Norway.
   Like Toshiba, that company allegedly was involved in the sale of
computerized milling equipment that the administration says has
been used to produce submarine propellors that are hard for
detection equipment to hear.
   Cabinet members warned lawmakers earlier this week that
stringent sanctions against Toshiba could mean a veto of the
1,000-page trade bill that lawmakers are drawing up in a
House-Senate conference committee.
   House members had been holding out for allowing the president to
make the decision on whether sanctions should be mandatory. But
after three hours of debate, they relented and accepted a somewhat
softened proposal by Garn.
   The full conference committee in theory could drop the provision
or alter it, although that would be hard to arrange.
   There was considerable reluctance, but no outright dissent, as
Foreign Affairs Committee Chairman Dante Fascell, D-Fla., accepted
the Senate offer on behalf of the House.
   Rep. Stephen L. Neal, D-N.C., repeatedly urged the panel to
trust the judgments of the State and Defense departments as well as
the National Security Council that a Toshiba ban would amount to a
mistake.
   Garn retorted: ``I was elected as U.S. senator to represent the
State of Utah in the U.S. Senate, and not Toshiba and not England
and not the State Department and not (Defense Secretary) Frank
Carlucci.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
