<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 2154EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TaxGap     03-31 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Gap,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tax Gap Expected Incease by One-Third To $114 Billion by 1992</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation and economic growth over the next
four years will boost by one-third _ to almost $114 billion _ the
gap between federal income taxes owed and voluntarily paid, the
Internal Revenue Service said Thursday.
   However, IRS Commissioner Lawrence B. Gibbs cautioned Congress
against counting on that money as potential income to reduce the
federal budget deficit. An undetermined portion of the ``tax gap''
represents taxes that would not be worth the effort to collect even
if enforcement activities were stepped up.
   ``Our estimates of the income-tax gap are measures of total
non-compliance,'' Gibbs told the Senate Budget Committee. ``They
are not intended to be measures of the potential for additional
enforcement yields.''
   Using information collected in 1983, the IRS estimates the tax
gap at $84.9 billion for 1987. That is down from $95 billion in
1986. The agency projects an $87 billion gap next year and $113.7
billion in 1992.
   Gibbs said the estimates for this year and the future are less
than they would have been had not Congress made significant changes
in the tax law in 1986. Those changes included cuts in tax rates,
reduced itemized deductions and higher personal exemptions, which,
the IRS believes, will reduce incentives for cheating.
   That increase in voluntary compliance among individuals will be
offset by inflation and growth of the economy, Gibbs said.
   Although the new estimates still indicate a sizable tax gap, the
commissioner said, they are considerably below what the agency had
forecast in 1983. The 1983 projection was for a gap of $115 billion
for 1987.
   The IRS said individuals accounted for $63.5 bilion of the 1987
gap and corporations were to blame for the remaining $21.4 billion.
While the agency expects the voluntary compliance rate among
individuals will increase slightly over the next few years,
corporate compliance will decline, partly because the 1986 law
shifted a significant part of the tax burden from individuals to
corporations.
   Individuals' underreporting of income was to blame for $48.3
billion of the tax gap in 1987; overstated deductions, $6 billion;
overstated credits, $900 million; math errors, $1 billion; and the
failure of many people to even file a required return, $7.2 billion.
   Jerome Kurtz, who headed the IRS during the Carter
administration, cautioned against reading too much into the tax-gap
figures, noting they are estimates based on small samples. He and
Donald C. Alexander, who was IRS commissioner during the Nixon
administration, agreed on a major point: The agency must be given
enough money to provide a top level of service to taxpayers.
   Recalling several years of what he said were underfunding of the
IRS, Kurtz said, ``If you have to write a letter to the IRS to
straighten out an account, you're going to learn the meaning of
frustration.'' In hiring and retaining employees, he said, ``the
IRS is not competitive with private industry.''
   Alexander added: ``How can someone whose salary is so low as to
be eligible for food stamps be expected to answer all the complex
questions thrown at taxpayer assistance (employees) during the
current (return) filing period?''
   The telephone ``assistors'' who field taxpayers' telephoned
questions are paid as little as $13,000 a year _ considerable less
than many garbage collectors, Alexander said.
   Jennie S. Stathis, an associate director of the General
Accounting Office, which oversees other federal agencies for
Congress, said the IRS already is weighing several GAO
recommendations for reducing the tax gap.
   These include a capacity for matching business information
documents against business returns just as computers already match
individual wage and income statements against returns; stepping up
efforts to improve the reporting of taxable tips; and trying to
find a bigger share of illegal income to tax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
