<DOCNO> AP880331-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 2220EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Medicare-TPA     03-31 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medicare-TPA,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medicare Won't Raise Payments for New Anti-Clotting Drug TPA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials said Thursday they have
decided against increasing Medicare payments to hospitals for
treating heart attack victims with an expensive new anti-clotting
drug called TPA.
   ``There is a question as to whether the circumstances involving
TPA are so unique as to justify some special accommodation,''
Medicare chief William L. Roper said in a letter to the American
Hospital Association. ``We have concluded that they are not.''
   The hospitals have been pressing the Health Care Financing
Administration to take into account the high cost of TPA _ which
runs about $2,000 a dose _ in paying for the treatment of heart
attack victims.
   Medicare pays hospitals a flat, predetermined amount for
treatment of various illnesses rather than reimbursing hospitals
for itemized expenses _ such as particular drugs or procedures _
used on a particular patient.
   Those fees are adjusted annually to take into account rising
costs and other factors and are predicated on the assumption that,
while a hospital may lose money on one patient, it is just as
likely to reap an excess profit on another patient with the same
diagnosis.
   TPA costs about 10 times as much as other clot-dissolving drugs,
such as streptokinase, which have been available longer and have
been used on many more patients.
   Nonetheless, an HCFA fact sheet issued in connection with the
decision raises the possibility that use of TPA ``may even result
in cost savings'' by reducing the length of time a heart attack
patient would need to be hospitalized.
   ``It is too early to know what the exact outcome will be,'' the
fact sheet said.
   It noted that if TPA use does prove to increase overall costs
for treating heart attack patients, such a determination would be
taken into account automatically in the annual hospital payment
adjustments.
   Although TPA, short for tissue plasminogen activator, has been
judged safe and effective by the Food and Drug Administration for
quickly dissolving blood clots in heart attack patients, the
evidence is less clear on whether it is significantly more
effective than streptokinase in saving lives.
   Trials making a direct comparison between the two drugs are
about to begin in England, but results will not be known for a
couple of years.
   Study results released at the annual meeting of the American
College of Cardiology this week showed TPA reduced the number of
heart attack deaths by more than 50 percent, when compared to a
placebo, in a study of 700 patients. A much larger trial, involving
about 17,000 patients, showed a combination of streptokinase and
aspirin reduced mortality by nearly 60 percent.
   The HCFA fact sheet also said some of the warnings carried on
TPA labeling ``include factors likely to be more prevalent in the
Medicare population than in the general population.''
   ``For example, almost 50 percent of Medicare beneficiaries
admitted for (heart attacks) in fiscal year 1986 were 75 years or
older, an age cohort for which physicians are cautioned to weigh
the expected benefits of TPA against the risks,'' it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
