<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MIARepatriation     03-31 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MIA Repatriation,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam To Send Back 27 Remains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vietnamese government is prepared to make
the single largest repatriation of American remains since the end
of the Vietnam War, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   ``We are announcing that Vietnam will repatriate 27 remains to
U.S. government representatives on April 6, 1988 in Hanoi,'' said
Dan Howard, the Defense Department's chief spokesman.
   Once transferred in Hanoi, the remains will be flown to the
Army's Central Identification Laboratory in Honolulu, Hawaii, for
identification, Howard added.
   ``This will be the largest number of remains repatriated at one
time,'' the spokesman said. ``Previously, the largest turnover of
remains was 26 on Aug. 14, 1985.''
   There are currently 2,404 Americans still listed as missing in
Indochina as a result of the Vietnam War, of whom 1,767 are listed
as missing in either North or South Vietnam. Up to now, the remains
of 152 Americans have been repatriated to the United States and
subsequently identified by the laboratory.
   On March 2, the Vietnamese turned over 17 remains to U.S.
officials. Those remains have yet to be identified, however.
   The upcoming transfer would be the fourth since retired Army
Gen. John Vessey traveled to Hanoi last August as a special
presidential emissary, hoping to step up the process of accounting
for missing Americans.
   ``We've continued to press the Vietnamese and we are getting
some results,'' Howard said Thursday.
   Asked if the Pentagon could explain the sudden increase in
repatriations, Howard replied: ``It's really not for us to do that.
The Vietnamese are the ones who should be explaining to the
American people and to the world what happened to the rest of the
remains and where they are.''
   Lt. Col. Keith Schneider, another Pentagon spokesman, said the
Vietnamese government informed U.S. officials during technical
meetings in mid-March they were investigating 29 new reports of
remains being found or information regarding servicemen uncovered.
   Then earlier this week, the Vietnamese disclosed they did have
27 remains to repatriate, Schneider added.
   ``The U.S. government appreciates the initiative taken by
Vietnam to repatriate these remains and hopes it represents just
one of many continued steps to resolve this long-standing
humanitarian issue,'' the Pentagon said in a statement.
</TEXT>
