<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BloodPressureDeaths     03-31 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blood Pressure Deaths,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Cuts High Blood Pressure Related Deaths Almost In Half</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 5:30 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High blood pressure patients given the drug
metoprolol had a 48 percent lower death rate than patients given
more commonly used drugs, researchers said Thursday.
   Metoprolol (pronounced muh-TAH-pro-lawl) is one of the heart
drugs known as beta blockers. The researchers said this is the
first study to show that beta blockers can prevent more deaths in
people with hypertension than can the widely used diuretics called
thiazides.
   The American Heart Association estimates that 59 million
Americans suffer from high blood pressure, or hypertension.
   ``We now have scientific proof that if we start with a beta
blocker ... we will have a substantial reduction in deaths,'' said
the study's principal author, Dr. John Wikstrand of Gothenburg
University's Sahlgrenska University Hospital in Sweden.
   Customary practice in the United States had been to prescribe
diuretics first for high blood pressure and to try beta blockers
later if the diuretics weren't working, said Dr. Stevo Julius of
the University of Michigan Medical Center in Ann Arbor.
   New recommendations by a committee of the National Heart, Lung
and Blood Institute say that diuretics, beta blockers, or two newer
classes of anti-hypertension drugs can serve as the first-line
treatment for high blood pressure, said Julius, an advisor to that
committee.
   Julius, who was not part of the study, joined Wikstrand at a
press conference at New York's Plaza Hotel to discuss the study's
findings. The press conference was sponsored by metoprolol's
developer, the Astra pharmaceutical company of Sweden, and by
Ciba-Geigy Pharmaceuticals, which holds the license to market the
drug in the United States.
   The results of the study will appear Friday in the Journal of
the American Medical Association.
   Two earlier studies that compared beta blockers and diuretics
failed to find any significant difference in the death rate, said
Dr. Curt Furberg of the Bowman Gray School of Medicine in
Winston-Salem, N.C.
   Furberg, who recently wrote a medical journal article reviewing
anti-hypertension drugs, called the new study interesting. But, he
said in a telephone interview, ``I'm not sure how it's going to be
accepted. It's possible we need to test it in a separate study.''
   Wikstrand and colleagues at 66 centers in Europe and Canada
monitored 3,234 men given either metoprolol or diuretics for a
median period of 4.2 years. The researchers found a 48 percent
lower death rate among men given metoprolol than those given
diuretics.
   The drop was mostly due to a reduction in deaths from stroke and
coronary heart disease, two complications of high blood pressure,
the researchers said. There was no significant effect on other
causes of death, suggesting that the drugs are safe, they said.
   The thiazides make up one class of diuretics, which relieve high
blood pressure by stimulating the body to expel fluid, thus
lowering the total volume of blood in the bloodstream.
   Beta blockers block the stimulating action of adrenaline,
reducing the rate and the force at which the heart pumps blood
through the body _ and reducing high blood pressure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
