<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     03-31 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Says No Surprise If Afghan Talks Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said in an
interview released Thursday that he would not be surprised if
Afghanistan peace talks fail, and he accused the United States and
Pakistan of blocking their success.
   The ruling Politburo discussed what action to take in the Geneva
talks in light of a U.S. ``departure'' from willingness to
participate in a political settlement in Afghanistan, the Tass news
agency said.
   Tass also carried an interview Shevardnadze gave to the
Bulgarian newspaper Rabotnichesko Delo earlier this week, when the
Soviet official was in Bulgaria for a Warsaw Pact meeting.
   ``Not everything depends solely on us and the Afghan
government,'' Shevardnadze said. ``This is why one cannot but take
into account the possibility that the talks may not lead to the
accords expected of them.
   ``If this happens, we shall not see this outcome as
unexpected,'' Shevardnadze said.
   Shevardnadze said that if the U.N.-mediated talks fail, the
Soviet Union will withdraw its 115,000 soldiers from Afghanistan
``in a way convenient for the government of Afghanistan and
ourselves.''
   He didn't indicate whether the Soviet Union would stick to the
nine-month withdrawal timetable already agreed to in Geneva.
   Shevardnadze accused the United States and Pakistan, which
represents the guerrillas in the talks, of putting up last-minute
barriers with demands that Soviet aid to the Afghan government
cease at the same time as U.S. aid to the insurgents.
   The demand is intended to give the guerrillas legitimacy ``as
something more than a group engaging in armed struggle against a
lawful government,'' he said.
   Tass said the Politburo, holding a regular weekly meeting
Thursday, reviewed Shevardnadze's discussions March 21-23 in
Washington with Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   ``Note was taken of the actual departure by the American side
... from its earlier stated readiness to take part in a political
settlement of the situation around Afghanistan on the basis of the
Geneva accords. Variants of our further steps in this question were
studied with due consideration for this,'' Tass said.
   The news agency did not say how the United States had
backtracked or what steps the Politburo was considering.
   Talks aimed at ending the 10-year-old war in Afghanistan
recessed for the Easter holidays. Negotiations were scheduled to
resume Monday, but informal contacts were expected over the weekend.
   Pakistan's acting foreign minister, Zain Noorani, said he was
ready to sign an agreement anytime and hoped for progress soon on
the issue of aid to the warring sides.
   He rejected Shevardnadze's comments that an agreement could be
signed even if the United States did not participate.
   The entire deal then would have to be renegotiated, the
Pakistani diplomat said.
   The New York Times, in its Thursday edition, quoted unidentified
U.S. officials as saying Washington was considering an arrangement
under which Pakistan would sign the accord, but the United States
and Soviet Union would have a separate understanding on aid to the
guerrillas.
</TEXT>
