<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--Autopsies     03-31 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Autopsies,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frequency Of Autopsy Declining In U.S., CDC Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The frequency of autopsies is declining in the
United States, possibly making it harder for researchers to
determine causes of death, the national Centers for Disease Control
said.
   In 1985, autopsies were conducted in 14 percent of deaths in the
United States, down from 17 percent in 1980, the CDC reported
Thursday, citing data from the National Center for Health
Statistics.
   The decline ``may have adversely affected the accuracy of
determining the underlying cause of death,'' researchers with the
Atlanta-based CDC said in their weekly report.
   During the five-year period, the frequency of autopsies
performed varied widely among causes of death, from 12 percent of
natural deaths to 97 percent of homicides.
   Autopsies in natural deaths dropped from 13 percent in 1980 to
10 percent in 1985, the CDC said. On the other hand, autopsies
following unintentional injuries and poisonings rose from 46
percent to 51 percent, and autopsies in suicides rose from 48
percent to 52 percent.
   In 1985, 34 percent of autopsies performed in the United States
involved deaths from other than natural causes, compared to 30
percent in 1980, the CDC said.
</TEXT>
