<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BaldrigeAward     03-31 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baldrige Award,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Award Aimed at Promoting Quality in American Products</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of a new national award aimed at
promoting the quality of American products said Thursday they have
raised $2.2 million to finance the competition and will announce
the first winners in November.
   The Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award was created by
Congress in August and named after the late commerce secretary, who
was killed last year in a horse riding accident.
   Officials said Thursday that a maximum of six awards will be
given annually _ two each for large manufacturing companies, large
service companies and smaller companies engaged in either
manufacturing or service.
   ``Quality is a key weapon in America's arsenal in the
international battle for markets,'' Commerce Secretary C. William
Verity said in making the announcement. ``This award, which will be
America's Nobel Prize for quality, should help recognize the firms
that are making a difference when it comes to quality.''
   The competition will be supervised by the Commerce Department's
National Bureau of Standards in conjunction with a private
foundation created by the legislation to raise money for the
contest each year.
   Directors of the new foundation are: Sanford N. McDonnell,
chairman emeritus of the McDonnell Douglas Corp.; John J. Hudiburg,
head of Florida Power & Light Co.; John Young, chairman of
Hewlett-Packard; and Robert C. Baldrige, brother of the late
commerce secretary.
   They said $2.2 million of a total goal of $9.9 million already
had been raised from American businesses.
   Hudiburg said the new award would indicate to the world that
``we're willing to invest whatever it takes to insure that
America's commitment to excellence is recognized both at home and
abroad.''
   Officials said the winning companies would be picked on the
baisis of such criteria as quality assurance programs, with the
largest weight in the judging going to customer satisfaction.
   After a review of written applications, the contest judges will
make on-site inspections to pick the winners. The prize will carry
no monetary award but winners will be allowed to mention the award
in advertising.
   The U.S. prize was modeled after the Deming prize, which Japan
has been awarding since 1951 to recognize quality achievements by
Japanese companies.
   The Japanese prize was named to honor W. Edwards Deming, an
American quality control export revered in Japan for his work with
Japanese companies after World War II.
   Companies interested in finding out more about the contest can
write: Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award, National Bureau of
Standards, Gaithersburg, Md., 20899. Officials said an application
fee of $1,500 is being charged to cover expenses, with a deadline
of May 20 for applications.
</TEXT>
