<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-ChinaPharmaceutical     03-31 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-China Pharmaceutical,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Company Signs Drug Pact With China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. pharmaceuticals company signed an
agreement with the Chinese government Thursday that officials say
could lead to increased American drug sales in China and
development of Chinese drugs for world markets.
   Officials of G. D. Searle & Co. and representatives of the State
Pharmaceutical Administration of China said it was too early to
tell what specific drugs might be involved in the research
agreement. But both sides said it could involve a range of
products, including possible future AIDS treatments developed in
China.
   ``This is a good beginning between the United States and
China,'' said Liu Yonggang, a vice president of the Chinese
administration who signed the Sino-Searle Research and Development
Trust at the Chinese Embassy. Speaking through a translator, Liu
said it was the first such agreement with an American company.
   The agreement says Searle will have the right to license
exclusively any products that result from research and development
under the trust.
   Richard U. DeSchutter, president of Searle's international
operations, said the company already sells seven products in China,
although sales have been less than $100,000 annually. He said the
agreement includes $500,000 for drug development, with provisions
for increased funding later.
   DeSchutter said the potential Chinese market for foreign drugs
could be between $3 billion and $5 billion annually. Imports of
drugs and medical devices last year reached about $300 million,
Chinese officials said. They had no figures for the U.S. share of
the market.
   Liu acknowledged that China, where herbal medicine makes up a
large share of the market, still lags behind other countries in
product quality and research.
   He said more than 1,800 factories manufacture drugs or medical
devices in China _ including 600 facilities producing 4,000 kinds
of herbal medicines. Liu said China doubled its production of
pharmaceuticals between 1979 and 1987 and plans to put more
emphasis on exports.
   Dr. Shen Jiaxiang, deputy director of the Chinese pharmaceutical
agency, said there are some ``interesting findings'' related to
AIDS in China, although the country has had only about a half dozen
cases of the fatal disease, all involving tourists.
   Shen, talking to reporters after the signing ceremonies, said
researchers have identified several Chinese traditional remedies
that enhance the human immune system. AIDS, or acquiried immune
deficiency syndrome, breaks down the body's resistance to other
diseases. More than 31,000 Americans have died of AIDS.
   ``We may provide some help, but we don't have a cure,'' Shen
said.
   He said AIDS research is not specifically mentioned in the
agreement with Searle, but it might be one area to discuss.
   DeSchutter said the company has been involved in AIDS research
and the pact could lead to some cooperation in that area with the
Chinese.
   ``We have not had a chance to talk that out, but it's possible
our approaches could be synergistic,'' he said after the news
conference.
   Searle, with headquarters in Skokie, Ill., develops,
manufactures and markets prescription pharmaceuticals worldwide. It
is a wholly owned subsidiary of Monsanto Co.
</TEXT>
