<HEAD>Teen-ager Accused of Killing Parents on Their Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALISPELL, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager was accused Thursday in the
slayings of his parents, who were shot on their wedding anniversary
with a high-powered rifle, authorities said.
   Keith Wood, 16, of Kalispell was charged with being a delinquent
youth by reason of committing deliberate homicide. Authorities said
he was taken into custody at school Wednesday and admitted to the
killings. He was being held in the Flathead County Juvenile
Detention Center.
   County Attorney Ted Lympus said he probably try to have the
teen-ager tried as an adult.
   Nancy Wood, 37, and Jimmie Wood, 38, were shot Tuesday night at
their home in a remote area 17 miles northwest of Kalispell,
authorities said.
   Wood's body was discovered Wednesday morning by a co-worker who
had gone to the house to investigate after Wood did not show up for
work. The co-worker notified authorities.
   Authorities say the boy allegedly shot his mother in the head
with a 30.-06 rifle, stuffed her body in a sleeping bag and dragged
it to a bedroom, where he waited for Wood.
   Wood arrived home about an hour later with a bouquet of yellow
roses for his wife on their wedding anniversary, and was shot in
the back of the head at close range, authorities said.
   Authorities said they knew of no motive.
   The Woods also have an 18-year-old son who lives in Kalispell
and was not at their home at the time of the shooting, authorities
said. Lympus said he did not know what anniversary the couple was
celebrating.
