<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Strom Thurmond met today with
embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese III to convey the ``deep
concern'' expressed by some members of Congress in the wake of
resignations by two top Justice Department officials.
   The South Carolina senator, the ranking Republican on the Senate
Judiciary Committee, refused to comment further on the nature of
the discussions with Meese, who is under investigation by an
independent counsel.
   In a statement issued by his office, Thurmond said, ``a numn Capitol
Hill have expressed deep concern about the
problems at the Justice Department.
   ``I went today to talk to the attorney general to convey these
concerns to him.''
   The meeting with Thurmond was the reason Meese was late fber
of people oor a
scheduled 12:30 p.m. EST news conference at FBI headquarters, where
he refused to answer reporters' questions on the resignation of two
of his top aides. The resignations came amid increasing skepticism
on Capitol Hill over whether Meese can continue to run the Justice
Department.
   At the news conference, called to announce a major drug bust,
Meese briskly turned aside at least half a dozen questions relating
to the possibility that he might quit in the wake ofeld's reported remarks
require a presidential
inquiry and decision.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, asked about Specter's
statement, said only, ``Thank you for his general views.''
Fitzwater said he had ``no reaction'' to the remarks attributed to
Weld.
   The presidential spokesman said Meese was at the White House
today for a ``security meeting'' on an undisclosed subject.
   ``The president was involved in the meeting,'' he said, but
``there were no private discussions between the two either before
or after the meeting and none are planned.''
   Meese is the target of a broadening criminal investigation.
Department sources have said the top officials quit because they
felt Meese's legal problems were ``poisoning'' the Justice
Department.
   On Wednesday, Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., said flatly that Meese
should resign. Senate Democratic Leader Robert Byrd also called for
his resignation, calling him ``the crown jewel of the sleaze factor
in Reagan administration history.''
   Specter, interviewed on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show, referred to a
report in today's Washington Post that quoted sources familiar with
Tuesday's meeting of Meese, Weld and Deputy Attorney General Arnold
Burns, at which Weld and Burns turned in their resignations.
   The Post said Weld told Meese the attorney general's situation
presented a close call but that if it were up to Weld he would
present it to the grand jury for an indictment.
   The New York Times, in a similar report, quoted sources as
saying Weld had previously commented that ``he would have to
seriously consider indicting Meese.'' The newspaper said that Weld,
asked about that comment, would not respond on the record.
   Specter, asked about the quotes attributed to Weld, said, ``Up
until this moment, or perhaps yesterday, you had a situation where
the independent counsel was looking ... but I think now is a
different matter. The president has to talk to Mr. Weld, has to
examine the facts and then has to make a presidential decision.''
   Specter earlier questioned ``whether the U.S. Department of
Justice can function'' with Meese in charge.
   ``You finally reach a place where there is a cloud of suspicion,
a sufficient cloud of suspicion, that I think you owe it to the
president to remove yourself,'' Packwood said.
   Weld told the Times that he had become concerned about the
collective ``damage'' being done to the Justice Department by
having a man under investigation as its leader.
   The Times quoted a source as saying Weld told his aides in
announcing his resignation that, to him, ``it was a question of
moral authority and the tarnishing of the department.''
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said today that Reagan's
``duty'' is ``to bring about the resignation of Mr. Meese.''
   ``The president owes a duty to the country that may be much
higher than that which he owes to his personal friend,'' Metzenbaum
said at the start of a Senate Judiciary subcommittee hearing on
antitrust matters.
   The question, said Metzenbaum, is, ``if Mr. Meese does not
shortly resign whether the public will be losing confidence in
government as a whole.''
   The Boston Herald, meanwhile, quoted Weld as saying in an
interview that, when he and Burns told Meese they were resigning,
the attorney general ``thought we were joking. I told him it was
so. He seemed a little taken jaback.''
   For his part, Meese said ``there's no reason to resign'' and
Reagan reiterated his support for his old friend, saying ``he's
been a friend for over 20 years. I have every confidence in him.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater was asked Wednesday why
Meese remained on the job when White House chief of staff Howard
Baker, Vice President George Bush and first lady Nancy Reagan
wanted him out.
   ``I don't think any of that is true,'' Fitzwater replied.
   Mrs. Reagan's press secretary, Elaine Crispen, said today that
reports that the first lady was campaigning for Meese's removal
were ``absolutely not true.''
   ``She hasn't talked to anyone and no one has talked to her about
the issue,'' Mrs. Crispen said by telephone from Los Angeles, where
Mrs. Reagan is visiting before joining the president at their
California ranch Friday for an easter vacation.
   Quitting with Burns, the No. 2 official in the department, and
Weld, were four of their aides.
   Meese predicted on Wednesday that Solicitor General Charles
Fried, who had said he was reconsidering his future with the
department, would not follow suit.
   Meese, who met with Fried on Wednesday, said ``I have no doubt
that Mr. Fried will remain a strong member of the management team.''
   ``Business is operating as usual at the Justice Department,''
Meese declared. He said replacements were being sought for Burns
and Weld and that ``everything is going along well.''
