<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Meese 1stLd-Writethru a0694 03-31 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Particularly Reluctant To Lose Meese, Observers Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: When Donovan, to show Donovan was
acquitted of charges</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Meese Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidents can be reluctant to fire their
closest aides, and President Reagan, who has shown great loyalty to
top advisers in the past, is unlikely to oust his longtime friend,
Attorney General Edwin Meese III, White House observers say.
   ``He's been a friend for over 20 years,'' Reagan told reporters
Wednesday in response to questions about whether he would remove
the attorney general, who faces mounting legal problems. ``I have
every confidence in him.''
   His statement recalled the time in the summer of 1984 when the
president, arriving in Dallas for the Republican National
Convention, was quizzed about whether he would oust Labor Secretary
Raymond Donovan, who faced a federal indictment.
   Reagan declared that he wouldn't give in to a ``lynch mob
atmosphere.''
   When Donovan finally was indicted, he saved Reagan the decision
by resigning immediately. Donovan later was found innocent in New
York court of larceny and fraud charges involving a construction
company he co-owned.
   Reagan so dislikes firing top aides that an embittered Secretary
of State Alexander M. Haig Jr. had to try at least twice to quit
before the president finally accepted his resignation in June 1982.
   Reagan didn't fire Interior Secretary James Watt after he made
offensive remarks about blacks, women, Jews and the handicapped in
1983. Watt offered to step aside.
   ``After watching Ronald Reagan and reading about him all these
years, I've come to the conclusion that it is a matter of
leadership style that dictates that he not fire people,'' said
Robert A. Bonatati, who was Reagan's labor adviser early in the
administration.
   ``He never gets on the side of firing people and he always
defends people who are under attack.''
   Reagan has said steadfastly that he thinks public officials
ought to be presumed innocent until found guilty in court. He's
even gone further than that with two major figures in the
Iran-Contra affair, saying he believes former national security
aides Oliver L. North and John M. Poindexter are innocent of
charges they conspired to defraud the government.
   Reagan's close association with Meese goes back to his days as
governor of California from 1967-75, when Meese was a valued
counselor. During his first months in the presidency in 1981,
writes Reagan biographer Lou Cannon, ``Reagan valued Ed Meese's
advice above all others, believing that Meese would see to it that
conflicting points of view were presented to him without
coloration.''
   In quintessential Reagan style, the president threw his arm
around Meese when reporters tried to question him about the
attorney general early last fall, just after the two had appeared
in the White House press room to announce Anthony M. Kennedy's
selection for a Supreme Court vacancy.
   But Reagan is not the only president who has shown great loyalty
to his aides. A former high-ranking official in the Carter
administration, describing the difficulty that Jimmy Carter had in
ousting budget director Bert Lance, said ``it's always difficult
for presidents to let go of people close to them, and that was true
of Lance, and it's certainly true of Meese.''
   ``These are the toughest issues for presidents to face,'' said
the source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Presidents do sometimes swing the ax, however. President
Eisenhower ousted top aide Sherman Adams and President Johnson got
rid of close associate Walter Jenkins. Gerald Ford eased out
Agriculture Secretary Earl Butz.
   ``It's a major problem for all presidents,'' said the University
of Virginia's Larry Sabato. ``But few presidents have been as
reluctant and as reticent as this president to ditch people who
become political liabilities. Eisenhower thought it was important
to be cleaner than a hound's tooth.''
   Bonatati noted he lost his job at the White House despite
Reagan's aversion to firing.
   He said that when Faith Ryan Whittlesey arrived in early March
1983 to succeed Elizabeth Dole as director of the White House
Office of Public Liaison, Whittlesey fired him and several other
presidential advisers with short notice.
   ``She pretty much cleaned house,'' Bonatati said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
