<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Pulitzers-Journalism 3rdLd-Writethru a0765 03-31 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pulitzers-Journalism, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0765,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Charlotte Observer, Miami Herald, Wall Street Journal Win 2
Pulitzers Each</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 11, ``The Philadelphia xxx, and graf 13, ``Jacqui
Banaszynski xxxx, to restore identification as Knight-Ridder papers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Charlotte Observer, the Miami Herald and the
Wall Street Journal each won two 1988 Pulitzer Prizes on Thursday,
with the Observer receiving the gold medal for public service for
its reports on Jim and Tammy Bakker's PTL television ministry.
   The Observer and the Herald led Knight-Ridder newspapers to a
total of six Pulitzers.
   The Pulitzer Prize board cited the Observer for revealing misuse
of funds by the ministry ``through persistent coverage conducted in
the face of a massive campaign by PTL to discredit the newspaper.''
   The Observer's Doug Marlette also won a Pulitzer for his
editorial cartooning in Charlotte and at the Atlanta Constitution.
   The Herald's Dave Barry won the commentary Pulitzer for what the
board called ``his consistently effective use of humor as the
device for presenting fresh insights into serious concerns.'' His
colleague Michel duCille won the feature photography award for
photographs of a housing project plagued by a cocaine epidemic.
   Daniel Hertzberg and James B. Stewart of the Journal won the
award for explanatory journalism for their stories about an
investment banker charged with insider trading and the day after
the Oct. 19 stock market crash.
   The Journal also won a Pulitzer in specialized reporting for
Walt Bogdanich's series of reports on faulty testing by American
medical laboratories.
   Three Chicago Tribune reporters _ Dean Baquet, William Gaines
and Ann Marie Lipinski _ won the investigative reporting prize for
what the board termed ``detailed reporting on the self-interest and
waste that plague Chicago's City Council.''
   ``We're thrilled,'' said Ellen Soeteber, the Tribune's assistant
managing editor for metropolitan news. ``I think the team of
reporters deserved this so much. It was their concept. It was their
idea, and they brought it off beautifully. I'm so glad some of the
leaders in our profession recognized it.''
   Two Pulitzers were given for general news reporting. One went to
the staff of the Alabama Journal of Montgomery for an investigation
of the state's unusually high infant mortality rate, which prompted
remedial legislation. The second was awarded to the staff of the
Lawrence (Mass.) Eagle-Tribune for an investigation that revealed
flaws in the Massachusetts prison furlough system and led to
reforms.
   Tim Weiner of The Philadelphia Inquirer, another Knight-Ridder
newspaper, won the national reporting prize for his series on a
secret Pentagon budget used to sponsor defense research and an arms
buildup.
   The international reporting Pulitzer was won by Thomas L.
Friedman of The New York Times for what the board called ``balanced
and informed coverage'' of Israel. It was Friedman's second
Pulitzer for international reporting; his first was in 1983 for his
reporting from Lebanon.
   Jacqui Banaszynski of the St. Paul (Minn.) Pioneer Press
Dispatch, also a Knight-Ridder newspaper, won the Pulitzer for
feature writing for her series about the life and death of an AIDS
victim in a rural community.
   Tom Shales of the Washington Post won the criticism award for
his writing on television, and Jane Healy of The Orlando Sentinel
won the editorial writing prize for editorials that protested
overdevelopment of Florida's Orange County.
   The Pulitzer for spot news photography was awarded to Scott Shaw
of the Odessa (Texas) American for his pictures of little Jessica
McClure being rescued from a well.
   Except for the award for public service, which brings with it a
gold medal, Pulitzers carry a cash prize of $3,000. The winners are
selected by the Pulitzer Prize board and announced by the president
of Columbia University, which administers the competition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
