<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Shanker-Schools     03-31 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shanker-Schools,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Union Chief Calls for Experimental Schools Within Present
System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the American Federation of
Teachers said Thursday that small groups of teachers should be
given the autonomy and funds to create experimental schools within
regular public schools.
   AFT President Albert Shanker said the current public school
system is not working for as many as 80 percent of the students and
``we've got to do something totally different.''
   Shanker suggested that groups of six to 12 teachers be allowed
to organize their own schools, provided they can win the approval
of principals, fellow teachers, parents and education authorities.
   ``It is time once again to take a major step forward in trying
to improve the schools of our nation,'' said Shanker, whose
665,000-member union represents teachers in some of the nation's
largest cities, including New York and Chicago.
   He said state-mandated reforms and more stringent standards
imposed over the past five years have improved schools for students
at the top, ``but unfortunately (reform) is bypassing about 80
percent of kids.''
   ``We now need to seek ways that will enable any group of
teachers ... and parents of children who want to do something
different to opt for a different type of school,'' he said in a
National Press Club address.
   The autonomous schools ``ought to get their per capita share of
what the school spends,'' he said. Public schools spend roughly
$4,000 per pupil on average.
   Shanker said, ``There would have to be a guarantee that such a
school would be left alone for five or 10 years provided that
parents wanted to keep sending their kids there.'' They would be
strictly voluntary for teachers and students.
   ``If there's anarchy, the customers will be gone in no time at
all,'' he said. ``This is not pie in the sky.''
   He said such a system would give teachers an alternative to
trying to ``shove reform down the throats'' of unwilling colleagues.
   Shanker said only a handful of districts now are trying to
restructure public schools. He claimed his idea could open the door
for thousands of experimental schools.
   Shanker said he would want the teachers to include in their
proposals ways for teachers to govern themselves, to give students
alternatives to sitting in class for six hours listening to
lectures and to spur cooperative learning. The students also should
``reflect the composition of the entire school'' and not just be
drawn from the top or bottom, he said.
   Last week, Mary Hatwood Futrell, president of the National
Education Association, proposed that state leaders and teacher
unions designate at least one experimental school district in each
of the 50 states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 2339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WhiteHouseRepaint     03-31 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-White House Repaint,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Getting Repainted In Spruce-Up For 1992 Bicentennial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paint that has built up on White House walls
since 1797 is being removed as part of a project designed to spruce
up the presidential residence for its bicentennial in 1992.
   The National Park Service said the job will involve removing
some 30 coats of paint and repairing some of the carved stonework
on the sandstone walls. Work began this week.
   The work will be done on the exterior north walls and part of
the south walls and will be the first time in nearly two centuries
that these walls have been exposed.
   The walls will be kept bare until the spring of 1989 to allow
the porous sandstone to dry so the paint will adhere to the walls
better. Repainting is scheduled for next spring.
   The paint is being removed by brushing chemicals on the walls
and then flushing them with a stream of water.
   The work is being done by Ramco Technologies of Hartford, Conn.,
under a $384,200 contract.
   Vincent Palumbo, master carver for the National Cathedral, will
oversee repair of the stone carvings.
   The project is part of a long-range exterior restoration program
to repair and replace deteriorated stonework, remove old paint,
repoint and seal masonry joints and then repaint. The east wall was
restored in 1980 and the north portico in 1984.
   The entire program is to be completed for the bicentennial of
the laying of the cornerstone of the ``President's House'' in 1792.
The White House has been the home and office of every president
since John Adams.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1625EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NewYorkPrimary     03-31 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New York Primary,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York: Next Big Battleground For Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats looking ahead to New York's April
19 presidential primary are focusing on the mystery of a Cuomo
endorsement and the status of Jesse Jackson's ticklish relationship
with the state's influential Jewish community.
   The questions are obvious:
   Will Gov. Mario Cuomo endorse his fellow Northeast governor,
Michael Dukakis? Or will he stay on the sideline, fueling
speculation that he wants the nomination for himself?
   Can Jackson overcome the sour taste lingering from his 1984
campaign when he infuriated New York Jews by privately referring to
New York City as ``Hymietown?''
   ``Jesse got 26 or 27 percent (of the vote) in '84 after the
`Hymietown' crack and with a Fritz Mondale who had a very strong
call on the black constituency,'' said Cuomo. ``He'll do at least
that this year and probably substantially better. If he does 10
points better, he'll be at 37 (percent). You have four candidates
in the race, that's a big number.''
   Cuomo, perhaps the most prominent Democratic non-candidate, has
said his endorsement means little, but even his chief political
adviser, son Andrew, doesn't buy that.
   ``In New York, it has a particular importance,'' said the
younger Cuomo. ``It helps the candidate among those people who
haven't made up their minds yet or who are soft in their support.''
   The governor has said that within the next week or so he will
either endorse someone or announce that he's sitting it out.
   In 1984, Cuomo got behind Walter Mondale early, and with the
governor's powerful political machine in charge, Mondale scored an
important victory to blunt Gary Hart's insurgent campaign.
   At times, the New York governor has appeared to lean toward
Dukakis, but lately he has been saying nice things about Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. and has been proclaiming that Jackson could
win in November at the head of the ticket or would be good as the
vice presidential candidate.
   And Cuomo has said Jackson could well win the New York primary,
an outcome that would seriously damage Dukakis, Jackson's chief
rival for front-runner status, and perhaps increase the likelihood
of a deadlocked national convention.
   Polls have thus far have shown Dukakis in the lead and Jackson
doing only slightly better than the 26 percent he won in 1984.
   Also on the New York ballot will be Democrat Paul Simon and an
uncommitted slate of delegates sponsored by a group of New York's
elected county clerks who would like to see Cuomo in the race. They
say the uncommitted delegates could be valuable to Cuomo if there's
any move to draft him at the party's national convention in Atlanta.
   While Cuomo has said he doesn't want a draft, he has refused to
rule out accepting one. New York City Mayor Edward Koch, one of the
state's most powerful Democrats, has said he's ready to lead a
draft-Cuomo move at the Atlanta convention.
   Numbers make New York's Democratic primary important. As the
second largest state in the nation, New York's 275-member
delegation will be second in size only to California's with 336
delegates. The New York primary results will determine the
allocation of 255 of the delegates.
   For Gore, New York could mark a new beginning or the end of the
road.
   ``I have to have a result in the New York primary that convinces
you that this campaign has gained a significant momentum,'' Gore
told a group of prominent New Yorkers early this week.
   In an attempt to carry that off, Gore has hired New York
political consultant David Garth, agreed to pump more than $1
million into New York and adopted a new campaign strategy of
attacking Jackson.
   In a speech to Jewish leaders, Gore contrasted his support of
Israel with Jackson's recognition of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   In New York's Democratic primaries, Jews traditionally represent
about 25 percent of the electorate with blacks at about the same
level. While Jackson is expected to capture the lion's share of the
black vote, anything more than a single-digit showing for him among
Jewish voters would be considered something of a miracle.
   Nonetheless, a recent poll by the Marist College Institute for
Public Opinion found that among Jewish Democrats surveyed,
Jackson's favorable rating has jumped to 36 percent from 17 percent
in January. But less than 4 percent of those Jewish Democrats
surveyed in the most recent poll said they would vote for Jackson.
   A Gallup poll, conducted at the end of last week, had Dukakis
leading at 44 percent to 28 percent for Jackson. Gore was at 3
percent and Simon at 2 percent.
</TEXT>
