<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--MexicanMangoes     03-31 0122</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Mexican Mangoes,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mangoes From Mexico OK If Bathed In Hot Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold shower won't do it, but a hot bath will
be just fine for mangoes imported from Mexico, the Agriculture
Department said Thursday.
   The dip in hot water is prescribed to destroy hitchhiking fruit
flies that could come into the United States from Mexico, said
James W. Glosser, acting administrator of the department's Animal
and Plant Health Inspection Service.
   About 65 percent of the mangoes eaten in the United States come
from Mexico and were previously fumigated with a chemical, ethylene
dibromide. However, the Environmental Protection Agency banned this
treatment.
   Glosser said the hot-water dip ``destroys all the fruit fly
species that exist in Mexico.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
