<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1636EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a-723 03-31 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a-723,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Stops Missile Attacks; Iran Shells Tanker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 UPDATE with shaky truce apparently in effect in
``war of cities.'' Picks up 3rd graf pvs, In Ankara ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq fired three missiles into Iranian
cities Thursday, then said it would stop for three days. No further
attacks by either side were reported in the month-old round of the
``war of the cities.''
   The Iraqi News Agency said the cease-fire would begin Thursday
midnight (4 p.m. EST) and last through the three days of a visit to
Baghdad by Turgut Ozal, prime minister of Turkey.
   As the announced time passed, neither side had reported any
attacks on each other's cities for hours.
   A Cypriot supertanker set afire by an Iranian warship earlier
Thursday meanwhile ran aground in the Persian Gulf.
   In Ankara, the Turkish capital, Iranian Embassy spokesman Riza
Bagri said Iran's missile launchings would ``automatically come to
an end'' if Iraq stopped attacking Iranian cities with rockets and
bombs.
   Tehran radio did not confirm Bagri's statement, but said Iraq
was the ``instigator'' of attacks on cities and Iran took
``retaliatory measures.''
   Hundreds of civilians have been killed since the missile duel
began Feb. 29 and thousands have died in raids on cities since the
Iran-Iraq war began in September 1980.
   An Iranian warship pounded the 232,164-ton supertanker Haven,
loaded with 1.5 million barrels of Saudi Arabian crude, for 90
minutes at dawn Thursday. The 45-member crew was rescued from the
burning ship, which ran aground later off the United Arab Emirates.
   Shipping executives believed the attack was a response to
several Iraqi attacks in recent days on tankers owned or chartered
by Iran. About 500 ships have been attacked by both sides.
   A U.S. Navy spokesman said two portable anti-aircraft missiles,
tentatively identified as Soviet-made SAM-7s, were found on a
drifting Iranian speedboat the Navy recovered last week. The
Iranians use speedboats for attacks on neutral shipping.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's revolutionary patriarch,
exhorted his people to new effort in the long conflict, declaring:
``Today is the day of war. Today we must rush to the war front in
order to inflict punishing blows on the enemy, and with the help of
God we will succeed.''
   ``The enemy has proved his brutal actions by firing chemical
weapons on residential areas,'' he said in remarks reported by
Tehran radio.
   A dispatch from Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency
said a team of Swiss physicians arrived to visit victims of alleged
Iraqi chemical weapons attacks on border towns.
   It also said Iraq dropped chemical bombs on Marivan, a Kurdish
town about 25 miles northeast of Halabja, killing ``a number'' of
civilians.
   Iran claims Iraq dropped gas bombs on Halabja and two nearby
Kurdish towns in Iraq two weeks ago, after Iranian troops captured
them. Iran said 5,000 people were killed in the attack and 5,000
wounded.
   Iraq said it fired two surface-to-surface missiles Thursday into
Isfahan, which was Persia's capital in the 17th century, and one
into Qom, seat of Iran's religious hierarchy.
   Since the missile exchange began, Iraq has reported launching
105 missiles at Iranian cities. Iran says it has fired 45 missiles
at Baghdad and dozens into other Iraqi cities.
   Turkish Embassy officials in Baghdad said Ozal would arrive
Friday afternoon accompanied by senior officials. Turkey maintains
good relations with both Iraq and Iran and has tried to act as
mediaor.
   An Iraqi government spokesman was quoted by the official news
agency as saying attacks on Iranian cities would not resume ``until
six hours after the Turkish prime minister's departure'' on Sunday.
   The Cypriot tanker was attacked near the narrow Strait of
Hormuz, through which all ships must pass to enter or leave the
gulf. Shipping executives said it drifted for more than three hours
before running aground.
   Crew members huddled on the stern, unable because of the fire to
reach the engine room and stop the engines, and they were rescued a
few at a time. Tugboats brought the blaze under control later, said
the informants, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Maj. Barry Willey, a spokesman for the U.S. Central Command,
said the SAM-7s were found along with other weapons in an abandoned
Iranian speedboat picked up in the Strait of Hormuz a week ago.
   He said a twin-barreled gun mounted in the cockpit of the
30-foot boat was a Soviet-made ZSU 23mm anti-aircraft weapon.
   SAM-7 missiles, which Iran is known to possess, are
shoulder-fired weapons similar to the U.S.-made Redeye.
</TEXT>
