<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 2213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArmsTreaty     03-31 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Byrd Puts INF Pact on Hold Over Future Weapons Question</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd said
Thursday he will not call up the U.S.-Soviet medium-range missile
treaty for debate until the question of whether the pact bans
futuristic weapons is better resolved.
   But Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., the Senate's deputy GOP leader,
said the White House has put ``400 lawyers to work'' on the issue
and added: ``I think it can be resolved.''
   Sen. Chic Hecht, R-Nev., a member of the Senate Intelligence
Committee, said, however, that the general question of futuristic
weapons is a serious one and must be addressed sooner or later.
   Hecht said U.S. intelligence reports show the Soviet Union has
10,000 scientists working on the development of futuristic weapons
using lasers and directed energy.
   Hecht said the information came from a classified intelligence
briefing, but that he had been given permission to release it.
   Byrd told reporters that the question of futuristic weapons had
been addressed inadequately by the administration and it was not
clear that they are banned by the treaty's restrictions.
   ``It is too important to risk going ahead,'' Byrd said. ``It is
better to be sure, to be cautious and to be right. I intend not to
call it up until it is better resolved than it is now.''
   ``The treaty has to be good for us,'' Byrd said, adding that his
decision to delay action on the treaty is ``a signal to the
administration not to do in haste'' what should be done with care.
   On another treaty issue, a group of Republican senators told
reporters at a luncheon meeting they believed compromise eventually
will be reached on a move by Democrats to attach to the pact
language intended to bind future presidents to the current view of
the meaning and impact of the treaty.
   Sen. Daniel Evans, R-Wash., a member of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, called the Democratic effort ``an egregious
insult to President Reagan'' and said it will not be settled
without a pitched battle.
   ``The Democrats will not let the treaty die because of this but
we might come perilously close before someone backs down,'' Evans
said.
   ``There is one group trying to kill the treaty and another group
trying to embarrass the president, and neither group will win,''
Evans said.
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said he also believed the
controversy will be resolved.
   ``The Democrats will not let the treaty die on this issue,''
McConnell said. ``I cannot believe that when push comes to shove
they are going to want to be held responsible by the American
people for failure to ratify this treaty.''
   The dispute grew out the Reagan administration's
reinterpretation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty to
permit the deloyment of a strategic defense system.
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted 17-2 vote on
Wednesday to approve the treaty and send it to the full Senate,
where it was expected to be taken up following next week's Easter
recess.
   Ambassador Maynard Glitman, the chief U.S. negotiator for the
treaty, told the committee that the treaty does ban future weapons
and that the Soviets understands they are banned.
   Glitman said the treaty calls for the elimination of all
``weapon delivery vehicles'' with a range from between 400 miles
and 3,400 miles, asserting this covers all weapons, not just those
armed with nuclear warheads.
</TEXT>
