<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JFKStatue     03-31 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-JFK Statue,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Viewing of JFK Statue Finalists Held Before April 7
Selection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five statues of the late President John F. Kennedy
were displayed on a tabletop Thursday for members of a special
legislative board who will select one of the designs for a monument
on the Statehouse lawn.
   Selection of the winning sculpture design will conclude a
yearlong competition that included hundreds of entries from artists
around the country.
   Three of the statues on display at the John F. Kennedy Library
were made of white plaster, one of bronze and one, still wet, of
clay. They ranged in height from 2 feet to 3 feet.
   All the finalists show Kennedy in traditional design in full
figure. In one submission, he is wearing an open overcoat, which is
blowing in the wind.
   The five semifinalist sculptors are: Frederick Hart of Markham,
Va.; Penelope Jencks of Newton; Robert White of St. James, Va.;
Isable McIlvain of Concord, and Norman Legassie, Jr. of Old Lyme,
Conn.
   ``For the past 25 years, since the death of John F. Kennedy,
Massachusetts has been without an official state monument to its
beloved native son,'' said state Rep. John MacGovern, the
commission chairman. ``The absence of the late president from this
state's proud display of monuments is about to be corrected with a
memorial that every citizen of the commonwealth can be proud of.''
   After a brief introduction by former Kennedy aide Dave Powers,
MacGovern said the nationwide search for a sculptor was almost
over. Paraphrasing Winston Churchill, MacGovern said, ``this is not
the beginning of the end, it is perhaps the end of the beginning.''
   Commission members will be casting their votes for a memorial
finalist over the next few days.
   Caroline Kennedy, Kennedy's daughter and a member of the
commission, will attend the April 7 news conference annoucing the
winning sculpture.
   The JFK statue, which will be the commonwealth's official
monument to Kennedy, will be erected on the west front lawn of the
Statehouse. It is hoped that the dedication of the memorial will
take place May 29, 1989, which would have been Kennedy's 72nd
birthday.
   Kennedy, a Democrat who was elected president in 1960 and
assassinated in 1963, began his political career in the 1940s
representing Boston in Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
