<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HondurasExercise     03-31 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras Exercise,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon: Honduras Exercise To Cost At Least $5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deployment of more than 3,100 troops to
Honduras as a show of force and warning to Nicaragua will cost at
least $5 million, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   Dan Howard, the Defense Department's chief spokesman, said final
figures won't be available for 30 to 60 days. But, he said, ``The
total cost of the operation is estimated at somewhere between $5
million and $10 million.''
   Howard was asked about the cost of the so-called Emergency
Deployment Readiness Exercise after announcing the last soldiers
from the 82nd Airborne Division had returned home to Fort Bragg,
N.C., Thursday morning.
   ``Some logistical support people will be returning tomorrow
(Friday),'' he added. ``All the equipment and supplies not expended
in the operation will be returned to the United States.''
   Soldiers from the 82nd Airborne and the 7th Light Infantry
Division at Fort Ord, Calif., were airlifted on March 17 and 18
after Nicaraguan troops crossed into Honduras to mount an attack on
U.S.-backed Contra guerrillas.
   The American soldiers were then flown to different parts of
Honduras for exercises with Honduran army units.
   ``We're very pleased with the accomplishments of this
exercise,'' Howard said. ``It demonstrates the responsiveness and
deployability of the Army's light forces in a joint operation.''
</TEXT>
