<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Abstract     03-31 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abstract,200</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<HEAD>Love Numbers: Census Has a Book for You</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Numbers lovers can rejoice. The latest edition
of the Statistical Abstract is at hand with detail on everything
they ever wanted to know, and probably more.
   The 108th edition of the volume goes on for 970 pages, including
1,425 tables and charts, compiled by the Census Bureau from a wide
variety of sources.
   Selling for $25 _ $5 more for hardbound _ the volume is widely
used by students, teachers, journalists, government workers,
businessmen and the just plain curious.
   A sampling of facts from the volume:
   _The nation produced $18.7 billion worth of computers in 1985,
nearly nine times the worth of those manufactured a decade earlier.
   _The U.S. fish catch totaled 8.2 million pounds in 1986. The
biggest item, menhaden at 2.4 million pounds.
   _There were 909,000 Americans in hospitals on any given day in
1985, a total that has been declining in recent years.
   _Some 5.57 percent of mortgages were delinquent in 1986, down
from 5.84 percent a year earlier.
   _Alaska has the nation's highest birth rate, followed by Utah
and New Mexico. The highest rate for abortions is in California,
followed by New York and Hawaii.
</TEXT>
