<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0706 03-31 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Local Officials Seek High-Level Help in Ethnic Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-2 to recast.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regional Communist Party officials admitted they
are powerless to end an ethnic dispute that has led to a massive
work stoppage by Armenians in a southern city, and they appealed to
Moscow for help, a newspaper reported Thursday.
   The government daily Izvestia said the Stepanakert City
Committee unanimously passed a resolution calling on national party
leaders to again take up the issue of the Nagorno-Karabakh region
of Azerbaijan.
   Armenians are demanding that the Armenian-dominated region be
made part of their republic, which neighbors Azerbaijan.
   The local committee's appeal, adopted at a meeting Wednesday,
did not persuade people to return to work, according to one
resident in Stepanakert, the main city of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   ``People aren't even thinking of going to work,'' said the
resident, a man answering the telephone at the Sovietsky Karabakh
newspaper Thursday. He refused to identify himself.
   Izvestia said the plenary meeting of the Stepanakert City
Committee was stormy and that one speaker broke down and cried.
   ``The majority of the Communists decisively condemned the tactic
of `forced pressure' on the country's leadership, and along with
that every speaker underlined that the Nagorno-Karabakh problem has
not been removed, that it still needs a settlement,'' Izvestia said.
   Izvestia said the work stoppage gave new ammunition to people
who say Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms permit too
much outspokenness.
   Izvestia quoted a Stepanakert party official, Robert Kocharyan,
as saying that ``continuing worker absences give supporters of the
old (way) grounds to say: `Here's your result! You let the people
get out of hand. You shouldn't give them such an occasion.'''
   Izvestia did not provide other details of the meeting, and a
woman answering the telephone at the city committee's offices
referred all questions to the party Central Committee in Moscow.
   Stepanakert workers have vowed to continue the walkout, which
began March 24, until the central government and party reverse
their decisions to keep Nagorno-Karabakh under the control of
Azerbaijan.
   The Communist Party Central Committee refused the Armenians'
demand in February and was asked by the local committee to
reconsider the decision. The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the
national parliament, ordered cultural and economic improvements for
the region on March 23 but did not address the territorial issue.
   All but bakeries and dairies, some stores and some public
transportation and medical clinics have been closed in Stepanakert
since the strike began.
   Kocharyan said just 308 workers, only one-fifth of the force,
showed up Thursday at the silk factory where he works.
   ``For me that's zero, and as a party secretary, I'm ashamed for
myself and my comrades,'' he told Izvestia.
   The man at the Sovietsky Karabakh newspaper said there were no
demonstrations in Stepanakert and that few policemen were on the
street.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov provided
the first official confirmation that Paruyr Ayrikyan, a former
political prisoner, was among Armenian nationalists arrested last
week in the Armenian capital, Yerevan.
   The spokesman, at a regular news briefing, said he did not know
under which criminal statute Ayrikyan was being held.
   The Soviet government has forbidden foreign journalists from
traveling to Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh. Gerasimov was asked
about that policy after he criticized Israel's government for
barring journalists from the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
where unrest has raged since December.
   ``I have to reject your parallel,'' Gerasimov said. ``We have
not occupied anybody anywhere in this situation.'' He said
journalists would have to ``wait a little while'' to visit the
region, ``until the passions cool down.''
</TEXT>
