<DOCNO> AP880331-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 2356EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CPB-LatchkeyKids     03-31 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CPB-Latchkey Kids,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Broadcasting Corp. Publishes Booklet For Latchkey Kids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Corporation for Public Broadcasting has
published a booklet designed to teach ``latchkey'' children basic
skills they will need to make their time at home alone safer.
   The 16-page booklet, titled ``What If I'm Home Alone? Your
Family's Guide to Home and Personal Safety Skills,'' teaches
children such things as how to get home from school safely, how to
use a telephone in an emergency, how to escape a fire and how to
deal with strangers who knock at the door.
   The publication is written in an easy-to-read, entertaining
style with large type and illustrations. It also includes a quiz at
the end so parents can assess how well their children understand
the safety tips.
   The booklet opens with a letter to parents suggesting ways they
can make their home safer and includes a form for emergency and
other phone numbers they can fill in and post near the telephone.
   The booklet is part of a CPB public service campaign designed to
help American families cope with changes in society that have left
a majority of families headed by a single parent or two working
parents.
   An estimated 5 million to 6 million children ages 5 to 12 who
daily come home to an empty house or apartment or have to care for
younger siblings, CPB said.
   The campaign is being run in conjunction with public
broadcasting's year-long, national ``Child Care America'' project
being kicked off April 10. The project will focus attention on the
issue throughout the year with outreach activities and programming,
including a PBS documentary called ``Who Cares for the Children?''
   CPB is a private, nonprofit corporation funded by Congress to
develop noncommercial radio and television services.
   Copies of the booklet are available for $1 each, by check, by
writing to ``What If I'm Home Alone?,'' Corporation for Public
Broadcasting, P.O. Box 33039-LK, Washington, D.C., 20033.
</TEXT>
