<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Mood 1stLd-Writethru a0673 03-31 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Mood, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0673,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After A Month of Missiles, Tehran Fears Poison Gas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-end with 18 grafs to ADD Khomeini remarks on
missiles and elections, reorder info. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The warning broadcast over the radio for the
first time Thursday was simple: three beeps, a pause, then three
more beeps.
   That signal would mean Iraq has launched a poison gas attack on
Tehran, where Iraqi missiles have fallen day and night and where
fears of chemical warfare by Baghdad are growing.
   After the warning beeps on Tehran Radio, an announcer said:
``God willing, we hope no such thing will ever happen, but the
enemy is so mean and despicable he could do anything.''
   An official of the Islamic Guidance Ministry escorting visiting
Western correspondents around the battered capital, a city of more
than 6 million people, said the Iraqis ``would pay dearly if they
dared to do it.''
   The city of Tehran seems to have paid enough already. Officials
said half of its population has left since Iraq's missiles began
wrecking apartment houses, markets, shops, office buildings,
hospitals and schools.
   On Thursday, many Tehran schools and stores stayed closed in
case of attack, but people came up to the streets from underground
shelters. There were few of the traffic jams for which Tehran was
notorious before the missiles.
   The missiles that have been rained on the city since Feb. 29,
when the Iraqis began firing such weapons into Tehran for the first
time in the war.
   Iraq says it has launched more than 100 surface-to-surface
rockets at Tehran in that period. Others have have hit the holy
city of Qom, 100 miles to the south, and Isfahan in central Iran,
which was the capital of Persia during the 17th century.
   Iran has fired about half as many missiles into Baghdad, a city
of 5 million.
   A statement by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini exhorted his people
to ignore Iraqi missiles and turn out for the April 8 parliamentary
elections.
   ``Even if the nation is subjected to missile and bombing
attacks, it will go to the ballot box,'' said the statement, read
on the radio by an announcer. ``I personally will participate in
the elections under any conditions.''
   By Thursday, no Iraqi missiles had exploded in Tehran for three
days, although other cities were hit. Iraq declared Thursday that
it was suspending attacks for three days because of a visit to
Baghdad by Turgut Ozal, prime minister of Turkey.
   Officials in Tehran said they believe the reason is the
scheduled arrival Monday of two U.N. experts, James Holger of the
United States and Dr. Manuel Carmona of Spain, to investigate the
alleged Iraqi gas attacks in Kurdistan. A 1925 Geneva agreement
outlaws the use of chemical weapons.
   Civilians usually have about four minutes notice of incoming
rockets after they are detected by radar installations at the
border, about 290 miles to the west.
   The radio and street loudspeakers blare warnings. People scurry
to bomb shelters, basements and underground parking lots. Yellow
signs on walls show where shelters are located.
   State television broadcasts film of Londoners sheltering in
subway stations during the German blitz of 1940. The message seems
to be that, like Britain and its Allies, Iran will win the war.
   But it is poison gas that residents of Tehran fear most,
according to those questioned randomly on the streets Thursday.
   Iran said Iraqi warplanes dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs
on three Kurdish towns in northeast Iraq on March 16-17 after
Iranian troops have captured them.
   The Iranians, at war with Iraq since September 1980, said 5,000
civilians and some Iranian soldiers were killed, and another 5,000
people were wounded. They claimed the Iraqis dropped chemical bombs
because the Kurds, long in rebellion against Iraq, welcomed their
``liberators.''
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency also said Thursday
that Iraqi warplanes dropped chemical bombs on villages in the
Marivan border region of northwest Iran earlier in the day, killing
several people.
   After months of international criticism for failing to comply
with a cease-fire resolution the U.N. Security Council passed last
summer, Iran is making all the mileage possible from the claims of
chemical warfare.
   Tehran's official press has likened the alleged Iraqi use of gas
bombs in Kurdistan to the Americans dropping atomic bombs on
Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945, and demanded international
condemnation of Iraq. Iraq has denied the claims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
