<1ST_LINE>u a AM-EmergencyLanding     03-31 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emergency Landing,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Military Jet Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian military jet having problems
with its oxygen system made an emergency landing Thursday at
Charleston's Yeager Airport after the pilot became dizzy, officials
said.
   The airport director said the single-seat F-A-18 and another
traveling with it landed safely at 4 p.m. The pilot, who was not
immediately identified, was treated at the scene and was reported
to be OK.
   Jeff Bubar, the airport manager, said one jet experienced
problems with its liquid oxygen supply and the pilot was forced to
seek the nearest airport with military facilities.
   ``The pilot was having problems with his oxygen system and was
feeling lght-headed and having problems breathing and decided to
put it down,'' said Robert Greter of the Civil Air Patrol.
   Greter said the jets carry liquid oxygen that is coverted into
gas.
   ``He didn't faint. He just felt slightly ill,'' said Dr. Jerill
Cavender, who treated the pilot.
   Cavender said the pilot was flying at 33,000 feet when the
system apparently had problems converting the liquid into gas.
   Randy Clark, air traffic control supervisor for the Federal
Aviation Administration, said the planes were en route from Florida
to Canada on a training flight.
   The West Virginia Air National Guard, which maintains facilities
at Yeager Airport, refused to comment.
   Firefighters late Thursday afternoon still were keeping an eye
on the slate-gray, 75-foot-long planes parked on a corner of the
tarmac.
   The twin-engine attack jet, known as the Hornet, was built by
McDonnell-Douglas Corp. The planes that landed in Charleston
appeared to have missiles beneath each wing, but it was not clear
whether they were live.
   The plane is designed primarily for air-to-air combat and for
air-to-ground bombings.
   One plane was decorated with an Indian and crossed tomahawks on
one of its two tailfins, and the other was decorated with a
saber-tooth tiger.
</TEXT>
