<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada     03-31 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mulroney Shuffles Cabinet In Pre-Election Buildup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney announced a major
Cabinet shuffle Thursday, bringing in an old school friend and
changing the key trade and immigration portfolios.
   ``This puts us in fighting trim for an election, when it
comes,'' the prime minister said.
   Mulroney is expected to call an election this fall or early in
1989, well before the August 1989 end of his Progressive
Conservative Party's five-year term. Canadian governments
traditionally call early elections when their popularity ratings
are high.
   The most important change was the post of minister for
international trade.
   The combative incumbent, Pat Carney, was transferred to
presidency of the Treasury Board, which had been held by Deputy
Prime Minister Don Mazankowski.
   Transport Minister John Crosbie, an affable Newfoundlander noted
for his witty ripostes in the House of Commons, took over at trade.
   He will have the task of winning Parliament's approval of the
free-trade agreement reached with the United States last year and
selling the country on the 10-year deal.
   At least two of Canada's 10 provinces, including powerful
Ontario, oppose the treaty, which would dismantle tariffs and
loosen other barriers in the world's largest trading partnership.
   Once a contender for the Conservative leadership, Crosbie
favored free trade long before Mulroney was converted to the
concept. Referring to his reputation as a somewhat of a renegade,
Crosbie told reporters: ``I certainly want to be a cannon (but) not
a loose one.''
   The biggest surprise in the reshaping of the 38-member Cabinet
was Mulroney's decision to bring in an old friend from his student
days at Laval University, Lucien Bouchard.
   Bouchard, the Canadian ambassador to France since 1985, was
named secretary of state and a member of the inner Cabinet as
Mulroney attempted to shore up support in Quebec province following
a series of scandals involving provincial ministers.
   Bouchard is a former supporter of the separatist Parti Quebecois
and voted in favor of autonomy for the province, dominated by
French-speakers, in a 1980 referendum. The referendum was defeated,
and Bouchard eventually joined the Conservative camp.
   ``I have to prove it is possible to be both a Canadian and a
Quebecer,'' Bouchard said Thursday after new Cabinet members were
sworn in by Governor General Jeanne Sauve in Ottawa.
   A lawyer from Chicoutimi, Bouchard is not a member of Parliament
but can serve in the Cabinet pending the next by-election for an
empty seat from Quebec. He replaces David Crombie who resigned
Wednesday to head a commission on the development of the Lake
Ontario waterfront.
   Employment and Immigration Minister Benoit Bouchard and his
deputy, Gerry Weiner, were both shifted from a department that has
been criticized by the opposition for the influx of illegal aliens
into Canada, estimated at 2,000 per month. Bouchard takes over as
transport minister, while Weiner becomes minister of state for
multiculturalism.
   The Bouchards are not related.
   The new immigration minister is Barbara McDougall, formerly in
charge of privatization. Her deputy is Monique Vezina, who moves
from supply and services.
   Foreign Minister Joe Clark and Finance Minister Michael Wilson
kept their jobs.
   The latest polls show the Conservatives have rebounded this year
from their third-place standing over the last two years.
   Thanks to strong economic growth and a drop in unemployment to
7.8 percent _ a seven-year low _ the Conservatives are
neck-and-neck with the main opposition Liberal Party and socialist
New Democratic Party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
