<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hogs-Pork     03-31 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hogs-Pork,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hog Production Continues To Climb Despite Slimmer Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hog farmers continue to expand production, an
Agriculture Department report showed Thursday.
   As of March 1, the inventory of hogs and pigs in the 10 major
pork states totaled an estimated 40.5 million head, up 6 percent
from both a year ago and two years ago, the report said.
   The number of breeding hogs was up 4 percent and 10 percent from
March 1 of 1987 and 1986, respectively, to 5.42 million head. That
indicated further production increases in the months ahead.
   Officials said the March 1 inventory of market hogs _ animals
headed for slaughter and the consumer market _ totaled 35.1 million
head, up 6 percent and 5 percent from the previous two years.
   The pig crop during the winter months of December, January and
February was 15.8 million head, up 6 percent from the same period
of 1986-87, the report said, and 11 percent more than in the winter
of two years ago.
   Looking a future prospects, the report said hog farmers surveyed
intend to have 2.4 million sows give birth in the March-May period,
2 percent more than a year ago and 11 percent more than the actual
farrowings of two years ago.
   The 10 leading hog states account for about 79 percent of the
nation's pork. The following list shows the March 1 inventory. The
first number, in thousands, is the total number of hogs in the
state, the second is the March 1 figure's percentage of a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Georgia         1,100  102
Illinois        5,500  112
Indiana         4,000  101
Iowa           13,200  107
Kansas          1,400  101
Minnesota       4,270  107
Missouri        2,850  104
Nebraska        3,850  101
North Carolina  2,400  104
Ohio            1,900  101
