<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Swaggart 1stLd-Writethru a0708 03-31 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swaggart, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0708,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede TULSA, Okla.</HEAD>
<HEAD>State Church To Discuss Swaggart Case Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with state council setting new meeting to
discuss case. No pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Assemblies of God state council that
wanted Jimmy Swaggart barred from preaching for three months will
meet Friday and may endorse the harsher penalty demanded by the
church's national leaders, a member said Thursday.
   The TV evangelist had cited the Louisiana District Council's
recommendation for a three-month ban when he said through his
lawyer Wednesday that he would defy the Assemblies national
leadership's order that he step down for a year.
   Swaggart stepped down from the pulpit Feb. 21 after tearfully
confessing to an undisclosed sin. A prostitute has said Swaggart
paid her to pose nude for him.
   Risking dismissal by national church leaders, Swaggart plans to
return to preaching May 22, three months after he stepped down,
said his lawyer, Bill Treeby.
   Juleen Turnage, national Assemblies of God spokeswoman at the
church's headquarters in Springfield, Mo., said the Louisiana
district presbytery would meet in Baton Rouge on Friday to discuss
Swaggart's case. She said she had no other details and the national
office did not plan to send a representative.
   The Rev. Ansley Orfila of Slidell, La., one of 19 members of the
Louisiana council, said there was little the council could do to
challenge the penalty imposed by the national body. He said
Swaggart probably will leave the denomination.
   Referring to the church's national leaders, Orfila told the
Springfield (Mo.) News-Leader: ``The executive presbytery may not
have the right to discipline him, but they have the power. I don't
think we'll meet to defy them. Maybe it will be just to decide how
to handle things.''
   Contacted Thursday, Orfila confirmed what he told the newspaper
but declined to comment further.
   State church officials decided to meet Friday after discussing
the case in a telephone conference call, the newspaper said. The
call was made shortly after the church's national officials
announced Tuesday that they had rejected the three-month ban as too
lenient.
   The Rev. Forrest Hall, secretary-treasurer of the Louisiana
District Council, said the state church will probably wind up
supporting the national recommendation. ``But the men of the
district are independent-minded,'' he told the News-Leader.
   Gus Weill, a spokesman for Swaggart, said Thursday he was
unaware of any meeting by the district council.
   Meanwhile, one of Swaggart's fellow ministers said that Swaggart
claimed evangelist Oral Roberts had cast demons out of him and that
Swaggart's feeling of being released from sin might have played a
role in his decision to return to the pulpit this spring.
   But a spokesman for the Tulsa, Okla.-based evangelist said
Roberts did not recommend Swaggart's immediate return to the pulpit.
   ``If anyone is to report that Oral Roberts is recommending that
Jimmy Swaggart defy the Assembly of God ruling from Springfield,
that is not accurate,'' said Roberts' son Richard. ``My dad had
nothing to do with his decision. We believe that that is a matter
that Jimmy Swaggart must make his own decision and follow the
leading of God.''
   The Rev. Mike Evans, pastor of the Church on the Move in Euless,
Texas, said Wednesday that while he was visiting Baton Rouge in
February, Swaggart told him of Roberts' prayer.
   ``Oral Roberts called him up and told him that he saw demons
with long fingernails digging the flesh into Jimmy Swaggart's body
and he cast those demons out of his body,'' said Evans. ``I think
this explains some of the rationale behind Jimmy's decision to
return to television after three months.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
