<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0834 03-31 0929</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0834,920</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADs with 5 grafs to UPDATE; pick up 3rd graf pvs, bgng:
``Ed Meese. Note grafs 3-4 EMBARGOED for 8 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runners Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson
sharply attacked the Reagan administration on Thursday as they
pointed toward next week's primary showdown in Wisconsin. The White
House said President Reagan was ready to begin working for George
Bush, the Republican nominee-to-be.
   Democratic hopeful Albert Gore aimed his fire at his party
rivals, saying that Dukakis was ``afraid to say a single word about
Jesse Jackson.'' Gore said he would continue to criticize Jackson,
adding he intended to treat him like he would any other combatant
in the race.
   
   Following 2 grafs embargoed for 8 p.m. EST
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Dukakis, criticized for campaigning in an aloof manner, served
lunch at a senior citizen center and then served up a stinging up
attack on the Reagan administration in an evening speech.
   ``This administration has walked away from the American dream,''
he said. ``I'm running for president because during the past seven
years I've seen too many people thrown out into the streets after
decades on the job...and I've talked to too many local leaders
who've seen their communities become ghost towns of boarded up
hopes and foreclosed dreams.''
   
   End material embargoed for 8 p.m. EST
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Jackson called on embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese to
resign. ``It is not a question of guilt or innocence. He simple
cannot fulfill the requirements of the job,'' Jackson said.
   ``Ed Meese deserves due process. We deserve an attorney
general,'' he said, referring to Meese's troubled legal situation
and recent resignations by high Justice Department aides.
   On the Republican side, Bush and his aides were looking ahead to
general election strategy, and GOP sources said one serious
possibility was for Treasury Secretary James Baker III to resign
and oversee the campaign.
   Baker was Bush's campaign manager in his unsuccessful 1980 run.
   In contrast, Democrats were still trying to clear up their muddy
nomination picture.
   Gore defended his own criticism of Jackson and characterized
Dukakis as timid on the same score as the Democratic field pointed
toward Wisconsin, next way station on the campaign marathon.
   Suellen Albrecht, the state party chairwoman, said either
Jackson or Dukakis figures to win in her state. But Gore began
running a television commercial attacking Chrysler Corp. Chairman
Lee Iacocca for closing a plant in Wisconsin, and Sen. Paul Simon
was campaigning in what could be his last stand.
   Dukakis and Jackson were in a close race for the lead in
national convention delegates, although neither man had even a
third of the 2,082 needed to win the nomination.
   Jackson's victory in the Michigan caucuses last week elevated
him to the front rank of the race, to the dismay of some party
officials who fear his race and liberal positions would lead to a
massive Democratic defeat in the fall if he should be nominated.
   Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, a Jackson supporter, told a Capitol
Hill news conference that there is evidence of a ``Stop Jesse
Movement'' forming among Southern Democrats _ and he saw a certain
irony in that.
   ``I would suggest to you that the people involved in this effort
are probably people who did not want to see a Mike Dukakis or Jesse
Jackson in this race. ... They're now coalescing behind a Mike
Dukakis candidacy,'' he said.
   There is no question that Jackson has been the talk of the race
since his stunning Michigan landslide last Saturday.
   Gore, who picked up the endorsement of the Milwaukee Sentinel on
Thursday, has criticized Jackson in recent days for lacking
experience and for associating in the past with PLO Leader Yasser
Arafat and Cuba's Fidel Castro.
   He said he was holding Jackson to the same standard as he would
any other politician, and added that Dukakis ``is afraid to say a
single word about Jesse Jackson.''
   Jackson spent the day foraging for votes in Wisconsin, and he
told an audience of high school students that it is not always the
elected officials who lead the drive for change.
   ``The reality is that this drive for social justice, this drive
for equal protection under the law was led by young America. I was
part of the generation, of that leadership. I learned to lead by
heading a student body as a college student,'' he said.
   Jackson picked up an endorsemnent from Richard Congdon, an
attorney who headed Richard Gephardt's now-defunct campaign in
Wisconsin.
   And he got some kind words from withdrawn candidate Gary Hart.
The one-time front-runner in the race said Jackson's campaign has
been sending a message to the party's leaders that the voters are
dissatisfied with politics as usual.
   ``Jesse is as much a messenger to the party leaders as a bearer
of his own message,'' Hart said in an interview with the Denver
Post. The former Colorado senator also said he has advised Jackson
to deliver a series of speeches on the budget deficit, education,
military reform and other issues _ and added that he was ``more
than prepared'' to help himn write them.
   Among the Republicans, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
did not say when Reagan would begin campaigning for Bush. But he
said the situation that once led the president to declare his
neutrality in the GOP race had changed following Sen. Bob Dole's
withdrawal from the campaign.
   Pat Robertson is Bush's only active challenger, but Fitzwater
noted that the former television evangelist ``recognizes the
realities of the situation.''
</TEXT>
