<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Nofziger 1stLd-Writethru a0752 03-31 0773</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nofziger, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0752,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Unrepentent Former Reagan Aide Deserves Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 7th graf bgng, `Nofziger also,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with defense comment and reference to April 8 sentencing date;
INSERTS 2 grafs after 13th graf pvs bgng, `Whatever his,' with
additional defense comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential aide Lyn Nofziger should
be imprisoned for illegally lobbying the White House because he
flouted the law and compared his offense to ``running a stop
sign,'' a prosecutor said Thursday in court papers.
   Independent counsel James C. McKay said in a sentencing memo
that remarks Nofziger made following his conviction Feb. 11 showed
``a total lack of remorse or contrition'' about violating the
Ethics in Government Act's ban on lobbying former colleagues less
than a year afte leaving government service.
   Nofziger, 63, should be fined and imprisoned to ``impress
present and former government employees, as well as the general
public, that Congress intended those restrictions to be taken
seriously and that they will be enforced with meaningful
penalties,'' McKay said in the memo filed with U.S. District Judge
Thomas A. Flannery.
   Minutes after the verdict, Nofziger stood outside the U.S.
Courthouse and called the ethics statute ``a lousy law.'' He also
said, ``I don't think I did anything wrong'' and compared the
offense to ``running a stop sign.''
   Nofziger, President Reagan's former political director, repeated
his profession of innocence in a Feb. 18 letter to the court that
was quoted in the prosecution brief. ``I have never thought, and I
do not think today, that I am guilty morally, ethically or legally
of the crimes of which I am convicted,'' he wrote.
   McKay said ``that intransigent attitude is a consideration
arguing in favor of a sentence that includes a period of
incarceration.''
   The sentencing is scheduled for April 8.
   ``To request jail time for a 63-year-old man with a spotless
record of public service who did not intend to violate the law is
ridiculous, unnecessary and totally lacking in compassion,'' said
defense lawyer E. Lawrence Barcella.
   McKay said Nofziger also ignored the advice of lawyers he
consulted about the ethics law when he left Reagan's staff in early
1982 to form a consulting business with Mark A. Bragg.
   The prosecution brief recounted an incident in which Nofziger
uttered a profanity when one of the attorneys, Martin L. Artiano,
advised him not to make any White House contacts without first
contacting the law firm.
   During the trial, associate independent counsel Merrick Garland
related the episode to the judge during a bench conference out of
hearing of the jury and the public, according to the trial
transcript.
   Garland told the judge that after responding with the profanity,
Nofziger said, ``These are my friends and I am going back to them
if I want to.''
   McKay noted in the sentencing memo that Nofziger's defense
lawyers have ``attempted to minimize the significance of this
episode by asserting that defendant Nofziger's profanity ... was
characteristic of their client's jocularity.''
   ``Perhaps so,'' McKay wrote, ``but his lawyers at the time took
the incident seriously. They have told staff members of the
independent counsel that this episode caused concern'' within the
law firm.
   ``Whatever his choice of words, however, it is evident that
defendant Nofziger was alerted to and deliberately chose to ignore
written and oral advice that Section 207(c) (of the ethics law)
applied to him,'' McKay said.
   ``Lyn doesn't recall ever having such a conversation,'' Barcella
said. Artiano only recalled it after ``a lot of prompting'' during
``repeated interviews with the independent counsel and numerous
sessions with the grand jury,'' Barcella said.
   ``Even Artiano has said Lyn was joking when he said it and
thereafter Lyn came and asked for their advice about Ethics in
Government Act matters,'' Barcella said.
   Flannery did not allow the defense to argue during the trial
that Nofziger acted with advice of legal counsel when he lobbied
the White House.
   Nofziger could be sentenced to up to two years in prison and
fined up to $10,000 on each of three counts of illegally lobbying
the White House on behalf of Wedtech Corp., a maritime engineers'
union and the manufacturer of the Air Force's A-10 anti-tank plane.
   McKay did not make a specific recommendation about the length of
the prison term but said Nofziger should be fined cumulatively for
each of the three convictions.
   ``Nofziger's special entree to the most powerful officials in
government, including the president himself, epitomized the very
danger to public perception about the integrity of governmental
decision-making that motivated Congress to enact the one-year
no-contact prohibition,'' the prosecutor said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
