<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0822 03-31 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0822,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Attorney General Meese Must Go</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 11th graf pvs, bgng: Then, taking, to CORRECT reference
to Mrs. Reagan</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHEBOYGAN, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Jesse Jackson called Thursday
for the resignation of Attorney General Edwin Meese III and said,
``It is not a question of guilt or innocence. He simply cannot
fulfill the requirements of the job.''
   The presidential hopeful, a longtime critic of President
Reagan's Justice Department, said he is ``appalled at the state of
emergency'' there. He blamed the problems on Reagan's tolerance of
what he called a low moral tone in the administration.
   ``Justice is the jugular vien of democracy. With justice, almost
everything is possible,'' Jackson told at rally of about 2,000 at
the Sheboygan Armory. ``Without justice, almost nothing is
possible.''
   Jackson said Meese must go because he is being consumed
defending himself against allegations of wrongdoing. The candidate
called the recent resignations of top Justice officials ``a
national disgrace'' because, he said, they left ``rather than have
their reputations sullied in association with the attorney
general.''
   To an enthusiastic, mostly white crowd which cheered his attacks
on Meese, Jackson said:
   ``Increasingly, the administration of justice is being
sacrificed to the defense of the attorney general. ... This is not
a question of the shameful prospect of an attorney general who
spends more time in court as a defendant than as a prosecutor.''
   The attorney general must take the lead in shaping national
policies to cut drug traffic and reduce crime, activities that
simply take a great deal of time, Jackson argued.
   ``It is not a question of guilt or innocence. He simply cannot
fulfill the requirements of the job. Ed Meese deserves due process.
We deserve an attorney general,'' he said.
   Jackson said Meese will probably not resign, so Reagan must ask
him to leave.
   ``Today in Washington, once again there is a leadership vacuum
in this collapsing administration,'' Jackson said. ``Ed Meese does
not have the judgment to submit his resignation. The president does
not exercise leadership to ask for it. The vice president _ now
leader of his party _ does not have the strength to get the
president to act,'' Jackson said. ``So the nation must depend _
once again _ on Mrs. Reagan.''
   Then, taking the line from Mrs. Reagan's drug campaign, the
Democrat added: ``When Mr. Meese asks Mr. Reagan whether he should
stay on, Mrs. Reagan should advise him, `Just say no.'''
   Jackson would not respond directly to attacks from fellow
Democratic candidate Sen. Albert Gore Jr. on his lack of
govermental experience. But the civil rights activist did so by
implication.
   ``Some officeholders are not leaders,'' he said in Sheboygan.
``All leaders are not officeholders.''
   At Pulaski High School in the heart of Southside Milwaukee,
Jackson talked to 2,000 students about the nature of leadership.
   He detailed major civil rights achievements _ the Civil Rights
Act, voting rights, open housing _ and then talked about who was
responsible.
   ``These rich achievments are in some elected officials' resumes,
but the reality is that this drive for social justice, this drive
for equal protection under the law was led by young America. I was
part of the generation, of that leadership,'' he said.
   Southside Milwaukee was the site of sometimes violent
confrontations during the 1960s as activists marched into all-white
neighborhoods to support open housing laws. Jackson received a warm
welcome from the mostly white crowd.
   In Washington, Rep. Mickey Leland of Texas, who said Wednesday
he believes a ``stop Jesse'' movement is afoot, told a news
conference that ``while there is evidence that a movement aimed at
stopping Jesse has been mounted by Jackson detractors, we have not
yet identified exactly who they are.''
   Leland speculated that ``the architects of Super Tuesday are
behind this.''
   Jackson picked up the endorsement of Richard Congdon, a Waukesha
lawyer who headed Richard Gephardt's campaign in the state.
   Jackson is on the air in Wisconsin with a $40,000 television
buy, said campaign manager Gerald Austin.
</TEXT>
