<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Greece-Daedalus 1stLd-Writethru a0847 03-31 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Daedalus, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0847,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pedal-Pusher Plane Succeeds in Test Flight Before World Record
Attempt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``Friday's test ... and 9th graf, ``Conditions
appeared ... to CORRECT Friday to Thursday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sophisticated, ultralight aircraft run
by human power made six successful test flights Thursday preparing
for a record distance attempt inspired by the 3,500-year-old Greek
myth of Daedalus.
   The record attempt was to be made Friday, but organizers of the
3-year-old, $1 million project postponed the flight until the
weekend because gusts of up to 30 mph are expected Friday.
   The Massachusetts Institute of Technology project is aimed at
breaking the world record for human-powered flight over the 74-mile
distance from Crete to the island of Santorini, also known as Thira.
   Thursday's test flights each lasted less than three minutes in
calm dawn weather above a Greek air force base next to Iraklion
airport.
   Flight Director Steve K. Bussulari, an MIT aerospace expert,
told reporters the 68-pound Daedalus 88 ``is in good shape ... and
we may see favorable conditions'' for a flight Saturday or Sunday.
   Five pilots _ four Americans and a Greek _ took turns pedaling
the pink-and-silver ultralight at speeds of about 14 mph, flying
about 15 feet above the tarmac.
   The craft is named in honor of the mythical inventor Daedalus,
who tried with his son Icarus to escape from Crete on wings made of
feathers and wax. Daedalus succeeded, but Icarus flew too near the
sun, the wax melted and he fell into the sea.
   The record flight requires temperatures below 70 degrees and
almost dead calm.
   Conditions appeared perfect Thursday following nine days of
blustery weather.
   Frank Scioscia, 27, a professional cyclist from Scranton, Pa.,
reported, ``It feels like a day for the record, pretty calm. I was
flying the plane with no hands.''
   But Bussulari noted that Daedalus 88 would have run into strong
headwinds about five miles off Santorini and that in any case, ``We
felt we needed a test flight to shake down the airplane.''
   The pilots are taking turns standing by in readiness for the
flight. The pilot who had been scheduled to fly Friday was Greg
Zack, 26, of Wilmington, N.C., whose father was born in Greece.
   The pilot pumps bicycle pedals that turn the ultralight's
propeller. He uses a joystick to steer the plane, coordinating with
ground-based radio instructions.
   ``For the record the pilot must keep pedaling a steady 15 mph
but the effort is equivalent to riding 23 miles an hour on land,''
said Glenn Tremml, a medical student from New Haven, Conn.
   Tremml set the 37.2-mile world record for human-powered flight
in California in 1987, flying a Daedalus prototype.
   Two backup flying machines are ready if needed.
   All the craft are made of lightweight composite material _
graphite epoxy, plastic fiber and mylar, an extra-thin plastic skin
that covers the 112-foot wingspan.
   Its organizers said the Daedalus project has produced new
information on endurance and low altitude flying aerodynamics and
meteorology during its three years of development.
   Project director John S. Langford explained, ``The project does
have a research and educational application, particularly in human
physiology and aeronautics. The plane itself doesn't have any
practical application. It should be seen as a work of art.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
