<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Lebanon     03-31 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Fight Lebanese Guerrillas North of `Security Zone'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HASBAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli forces left their
self-proclaimed ``security zone'' in south Lebanon Thursday
afternoon in pursuit of Lebanese communist guerrillas who tried to
infiltrate, police reported.
   They said three guerrillas were wounded in a 30-minute firefight
four miles into the foothills of Mount Hermon, north of the
security zone. A guerrilla who escaped told reporters in the
Syrian-policed town of Hasbaya there were at least four Israeli
casualties.
   Israeli authorities did not comment on the claim and it could
not be verified independently.
   Police said the eight-man guerrilla squad was caught trying to
infiltrate into the zone, which Israel established north of its
border in 1985 after withdrawing most of its occupation army from
south Lebanon.
   Two helicopter gunships strafed olive groves on Mount Hermon's
slopes as about 40 soldiers chased the fleeing guerrillas, police
said.
   Militiamen of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army left the
zone on Wednesday to attack Shiite Moslem guerrillas in the village
of Kfar Roumman, with the aid of Israeli gunships.
   Police said seven people, including two Shiite guerrillas, were
killed and 15 wounded in and around Kfar Roumman.
</TEXT>
