<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0838 03-31 1015</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0838,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Announces Financial Moves; Senate Passes Resolution</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Adds 4 grafs to UPDATE with senators' letter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House announced steps Thursday to
encourage American companies to withhold payments from Panama and
warned that mandatory action will be considered if the voluntary
measures are not sufficient.
   The action follows the disclosure that some American firms are
paying taxes and fees to Panama for doing business there,
undercutting the economic sanctions imposed by the United States to
force the ouster of strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Announcing the new action, White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said, ``we are giving U.S. companies and persons an
incentive and opportunity not to provide financial support to the
Noriega regime.
   ``Should these measures prove insufficient, we will review
additional legal steps that may be necessary to deny transfer of
funds to the Noriega regime from U.S. companies and persons,''
Fitzwater said.
   Fitzwater said U.S. government payments owed the government of
Panama will be deposited in the Federal Reserve Bank in New York.
The United States already is withholding canal fees, toll payments
and other funds. Fitzwater said withholding taxes for U.S. employes
in Panama and rental payments also will go in the new account.
   He also said the Justice Department will take part in legal
cases by private parties who owe debts to Panama, declaring
President Eric Delvalle is the legitimate leader of the country.
The U.S. Treasury Department will help establish an account for
payment of funds in these cases.
   Moreover, the Internal Revenue Service will issue guidance
explaining how tax credits can be claimed for Panamanian income
taxes paid into an account at the Federal Reserve Bank in New York,
instead of to the Noriega government.
   Fitzwater said he did know how much money would be involved by
the action, but estimated it could deprive Noriega of ``millions
and millions.''
   On Capitol Hill, meanwhile, the Senate voted 92-1 to approve a
resolution urging President Reagan to act at once to cut off the
flow of dollars from U.S. corporations to the Noriega regime.
   Panama has received an infusion of an estimated $19 million in
quarterly tax revenues. About $5.5 million of that money reportedly
came from taxes and fees paid by U.S. companies doing business in
Panama.
   Texaco Inc. and Eastern Airlines confirmed they had made
payments to the Panamanian government and said they were a routine
part of their business there.
   Fitzwater said the administration understands the legal concerns
of the companies involved. ``I'm not trying to cast any blame or
concern upon them. That was the system. They've got their laws.
They've got things they've got to comply with and we're trying to
help them through changes in IRS regulation.''
   He played down the amount of money involved, saying it was not
significant.
   Asked if it was not a setback for U.S. efforts, Fitzwater said,
``It's a minor setback in the sense that one day there's zero
(money) and the next day there's something, but these are fairly
small payments in the total picture and are not going to solve Mr.
Noriega's very serious and long-term problem.''
   He said the administration was studying a plan by which the
companies would make tax payments into an account in the United
States controlled by President Eric Delvalle, who has been in
hiding since demanding Noriega's resignation.
   The United States continues to recognize Delvalle as the
legitimate head of Panama's government.
   The Senate resolution was introduced by Majority Leader Robert
C. Byrd of West Virginia.
   ``The use of these monies (paid by American companies) has
enabled Gen. Noriega to buy himself time and prolong himself in
power as he ruthlessly continues in his efforts to thwart the
democratic will of the people of Panama and crush the general
strike,'' Byrd said.
   The resolution urges Reagan to use his authority under the
Emergency Economic Powers Act ``to prevent future transfers to the
Noriega regime of currency and credit subject to the jurisdiction
of the United States.''
   It also urges Reagan to consider placing such funds into an
escrow account until Noriega is ousted and democratic rule restored
in Panama.
   Only Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., voted against the resolution.
He did not explain the reasons for his vote.
   In another legislative move, Sen. David Durenburger, R-Minn.,
introduced legislation to deny U.S. foreign tax credits to American
companies which have made tax payments to Noriega's regime.
   ``In effect, the U.S. taxpayer is not going to subsidize the
illegal Noriega government,'' Durenburger said.
   Texaco spokesman Peter Maneri said its payments covered
corporate income, sales and excise taxes due for March. He said the
company does not see any conflict with U.S. economic sanctions.
   ``We continue our operations in Panama based on normal
commercial considerations,'' Maneri said. ``We do not become
involved in any political activity in a host nation; we're just
doing business down there.''
   Eastern spokeswoman Virginia Sanchez said the airline paid about
$178,000 in cash for monthly operating fees, including navigational
aids, communications, airport rentals and landing fees.
   ``There is nothing unusual or out of the ordinary about these
payments,'' she said.
   Meanwhile, a group of 13 senators urged the administration to
make arrangements to help Panama's banking system resume normal
operations after Noriega's departure.
   In a letter to Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III, the
senators suggested the Treasury use the resources of the Exchange
Stabilization Fund to provide the National Bank of Panama with a
line of credit for the Panamanian banking system.
   The senators said the funds should be made available only after
the United States government is satisfied that Panama acted to
eliminate the use of Panamanian banks ``by drug traffickers to
shield illegal activities.''
   The letter was signed by Sens. Robert W. Kasten Jr., R-Wis.;
Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.; Alfonse M.
D'Amato, R-N.Y.; Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.; Dave Durenberger,
R-Minn.; Warren B. Rudman, R-N.H.; Tom Harkin, D-Iowa; John W.
Warner, R-Va.; Pete Wilson, R-Calif.; Christopher J Dodd, D-Conn.;
John F. Kerry, D-Mass.; and Bob Graham, D-Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
