<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Church 1stLd-Writethru a0629 03-31 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Church, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Criticize Dissidents, Seek to Ease Restrictions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Five grafs SUB for 9th graf pvs, Yakunin was ... UPDATING
with Yakunin comments. Picks up 10th graf pvs, Filaret said ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church leaders said Thursday they are working with
the authorities to ease restrictions on religion in a society
dominated by atheists, but may fail unless clerical dissidents stop
causing trouble.
   Metropolitan Filaret of Kiev and Galitsky said the Rev. Gleb
Yakunin, a former political prisoner, and the Rev. Nikolai Gainov
were two of those in the Russian Orthodox church who seek ``to
press on us methods of solving our problems that would lead to
confrontation between church and state.''
   He described the dissidents as a small group of priests and lay
people.
   The church always has cooperated with the government, which is
dominated by the officially atheist Communist Party, but its
leaders say they want to moderate a 1929 law that requires
registration of religious groups and prevents charitable activities
and religious education of the young.
   Although they did not directly attack the law during a news
conference, their veiled criticisms appeared to be among the
strongest in years.
   Filaret stressed, however, that the church ``will continue to
use the same method of solving problems it has used in the whole
post-revolutionary period.''
   Last week, Yakunin called for the resignation of Patriarch
Pimen, 78, as head of the Russian Orthodox church on grounds he is
ill and senile.
   The priest also has criticized the willingness of church leaders
to subordinate themselves to the government, demanding greater
freedom to practice religion and publication of more religious
books.
   Yakunin was excluded from the ministry for 20 years, but
reinstated last year and assigned to a small parish outside Moscow.
   Contacted by telephone Thursday night, Yakunin said Filaret's
comments were moderate.
   ``Earlier they (church leaders) would have taken our work away
and imprisoned us. It's a sign of perestroika that they are willing
to listen to us,'' Yakunin said, referring to Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's word for restructuring of society.
   Yakunin said he and Gainov are not seeking confrontation between
church and state but simply want to ``help the church improve its
situation.''
   ``We think church leaders are falling behind matters of
perestroika and want them to work more actively,'' he said.
   Filaret said the church has the right to discipline dissidents,
but ``we are urging them to use common sense and join with us to
solve the problems.''
   Archbishop Kiril of Smolensk said the government is rewriting
the 1929 law and consulting Russian Orthodox officials, but
described the consultations as a ``discussion of principle'' not
involving the text.
   Kiril said the law, adopted at the height of anti-religious
fervor after the 1917 Bolshevik revolution, was no longer
appropriate for Soviet society.
   He said the replacement statute should be ready soon, but the
text was not complete and he could not provide details. The
archbishop said church officials were optimistic that it ``will
open the possibility for a fuller church life for all believers.''
   A list was revealed of nine people who will be made saints
during celebrations in June of the 1,000th anniversary of
Christianity in what is now the Soviet Union.
   Metropolitan Yuvenali of Krutitsky and Kolomensky granted that
the list did not include anyone killed during the repression after
the revolution, as critics have demanded. He said study of the
issue would continue.
   Yuvenali accused the Russian Orthodox church that split away
after the revolution and now is based abroad of canonizing such
people for political purposes.
   Church officials said Patriarch Pimen participated in opening
and closing ceremonies and fulfilled his other obligations during a
three-day conference completed Thursday.
</TEXT>
