<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Germany-Crash 1stLd-Writethru   03-31 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0646,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fighter Jet Crashes, Explodes in Town Center; 2 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with identity of pilot;
picks up 4th graf pvs: Wreckage was ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORST, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Air Force jet fighter slammed
into the middle of this small town and exploded Thursday, killing
the American pilot and at least one resident, injuring 16 people
and forcing scores to evacuate.
   ``The neighborhood looks like the bombed-out houses of World War
II,'' said Herbert Loef, a 52-year-old baker who lives down the
street from where the F-16 crashed into at least five homes.
   In Washington, Air Force spokesman Capt. Virginia Cody
identified the pilot as Lt. Thomas Edward Doyle, 24, of Oroville,
Calif. He entered active duty in May 1985 and had been at Hahn Air
Base since September 1987. He graduated from the Air Force Academy
in 1985.
   Wreckage was scattered over a wide area, and several hours after
the flames had been doused, black smoke still billowed from Forst,
a town of 6,000 people.
   Emergency crews evacuated more than 70 residents because the
plane was carrying a canister of hydrazine, which is used to
restart engines and which produces toxic gas when mixed with water.
Officials said there was no evidence of a gas leak.
   The plane crashed eight miles from a nuclear power plant, one
day after a French jet fighter crashed and exploded just a mile
from a nuclear plant in the West German state of Bavaria. The pilot
in that accident also was killed.
   The crashes sparked calls from members of West Germany's
opposition Social Democrats and the environmentalist Greens party
for more restrictions on military training flights.
   Witnesses reported seeing smoke and flames pouring from the F-16
as it plunged toward Forst, about 60 miles south of Frankfurt. It
struck the roof of one house, tore off the front of another and set
several on fire, they said.
   Hilde Loef said her first thought when she saw the jet was, ``My
God, the planes are coming awfully low today.''
   ``Then I saw smoke and flames streaming out of the jet,'' she
said.
   The body of Theo Huber, 60, was found in the wreckage of his
home, officials said. Rescuers were searching for any other victims.
   Twelve firefighters were hospitalized for smoke inhalation, two
residents were treated for shock, and two more were being held for
observation in a hospital after apparently suffering smoke
inhalation, officials said.
   Authorities said the 10 a.m. disaster could have been far worse
had the plane crashed a couple of hours earlier, before residents
left for work.
   U.S. Air Force Maj. Gregory Smith told reporters at the scene
that an investigation into the cause of the crash was under way. He
said there was no live ammunition on the jet.
   The F-16 was part of the 50th Tactical Fighter Wing based at the
Hahn Air Base in the nearby Eifel Mountains, said Lt. Col. Edward
Neunherz, another Air Force spokesman.
   The crash occurred 185 miles west of Wednesday's crash of the
French jet fighter, which went down in the Bavarian village of Ohu
near the Isar nuclear plant.
   Environmentalists maintained the country had escaped disaster by
a ``split second,'' and the accident raised concerns about military
flights over nuclear power plants. But officials said the concrete
domes built over West German nuclear plants are designed to
withstand the force of a plane crash, so there was no danger of a
nuclear accident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
