<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0795 03-31 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0795,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Critical Of Democrats On Dismissal Of Charge Against
Mecham</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Senate refusing to reinstate third
charge. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After hours of backroom negotiations
Thursday, the Arizona Senate let stand its dismissal of the third
and strongest impeachment charge against Gov. Evan Mecham.
   The decision not to reinstate the charge cleared the way for
final arguments Monday on two other counts against the first-term
Republican. Senators could vote Monday or Tuesday on whether he
should be removed from office.
   ``Is there any other matter to be taken up?'' asked Arizona
Chief Justice Frank X. Gordon as the senators convened in the late
afternoon after a day of caucuses and private meetings. Gordon's
question was answered with silence.
   Gordon then wished the Senate luck in reading and understanding
a thick stack of legal instructions given to them as they left for
the weekend.
   Mecham 63, is the first U.S. governor in six decades to face an
impeachment trial.
   On Wednesday, the Senate decided 16-12 to dismiss a charge that
he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan and to vote to convict or
acquit on two other charges _ that he tried to obstruct an
investigation of an alleged death threat by a staff member and that
he misused $80,000 from a protocol fund.
   The campaign loan charge was considered the strongest of the
three because there is more extensive documentation of what
occurred and because it is the only one that also has led to a
criminal indictment against Mecham.
   In contrast, the obstruction charge boils down in part to which
of two people to believe, and the other in part to technical
definitions of whether the $80,000 was public or private money.
   Several senators, in voting for dismissal, had said they feared
they would prejudice Mecham's criminal trial April 21 if they took
evidence on the last charge.
   Alan Stephens, Democratic minority leader, said Thursday neither
he nor the 10 other Democrats who voted for dismissal were willing
to reconsider.
   One of those who voted on the prevailing side would have had to
seek reconsideration for the matter to be reopened.
   ``There was a lot of backroom manipulating today,'' said
Stephens. ``People apparently made their decisions on the merits of
the arguments and that didn't change in 24 hours.''
   Only five of the 19 Senate Republicans supported the dismissal
of the last charge. Senate rules gave members 24 hours to rescind
any action.
   Stephens said his main concern was not letting the trial drag on
past Mecham's scheduled May 17 recall election. But some
Republicans argued that they were duty-bound to hear all the
evidence on all the charges.
   Republican Tony West complained angrily that the Democrats had
divided the impeachment proceeding along partisan lines for the
first time since it began Feb. 29. ``That action yesterday was
political roulette,'' he said.
   ``If there are not the votes to convict, and Gov. Mecham is back
on the ninth floor (in the governor's office) on Wednesday ... they
have dealt themselves a losing hand,'' West said.
   It would require a two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate to
convict Mecham. If he is convict, the Senate may then take a vote
to disqualify him from ever holding office again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
