<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-31 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>March Leaves Like a Lion in Colorado</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   March went out like a lion in much of Colorado on Thursday,
unloading more than 3 feet of snow, but the weather was more like
the proverbial lamb in much of the East and South.
   In south-central Colorado, 42 inches of snow were reported near
Rye by afternoon. Near Fort Collins in the northern part of the
state, Buckhorn Mountain logged 34 inches before noon, while
Bellevue recorded 27 inches.
   As the slow-moving storm continued to dump snow on the region,
the weather service issued a winter storm warning for blowing and
drifting snow and poor driving conditions as slush on roadways
turned to ice at nightfall.
   At Denver's Stapleton International Airport, crowded with
holiday weekend travelers, spokesman Norm Avery warned that delays
of two hours or more could be expected. Snowfall at midafternoon at
the airport was 8 inches.
   A winter storm watch was posted for northwestern Kansas, where
rain was expected to change to snow overnight and heavy snow was
possible Friday.
   Advisories for snow and blowing snow were posted for
southeastern Wyoming and the southern Nebraska Panhandle. By
midday, the Snowy Range Ski Area near Laramie, Wyo., reported 22
inches of snow.
   During the morning, high winds were reported in Utah, where
gusts reached 80 mph at Centerville.
   Elsewhere, a wind advisory continued in the mountains and
deserts of Southern California and in northwestern Arizona. A
freeze warning was posted for Thursday night for higher elevations
in southeastern Arizona.
   Skies were sunny in New England, and in much of the nation west
of the Rockies, while temperatures reached the 70s and occasionally
the 80s from Texas to the southern Atlantic Coast and in Southern
California.
   Early afternoon readings were in the 30s and 40s in the upper
Mississippi Valley, though, and were below freezing in the northern
Rockies.
   Rain extended from the southern half of the Great Plains to the
lower Ohio Valley, with thunderstorms mainly along the central Gulf
Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 16
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 84 degrees at Avon Park,
Fla., and Fort Myers, Fla. The early-morning low for the nation was
8 degrees below zero at Yellowstone Park.
   Heavier snowfall for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 4 inches at Denver and 3 inches at Pueblo, Colo. Heavier
rainfall included 0.68 inch at New Orleans; 0.46 inch at Memphis,
Tenn., and 0.45 inch at Jonesboro, Ark.
   The forecast for Friday called for snow in the central high
Plains and the central Rockies; showers and thunderstorms in the
southern Plains, the lower Mississippi Valley and the Tennessee
Valley; rain showers from the central Plains across the lower Great
Lakes, Ohio Valley and mid-Atlantic states, and fair to partly
sunny skies will prevail across the rest of the nation.
   Highs only in the 30s and 40s were forecast from northern New
Mexico and Arizona to Nebraska, and in the upper Mississippi Valley
and the upper Great Lakes; in the 60s and 70s in much of Oregon and
western Nevada, and across much of the southern tier of states and
the mid-Atlantic Coast; up to the low 80s in California, the lower
Rio Grande Valley and Florida, and in the 50s in most of the rest
of the nation.
</TEXT>
