<HEAD>Former Conrail Engineer Indicted By Federal Grand Jury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to ADD that Gates was a Conrail
engineer and that crash was Amtrak's worst. PICK UP 3rd graf pvs,
`The indictment ...'; ADDS two grafs at end with prosecutor's
comment. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Conrail engineer sent to prison on
state charges in an Amtrak crash that killed 16 people was indicted
Thursday on federal charges including lying to investigators about
his drug use the day of the accident.
   Rick L. Gates, 33, of Essex, was charged with conspiracy,
obstruction of an agency investigation and making false statements,
said U.S. Attorney Breckinridge Willcox.
   The collision of the passenger train and three locomotives
operated by Gates was the worst accident in Amtrak history.
   The indictment alleges Gates lied under oath to National
Transportation Safety Board investigators after the Jan. 4, 1987,
crash near Chase, saying he had not consumed any drugs that day.
   Gates, however, shared a marijuana cigarette with brakeman
Edward Cromwell that day, according to the statement of facts read
into the record when he pleaded guilty in Baltimore County Circuit
Court on Feb. 17.
   The indictment also alleges Gates falsely testified about the
status of the signals he saw in the three Conrail locomotives and
along the tracks that day and about what pre-departure tests he
conducted.
   The conspiracy count alleges he joined with Cromwell to develop
a false story about what happened.
   Gates was the only person named in the indictment. If convicted,
Gates faces a maximum of five years in prison and a $250,000 fine
on each count.
   On Tuesday, Gates was sentenced to five years in prison and
fined $1,000 on a misdemeanor charge of manslaughter by locomotive.
   Sixteen people were killed and more than 170 others were injured
in the crash. Gates originally was charged with 16 counts, but
Gates agreed to a plea bargain, merging the names of all 16 victims
into a single count.
   Willcox said he had deferred any federal action against Gates
until the state prosecution had ended.
   ``Now that those charges have been resolved, it is appropriate
to vindicate the strong federal interest in ensuring that the
National Transportation Safety Board hearings are not obstructed by
those with the most direct and relevant information,'' the
prosecutor said.
</TEXT>
