<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ActivistSlain     03-31 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Activist Slain,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Backers Of Slain Activist Request Special Legislative Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for PEMBROKE, N.C.-dated story on AM-News Advisory.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of slain judicial candidate
Julian Pierce asked Gov. Jim Martin on Thursday to convene a
special legislative session to allow another minority candidate to
seek the post.
   Martin was noncommittal after the closed meeting in his office.
He said he would consult with Pierce's former opponent, party and
legislative leaders and others, and expected to reach a decision
next week.
   Pierce, 42, a Lumbee Indian attorney, was shot to death Saturday
at his rural home in racially troubled Robeson County, where he was
running for a newly created Superior Court judgeship.
   At first, authorities said the killing looked like a political
assassination. But Tuesday they arrested a young Indian man and
said a second suspect committed suicide, and attributed Pierce's
killing to a romantic dispute.
   Pierce and Robeson County District Attorney Joe Freeman Britt,
who is white, were slated to meet in the May 3 Democratic primary.
   Under law, if a candidate dies more than 30 days after filing
for a primary has closed, his opponent wins the nomination. In this
case, there is no Republican in the race, so Britt would also
automatically win the general election in November.
   Supporters of Pierce asked for a special session to amend the
law to let another candidate enter the race.
   The governor, who planned to meet with Britt on Friday, told
reporters: ``I'm going to do my best to try to get input that I
need and then take a brief time to think about it very prayfully
and come up with the best answer that I can.''
   The new Superior Court judgeship was created under a law
intended to help a non-white candidate get elected in a county
where blacks and Indians make up 58 percent of the registered
voters.
   Two months ago, the Robesonian newspaper office was seized for
several hours by two Lumbees who said they wanted to call attention
to racial injustice and official corruption.
   Harvey Godwin, who was manager of Pierce's campaign, said that
was pleased with the discussion with the governor and that Martin
``listened to every word. ... I was impressed with him.''
   Pierce supporters have decided on a replacement candidate,
Godwin said, but he declined to identify the person.
   Britt has not commented on the special session question.
   Earlier, Martin said there was no reason to doubt that Pierce's
slaying resulted from a romantic dispute. He chided those who
continue to suggest otherwise, saying some want to stir up more
racial strife in Robeson County.
   ``There are people who want to take advantage of the problems
... and they're going to make up all kinds of theories,'' Martin
said.
   Sheriff Hubert Stone said John Goins, 24, killed Pierce and
later took his own life. Goins blamed Pierce for disrupting Goins'
relationship with the daughter of a woman Pierce was dating,
according to Stone.
   The other suspect, Sandy Gordon Chavis, is described as a
longtime friend of Goins.
   Martin said that Goins had left suicide notes and that there was
solid evidence linking him to the slaying.
   Vernon Bellecourt, a representative of the American Indian
Movement, said Wednesday that Goins' personal feelings ``could have
been manipulated by those that would have motives to see that
Julian Pierce was out of the way.''
</TEXT>
