<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BikiniFuror 1stLd-Writethru a0851 03-31 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bikini Furor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0851,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fraternity-Backed Bikini Contest Canceled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with contest canceled. PICKS UP
7th graf pvs, `The Jimmy ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bikini contest planned for Thursday
night by a University of Massachusetts fraternity to raise money
for charity was canceled hours before it was to begin after women
students threatened to picket.
   Joe Giarusso, assistant general manager of the off-campus Pink
Cadillac bar where the contest was to have been held, said the
makers of Miller Lite beer withdrew as sponsors.
   ``There are no prizes and the event has been canceled,'' he
said. He refused further comment.
   Women had earlier vowed to picket the bar, and 34 students had
signed a petition denouncing the contest organized by Delta Upsilon
as sanctioning ``ogling and girl watching.''
   Robert O'Brien, chairman of the fund-raising committee of Delta
Upsilon, said the contest was canceled ``because of a small, vocal
minority. We did not back down. It is our legal right to have the
contest.''
   Sue Madden, a UMass graduate student and an organizer of the
protest, was making placards for the demonstration when she learned
the contest was off.
   ``We're all stunned,'' she said. ``We're pleased that Miller
Lite was sensitive to this issue to help us achieve our cause.''
   ``Often women are reduced to their body parts in this society
and we don't think men have a right to judge us for our bodies,''
protester Becky Lockwood said earlier. ``This is objectifying women
to make money off us.''
   Delta Upsilon fraternity brothers said they didn't understand
the furor.
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said fraternity president Paul Kearney.
``Why should they be upset if it's a fund-raiser? They do it
everywhere else.'' He added: ``If they go to the beach, are they
going to call that sexist too?''
   O'Brien had said proceeds of the contest would be used by the
fraternity, which has $10 in its account, for its yearly beer keg
roll, a charity event that benefits the Jimmy Fund.
   The Jimmy Fund, the official charity of the Boston Red Sox,
raises money to fight cancer in children. Last year Delta Upsilon
raised $3,000 for the Jimmy Fund rolling empty beer kegs from
Boston 100 miles west to Amherst.
   The fraternity circulated fliers last week saying the bikini
contest was being presented by ``Delta Upsilon & The Jimmy Fund in
association with the Amherst Police'' department, but the event is
not sponsored by the Jimmy Fund.
   Jimmy Fund associate director Michael Rafferty said he asked the
fraternity not to use its name for the event.
   Police Chief Donald Maia, who had accepted an invitation to
emcee the contest, changed his mind over the weekend, saying he had
thought the contest was a beauty pageant.
   ``It's gone beyond that now,'' he said. ``It would be
inappropriate for me to be there.''
   Roger Libby, a former UMass sex education professor who tours
campuses lecturing on safe sex, said he would replace Maia as emcee.
   Jimmy Fund planning director Mark Cummings said the organization
approves only those activities that turn over entire proceeds to
the fund. He added, ``It is in bad form and bad taste to use the
Jimmy Fund with this contest.''
</TEXT>
