<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Pulitzers-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0799 03-31 0905</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pulitzers-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0799,0929</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pulitzer Winners Blush, Dance, Bask in Praise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 8 grafs after 8th graf pvs, `The book...', to UPDATE
with comment from Knight-Ridder, cartoonist Doug Marlette, Miami
Herald; picking up 9th graf pvs, `At the...'. INSERTS 3 grafs after
15th graf pvs, `I think...', to add comment from Wall Street
Journal winners. Picks up 16th graf, `Scott Shaw...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Pulitzers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tim Weiner blushed happily and climbed on top of
a desk Thursday as his colleagues at The Philadelphia Inquirer
applauded after he captured the Pulitzer Prize for national
reporting.
   But Tom Shales of the Washington Post was in shock.
   ``I'm in a state of slack-jawed dumbfoundedness,'' said Shales,
the winner for criticism for his writing on television. ``I'm
shocked and delighted and very proud of the paper. It's an award
that really comes to the paper _ not to me; it's a nice feeling to
have brought it to the paper.''
   Reporters at the Inquirer, which claimed its 14th prize in 13
years, crowded around the newsroom and applauded when word of
Weiner's prize moved on The Associated Press wire.
   The recipient, who won for his series on a secret Pentagon
budget used to sponsor defense research and an arms buildup,
climbed onto a desk to say, ``I thank you very much.'' He then
puffed on a cigar.
   Weiner, 31, who came to the Inquirer in 1982 from the Kansas
City Times, said he feels like he just received a ``$10 million
check from Ed McMahon. I'm just a very happy guy and very lucky.''
   Toni Morrison, winner of the fiction award for ``Beloved,'' said
joy was uppermost in her feelings because ``I really was thinking
dark and difficult thoughts about what was available to this book
in terms of recognition.''
   The book became a center of controversy when it did not win two
other major literary prizes, and Morrison said she respected the
Pulitzer committee for ignoring ``outside matters of speculation
and gossip and some slander.''
   Knight-Ridder newspapers won six awards, including two each at
The Miami Herald and the Charlotte (N.C.) Observer and one each at
the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch and the Inquirer.
   Jim Batten, Knight-Ridder president, said the group has ``worked
hard over the years to attract some of the best people in the
American newspaper business and create a climate that encourages
people to do their best work.''
   Dave Barry, the 40-year-old Miami Herald humorist who won for
commentary, said he hopes winning the Pulitzer ``will make me
taller.''
   ``It's fun to win a Pulitzer; everybody should do it,'' Barry
said.
   His fellow Miami staff member, photographer Michel duCille,
garnered his second Pulitzer for photos of apartments inundated by
the drug crack.
   ``I don't want to lessen the Pulitzers, but I feel more proud
that the photos ... made changes in the community,'' duCille said.
   Cartoonist Doug Marlette, 37, who moved from The Charlotte
Observer to The Atlanta Constitution during the year, was honored
for work done at both papers.
   He said his biting approach can be traced in part to ``a
grandmother bayoneted by a guardsman during a mill strike in the
Carolinas. There are some rebellious genes floating around in me.''
   At the Alabama Journal in Montgomery, ``There was a lot of
dancing and yelling and singing when the announcement came over the
wire _ but that's not unusual for the Journal newsroom,'' quipped
Jim Tharpe, managing editor.
   The Journal and the Lawrence (Mass.) Eagle-Tribune each won an
award for general news reporting; the Alabama paper's series dealt
with infant mortality.
   ``The Journal decided it was time to commit some resources to
the problem,'' said Bill Brown, executive editor of the Journal and
its sister daily, The Montgomery Advertiser.
   ``A Pulitzer Prize is nice,'' said Tharpe, ``but it's a plaque
on the wall. If we hope something will come of our work as
journalists, it's that the state will deal with the problem of
infant mortality.''
   At the Chicago Tribune, the winners were Dean Baquet, William
Gaines and Ann Marie Lipinski for investigative reporting on ``on
the self-interest and waste that plague Chicago's City Council.''
   ``We're thrilled. It's been quite a few years since we've won
one here for local news coverage,'' said Ellen Soeteber, assistant
Tribune managing editor for metropolitan news.
   ``I think the team of reporters deserved this so much. ... It
was their idea, and they brought it off beautifully,'' she said.
``I'm so glad some of the leaders in our profession recognized it.''
   The Wall Street Journal captured two prizes: Walt Bogdanich for
specialized reporting and Daniel Hertzberg and James B. Stewart for
explanatory journalism.
   ``I know many great people who have only been recognized after
they died, but all else being equal, it's wonderful to get
recognition,'' said Stewart, 36.
   ``If I can win the Pulitzer Prize, the Cleveland Indians can win
the pennant this summer,'' said Bogdanich.
   Scott Shaw, a photographer for the Odessa (Texas) American, said
he had not been expecting to win the spot news award for his
coverage of the 58-hour operation that rescued little Jessica
McClure and fascinated a nation.
   ``I am pretty young. I am just pretty surprised,'' said Shaw,
24. ``Ever since I took the photo that night, the editors said I
was going to win. They were sure of it that night. And so it
happened.''
</TEXT>
