<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham-Analysis 2ndLd-Writethru a0874 03-31 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Analysis, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0874,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impeachment Vote Nears but Senators Won't Predict Outcome</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9 pvs, `Attorneys had ...' with two grafs to
UPDATE with Senate refusing to reinstate third charge.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arizona Senate on Thursday appeared to
be just days away from the moment of truth in Gov. Evan Mecham's
impeachment trial after dismissing the third and most serious
charge against him.
   Senators declined to predict the outcome of next week's vote on
the two remaining charges. A two-thirds majority of the 30-member
Senate would be needed to remove the first-term Republican from
office.
   ``I'm prepared to vote,'' Republican Sen. Carol Macdonald said
one day after testimony was completed on the second impeachment
count. Like other senators, she declined to say what she had
decided.
   Many senators said they will wait until Monday's closing
arguments by prosecution and defense lawyers before deciding
whether to remove Mecham from office.
   The vote is likely to be taken Monday or Tuesday on impeachment
charges that Mecham tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged
death threat by a state official and that he misused $80,000 from
the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership.
   But before the vote could be taken, senators had to resolve a
last-minute political imbroglio Thursday over the dismissal of the
third charge, that Mecham concealed a $350,000 campaign loan.
   Wednesday's surprise vote to dismiss that article and vote on
the first two led to charges and counter-charges by Republicans and
Democrats that each side was playing politics.
   After a day of backroom negotiations Thursday, the Senate
decided against reinstating the third charge. Wednesday's action
was approved by all 11 Democrats but only five of the Senate's 19
Republicans.
   Attorneys had indicated Wednesday it would take at least five
weeks to present the case on the third charge.
   Republican Sen. Greg Lunn, who opposed throwing out the article,
said the dismissal was a ``serious error'' and added, ``Frankly,
I'm resentful, at this late stage in these proceedings, that we're
cutting deals as if this were an amendment to another piece of
legislation in order to get us out before adjournment.''
   Senate Republican Majority Leader Robert Usdane was more
philosophical, saying, ``It's a political trial. It's just a matter
of the way we work.''
   Mecham wanted the $350,000 loan count dismissed on grounds that
having it tried first in the Senate would taint his April 21
criminal trial on similar charges.
   The 16-12 vote to grant the governor's wish resulted from a
combination of Mecham's five staunchest GOP backers _ who want all
the charges dismissed _ and all 11 Democrats, who have been trying
for weeks to force the Senate to vote on each impeachment article
as evidence is completed.
   The Democrats contended their strategy was aimed at ensuring a
Senate vote on whether to remove Mecham from office well before he
is to face a May 17 recall election.
   Minority Leader Alan Stephens, a Democrat, said Republicans
possibly ``saw the potential for some to take advantage of this ...
and create a situation where they would never, never have to cast a
vote on this'' because Mecham could be removed from office by the
recall before the Senate got a chance to vote.
   Because the Senate can make its own rules, lawmakers will not
have to reach their conclusions ``beyond a reasonable doubt,'' as
in a criminal trial. Instead, they are to decide if there is
``clear and convincing evidence'' to convict Mecham, and it's up to
each of them to decide what that means.
   Also, GOP Sen. Bill DeLong noted, the governor does not have to
be guilty of a crime to be convicted in an impeachment trial;
Mecham can be removed for malfeasance in office.
   ``There's more than just the guilt or innocence on the
charges,'' DeLong said, adding that he expected senators to be told
by the presiding officer that they must ``take action which is in
the best interest of Arizona ... based on (Mecham's) ability to
continue in office.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Laurie Asseo is covering her fourth Arizona
legislative session for the AP.
</TEXT>
