<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0773 03-31 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0773,0881</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riots Ordered for Shultz Visit; Shamir Vows to Crush Rebellion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with three-day closure lifted;
picks up 4th graf pvs, ``Issuance of ...</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HERODION, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Palestinian
rebellion called Thursday for riots during the visit of Secretary
of State George P. Shultz next week, and Israel's prime minister
vowed to crush the uprising.
   Soldiers shot one Palestinian dead, bringing the Arab death toll
to at least 124 since violence began Dec. 8 in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip, where 1.5 million Palestinians live. An
Israeli soldier also has been killed.
   Israeli officials lifted a three-day closure of the West Bank as
scheduled at 3 a.m. Friday (8 p.m. EST Thursday), allowing
residents to travel out of their towns and villages. A curfew that
confined people in the Gaza Strip to their homes was also ended at
that time.
   Five-hour nightly curfews imposed before the shutdown were
scheduled to continue in Gaza. The end of the three-day confinement
meant that journalists could travel freely in the territories.
   Issuance of Leaflet No. 12 from leaders of the rebellion
indicated Israel had not removed its leadership despite mass
arrests last week of more than 1,000 people, including those Israel
said were responsible for publishing the leaflets.
   Arabs known to be involved have said that, if the Israelis
caught some of them, other people would be ready to take their
places.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told hundreds of cheering Jewish
settlers Israel would crush the rebellion in the lands it has
controlled since capturing them from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967
Middle East war.
   ``Some Arabs are going crazy down there. They are trying to harm
what we have built,'' Shamir said at Herodion, site of the biblical
King Herod's palace.
   ``They say ... this land belongs to the rioters, the killers,
the terrorists. But if somebody tries to harm this ... we will
break his hand on these rocks.''
   Authorities put new restrictions on the 130,000 Arabs of east
Jerusalem but Greek Orthodox Christians, fearing for their safety,
decided nonetheless to cancel pre-Easter processions.
   Soldiers allowed the 650,000 Palestinians in the Gaza Strip to
leave their homes for the first time in three days when the army
lifted a curfew for five hours.
   Street clashes between young Arabs and soldiers soon began in
Khan Yunis, Rafah and the Jabaliya refugee camp, and the army
restored the curfew at Jabaliya, Israel radio said.
   One Palestinian was wounded in Rafah, the radio said. Shifa
Hospital officials said another Arab from Khan Yunis was shot in
the neck and Israel television said a Palestinian was wounded in
the West Bank city of Tulkarm.
   In the West Bank city of Yatta, soldiers shot an 18-year-old
Palestinian dead during several hours of clashes with protesters
hurling rocks and bottles, the army said.
   Mayor Ismael Abu Hemaid said Suleiman Ahmed al Jundi died of a
stomach wound.
   The latest leaflet, signed by the Palestine Liberation
Organization, urged ``all the Arab world to block Shultz' plan and
to stop him from killing the uprising.''
   It ordered riots Monday through Wednesday of next week to
protest the Shultz visit and a proposed U.S. peace plan. The
secretary of state is to begin a shuttle through the region Sunday.
   ``We are telling the Arab world, we don't need money. We are
ready to starve. We will never kneel. We are going to die as
martyrs,'' the leaflet said.
   Shamir's equally tough declaration at Herodion: ``We will
continue to act against the violence until we stamp it out.''
   Military jeeps escorted Shamir's car and a busload of
journalists through an army roadblock sealing off the West Bank.
Reporters saw six Palestinian flags, which are outlawed, hanging
from power lines.
   Patriarch Diodorus of Jerusalem canceled three pre-Easter
processions of the Greek Orthodox church because of the violence,
said the Rev. Thimoteus Margaritis, church spokesman.
   He said it was the first cancellation since the 1967 war.
Margaritis said only 1,500 pilgrims were expected for the Orthodox
Easter on April 10, compared with 10,000 last year.
   Tourism to Israel declined 13 percent in the first week of March
compared with the same period of 1987, a Tourism Ministry
spokeswoman said.
   Benjamin Netanyahu announced his resignation as Israel's U.N.
ambassador to protest a meeting between Shultz and two
Arab-Americans linked to the PLO.
   It was the strongest indication yet of Israeli displeasure over
the meeting last Saturday with the members of the Palestine
National Council, which acts as the PLO legislature.
   In remarks broadcast on Israel radio, Shultz said it was
``beyond the pale'' to suggest he could not meet with American
citizens.
   The Interior Ministry imposed new travel restrictions on Arabs
in east Jerusalem, requiring Palestinians aged 16-35 to have
special permits for trips to Jordan, ministry spokeswoman Tova
Elinson said. She said permits would be issued only for stays of
nine months or longer.
   Israel radio said the limitations were designed to stop the PLO
from sending couriers into the occupied territories.
</TEXT>
