<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 2325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-US-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0774 03-31 0882</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0774,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Seeking Agreement From Soviets on Continued Aid to Combatants</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New thruout with Shultz saying Soviets could keep arming
Kabul if US could keep supplying rebels.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANNON, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said
Thursday the Soviet Union could keep arming Marxist forces in
Afghanistan as part of a peace agreement, provided the United
States could maintain supplies to the rebels.
   ``It would be better to have a moratorium,'' Shultz said as he
launched another overseas trip to pursue peace in the Middle East.
   But, he told reporters aboard a U.S. Air Force jet en route to
Rome, ``To date, the Soviets have not wanted to do that.''
   The issue of U.S. and Soviet military aid to rival forces is the
main roadblock to an agreement to end the war in Afghanistan after
more than eight years.
   Shultz proposed in March to Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze that both sides declare a moratorium. It would be in
effect while the Soviets withdrew their estimated 120,000 trroops
and for three months afterward.
   The Soviets accused the United States of posing a last-minute
obstacle to an agreement. Negotiations between Afghanistan and
Pakistan, which were held under U.N. auspices, stalled.
   Shultz, who will go on to Jerusalem on Sunday to begin a
five-day Mideast shuttle, made it clear he preferred a suspension
of Soviet aid to the Marxists and U.S. support for the resistance
group. U.S. aid has included Stinger missiles that were effective
against Soviet aircraft and helicopters.
   But Shultz said the overall goal was ``a balanced outcome.'' He
said there was nothing in the Geneva accords on Afghanistan ``that
tells us we cannot support our friends.''
   He said, ``If the Soviets exercise restraint, we are prepared to
exercise restraint.''
   Shultz said he did not know whether the Soviets would go along
with providing equal levels of aid to the two sides.
   But he stressed the United States was prepared to guarantee a
settlement even while aid kept flowing to the combatants.
   ``If we have signed the accords and see a need to support our
friends, we will be able to do it,'' he said.
   Shultz said he discussed the idea on the telephone Wednesday
with Pakistani Prime Minister Mohammad Kahn Junejo and that
President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq then called President Reagan.
   ``So these things are in place,'' Shnultz said. ``Where we will
all come out remains to be seen.''
   U.S. officials in Washington said earlier that the Reagan
administration was seeking Moscow's approval for continued outside
aid to the Afghan combatants after Soviet troops are withdrawn.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said there has been no
indication of approval from the Soviets. Other officials sought to
dispel the notion that the Soviets had even indicated a willingness
to consider the proposal.
   The United States, the Soviet Union, their clients in
Afghanistan and the government of neighboring Pakistan, have been
involved for months in U.N.-sponsored efforts to bring about a
withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops fighting in
Afghanistan.
   The Soviets have agreed in principle to begin the troop
withdrawal two months after a settlement is reached and Pakistan is
eager for such a deal so that millions of Afghan refugees on
Pakistani territory can go home.
   Preventing a final agreement, however, has been a U.S. demand
that the Kremlin stop aiding the Afghan government after Soviet
troops depart. Until such aid ceases, the United States will
continue backing the Afghan rebels, Reagan has said.
   During talks with Shevardnadze in Washington last month, Shultz
renewed a plea for what the United States has been calling a
``symmetrical cessation'' of superpower aid to the Afghan
combatants.
   The new proposal, rather than calling for symmetrical cessation
of aid, envisions parallel continuation of assistance.
   ``We now express the policy in terms of `we will continue aid to
the Mujahadeen as long as the Soviet Union continues aid to the
Kabul government,''' Fitzwater said.
   ``The basic point to make is that our policy has not changed in
the sense that we will not desert the Afghan rebels,'' the
spokesman said. ``We will not cut off money to them as long as the
Soviets are providing aid.''
   Fitzwater did not explain how the new U.S. language might be
more palatable to the Soviets except to say ``there are some
negotiating reasons why it could hopefully allow the agreement to
be signed in Geneva and clear the way for a pullout.''
   A State Department official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said ``it would go too far,'' to say Shevardnadze signaled an
interest in the proposal last week, although he did not
specifically reject the idea.
   The source said that before the U.S. proposal was devised, some
administration officials warned against making an agreement to
continue aid to the Afghan combatants part of a secret
understanding with the Soviets.
   It would be against U.S. law to sign an Afghan peace accord that
required a cutoff of aid to the resistance forces while agreeing
privately with the Soviets to continue such assistance, the
official said.
   Asked on Thursday if a decision to continue aid would be part of
an open agreement, State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman
said ``that's always been our stance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
