<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 2330EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ethiopia-Mengistu     03-31 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Mengistu,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Troops Fighting ``Grim Battles'' With Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mengistu Haile Mariam, in
a rare mention of northern Ethopian insurgents, said Thursday his
troops are fighting ``grim battles'' against secessionist rebels,
Radio Ethiopia reported.
   It was the first government comment on reports of a new rebel
offensive, which resulted in the capture last week of a strategic
town and three Soviet officers advising the Ethiopian army.
   The rebel Tigray People's Liberation Front claimed Thursday it
had also captured Axum and Adowa, two historic towns in northern
Ethiopia.
   Assesa Mamo, North American representative of the Tigray
People's Liberation Front, said rebels took the towns Thursday
after a three-day battle.
   Mamo spoke from Washington in a telephone interview with The
Associated Press bureau in Nairobi, Kenya.
   State-owned Radio Ethiopia quoted Mengistu as saying rebels in
Tigray and neighboring Eritrea had launched a ``systematic and
highly destructive campaign,'' disrupting transport and
communications networks in their regions.
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Mengistu's statement indicated the fighting must be serious. They
said there were reports the Ethiopian leader is preparing a huge
counteroffensive against rebels of the Eritrea People's Liberation
Front and the Tigray rebel group.
   It is believed to be the first time Mengistu has conceded
publicly that the rebels, whom the government normally calls
``bandits,'' are in any way effective.
   Mengistu inherited the insurgencies 13 years ago when, with a
group of army officers, he dethroned Emperor Haile Selassie and
helped set up a Marxist government.
   Mengistu made the comments about the rebels in a report to the
eighth regular meeting of the Central Committee of his Marxist
Workers' Party of Ethiopia.
   He appealed to Ethiopians to ``rise in unity in the face of this
new challenge,'' according to Radio Ethiopia.
   The radio gave no further details of Mengistu's speech and it
was not clear whether his comments concerned the rebels' claims on
Axum and Adowa.
   Axum is 110 miles south of Asmara, Eritrea's provincial capital,
and Adowa is 30 miles from Axum.
   Eritrean rebels said Sunday they captured the town of Afabet,
killing or capturing 18,000 Ethiopian troops. The rebels said one
Soviet officer was killed and three taken prisoner. Afabet is 100
miles north of Asmara.
   The rebels claimed to have wiped out three government divisions
and captured tanks, weapons and other military equipment worth
millions of dollars.
   There was no way to verify the rebels' claims. But Western
diplomats in Addis Ababa said the figure of 18,000 troops, a third
of troops stationed in the north, sounded preposterous.
   The Soviet Union confirmed three of its advisers were captured,
but said nothing of a fourth officer being killed.
   Eritrean rebels have been fighting for 27 years in Africa's
oldest civil war.
   Rebels in Tigray claimed they captured three towns and more than
3,500 government soldiers in March. There is no way to confirm
independently such rebel reports, on which the government refuses
to comment.
   The fighting has aggravated relief efforts in the north, the
worst-hit drought region of Ethiopia. Most of the 6 to 7 million
Ethiopians threatened with starvation this year live in the north.
   Because of rebel activities, the government often closes roads
in the region, cutting off truck convoys.
   The U.N. World Food Program reported Thursday that a relief
convoy reached the town of Wukro in Tigray province, bringing the
first major food delivery to the drought-stricken area since
January.
   The emergency shipment of 1,500 metric tons, enough to feed
100,000 people for a month, arrived Sunday, said David Morton, the
U.N. representative in Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
