<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0748EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Oscars-Actor Adv05   03-31 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Oscars-Actor, Adv 05,0912</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, April 5 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>OSCAR COUNTDOWN: Best Actor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Comedy Makes a Rare Appearance Among Best Actor Nominees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedy makes a rare appearance in this year's
Academy Awards, with stand-up comic Robin Williams vying with four
dramatic performers for the prize as best actor.
   Some critics of Oscar's seriousness argue that Steve Martin
should have been nominated for best actor because of his modern-day
Cyrano in ``Roxanne.'' But in a year that saw a number of
impressive performances by comedians, only Williams drew the nod
for his manic disc jockey in ``Good Morning, Vietnam.''
   Williams plays Adrian Cronauer, the real-life announcer who
regaled American troops with jokes and rock 'n' roll over the army
radio service. The funny side of the role was a breeze for
Williams, and director Barry Levinson allowed him free rein.
   ``Obviously, the radio part offered me a chance to do some
open-field running,'' Williams says. ``Barry had been a comic
himself, and he would spark to some of my suggestions and let me go
with them. Many of the things in the movie, like the James Brown
impression and playing records at different speeds, happened
spontaneously.''
   Williams' depth of feeling in the later, dramatic scenes of
``Good Morning, Vietnam'' surprised some reviewers. Williams
studied drama under John Houseman at the famed Juilliard School in
New York, but even then his comedic side was emerging. One of his
teachers chided him: ``You're mimicking people. Where is YOUR
voice?'' He soon found it. After a broken romance, Williams dropped
out of Juilliard and began playing West Coast comedy clubs.
   The comic's contenders in the best actor race are thought of as
being more dramatic thespians.
   Michael Douglas was considered for two powerful roles: as the
venomous inside trader of ``Wall Street'' and the erring husband of
``Fatal Attraction.'' The actors branch of the Academy decided to
nominate him for ``Wall Street.''
   ``It was a marvelous role that Oliver Stone wrote,'' Douglas
says. ``I don't know why he chose me for the part, but he must have
seen something in me that even I didn't even know about.
   ``Playing a heavy is just fantastic; it's so much more fun than
being the good guy. I can understand the attraction that (villains)
have for actors.
   ``All of us try to be civilized human beings, but deep down
inside we have this feeling to tell everything like it is. The part
of Gordon Gecco was a wonderful opportunity for this release. After
playing moral redeeeming characters and goodie guys, it was a
ball.''
   Can an actor win an Oscar for a performance in a foreign
language? Sophia Loren did it in 1961 with ``Two Women.'' Now
Marcello Mastroianni stands a chance for his role as the vain
Italian aristocrat who pursues a new love to Russia in ``Dark
Eyes.''
   Mastroianni has acted in 116 films, and he still averages three
a year. Why does he work so hard at 64?
   ``Basically, I am an empty person,'' he said. ``When I act I
feel complete because I use the personalities of these characters
to fill this emptiness. I am also a childish person, and what
better way to live life than by traveling to all these countries
and getting paid to have fun and act like a fool, no?''
   What William Hurt feels about acting is not publicly known,
since he is one of the least interviewed of film stars. Obviously,
he is doing something right, since he has been nominated three
times in seven films and won the Oscar for ``Kiss of the Spider
Woman'' two years ago.
   His latest nomination came for his portrayal of Tom Grunick, the
handsome but not-too-bright network anchor man in ``Broadcast
News.'' Hurt's few interviews have produced somewhat turgid quotes.
As he himself explains: ``I have, fortunately or unforunately,
skill at going down paths of endless non sequiturs.
   In a recent Premiere magazine interview, Hurt expounded on what
he considered the major question of ``Broadcast News.''
   ``What is the nature, to put it simply, of romance in our time?
What are our motives in wanting to be together? How do we pair up?
Who do we mate with, and why do we do it? A lot of us don't know
the answer, a lot of us feel in flux,'' he said.
   Jack Nicholson has also been recently scarce in the media,
apparently content to do his work without theorizing about it in
public. In 1987, he shone in three roles: as the devil in ``The
Witches of Eastwick''; as the Depression bum in ``Ironweed''; as
star network anchor in ``Broadcast News.'' He won his ninth
nomination for his role as the former big-league ballplayer in
``Ironweed.''
   Despite the cynical roles he has played, Nicholson has
maintained that he remains an optimist. In a 1986 interview he
remarked:
   ``I don't want to do what I accuse other people of doing: not
taking the time to smell the roses. Something very wonderful has
happened to me. I don't want the fact that I see this endless din
and gloom in the world to make me incapable of expressing something
that's quite frankly wonderful. I'm a very fortunate person to be
where I am and do what I do.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Oscars-SupportingActress Adv07   03-31 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Oscars-Supporting Actress, Adv 07,0830</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs, April 7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>OSCAR COUNTDOWN: Supporting Actress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Supporting Actress Category Highlighted By Screen Veterans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anne Ramsey found out that she had been
nominated for an Academy Award as supporting actress when a friend
called her at 5 a.m.
   ``Within 15 minutes a television crew was at the house,'' she
said. ``I had time to wash my face, and that was about all. I was
absolutely flabbergasted.''
   The nomination of Ramsey, Danny DeVito's horrendous mother in
``Throw Momma From the Train,'' provided one of the highlights of a
race that includes a 60-year veteran of films, the cousin of a
presidential candidate, a classic Argentine actress and a young
actress who stood her own against a galvanizing performance by
Glenn Close.
   Here is a look at the nominees:
   Norma Aleandro played the Mexican Indian who devoted her life to
be the constant companion of a severely handicapped girl in
``Gaby.'' A distinguished theater actress in Buenos Aires, she was
forced into exile by the military government of Argentina. After
the junta was overthrown, she returned home to star in the
Oscar-winning ``The Official Story,'' which dealt with the
atrocities of the regime.
   ``Gaby'' was Miss Aleandro's first film in English. She regrets
that the movie has found a limited audience, apparently because
people were scared away by its theme.
   ``It's not a sad movie,'' she says. ``We are not speaking about
sadness. We are speaking about people, about seeking freedom.
Sometimes people forget that freedom is in the mind.''
   Anne Archer was nominated for the part of Michael Douglas' wife
in ``Fatal Attraction.'' Considering the galvanic role afforded
Glenn Close as the vengeful other woman, you might think that
Archer would have had reservations about her role.
   ``Not at all,'' she says. ``I always thought that (the wife) was
a strong and interesting character, and she got to go through an
interesting change. That is something you always look for: It's
important that a character be different at the end of a script than
in the beginning.
   ``She was sexy and vulnerable and strong. An interesting lady. I
never felt even remotely that she would be overshadowed.''
   Ann Sothern made her first movie in 1929, according to the
record books. After a long and diverse career in films and
television, mostly in comedy, she won her first Academy recognition
for a serious role in ``The Whales of August.''
   Along with co-stars Bette Davis, Lillian Gish and Vincent Price,
Sothern filmed ``The Whales of August'' on a remote Maine island.
   ``There was no hotel, only a tiny store,'' she recalls. ``We all
stayed in private homes; mine was a lobster fisherman's. The
weather was murder: beautiful and sunny in the morning, and stormy
in the afternoon.
   ``There was absolutely nothing to do at night. Fortunately, I
brought my cook and my poker chips.''
   Olympia Dukakis has long been a working actress in theater,
films and television, but she didn't impress a national audience
until ``Moonstruck.'' Her success came at the same time her first
cousin, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, sought the Democratic
nomination for president.
   She grew up in a Greek family in which everybody argued
politics. After graduating from Boston University, she worked as a
physical therapist to earn enough money to return and study theater
arts.
   Despite her newfound fame, she intends to remain in the theater;
she is the artistic director of the Whole Theater in Montclair, N.J.
   ``I'm not convinced this being a celebrity is going to be
long-lived,'' she says cautiously.
   Fame was also a long time coming for Ramsey: ``Thirty-nine years
later, after everything I've tried to do and everything I've
wanted, this has happened. What a curious moment. Thank God, thank
Danny (DeVito, who directed `Momma'), thank everybody.''
   Ramsey has more to be thankful for than an Academy nomination. A
year and a half ago, she underwent surgery for cancer of the
tongue. She apparently has recovered, but reconstruction of her
tongue gave her slurred speech. Happily, it fit perfectly into the
character of the fierce Momma.
   The actress admits that she dreamed of an Oscar as a child
growing up in suburban New York.
   ``I have a diary in which I wrote about it,'' she said. ``I was
a real movie buff when I was a little girl. I read all the fan
magazines, and I wrote for autographs and pictures from the stars.
I wanted to be an actress from the time my father took me to see
`The Petrified Forest' at the age of 4.
   ``I fell in love with actors, especially in the romantic films _
Tyrone Power, Errol Flynn, Greer Garson, Walter Pidgeon. I just
loved movies. And now this (nomination) has happened. It's
unbelievable.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
