<DOCNO> AP880331-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0839EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-MysteryofOradour Adv08   03-31 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mystery of Oradour, Adv 08,0848</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs April 8 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Book Revives Mystery of Nazi Massacre in France</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ORADOUR-SUR-GLANE, France (AP) _ Just after lunch on the warm
afternoon of June 10, 1944, the Nazi SS began rounding up people in
this prosperous country town and dividing them into groups. Then
they tortured, shot and burned them.
   Historians have long pondered the reasons for the slaughter of
642 children, women and men and the destruction of
Oradour-sur-Glane, carried out four days after the Allied invasion
of Normandy in a village with no history of ties to the French
Resistance.
   A new book by a British businessman, Robin Mackness, claims to
solve the mystery, suggesting that the massacre was a desperate
attempt by the Nazis to find a lost fortune in gold.
   Survivors of the massacre and the families of those who died
have vowed to stop publication in France of ``Oradour, Massacre and
Aftermath,'' already No. 5 on the British bestseller list and
scheduled for publication by Random House in the United States this
fall. They claim the book warps history and insults the memory of
Oradour's ``martyrs.''
   Robert Hebras, 62, who says he hid under the bodies of his
neighbors to escape Nazi bullets, put it more bluntly.
   ``Everyone makes money from the name of Oradour-sur-Glane. This
must cease.''
   Oradour has been preserved _ in ruins _ exactly as it was the
day the Germans marched off after the slaughter. In 1945 the French
government declared the centuries-old village near Limoges a
national historic site and it has been visited by more than 500,000
people each year.
   Plaques mark the sheds, cellars and barns where men were shot in
the knees, interrogated, then machine gunned and their bodies
burned.
   A cross stands outside the church where women and children
huddled in terror for hours listening to gunfire kill their menfolk
before the SS came to gun them down and set the sanctuary ablaze.
   A piece of twisted metal in the corner of the altar was once a
baby carriage. A car on the village green rusts where it was parked
by the mayor's son.
   Only 13 people survived.
   ``My wife lost all her family, her mother, sister, uncle,
aunt,'' said Rene Montaigne, a spokesman for the survivors'
association. ``She still goes to the ruins because she feels at
home there. She sees them all, even though they are dead.''
   The new Oradour-sur-Glane, built adjacent to the ruins, has
taken decades to recover.
   ``No one got married here for 20 years and it was only a couple
of years ago that we had a wedding in June,'' said Dr. Robert
Lapuelle, mayor of the town since 1959. ``It was 1963 before we had
enough youngsters to make a soccer team.
   ``No wonder people here are upset about this book.''
   Mackness' story is full of intrigue and personal adventure
involving smuggled gold ingots and a shadowy figure named Raoul.
   Mackness writes that Raoul told him that the ingots were a part
of more than half a ton of gold that he and a few French Resistance
companions seized during a midnight ambush of an SS convoy.
   According to the book, the only survivors of the ambush were
Raoul, who buried the treasure by the side of the road, and a
German soldier who reported the event.
   The gold apparently was a sort of floating pension fund for some
officers of the 2nd SS Panzer Division, planning to stash it in
Swiss banks for after the war, Mackness writes.
   It goes on to say that following the ambush, SS Maj. Otto
Dickmann rushed to the scene and, finding nothing and panicking,
dashed to Oradour, the nearest village.
   About 10 books have offered different explanations for the
slaughter. But all have left questions dangling.
   Mackness claims to answer many of these, but he seems to be
having trouble getting anyone to accept his story because his
sources are concealed.
   Dickmann and Raoul are dead. Mackness refuses to divulge the
names of his living sources, many of whom, he says, fear
prosecution for the massacre.
   For many historians, Mackness' word isn't enough.
   ``No historic fact allows me to give this business the least
credibility,'' Jacques Delarue, a French historian, was quoted by
the French newspaper Le Figaro as saying.
   But Mackness stands by his story.
   ``It fits the known historical facts,'' he said in a telephone
interview from London.
   ``The people in France who object to my book haven't read it
because it hasn't been, and may not be, published there.''
   In Oradour, Mackness is accused of dancing on the graves of the
dead.
   ``Mr. Mackness' ambush never happened, at least not near
Oradour,'' said Mayor Lapuelle, who added that the villagers want
to preserve the simple, brutal truth of the event, so ``this will
never happen again.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs April 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
