<DOCNO> AP880331-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1334EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-AIDS-Retarded Adv06   03-31 1192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Retarded, Adv 06,1227</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, April 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Film Teaches Safe Sex to Retarded Adults</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retarded men and women around the nation are
being shown an explicit videotape about sex in hopes it will help
keep them safe from AIDS.
   The video uses startling illustrations _ including still
photographs of surrogates in specific sexual positions.
   ``You can't generalize or use words. They don't know what you're
talking about,'' explained Alice Rose, program director of the
Cerebral Palsy Association of San Francisco, which will present the
video at 12 group homes.
   ``Their ability to abstract information is impaired,'' added
Rebecca Porper, a public health educator from the New York City
Department of Health who appears in the film. ``You have to deal
absolutely in black and white, with no grays, and it has to be
reiterated in several ways, preferably multi-sensory.''
   The Young Adult Institute, the non-profit agency that created
the 17-minute video, with help from the city health department,
acknowledges the idea offends some people.
   ``Someone called from Iowa and said, `How dare you put
homosexuals on the tape?''' said Perry Samowitz, the institute's
training director. ``We don't want to come across as crazy liberals
from New York who are promoting promiscuity. But what are the
alternatives? We don't want our clients to die _ no matter who
gives us flak.''
   The main goal is ``to make sure a condom is worn'' if a retarded
adult decides to have sex, Samowitz said.
   For Tina Mills, who has Down's syndrome and lives with 14 other
mildly retarded people in their 20s and 30s at a suburban Yonkers
apartment building, talking about AIDS is scary. But after she saw
the video, she said, ``I tried to urge that (condom use) to a
friend at the workshop.''
   ``There are times I don't really want to talk about it or think
about it,'' agreed fellow resident Dan Sigman. ``It's kind of
painful, but it's better to learn all about it. AIDS kills.''
   No statistics indicate how many AIDS victims are retarded,
according to Chuck Fallis, spokesman for the federal Centers for
Disease Control. Ms. Porper said she knew of eight AIDS cases among
the retarded in the metropolitan area, and a retarded New Yorker
died last year of AIDS contracted through a blood transfusion,
according to Lou Ganim, a spokesman for the state Office of Mental
Health and Developmental Disabilities.
   The risk of AIDS is no less real for the retarded. And so the
film is explicit.
   In one photograph, male surrogates are positioned as if they
were about to engage in anal sex so viewers can understand the link
between that practice and AIDS. Oral sex and the use of condoms in
heterosexual intercourse are also illustrated.
   ``I'm sure we'll get one or two people who will go bananas about
it,'' said Ms. Rose. ``A small proportion of people do not believe
that their children, whether adults or not, have a right to be
active or have knowledge of sexual activity.''
   ``I don't dare bring it up with my parents,'' said Abbie Colpoys
of the Yonkers group home.
   ``My parents talk a lot about that kind of thing. They warn me
about what could happen to me,'' said Ms. Mills. ``I say, `Ma,
please _ I can take care of myself. I care about myself.'''
   Teachers stress in group discussions that the film is not
intended to advocate any act, and that abstinence is acceptable.
Role-playing is included to help participants refuse unsafe sex.
   ``It teaches them how to be sensitive and relate to people in a
caring, responsible way,'' said Joel M. Levy, executive director of
the YAI, which runs 50 programs for the retarded in the New York
area, including 24 group homes.
   Group home residents also practice putting condoms on a plastic
penis and are told to use condoms themselves, even when it's not
clear where a romantic moment will lead.
   ``The mildly and moderately retarded know their judgment is
impaired,'' said Ms. Porper. ``If you give them a choice they are
incapable of making _ like when to put on a condom _ it raises
tremendous anxieties in them.''
   Some professionals have qualms about the film's approach.
   ``I think the general feeling of our staff is that it was too
negative, too scary,'' said Cathy Berger, prevention specialist
with the Wisconsin Council on Developmental Disabilities. YAI sent
the tape to 150 agencies, and the Wisconsin council was among five
that returned it, said Samowitz.
   ``They (the filmmakers) see this as a very serious issue and
their intent is to make people aware of it by scaring them. We're
concerned about that approach,'' said Ms. Berger.
   It also concerns Yonkers group home resident Sandy Mintzer. She
and her boyfriend understand safe sex, but cannot use condoms
because of poor hand coordination _ a problem for some retarded
people.
   ``It's hard to talk about because it's scary,'' said Ms.
Mintzer, who adamantly refused to see the film a second time.
   ``Sometimes, denial is an easier way of dealing with scary
feelings,'' the residential supervisor, Laura Eldridge, told others
in the group. ``But I don't feel it's healthy.''
   Some members of the Wisconsin council also were bothered by the
film's explicit nature or felt that it ``left some questions that
might confuse people,'' said Ms. Berger.
   They agree the retarded need AIDS education, she said. ``But
it's not like there's a canned program that works for everybody.
Agencies have different perspectives, and communities have
different attitudes.''
   The film is out of the question for Roman Catholic programs for
the retarded because of religious doctrine against condoms and
premarital sex, said Monsignor James Cassidy, director of health
and hospitals for the New York Archdiocese.
   ``We'd be against it purely from the medical point of view,''
said Cassidy. ``Condoms fail. If we relied solely on condoms, we'd
have every darn one of the females pregnant.''
   Instead, abstinence is taught to the 350 retarded adults served
through archdiocese programs. ``It's just a reinforcement of what
we've been doing all along,'' said Cassidy.
   Ganim, the spokesman for the New York mental health office, felt
ambivalent about the film.
   ``I certainly know it's explicit and some people have expressed
concerns about that,'' he said. ``But by and large, what we have
heard back about the tape has been positive. They've brought up the
fact that there is a need for this kind of thing.''
   Dr. Lloyd Kolbe, chief of the CDC's Office of School Health and
Special Projects, said no one has studied what kind of AIDS
information is available for the retarded and what might be
effective.
   Kolbe said CDC guidelines issued in January suggested that
schools address the issue of AIDS education for the disabled.
   ``We need to think about it,'' said Kolbe. ``The questions, I
think, are important ones.''
   ``It's not like you should just forget about it and pretend AIDS
doesn't exist,'' said Lauren Hoffman, a resident at the group home.
``A woman has to be prepared.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, April 6</NOTE>
