<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0551EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-Ritalin-Matthews Adv04   03-31 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ritalin-Matthews, Adv 04,0565</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Murder Case Called Attention to Ritalin</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-R Is for Ritalin I</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rod Matthews was a sullen, introverted boy,
fascinated with death, obsessed with fire. Shaun Ouillette was
outgoing and happy; he played hockey and talked of counseling
troubled youths.
   Sixteen months ago Matthews beat Ouillette to death with a
baseball bat. Last month the 15-year-old was found guilty of
second-degree murder and given life in prison.
   The horrible crime wasn't the only link between murderer and
victim. Both took Ritalin, a stimulant used to calm hyperactive
children.
   And while the trial served as a stage to the debate over the
drug, it also provided testimony on how Ritalin, in combination
with other treatment, can help children, and how its casual use can
allow deeper problems to go undetected.
   Matthews' attorney, John Philip White, claimed the drug nudged
the boy into the madness it took to plan and commit murder. The
Citizens Commission on Human Rights, an anti-psychiatry group
connected with the Church of Scientology, trumpeted the case as an
example of the dangers it associates with the drug.
   A stream of psychiatrists and psychologists gave offsetting
testimony. Defense witnesses said Matthews was psychotic, that the
Ritalin ``enhanced'' his obsession to kill. Prosecution witnesses
said the boy's emotional problems were not enough to obscure his
notion of right and wrong. Ritalin, they said, played no factor.
   Ironically, Ouillette's mother, Jeanne Quinn, says Ritalin
helped her son, calming him enough to allow the counseling and
therapy that taught him how to control himself.
   Guidelines by the American Academy of Pediatrics say Ritalin
should be prescribed after detailed diagnosis and used only in
combination with counseling and careful monitoring. According to
testimony, Matthews received Ritalin without other therapy.
   His mother, Janet, portrayed him as a quiet child who said
little more than yes or no in his early years. When he became a
behavioral problem in the third grade, a pediatrican prescribed
Ritalin.
   Mrs. Matthews said there were no special psychological or
physical tests, no monitoring of her son's progress over the next
five years.
   Mrs. Matthews said her son went off the drug a few months before
the killing, then asked for more pills a few weeks later. A bottle
of Ritalin was found in his school locker; no one knows if he was
taking the drug at the time of the killing.
   In contrast, Mrs. Quinn said her son ``went through all kinds of
tests'' before he was diagnosed as hyperactive and given Ritalin at
age 7.
   She said she attended sessions for parents with hyperactive
children, watched her son's diet and diverted his energies into
activities like hockey and bicycling.
   After four years, Ouillette was weaned from the drug.
   ``We had taught him to learn self-discipline and self-control,''
she said.
   White said the effect Ritalin had on his client remains a
mystery, but he believes that reliance on the drug, instead of
testing and therapy, played a role in the tragedy.
   ``The whole affair was a lost opportunity to spot a potential
problem,'' he said. ``As a result, we've got one boy in prison and
another boy dead.''

</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 4</NOTE>
