<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0555EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-RIsforRitalinII Adv05-1stAdd   03-31 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-R Is for Ritalin II, Adv 05-1st Add,0499</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, April 5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: going down.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In 1971, 1.1 percent of Baltimore County school students were
taking Ritalin, Safer said. By 1983, the number was up to 3.5
percent.
   ``The increase is a multiple of factors: parent-teacher
satisfaction, the ease of treatment and its relative success,'' he
said.
   Most Maryland school districts recommend parents seek medical
help only after teachers, counselors and administrators have met to
discuss a problem student.
   ``We don't prescribe Ritalin,'' said Robert Dubel,
superintendent of the Baltimore County School District. ``All we do
is refer children to medical help, the same as we would if a child
had problems seeing a blackboard. We would tell the parents and
they would have the child's eyes examined.''
   Yet when Baltimore County officials, threatened with a lawsuit,
reviewed their policy late last year, they found such a measured
response was not always the case.
   ``I am convinced that we probably do have some people out there
who sidestep some of the procedures and say `You have to get that
child on Ritalin,''' said Thomas Farley, an assistant county
attorney.
   In Georgia, Watry, the director of the medical examiners' board,
tells of one school counselor who would ``pressure parents on a
mass scale to use Ritalin.''
   ``He told parents he was playing the percentages because it had
helped with so many cases,'' said Watry.
   Late last year a special study group for the Georgia Department
of Education recommended school personnel be warned against
``pressuring'' parents to seek medication and leave diagnosis and
treatment to medical professionals.
   But often these professionals are not doing a complete job.
   The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends extensive testing
and discussion among doctors, parents and educators before
prescribing medication.
   Guidelines also stress that medication is only part of the
solution. Counseling, therapy, tutoring, even special classes for
parents are recommended.
   ``Almost everybody in the field will say you have to do more
than give the pill,'' said James Satterfield, a Los Angeles-area
psychiatrist whose research found hyperactive children responded
dramatically better to a combination of therapy and Ritalin.
   ``We've heard about pediatricians who have said, `Here's six
months of prescription, come back when it runs out,''' he said.
``That gives a message to parents that here's this magic pill, you
don't need any other treatment.''
   But some question if many of those getting treatment need it.
   Thomas Long, a psychologist and director of the National Center
for Family Studies at the Catholic University of America, believes
doctors choose medication when counseling and different parenting
might be enough.
   ``We have created a society that relies on medication to solve
our problems,'' he said. ``The first thing you go to when you have
a problem is some kind of pill.''
</TEXT>
