<1ST_LINE>a a AM-RitalinandTom Adv05   03-31 0967</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ritalin and Tom, Adv 05,0995</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, April 5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ritalin Prescribed for ``Attention Deficit''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-R Is for Ritalin II</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Each weekday morning our 7-year-old son Tom
starts breakfast with a tiny white tablet he calls his ``daydream
pill.''
   The pill has become part of our daily routine. There was a time
when my wife and I, people who think twice before taking aspirin,
would have been incredulous had you told us we'd be giving our
child a behavior-modifying drug.
   As Tom grew into an active toddler, he gave no indication
anything was amiss; we were sure he was a superstar. With blond
curls and a sturdy well-coordinated body, he was quick and good at
everything: an early walker and talker, a cheerful elf full of
eager questions.
   But by the time Tom was ready for kindergarten, we were
concerned. He couldn't seem to keep his mind on a task. He didn't
like to play alone, and he didn't stay with an activity for more
than a few minutes.
   We hoped it was just immaturity. Perhaps we had spoiled him?
   With his quick mind and pleasing personality, Tom drifted
through kindergarten. We wondered why he wasn't picking up academic
skills as quickly as we'd anticipated, but his school reports were
generally good and he was having a good year with soccer and T-ball.
   Everything changed in first grade. He was one of 30 classmates,
and most of the school day required independent seatwork.
   We realized something was very wrong when Tom began collapsing
into tantrums of free-floating rage and frustration after school.
We were completely taken aback, especially because we had high
confidence in his small, caring school.
   We were mystified by our little soccer player's rage. At what?
Was it the oversized class?
   The school principal assured us that, although the class was
large, the children were doing fine.
   We spoke to psychologist friends about whether some deep-seated
anxiety could be surfacing.
   Tom himself was unable to give us any clues until one night in
the midst of an emotional collapse, he said, over and over, ``I'm
dumb.''
   Fortunately for us all, Tom's class took a group intelligence
test about this time. Tom's score was so high in comparison with
his performance that the principal called us in. She wanted to do
further testing and mentioned ``attention deficit,'' a term that
seemed to fit the child we knew.
   The principal also mentioned Ritalin, saying she had seen
dramatic changes in kids like Tom. We were appalled by the
suggestion we give our boy a drug, skeptical that this was the
proper way to approach a learning problem.
   Instead, we tried a highly publicized diet and spent an
agonizing month keeping Tom from many of his favorite foods, ones
with cyclamates and additives. The stress of the diet increased
Tom's rage and frustration.
   We next urged the school to institute behavioral techniques,
such as rewarding Tom for even brief periods of concentration.
These helped, but only moderately, and we started to reconsider.
   After reading all the research we could find, and considering
the side effects (such as the possibility Tom would be one-quarter
inch shorter as an adult), we concluded the risks of trying Ritalin
were minimal.
   A factor in our decision was our own dependence on our morning
cups of coffee, which help us get going and stay focused. Were we
depriving Tom of the equivalent of a morning cup of coffee?
   The pediatrician said Tom might temporarily lose his appetite or
have trouble sleeping. None of this happened, and Tom was
surpringly amenable to taking the tiny pill.
   Indeed, Tom was the first to let us know it was making some
difference. He started calling it his ``daydream pill,'' saying it
helped him control the daydreams that distracted him in class. His
teacher soon reported his behavior was improving, and we saw this
reflected in his school work.
   Still, we couldn't be certain it wasn't just a placebo effect on
Tom and the teacher.
   This year, with a new teacher who shared our lingering
reservations, we withheld the Ritalin for a couple of weeks.
Simultaneously, Tom and his teacher reported he couldn't
concentrate and urged us to return to the pill.
   With the increased demands of second grade, Tom has begun taking
an additional 5 milligrams at lunch. Occasionally, when he's having
trouble staying with his homework, he'll say, ``Maybe I should take
a pill.'' Last week we filled yet another prescription at the
pharmacy where we are now recognized as regulars.
   Last month, Tom proudly brought home a report card with B's in
math and English and A's _ his first ever _ in reading and
spelling. In categories such as deportment, handwriting and follows
directions, which last year produced a string of F's for failure
and N's for non-satisfactory, there were 2 N's and 13 S's _ for
satisfactory.
   Is Ritalin a panacea? No. Even with the pill, Tom's attention
deficit still requires the guidance of a skillful teacher.
   Are we comfortable about him taking medicine? Yes and no.
   We like the results but are uncomfortable treating a symptom,
the cause of which no one knows. We are especially uncomfortable
that the psychologists and doctors seem unconcerned why Tom has
trouble paying attention.
   Will we keep giving him the pill? Yes, at least while Tom thinks
it's helpful. We'll also keep trying to find a deeper understanding
of what's involved.
   As Tom says, ``It's not perfect, but it works, some.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is the AP Southeast regional
reporter, based in Atlanta. His wife, attorney Gail Falk, helped
write this article about their son, Tom.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, April 5</NOTE>
