<1ST_LINE>a p AM-Dukakis-GreekRoots Adv04   03-31 0998</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Greek Roots, Adv 04,1023</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Greece Follows Dukakis Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MYTILENE, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' cousins in Greece like
to tell how his father ran away from his home on the Turkish
mainland to a merchant uncle who lived on the Greek island of
Mytilene, after being forbidden to leave for America.
   A telegram was sent home saying that young Panos was safe. ``And
the answer came, `Tie him up in a bundle if necessary and send him
back,''' said Elly Petridou, a retired bank employee who still
lives on the island.
   ``But my grandfather _ Panos' uncle _ knew the future lay in
America and didn't obey,'' she said. ``Instead, he found Panos an
English teacher and later on paid his fare from Mytilene to
America. ... And eventually his parents followed him there.''
   That was early in this century. Today, at least a few ``Mike
Dukakis-President'' stickers are showing up as far away from
America as this northern Aegean island where his father lived, as
Greek interest grows in the Massachusetts governor's campaign for
the White House.
   Greek television newscasts lead off with coverage of the U.S.
primaries, and Athens newspapers run front-page stories detailing
Dukakis' progress.
   Politicians and analysts discuss the 54-year-old Democrat's lack
of experience in foreign affairs. And they study his campaign
speeches for clues to what might be future American policy.
   Dukakis, in interviews with Greek media, stresses his Greek
heritage. But he avoids comment on eastern Mediterranean disputes
such as the Greek-Turkish disagreement over Aegean oil rights and
the divided island of Cyprus.
   A mix of pride and caution marks the mood among the half-dozen
cousins and their families who make up the Dukakis clan in Greece.
   ``We all think Mike is an exceptional person and we're convinced
he'll win the Democratic nomination. But that's still a long way
from getting to the White House,'' Patra Zourelli, a second cousin
who lives on Mytilene _ also known as Lesbos _ said in an interview.
   From a political standpoint in the United States, ``I can tell
you it's an advantage to be an immigrant's son,'' Dukakis was
recently quoted as telling the Athens daily Vrathyni. ``The
minorities see in me their children's opportunity to get ahead.''
   Dukakis' father, Panos, became a respected family doctor in
Brookline, Mass. His mother, Euterpe, now 83 and campaigning
actively for her son, was one of the first Greek-American women to
qualify as a teacher.
   ``Dukakis is probably unique in that his parents made it to the
professional classes. ... Usually it's the second generation which
makes that jump,'' Alexander Kitroeff, a historian who teaches at
Queens College, New York, said in a telephone interview.
   Dukakis' father was the youngest of four brothers who left
Greece as teen-agers in the early 1900s. It was a time when Greeks
flocked to America, working in textile factories, flower stalls and
shoeshine parlors to escape dire poverty at home.
   Mytilene, lying close to Turkey and covered with millions of
olive trees, boasts a literary tradition that began in the 7th
century B.C. with Sappho, Europe's first woman poet. Another lyric
poet from the island, Odysseus Elytis, won the Nobel Prize for
literature in 1979.
   The Dukakis family came from Pelopi, a cluster of stone houses
reached by a dirt road winding up Mytilene's highest mountain and
still considered one of the poorest villages on the island.
   Dukakis' grandfather moved away in the 1880s to make a better
life on the nearby coast of Turkey, where Greeks prospered as
store-owners and merchants.
   ``Mike's grandfather and mine were cousins who both left the
village of Pelopi and settled in Edremit on the Turkish side. His
grandfather ran a general store and mine ran a bakery,'' George
Grigoriou-Dukakis, 76, a retired agronomist, said in an interview.
   The Dukakis property at the top of the village was sold in 1933
and Yiannis Manolis, the villager who bought it, keeps the yellowed
sale contract in his pocket.
   ``I want to stay around long enough to welcome Michalis back
here as president,'' said Manolis, 81, who lives in a two-story
house he built on the ruins of the Dukakis home.
   There are no records surviving to clarify whether Dukakis'
father was born on Mytilene _ then ruled by Turkey _ or in Edremit.
   Dukakis' mother was born in the northern city of Larissa, then a
sleepy farm town but now a booming center for the Thessaly region.
   ``Cousin Euterpe is a tough lady who'd be called a feminist if
she were young now. ... Her family all left for the States in the
early 1900s after losing their land to the Turks,'' said Nikos
Milingos, a third cousin who runs a farm chemicals business.
   Like most of the relatives, the Milingos family first met
Dukakis when he came to Greece in 1976 during his first term as
governor. Now they visit Massachussetts regularly.
   ``We found him very warm and welcoming, but he's certainly a man
of principle,'' said Olympia Milingos. ``When we went for dinner at
their home in the days of energy-saving, Euterpe told us to take
sweaters because the heating would be low _ and it was.''
   The Greek-American community in the United States, numbering
between 1 million and 3 million by various estimates, is pouring in
funds to back its ``patrida'' (homeland) candidate.
   According to Dukakis aides, around 25 percent of his first $15
million in campaign funds came from Greek-Americans.
   Apart from the wish to claim a U.S. president of Greek descent,
many in Greece say that Dukakis' election would repair the damage
to their self-image caused by former Vice President Spiro Agnew.
   ``Spiro Agnew was an embarrassment to Greece and the migrant
tradition. It's a bad memory for us that we'd like to erase through
Dukakis,'' said former Culture Minister Dimitris Nianias, a member
of parliament for Mytilene.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
