<DOCNO> AP880331-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-JamesEarlRay Adv03   03-31 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-James Earl Ray, Adv 03,0646</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Inmate No. 65477 Says, `I Didn't Kill Anybody'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Killing King</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PETROS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Earl Ray has spent most of his ``free
time'' at Brushy Mountain State Prison plotting ways to get out,
either by going over the wall or into a courtroom.
   So far, he's been more successful at breaking out. In 1977,
inmate No. 65477 managed to scale the wall and remain free for
three days before being apprehended in the rugged hills near the
prison.
   A couple of years earlier, he escaped from his cell through an
air vent only to be captured inside the prison walls a few hours
later.
   But the 60-year-old Alton, Ill., native hasn't been able to get
back into court since March 10, 1969, the day he pleaded guilty to
killing the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
   And although he is doggedly determined to win a day in court,
Ray apparently has become more resigned to prison life than he was
in his escape-artist days, which included a 1967 breakout from the
Missouri State Penitentiary, where he was serving 20 years for
armed robbery.
   ``He's a good inmate,'' said James Worthington, an officer at
Brushy Mountain, a maximum security prison 40 miles west of
Knoxville. ``He does good time and doesn't cause us any trouble _
not of late, anyway.''
   Ray works in the prison laundry, earning $1 a day. He shares an
11-by-8-foot cell with another inmate and spends most of his
weekends in the prison law library.
   ``I work five days a week, from 7 a.m. to 3 o'clock in the
afternoon,'' he said in a recent interview with The Associated
Press. ``We get an hour a day for exercise in the yard through the
week and two hours on Saturdays and Sundays.''
   He maintained, as he has ever since pleading guilty, that he
didn't kill King and doesn't know who did. He said he pleaded
guilty only because he was pressured into it.
   Ray speaks in a quiet but determined voice when discussing his
legal problems. Although he has spent nearly half of his life
behind bars he still looks fit: his hair is dark, with white
sideburns, his dark blue eyes are alert and his body is trim in a
blue denim uniform.
   ``It's always a good idea to keep fit in prison,'' he said,
rubbing a scar on his left cheek, the result of an attack by three
black inmates in 1980. Two of his attackers got 60-year sentences
for attempted murder, and the third was given 20 years.
   ``I got careless for a moment,'' he said, recalling the assault.
``Like a fool I went into the law library when there were no guards
present. But, then I was lucky, too; they stabbed me in the arm,
face and chest but never hit an artery.''
   Worthington describes Ray as a quiet loner who usually keeps to
himself when he goes out to the prison yard for exercise with other
prisoners.
   Although married in 1983 to a Nashville artist who was teaching
art appreciation to inmates, Ray hasn't had a visitor since last
fall. To pass the time, he reads and paints _ mostly watercolor
landscapes from memory.
   He recently helped prepare a second edition of his
autobiography, which he said he wrote to tell his side of the story
about the King assassination.
   As for his 99-year sentence, he said, ``I really don't think I
should have had to spend all this time in prison. I didn't kill
anybody.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is the AP Southeast regional
reporter, based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
