<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0563</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day of reckoning for the rival suitors of
Federated Department Stores Inc. passed without ushering one of
them _ Campeau Corp. or R.H. Macy & Co. _ to the altar, but it
appeared Macy raised the stakes in the $6 billion takeover battle.
   Federated's board of directors was expected to choose between
the companies' final bids Wednesday, but deliberations dragged on
all day and into the night with no sign of an end to the
2-month-old contest.
   Federated spokesman Jim Sluzewski said late Wednesday evening he
did not know when a decision would be announced.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co. stock soared amid market
rumors that Lucky Stores Inc. might be planning a ``Pac-Man''
takeover bid to counter its supermarket rival's acquisition offer.
   American Stores has launched a $45-a-share tender offer for
Lucky, which would produce a deal worth about $1.74 billion.
American later said it would boost the offer to $50 a share, or
$1.93 billion, if Lucky's management supported the acquistion.
   Lucky declined to comment Wednesday, but analysts said Lucky
might be considering making its own bid for American Stores. In New
York Stock Exchange trading, American Stores jumped $2.75 a share
to $59.75, while Lucky fell $1.50 a share to $48.37{.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second consecutive monthly decline in
orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods is no cause for
alarm, analysts say.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that orders for durable
and non-durable goods dropped 0.8 percent to a seasonally adjusted
$210.86 billion last month following a 0.6 percent decline in
January.
   Economists said while businesses cut back on orders in the early
part of the year, the cutbacks were moderate and may set the stage
for faster growth.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracting for future construction projects
jumped 10 percent in February, recouping January's 8 percent
decline, a new report says.
   The survey, released Wednesday by the F.W. Dodge Division of
McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co., estimated the annualized value
of all newly started construction projects in February at $249.7
billion, the highest level since last October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices farmers got for raw products this month
were unchanged from February and up 7.4 percent from a year
earlier, the Agriculture Department says.
   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board reported
Wednesday higher prices for lettuce, cattle, eggs and broiler
chickens, while farmers received lower prices for hogs, milk, wheat
and sweet corn.
   Consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent
this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987,
the government says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Japanese automakers have been dumping small
trucks on the U.S. market, costing U.S. workers jobs and the U.S.
auto industry $500 million in lost wages, sales and profits, a
study commissioned by U.S. automakers says.
   The 42-page study released Wednesday said the five Japanese
companies are illegally selling compact pickup trucks for 10
percent to 48 percent less in the United States than they charge in
their Japanese home market.
   One of the companies accused, Toyota Motor Corp., immediately
denied the charges. The study was conducted on behalf of the Big
Three U.S. automakers.
</TEXT>
