<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service says it will
waive penalties for underpayments of estimated tax on most types of
retirement income for 1987.
   The agency earlier had decided not to impose such penalties on
wages earned in 1987, because of widespread confusion about the new
tax law and a complex W-4 withholding form.
   In another decision affecting retirees, the IRS said Wednesday
that owners of multiple Individual Retirement Accounts who passed
the age of 70{ in 1987 will be allowed more discretion in choosing
from which account to take a distribution. Such owners are required
to take money from an IRA by April 1.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal spending averaged nearly $3,433 per
American in 1987, about $41 more than the year before, the Census
Bureau says.
   Alaska led, with U.S. spending there averaging $5,421, more than
double the $2,536 spent per resident in last-place Wisconsin,
according to the report released Wednesday.
   If it were a state, the District of Columbia would be the easy
winner, however, with spending averging $23,360 per capita.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III says he
strongly disagrees with proposals to forgive some of the Third
World's $1 trillion debt.
   ``I believe this path leads both debtors and creditors off the
cliff,'' Baker told a Senate panel on Wednesday. ``This approach
would irreparably politicize the debt problem.''
   He argued for a U.S. contribution to increase the capital of the
World Bank, the largest single source of aid loans to Third World
countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thursday is the last day to qualify for the big
airlines' triple-mileage programs, and travelers have been flocking
to the skies to beat the deadline.
   To drum up business in the slow winter months, the major
airlines offered to triple all mileage credits accumulated by
participants in frequent-flier programs this year _ if the member
took at least one round-trip or two one-way flights on that carrier
by the end of the day Thursday.
   The deadline, coupled with the approach of Easter and school
vacations, seems to have touched off a flying spree, travel experts
said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. became the Pentagon's
top research contractor in fiscal 1987, winning awards totaling
$1.7 billion, the Defense Department says.
   Among educational and non-profit entities, the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology continued to hold down the top ranking,
winning research contracts during the year worth $407.6 million,
the Pentagon reported Wednesday.
   Overall, the Pentagon increased its spending on research by more
than 10 percent during fiscal 1987, with awards reaching a grand
total of $21.8 billion. That compared with $19.8 billion in fiscal
1986.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices finished lower Wednesday as an early advance was
wiped out in a late-afternoon decline that sent the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials down 20.22 at 1,978.12.
   The dollar fell despite modest central bank intervention.
   Bond prices were mostly lower in light trading.
   Platinum futures prices soared, copper and precious metals
futures advanced, energy futures were higher and livestock and meat
prices retreated.
</TEXT>
