<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LuckyStores Bjt   03-31 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lucky Stores, Bjt,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Stores Stock Jumps; Lucky `Pac-Man' Bid Rumored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucky Stores Inc. may turn the tables on rival
grocer American Stores Co. to thwart the pursuer's $1.74 billion
buyout offer, analysts say.
   Talk of the rarely used ``Pac-Man defense'' pushed American
Stores stock up $2.75 to $59.75 a share on the New York Stock
Exchange Wednesday, while Lucky lost $1.50 a share to close at
$48.37{.
   Earlier this week American Stores launched a $45-a-share tender
offer for Lucky. But the Salt Lake City-based supermarket giant
later said it was prepared to boost the offer to $50 a share, or
$1.93 billion, if Lucky's management supported the acquisition.
   Lucky has declined to comment on the offers, but analysts said
rumors focused on whether Lucky might be considering making its own
bid for American Stores.
   A combination of the two companies would rival Kroger Co. as the
nation's largest supermarket operation.
   Lucky Stores spokeswoman Lissa Perlman said the company
``doesn't comment on rumors.'' The only comment Lucky has made is
that its board is studying American Stores' two proposals.
   ``There has been conjecture all along about what options Lucky
might have,'' said Jonathan Ziegler, an analyst with the investment
firm Sutro & Co. in San Francisco.
   Ziegler noted that Lucky, which operates in the lucrative
California market, would have to take on a huge amount of debt to
acquire American Stores.
   Analysts specualted Lucky might be trying to put American Stores
stock ``in play'' on Wall Street to take the spotlight off itself.
   The rumors came a day after American Stores Chairman L.S. Skaggs
complained of ``various reports'' that Lucky might be considering a
``defensive acquisition'' of another company to make itself
financial unattractive.
   In a letter Tuesday to Lucky's board of directors, Skaggs
cautioned against a maneuver that could interfere with his
company's takeover plans and warned that any attempt to ``frustrate
the choice given to your shareholders through a defensive
acquisition'' would affect American's willingness to increase its
tender offer to $50 a share.
   Skaggs reiterated that American Stores would consider divesting
stores if it acquired Lucky, in order to mitigate any antitrust
concerns that might exist.
   American Stores is the nation's third largest grocery retailer
with 1,700 stores and annual sales of $15 billion. Lucky is the
sixth largest with 480 stores and sales of $7 billion.
   American Stores filed a lawsuit last week in Delaware charging
Lucky and its executives with breaching their fiduciary duties by
``following a course of conduct directed toward entrenching
themselves in control of Lucky Stores.''
   As part of defensive measures taken over a year ago to stave off
corporate raider Asher Edelman, Lucky voted senior management
lucrative ``golden parachute'' contracts and announced a
restructuring plan that included changing the company's state of
incorporation from California to Delaware and a buy-back of 27
percent of its outstanding shares.
   The company has noted that its bylaws also contain an
anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any
shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of Lucky's stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 0226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LotusBlueprint     03-31 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lotus Blueprint,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lotus Announces Enhanced Data Base Link</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lotus Development Corp. has announced
its Blueprint tool kit, an upgraded product by Lotus Development
Corp. to give its computer users easy access to a wide range of
non-Lotus data bases.
   ``I tend to view this as a building block kind of an
announcement,'' said David Readerman, an analyst at Smith Barney &
Co. in New York. ``They are trying to build a better connection
between third-party data bases and their own PC software tools.''
   ``It fits in their long-term strategy,'' said John Maxwell III
of Dillon Read & Co. Inc. in New York. ``It's a positive step for
the future.''
   Analysts say Blueprint is part of Lotus' strategy to expand
applications for its software in a period of increased competition
from spreadsheet manufacturers, such as Borland International Corp.
of Scotts Valley, Calif.
   Lotus stock rebounded slightly following Wednesday's
announcement.
   The stock had tumbled nearly $7 a share since last week after
the Cambridge-based firm announced plans to delay release of the
Lotus 1-2-3 Release 3 spreadsheet software until the fourth
quarter. The delay caused analysts to cut 1988 per-share earnings
estimates from about $1.95 to about $1.50.
   Lotus stock closed up 50 cents a share to $22.50 in
over-the-counter trading Wednesday.
   The Blueprint kit, scheduled to be released late this year, will
aid data base manufacturers in creating drives that will greatly
streamline the process of accessing software not specially designed
for Lotus systems, said Lotus spokeswoman Betsy Kosheff.
   The drives will be sold to consumers by data base firms
including Oracle Corp. of Belmont, Calif., which has formally
announced plans to place a Blueprint drive in its upcoming product
line. Other firms expressing interest in Blueprint include Microrim
Inc., PC Publishing Inc. and Synex Systems Corp., according to the
Lotus statement.
   Kosheff said the drive will allow Lotus system users to hit one
key to connect with various data bases, rather than the many steps
now required. Data obtained through Blueprint drives will be
compatible with existing and planned Lotus software, including
spreadsheets and graphics, she said.
   Lotus spokesman Philip Greenough said Blueprint is an
enhancement of Application Connection, a Lotus-created data base
connection drive introduced in 1986.
   The Blueprint drives will be available for use on all sizes of
Lotus computer systems, said Greenough.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
