<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-31 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down Sharply Against Yen; Stocks Also Close Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped sharply against the yen today
while stock prices fell slightly after three days of substantial
gains.
   After opening lower at 125.15 yen, the dollar dropped further
and closed at 124.50 yen, the day's low, down 0.93 yen from
Wednesday's close of 125.43 yen.
   The Bank of Japan appeared to step into the market to support
the dollar late in the morning and at the outset of the afternoon
session, traders said.
   ``Profit-taking dollar selling brought the dollar down, but
besides that there was no notable movement in the market,'' said
Ken Iiya of the Bank of Tokyo. The market still is anticipating a
weaker dollar, he said.
   Another trader said market participants were hesitant about
trading while awaiting the scheduled release of U.S. economic data
on Friday. In addition, he said, New York markets will close for a
holiday Friday and will not provide any lead for Tokyo after the
data is released.
   Figures to be released Friday include U.S. unemployment in March
and construction expenditures in February.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which rose 366.89 points Wednesday to a post-crash
high, sliped 59.81 points, or 0.2 percent, closing at 26,260.26
points.
   ``The market has come to a rest as investors stepped to the
sidelines, following the three days of sharp gains,'' said Yoshio
Shimoyama of Nikko Securities. The Nikkei average gained more than
1,000 points in the three days.
   The dollar's fall did not affect the market, which kept a
positive mood about prospects for the new fiscal year beginning
Friday, he said.
   Investors also were cautious while awaiting the U.S. economic
data, traders said. The volume of the first section was estimated
at 1.4 billion shares, down from 1.8 billion shares Wednesday.
</TEXT>
