<2ND_LINE>PM-British Stocks,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Off 12.3 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices fell on the London Stock Exchange today,
depressed by the continuing strength of the British currency and by
previous declines in New York and Tokyo.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was off 12.3
points, or 0.7 percent, at 1,744.6 at midday.
   Volume was a low 175 million shares, down from 232 million
shares a day earlier.
   Volume was light on the last day before the extended Easter
holiday weekend. The London market is closed on Friday and Monday.
   The market remained in negative territory all morning, moving in
a narrow range after an early markdown, dealers said.
   The early markdown was caused by the previous drop in New York
and Tokyo and by sterling's recent rise against the Deutsche mark.
   Sterling was boosted by comments on Wednesday by Chancellor of
the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, who emphasized the government's
commitment to fight inflation.
   Currency dealers interpreted Lawson's statements as evidence the
government will tolerate further rises in sterling without cutting
interest rates again.
   Sterling's rise depressed the major exporting companies' stocks
that get a competitive advantage from a weak pound.
</TEXT>
