<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Contel-Lemasters     03-31 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Contel-Lemasters,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contel Will Pay Resigned Exec $275,000 A Year For Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contel Corp. will pay a former president $275,000
a year for life in return for his agreement last year to resign,
the company said this week.
   John Lemasters, 53, will also receive stock and medical benefits
from Atlanta-based Contel, the former Continental Telephone Co.,
the company said in its proxy statement mailed to shareholders.
   A Contel spokesman said the benefits would continue for the rest
of Lemasters' life.
   Lemasters resigned as head of the $3 billion company April 30,
1987, following the failure of a proposed merger he had spearheaded
with Communications Satellite Corp. of Washington, D.C. He headed
Contel for two years.
   Contel officials acknowledged Wednesday they had received
telephone calls from some shareholders criticizing the termination
agreement, reached last year.
   A Contel spokesman said the agreement was a compromise to
persuade Lemasters to give up his original contract, which included
a $380,000 base salary in 1986 and a special stock bonus worth more
than $800,000 over four years. Lemasters also agreed not to work
for a competitor.
   Lemasters, now president of a Pompano Beach, Fla., computer
firm, is to provide consulting and other services to Contel until
Aug. 3, 1988.
</TEXT>
