<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Ritz-Carlton     03-31 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ritz-Carlton,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Over Name Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ritz-Carlton Hotel Co. has settled its
dispute with the owner of hotels in two cities over use of the
Ritz-Carlton name.
   William B. Johnson, chairman of the Atlanta-based Ritz-Carlton
Hotel Co., issued a joint statement Wednesday with William B.
Coleman, owner of Ritz-Carlton Hotels in New York and Washington,
D.C., saying they have agreed to work together to operate and
market Coleman's hotels in those cities.
   The Atlanta-based hotel company filed suit two years ago to
prevent Coleman from using the Ritz-Carlton name. Johnson's
company, W.B. Johnson Properties Inc., bought rights to the
Ritz-Carlton name when it acquired Boston's Ritz-Carlton Hotel in
1983.
   The joint statement said further details of the operations
agreement would be forthcoming.
   The Ritz-Carlton Hotel Co. operates hotels in Atlanta, Boston,
Laguna Niguel, Calif., Naples, Fla., and Rancho Mirage, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
