<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened narrowly mixed
today in very light activity on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Little price movement was expected with many traders taking to
the sidelines ahead of two eagerly awaited Agriculture Department
reports due out after the close, analysts said.
   The annual report on spring planting intentions will give the
market a broad indication of the potential size of this year's corn
and soybean crops.
   The quarterly grain stocks report will reveal the levels of
grain on hand as of March 1.
   Together, the reports will indicate whether futures prices
should go higher to encourage more planting to meet the expected
demand, or lower to discourage plantings.
   ``People are afraid to take any position going into these
reports whether the news is positive, negative or neutral,'' said
Steve Freed, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``It's been
a good four or five years since we've had that kind of situation.''
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.02} a bushel; corn was \ cent to
{ cent lower with May at $2.09\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1
cent lower with May at $1.60 a bushel; soybeans were { cent lower
to 1\ cents higher with May at $6.48{ a bushel.
   Most cattle futures were higher while pork futures were mostly
lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .08 cent to .10 cent higher with April at 75.02
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent lower to .05 cent higher
with March at 82.75 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to .12
cent higher with April at 45.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .30 cent to .35 cent lower with May at 55.55 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures retreated on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
