<1ST_LINE>u f BC-MCI     03-31 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-MCI,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MCI Looking for Positive Cash Flow by Early 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. expects that by early
1989 the company will achieve a positive cash flow for the first
time in its 20-year history, a company spokesman confirmed Thursday.
   Once that goal is achieved, MCI plans to reduce its debt and
later begin buying back the 16 percent stake in the company held by
International Business Machines Corp., said spokesman Bernard
Goodrich.
   The company, the nation's second-largest long-distance carrier,
wants to reduce its debt-to-equity ratio from 67 percent to around
40 percent over the next four years, Goodrich said.
   ``At that point, we would look at the market and see if the next
step is to buy back the IBM stock,'' he said. ``We're talking three
to four years before we would consider that and then we'd have to
consider market conditions.''
   Goodrich confirmed a report in Thursday's editions of The Wall
Street Journal, in which MCI officials outlined the company's
future plans.
   Financial pressures on the company have eased now that it has
finished building its digital network. It also has added 800
service, operator services and direct-dial service virtually
worldwide to match the offerings of industry leader American
Telephone & Telegraph Co.
   MCI acquired IBM's share of Satellite Business Systems in 1986
in exchange for 47 million shares of MCI stock. Under the
agreement, IBM cannot acquire more than 30 percent of MCI's stock
without the company's approval.
   With a stock repurchase, MCI could assure its independence and
increase its earnings per share, Goodrich said.
   MCI ended 1987 with earnings of $88 million, or 31 cents per
share, on revenues of $3.94 billion. The company's capital and
other expenses exceeded its cash flow by $200 million last year.
   IBM had no comment on MCI's stock-repurchase plans.
   A company achieves positive cash flow when its net profit plus
depreciation is greater than its expenditures on dividends and
investment in plant and equipment. MCI does not pay dividends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
