<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1228EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Trade 1stLd-Writethru f0023 03-31 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0023,0591</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: New material, editing thruout; also running on general news
wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators broke a
longstanding deadlock today and moved to place sharp import curbs
on Toshiba Corp. and a subsidiary for selling submarine-silencing
equipment to the Soviets.
   Approval of the Toshiba provision as part of a sweeping trade
bill came despite Reagan administration opposition and a major
lobbying campaign by the Japanese electronics manufacturer.
   On the eve of the action, several Cabinet officials warned
lawmakers that a stringent punishment for Toshiba could precipitate
a presidential veto of the 1,000-page trade bill. They said the
president should have more flexibility in determining national
security and trade relations with other countries.
   ``I was elected as a U.S. senator to represent the State of Utah
in the U.S. Senate and not Toshiba and not England and not the
State Department and not Frank Carlucci,'' declared Sen. Jake Garn,
R-Utah, in urging lawmakers to defy administration opposition.
   He said he was embarrassed that a Republican administration
would fight the sanctions, adding, ``The State Department has been
kicked in the shins and instead of saying ouch they have chosen to
surrender.
   The provision was accepted by a subcommittee of a House-Senate
conference committee working on a compromise version of the trade
bill.
   It would ban for three years U.S. government procurement of
Toshiba Corp. products. The company has massive sales within the
United States of televisions, microwaves and other electronic
products.
   It would ban import for three years of products manufactured by
Toshiba Machine Corp., the subsidiary involved with the Norwegian
firm of Kongsberg Vapenfabrikk in selling sophisticated
computerized milling equipment to the Soviets that the
administration says has greatly submarine propeller noise.
   There would be exemptions for national security.
   The measure also provides for a two to five-year ban in the
future on imports of products by foreign makers that violate the
so-called Cocom agreement under which western nations act to keep
high-tech equipment with military uses out of communist hands. But
the president could waive such action against parent companies in
some cases.
   Lawmakers are pushing to put the finishing touches on the trade
bill before starting on their spring break.
   ``We're going to give it our best,'' Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas, said Wednesday as a House-Senate conference committee
plowed through a stack of proposals but stopped short of the big
decisions.
   Congress wants to have all the provisions wrapped up except a
few minor loose ends before heading for its spring break at the end
of the week.
   The committee, attempting to fashion a compromise between rival
1,000-page trade bills passed by the two houses, heard Rep. Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo., appeal to lawmakers to save the heart of his
controversial trade plan.
   The plan to force 10 percent annual reductions in unfair
surpluses that other countries run with the United States formed
the centerpiece of Gephardt's abandoned campaign for president.
   He said any final version should focus on key countries that
make unfair trade practices part of a systematic trade strategy.
Wholesale negotiations should be shunned in favor of working on
major trade trouble spots, he said.
   Mandatory retaliation is needed when negotiations fail, he said.
``You have to have a stick in the closet,'' he said. But he added
that flexibility is necessary in dealing with trading partners and
the president should have the power to waive retaliation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ResortsInternational     03-31 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Resorts International,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Gives Up Tender Offer for Resorts International Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Donald Trump gave up his $22-a-share
tender offer for the Resorts International Inc. stock he doesn't
own, saying he is confident a takeover bid by
entertainer-businessman Merv Griffin will never be approved.
   Control of Resorts International is now held by Trump, who owns
nearly all of Resorts' 572,000 Class B shares that have 100 votes
each, giving him 88 percent of the company's voting power.
   On Wednesday, Griffin revised his offer for $36 a share for all
of the company's Class A stock and called for Resorts to sell
Griffin 1.2 million new Class B shares at the same price. The new
stock would give Griffin voting control.
   The company has 5.7 million Class A common shares that have one
vote each.
   Trump said late Wednesday he will return all tendered shares
after his offer. The merger agreement expires at midnight tonight.
   Trump said he will never sell his Class B stock and will not pay
more than $22 for Class A stock.
   Griffin said Wednesday he is no longer making his offer
contingent upon Trump tendering his Class B stock or terminating a
five-year management contract valued at about $100 million for
Resorts' hotel-casinos in New Jersey and the Bahamas.
   Consummation of the offer would result in Griffin owning a
majority of the voting power and more than 90 percent of the equity
of Resorts.
   Trump would be able to participate in Griffin's new offer only
by converting his stock to Class A shares.
   Griffin, through his privately held investment firm, Griffin
Co., made his revised offer to Resorts' outside directors, noting
he believes only those board members should vote on the proposal.
   ``The other directors have interests in Mr. Trump's competing
bid,'' Griffin said.
   Three of Resorts' six directors are nominees of Trump, who is
the company's chairman.
   Resorts referred media inquiries to Trump. Trump's attorney,
Jack Nusbaum of New York, said Trump would continue to use his
voting power to resist Griffin's offer and it was unlikely Resorts'
outside directors would meet independently to consider the proposal.
   Trump is offering $22 a share to buy the Resorts stock he
doesn't already own and take the company private.
   In mid-March, Griffin countered with a bid of $35 a share, or
$225 million, for all of the company's stock, but it was contingent
upon Trump tendering his stock and terminating the management pact.
Trump has repeatedly indicated he wouldn't agree to either
contingency.
   Griffin subsequently said he would boost his bid to $295
million, with Resorts' board members able to decide how to
apportion the additional $70 million between Class A and Class B
holders. The move was seen as a way to pay a higher price to Trump,
but the New Yorker again said he wasn't interested.
</TEXT>
