<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-UnitedWayAds     03-31 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-United Way Ads,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless, Rape Victims Featured in New United Way Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In new public service commercials for the United
Way, a mugger tears a coat off the back of a homeless man, an
assailant grabs an unsuspecting woman and an older man is felled at
the office by a heart attack.
   By the end of the 30-second ads, the homeless man gets a new
coat, the distraught woman dresses up to face the world again and
the older man enjoys restored health on a beach.
   They each got help from agencies assisted by donations to the
United Way.
   Roberta van der Voort, a senior vice president of United Way of
America Inc., said Thursday that by showing people the ``vital
link'' between their donations and good deeds, the ads may help
dispell skepticism about charitable organizations.
   Ruth Wooden, president of the Advertising Council, the
non-profit organization that oversees $1.1 billion a year in public
service advertising, said the United Way is the first organization
to address the issues of homelessness and rape in a national
advertising campaign.
   She said she expects ``exceptionally strong media play'' for the
campaign with the media donating more than $70 million in free time
and space this year, up from $40 million donated for the national
United Way campaign last year.
   The ads were created by the New York-based agency Lowe Marschalk
Inc., which took over responsibility for the campaign this year.
The ads continue the theme ``The United Way. It brings out the best
in all of us.''
   Van der Voort said the United Way raised about $2.6 billion last
year and channelled the money to 37,000 agencies that help people
in some way.
   But she said research showed many people were unaware that
United Way donations helped organizations such as the Salvation
Army provide coats to the homeless, rape crisis centers counsel
abused women and the Red Cross provide training that often helps
save the lives of heart attack victims.
   She said Lowe Marschalk was asked to ``tell a story in 30
seconds'' that demonstrates how donations help people in the
community.
   ``Twenty minutes ago, this man's last shred of dignity was
stripped right off his back,'' a narrator says in the spot where a
mugger tears the coat from a homeless man.
   ``Where do you go when your world is this cold, this cruel,''
the voice asks as the homeless man shivers in the shadow of a stone
column.
   The commercial then shows the man putting on a new coat, as Lowe
Marschalk makes the connection it has been asked to draw in three
succinct phrases.
   ``He got help at the Salvation Army. They got help from the
United Way. Thank God, the United Way got help from you,'' the
narrator says.
   The Advertising Council is distributing the commercials and
radio versions of the ads to networks, cable outlets and local
stations across the country. Print versions of the campaign should
be ready in a month, said Lowe Marschalk's president, Andrew J.
Langer.
   The agency has previously created public service campaigns for a
free press, Amnesty International and the city of New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BuyUS     03-31 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Buy US,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company, Two Executives Fined $604,000 For Using Foreign Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company fined $604,000 for using foreign-made
steel in hacksaws sold to the government will appeal a verdict that
found it violated the Buy American Act, its attorney said Thursday.
   ``It is not a rational interpretation of the Buy American Act,''
said Jerome Facher, who represented Rule Industries in the case.
   A U.S. District Court jury on Wednesday convicted Rule
Industries and two of its executives of 302 violations of the act,
which calls for goods purchased by the federal government for
public use be manfactured with mostly American-made parts.
   The number of violations corresponds with the number of invoices
the company submitted during its contracts with the General
Services Administration in 1981 and 1982 totaling $1.3 million.
   The jury ruled the company was liable because it purchased
10-inch steel ``blanks'' from suppliers in Sweden and Japan. The
blanks were milled, hardened and tempered in the United States.
   Rulings in the case indicated that it would not have been a
violation of the act had Gloucester-based Rule Industries purchased
sheets or coils of steel from foreign suppliers and cut the blanks
from them.
   ``The act is really being interpreted in a bizarre fashion,''
Facher said. ``It's a very complex and old piece of legislation
that dates back to the Depression and has never really been
definitively interpreted by a court.''
   The case is believed to be the first jury trial in the
enforcement of the 55-year-old act, U.S. Attorney Frank L. McNamara
Jr. said.
   McNamara had filed a civil lawsuit in 1985 against Rule
Industries, a diversified manufacturer of marine and hardware
products; its president, William Anastos, and its vice president,
Gary Sable. Each was charged with violating the act.
   The jury said the defendants falsely represented that domestic
steel was used to fulfill four contracts with the GSA, the main
contracting arm of the federal government.
   Rule Industries officials had said when the suit was filed the
GSA was well aware of its steel-purchasing practices.
   During the trial, several former employees testified that Rule
Industries executives hid the source of the steel by destroying
containers shipped from overseas, blackening out foreign markings
and removing shipping labels from packages.
   ``There were a number of very honest employees who got offended
when their company lied to the government,'' said Richard Stearns,
a first assistant U.S. attorney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
