<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Federated 5thLd-Writethru   03-31 0983</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated, 5th Ld-Writethru,1015</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federated Board Puts Off Decision After Macy Revises Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after the 8th graf with analyst's comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of Federated Department Stores Inc.
put off until Friday a decision on whether to reaffirm its merger
agreement with R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. or accept the competing bid of
Campeau Corp.
   In a statement today, Federated said both suitors presented
revised bids of more than $6.6 billion each to the board at its
day-long meeting Wednesday.
   The board had been expected to announce today whether it would
reaffirm its support for its agreement with Macy or reverse itself
and choose Campeau's offer.
   However, Federated said Macy submitted another revised offer
this morning and the board would meet again Friday morning to
consider both bids.
   For the first time since it announced its cash-and-stock offer a
month ago, Macy put a value on the stock end of its bid and also
gave shareholders the option of taking all cash for their shares,
Federated said in a statement.
   In its bid today, Macy offered $78.92 a share in cash for 80
percent of Federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares, and said it
would pay $60 in cash or exchange five shares in a new company,
Macy's-Federated Inc., for each remaining Federated share.
   The deal had a blended value of $75.14 a share, or a total of
$6.73 billion, Federated said.
   In its latest bid, Campeau offered to pay $74 a share for
approximately 80 percent of Federated's shares, and the same amount
for the remaining 20 percent after a merger, Federated said. That
would make the Toronto-based developer's bid worth $6.62 billion.
   Thomas Tashjian, an analyst with Seidler Amdec Securities Inc.
in Los Angeles, said Macy had an edge over Campeau with the offers
now on the table, but he cautioned, ``Campeau could always come out
and say they're going to offer a higher bid.''
   Wall Street analysts had said Macy would be forced to put a
value on the ``stub'' _ or securities _ portion of its offer to
compete with Campeau. Many investors, including arbitragers who
hold a sizeable portion of Federated stock, were leaning toward the
certainty of Campeau's all-cash offer.
   Investors reacted enthusiastically to the higher bidding.
Federated stock was up $2.25 to $72.50 in early afternoon trading
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Before Wednesday's meeting, Campeau offered $73 a share in cash,
or $6.53 billion. Campeau had said it would pay $82 each for 70.5
million Federated shares and $37 for each of the remainder of
Federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares in a subsequent merger.
   Campeau also had proposed a friendly merger under which it would
pay $73 a share for 70.5 million shares in a tender offer and $73
for the remaining shares following the merger.
   Macy's offer prior to the Federated board meeting on Wednesday
was $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million Federated shares, for
a total of $5.4 billion. Macy said it would exchange shares in the
merged company and issue convertible debt securities for the
remainder of Federated's shares. Analysts valued the offer at $6.3
billion.
   Federated said Macy presented an offer at the meeting similar to
today's proposal, but which had an aggregate value of $73.88 a
share or a total of $6.61 billion. That offer was superseded by
today's bid.
   Campeau had no comment on the latest Macy bid, Campeau
spokeswoman Joele Frank said.
   Federated gave Macy Chairman Edward Finkelstein and Campeau
Chairman Robert Campeau the opportunity to address the board on
Wednesday, but the New York Times reported in today's editions that
Campeau declined to appear. Finkelstein spoke to the directors and
presented ``his vision of the combined company,'' the Times said.
   Campeau has fought the merger agreement Federated forged with
Macy a month ago with lawsuits and higher bids. If Federated's
directors again select Macy's offer, Toronto-based Campeau is
expected to continue in court the battle it began with a
$47-a-share offer on Jan. 25.
   Macy's offer was scheduled to expire Monday. The expiration of
the Campeau offer was uncertain, pending completion of financing
requirements for the acquisition.
   Federated had given both companies the chance to submit what it
called ``final bids'' after Campeau's most recent offer.
   On Tuesday, the companies were in court after Federated
announced procedures for the submission of final offers. Campeau
objected to the guidelines on grounds they favored Macy, but U.S.
District Judge Leonard Sand denied the Canadian company's request
for a temporary restraining order blocking the procedures.
   Campeau argued the procedures were illegal because they embraced
Federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense and agreements between
Federated and Macy.
   Federated asked that whichever company was not chosen either
terminate its offer or extend it for 30 business days. An extension
would give the advantage to whichever company Federated backed,
because shareholders would likely tender their shares to the suitor
whose offer expired first.
   Sand stipulated that Federated could not invoke defensive
measures _ including its controversial poison pill _ before the
losing party had a chance to challenge those measures in court.
   The poison pill would make a takeover attempt more expensive by
allowing the retailer's shareholders to buy more company stock at a
discount, unless Federated's management supported the bid. Campeau
had sought unsuccessfully in court to have the pill invalidated.
   Campeau also objected to an agreement under which Federated
would pay Macy ``break-up'' fees if a Macy-Federated merger failed
for reasons other than a Macy default.
   Federated's divisions include Bloomingdale's, Burdine's,
Filene's, Foley's, Lazarus and Rich's department stores; Ralphs
supermarkets; Gold Circle discount stores; and Main Street and
Children's Place specialty stores.
   Macy owns nearly 100 department and specialty stores.
   Campeau, which started in real estate development in Canada,
moved into the U.S. retail market at the end of 1986 by acquiring
Allied Stores Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
