<HEAD>PIP Agrees to $67.9 Million Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postal Instant Press Inc., the nation's
largest franchiser of printing centers, said Thursday it has agreed
to be taken private by a management-led investor group for $67.9
million, or $17.41 per share.
   The pact ends six weeks of on-again, off-again acquisition
negotiations.
   An earlier, $17-per-share bid by the management group, headed by
PIP's chief executive Thomas Marotto, was permitted to expire two
weeks ago when the company entered into talks with an unidentified
third party that was offering $17.50 per share, or $68.25 million.
   However, PIP said Thursday that ``serious questions arose as to
the firmness of that offer'' and Marotto's group boosted its bid.
   PIP has 3.9 million shares outstanding.
   Marotto's group includes the Chicago-based investment firm of
Golder Thoma & Cressey, which specializes in leveraged buyouts in
which the assets of the firm being acquired are pledged as
collateral to line up takeover financing.
   PIP has about 1,000 printing centers in the United States,
Canada and the United Kingdom, all but a few of them franchised.
   Last year, the company escaped a hostile bid by Tarrytown,
N.Y.-based Kane-Miller Corp.
