<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mixed Thursday
on the Chicago Board of Trade in light trading ahead of two
important government reports and the three-day holiday weekend,
analysts said.
   The Agriculture Department's annual report on spring planting
intentions and its quarterly report on grain stocks, both due out
after the close on Thursday, were expected to set the trend for
corn and soybean futures prices for the next 30 days.
   Together, the reports were expected to indicate whether futures
prices should go higher to encourage more planting to meet the
expected demand, or lower to discourage plantings, analysts said.
   The reports were to be released at 2 p.m. CST. The markets
cannot react until Monday, however, because they will be closed
Friday.
   Soybean prices advanced in Thursday's session while wheat and
corn prices retreated.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 3\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $2.99 a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to \ cent higher with May at $2.09{ a bushel; oats were 1{
cents to 2} cents higher with May at $1.61} a bushel; soybeans were
2 cents to 4{ cents higher with May at $6.53 a bushel.
