<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Westinghouse-Siemens     03-31 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Westinghouse-Siemens,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German, U.S. Firms Plan Joint Ventures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. said Thursday it
plans a broad series of joint ventures with Siemens A.G., the giant
European electrical equipment manufacturer.
   ``These agreements will strengthen the competitive position of
both companies in today's global markets by combining our
respective world-leading technologies and capabilities,''
Westinghouse Chairman John C. Marous said in announcing the signing
of a letter of intent.
   The two companies together will make, sell and service factory
automation equipment, industrial circuit breakers and industrial
controls, Westinghouse said. The joint ventures, covering more than
20 products, will operate in selected world markets, including the
United States.
   Westinghouse, the largest U.S. electrical equipment
manufacturer, said it will own 51 percent of the joint ventures,
which will need the approval of government regulators and directors
of both companies..
   Westinghouse and Siemens have cooperated in various ways as
customers and in licensing agreements for more than 50 years,
Marous said.
   The approximately 358,000 employees of Munich-based Siemens
generated 1987 sales of $30.4 billion. The 110,000 employees of
Pittsburgh-based Westinghouse generated 1987 sales of $10.7 billion.
   The joint ventures in factory automation will combine existing
Westinghouse operations that employ 2,700 people, 1,700 of them in
the United States, and Siemens operations in Peabody, Mass., and
Roswell, Ga., employing 370 people.
   Businesses will be created to fulfill plans for the other two
areas, industrial circuit breakers and industrial controls, said
Westinghouse spokesman James P. Schmitt.
</TEXT>
