<2ND_LINE>AM-Sears Bank,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears Applies for Second Bank in Delaware</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck & Co. has filed with the
state to charter a second bank in Delaware.
   Sears, which already owns Greenwood Trust Co., has filed an
application to open a credit card bank called Discover Card Bank of
New Castle, Susan L. Winters, acting deputy bank commissioner, said
Wednesday.
   The filing comes under that part of Delaware law that pertains
to any new bank being established in the state. A hearing is set
for May 2 on the application.
   Sears issues its Discover credit card through Greenwood Trust,
which it acquired in 1985.
   Ms. Winters said Sears plans to transfer some of Greenwood
Trust's credit card acounts to the new bank if it is approved.
   Under federal banking laws, the growth of non-banks, which
includes Greenwood Trust, are restricted. Ms. Winter said the new
bank's ability to grow would not be restricted.
   When the federal law restricting the growth of non-banks was
filed, ``Sears made a commitment to look for ways to continue to
make credit card loans,'' said Paul Marrone for Dean Witter
Reynolds, the Sears subsidiary that oversees Discover Card
operations.
   ``The application we have filed is a first step in the
development of that commitment,'' Marrone said.
</TEXT>
