<1ST_LINE>r f AM-JimWalters-Bonds     03-31 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jim Walters-Bonds,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bonds Sold To Finance Kohlberg's Buyout of Jim Walter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In what is being billed as one of the largest
non-government issues in history, $1.45 billion in bonds have been
sold to help Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. pay off bank loans from
its buyout of Jim Walter Corp.
   Kohlberg Kravis took Jim Walters private last year for about
$2.4 billion, about $2 billion of which was financed by bank loans.
Since then the New York-based investment firm has been selling
selected Jim Walter's assets to help finance the deal.
   Jim Walter, which has its headquarters in Tampa, Fla., is a
diversified building materials and natural resources company that
operates primarily in the South and Southwest. It also is one of
the country's largest home builders, specializing in inexpensive,
partially finished ``shell'' houses.
   Walter had 74,000 single-family mortgages in 22 states totaling
$1.74 billion that were packaged together to back the bond issue.
   ``KKR realized they had a very unusual asset in these
mortgages,'' said Peter Hoey, senior vice president of Financial
Security Assurance.
   Hoey said the bond issue was ``totally sold out to a blue-chip
list'' comprised of large pension funds, life insurance companies
and banks from around the world.
   The mortgages were sold to a special trust and used to back the
bond issue, which Financial Security guaranteed with a triple-A
rating.
   Homeowners pay their morgtages into the trust, which has a
cushion to protect against any defaults by homeowners. That cash
flow will pay the interest on the bonds, which were sold in five
different maturities, each carrying a different interest rate.
   ``The purpose was not to take weak credit and make it triple-A
and take on risk, but to take complex and unusual collateral that
the marketplace has difficulty understanding'' and package it to
sell, Hoey said.
   The average buyer of a Jim Walter home requires a low-cost
mortgage and therefore is not a typical homebuyer.
   Jim Walter does not provide the land on which its houses are
built, which cuts down on the price of the homes. In addition, the
company leaves its houses as much as 30 percent incomplete, making
them affordable to blue-collar, first-time homebuyers, Hoey said.
   Kohlberg Kravis has spearheaded a number of major leveraged
buyouts, including the $6.2 billion buyout of Beatrice Cos. The
company said this week that it is seeking permission to acquire up
to 15 percent of Texaco Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0298 </DOCNO>
