<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     03-31 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds ,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $548.4 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 420 money market mutual
funds fell $548.4 million in the latest week, the Investment
Company Institute said Thursday.
   The decline, to $278.23 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $730.3 million drop in the funds' assets the
previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual fund trade
group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 210 general purpose funds rose $624.5 million to $82.86
billion, assets of 98 broker-dealer funds dropped $620.2 million to
$117.04 billion, and assets of 112 institutional funds declined
$552.7 million to $78.33 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds was
unchanged in the week ended Tuesday at 6.04 percent, according to
Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade journal based in Holliston,
Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 6.05 percent from 6.07 percent
the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
43 days, down from 44 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts was
unchanged from a week earlier at 5.70 percent as of Wednesday.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was also unchanged, at 5.15 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 6.78
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 6.79 the
previous week. Yields were 7.12 percent on 1-year CDs, unchanged;
7.53 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 7.52 percent; and 7.99 percent
on 5-year CDs, unchanged.
</TEXT>
