<HEAD>Fremont General to Sell Some Insurance Units</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fremont General Corp. said Thursday
it has agreed to sell all of its property and casualty insurance
operations to a management-led group for $82 million in cash, notes
and stock warrants.
   The operations are being acquired by a new company formed by
managers of a Fremont General subsidiary, Fremont Insurance Co.
   Being sold are Fremont Indemnity Co., Fremont Comspensation
Insurance Co., Fremont Reinsurance Co. and Comstock Insurance Co.
The latter two operations were discontinued last year, and Fremont
General sought unsuccessfully to spin off the first two to
shareholders.
   Upon completion of the deal, Fremont General will remain a
financial services concern with commercial and life insurance
operations, a real estate finance unit and half ownership of a
workers compensation insurance firm. It also is awaiting regulatory
approval to acquire Malibu Savings & Loan Association.
   Under terms of the deal announced Thursday, Fremont General will
receive $20 million in cash, a 90-day note for $5 million,
preferred stock with warrants to purchase 9.9 percent of the
buyer's outstanding shares valued at $35 million, and a 10-year
zero-coupon note valued at $22 million.
