<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ResortsInternational Bjt   03-31 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Resorts International, Bjt,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resorts Stock Falls as Trump Ends Bid, Vows to Block Griffin Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of Resorts International Inc. stock
slumped Thursday as investor Donald Trump, who holds 88 percent of
the company's voting power, withdrew his bid to take the
hotel-casino operator private and indicated he would block a
higher, rival offer by entertainer Merv Griffin.
   Resorts' Class A stock fell by $1.62{ per share to $28.87{ in
trading on the American Stock Exchange.
   Griffin's bid, which was revised Wednesday for the second time,
was an attempt to make an end run around Trump's repeated
objections and force Resorts' outside directors to vote on the plan
free of Trump's influence.
   ``The Delaware courts have consistently ruled that a
corporation's outside directors are charged with the duty to
conduct a fair bidding contest,'' the Griffin Co. said Thursday.
   ``Outside directors have been authorized by the courts to take
all reasonable steps, including diluting a major shareholder, in
order to obtain the best deal for the public shareholders.''
   However, some analysts were skeptical of whether Griffin could
succeed.
   ``Because Griffin's offer is conditional, they (Resorts' outside
directors) have an out. They can simply refuse to consider it on
grounds that it is unlikely it would be able to succeed,'' said Lee
Isgur, a leisure-time industry analyst with PaineWebber in New York.
   Resorts' board, composed of Trump and two of his nominees plus
three outside directors, is scheduled to meet Monday. Trump is
chairman of Resorts.
   Griffin's latest proposal dropped two previous conditions _ that
Trump agree to sell his stock and terminate a lucrative five-year
contract to operate Resorts properties in New Jersey and the
Bahamas.
   Instead, Griffin imposed a new contingency _ that Resorts agree
to sell him 1.2 million new shares of Class B stock, which carries
100 votes per share and would give Griffin more votes that Trump.
   Trump owns nearly all of the company's current 572,000 Class B
shares.
   He was offering $22 per share for the company's 5.7 million
Class A shares, which carry only one vote per share and hence only
12 percent of the company's voting strentgh. But he said the offer
was allowed to expire at 12:01 a.m. Friday and all tendered shares
will be returned to their owners.
   Griffin is offering $36 per share for the Class A stock, and the
same price for the 1.2 million new Class B shares he is seeking.
   Attorney Alan Applebauam, who represents the independent
directors, indicated that he feels all Resorts directors including
those nominated by Trump have the right to vote on Griffin's merger
proposal.
   But he said that the question of whether only outside directors
should vote on the proposal to issue new Class B stock to Griffin
``is a matter for further research.''
   Trump's attorney, Jack Nusbaum, reiterated that he feels the
full board should take up Griffin's offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880331-0304 </DOCNO>
