<1ST_LINE>u f AM-US-JapanTechnology     03-31 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Technology,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Countries Prepare to Sign New Five-Year Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and the United States have reached
substantial agreement on a new five-year pact to expand their
scientific and technical cooperation, the State Department said
Thursday.
   The new agreement, to be concluded in about three months, seeks
incentives to boost the flow of American students, researchers and
scientific workers to Japan, said officials of both countries who
declined to be named. They said more than 10 times as many Japanese
are currently in U.S. classrooms, laboratories and factories as
Americans studying or working in Japan.
   The 1980 U.S.-Japanese scientific exchange agreement, extended
several times since its expiration in 1985, was extended for
another three months ``to allow for legal editing of the new
document, and signing at a high level,'' the department said.
   It will be considerably more detailed than the existing pact on
the two countries' scientific and technological relationship and
also provide a new management structure to oversee that
relationship, the State Department said.
   It will provide for protection of patents and other intellectual
property rights while calling for the widest dissemination of
information resulting from joint research, the announcement said.
   Both countries were concerned about the need to increase the
flow of Americans to Japan, said the sources. They said the new
agreement provides steps to be taken by both sides to make Japan
more attractive for U.S. scientists and easier for them to go
there. It envisions more funding for Japanese language study and
fellowships by the United States, one said.
   The estimate that there are 10 times as many Japanese students
and scientists currently in America as Americans in Japan is a
rough minimum estimate, because in the United States it is
difficult to count students of science separately from those of
other subjects or even from tourists, one official said.
</TEXT>
