<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Roper     03-31 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roper,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE To Proceed Unopposed With Offer For Roper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. reached an agreement
Thursday with rival bidder Whirlpool Corp., allowing it to proceed
unopposed with a $507.6 million offer to acquire Roper Corp.
   GE spokesman George Jamison said the Connecticut-based company's
offer of $54 per share would be extended until 5 p.m. Monday.
   Whirlpool simultaneously announced it was terminating its
$50-per-share offer.
   The battle to acquire Roper, an appliance and lawn equipment
manufacturer based in Augusta, Ga., began last November. Earlier
Thursday, GE and Whirlpool said they were negotiating to resolve
their dispute over the proposed acquisition.
   ``For GE, the Roper factories and Roper's strong Sears
relationship makes this an important niche acquisition that will
significantly strengthen our appliance business in an increasingly
competitive global market,'' said Roger W. Schipke, GE senior vice
president in charge of the company's appliance business.
   Roper had recommended Tuesday that its shareholders accept GE's
latest tender offer, rather than the $470 million bid from
Whirlpool.
   Whirlpool and GE agreed Tuesday in Delaware Court of Chancery
that there would be no open market purchases of Roper stock until a
judge ruled on a GE request for a temporary restraining order.
   The companies said Thursday that agreement was being continued
while they negotiated, and eventually the two came to an accord.
   GE sought an order to prevent Whirlpool from making a ``street
sweep'' of Roper stock through market professionals rather than
from public shareholders. The reqest came in a hearing on a GE
application for a preliminary injunction to block a Whirlpool
acquisition of Roper.
   The terms of the agreement between GE and Whirlpool allow GE to
acquire Roper and its manufacturing capacity for kitchen ranges and
lawn equipment. Whirlpool, in return, will get rights to the Roper
name for major appliances. GE will supply Whirlpool with
Roper-brand electric and gas ranges at competitive prices for at
least two years, according to a press release from the companies.
   The parties also agreed to other commercial relationships
whereby GE would sell to Whirlpool certain industrial components
and materials.
   Lawsuits filed by both companies will be withdrawn upon
completion of GE's tender offer, the companies said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
