<DOCNO> AP880331-0313 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-31-88 2326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Trade 2ndLd-Writethru   03-31 0937</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0963</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 2 grafs after 17th graf bgng: The House ... to add
background on windfall profits. Picks up 18th graf pvs bgng: Farm
lawmakers ...</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Also moved on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators reached tentative
agreement Thursday night on a sweeping trade bill designed to open
foreign markets, but only after loading it with provisions that
lawmakers said could invite a veto.
   Repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies, tough trade
sanctions against Toshiba Corp. of Japan and millions of dollars in
new subsidies designed to boost U.S. grain exports were tentatively
included.
   ``We're going to need a trade policy in the next couple of years
and I think this is as good as anything that's going to come across
the president's desk,'' said Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill.,
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
   Rostenkowski and Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd
Bentsen, D-Texas, worked out the details of the central agreement
in private in the final hours of negotiations over different
versions of the bill passed last year by both houses.
   The measure erased a provision for driving down unwarranted
foreign trade surpluses that had been sponsored by erstwhile
Democratic presidential hopeful Richard A. Gephardt.
   ``The Senate version prevailed and I think that's unfortunate
and I'm against the bill,'' the Missouri congressman told reporters.
   Reagan administration veto threats hovered over the legislation,
and some members of the House-Senate conference committee were
disatisified with the bargain worked out between Bentsen and
Rostenkowski.
   ``My chairman has reached an agreement with Sen. Bentsen and has
laid it at the feet of the conferees with only a sort of very
general discussion and is now winging his way to Istanbul,'' said
Rep. William Frenzel, R-Minn.
   He said that it was uncertain that Rostenkowski would be able to
sell the package to other House members of a House-Senate trade
conference committee.
   Reagan administration officials had been threatening a veto over
provisions requiring employers to provide workers with notice of
plant closings and the Toshiba sanctions.
   Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., said in a statement Thursday night
that the plant closing provision and another relating to foreign
investment ``clearly would sink the legislation unless they were
removed.''
   Thursday afternoon, however, White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater appeared to back off a bit, saying that the
administration was not trying to signal a veto and still hoped to
receive a trade bill that it could sign.
   Rostenkowski told reporters before leaving on a congressional
fact-finding trip to Turkey that he hoped to get sufficient members
of the conference committee to sign the final product.
   ``When you get down to the serious negotiating, something has to
lose sometimes and I understand that the administration is
disappointed in some of this legislation,'' he said.
   Final arrangement began to fall into place Thursday morning when
one of 17 separate groups of conferees adopted the trade sanctions
against Toshiba and a subsidiary for selling computerized machinery
to the Soviets for the silencing of submarine propellers.
   The measure would ban U.S. government purchases of Toshiba
equipment for three years. It would bar import of products of the
Toshiba Machine Corp. subsidiary for three years. In the future,
such violations would be punishble by import bans of two to five
years.
   The House had held out for leaving retaliation up to the
president but Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah, refused to accept that
proposal and won out in the end. Another group of conferees broke
up without taking action on a proposal by Rep. John Bryant,
D-Texas, to require registration of foreign property ownership in
the United States. They said they would wrap up the issue in one
final meeting after the spring break.
   Repeal of the windfall profits tax was a major goal of Bentsen,
who is running for reelection this year in a state hammered hard by
low oil prices.
   Congress approved the tax in 1979 to when oil prices were
soaring. But the collapse of OPEC sent them plunging in 1985 and
dried up revenues from the tax. Critics say they want repeal
because the tax means costly paperwork.
   Farm lawmakers, meeting separately, said they were close to
agreement on a provision that would put in place export subsidies
of up to $500 million in 1990 unless negotiators reach agreement by
then on phasing out agricultural subsidies under the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   The so-called triggered marketing loan would benefit producers
of wheat, feed grains, soybeans and other oilseed crops.
   Farm lawmakers also agreed on boosting by $1 billion the Export
Enhancement Program, which furnishes grain companies and others
with surplus government crops to induce them to ship American grain
overseas.
   Gephardt's plan would have required the U.S. trade
representative to roll back ``excess and unwarranted'' foreign
trade surpluses by 10 percent annualluy if negotiations failed to
do the job.
   In its place, Bentsen and Rostenkowski adopted a Senate proposal
that would require the trade representative to list foreign unfair
trade practices and if necessary take action to force trading
partners to end them.
   The agreement between the two also transferred authority to
impose retaliatory import curbs from the president to the U.S.
trade representative _ a step that the White House had vigorously
opposed and which Rostenkowski had sought. But it provided
authority to waive such retaliation if the cost ``would be
substantially out of proportion to the benefits of action.''
   The president would retain his authority to decide whether to
grant import relief to industries that were hard hit by surges in
imports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
